<HEADLINE>
OTHER GUYS SET THE TABLE FO COWBOYS VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Sunday's on-going struggle for the Dallas
Cowboys came down to a game of who-do-you-trust?
</P>
<P>
   It was not the offense. Definitely not. Those people were
repeatedly handed choice plots of real estate and couldn't seal the
touchdown deal.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the defense. Definitely not. Those people only
survived because of a combo of one stupid play call by the New York
Giants and one Darren Woodson savior sack. Otherwise, Gary Brown
ran like Jimmy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, the Cowboys eventually scurried out of Texas
Stadium with a 16-6 win because the special-team forces provided 60
minutes of outrageous field position. New York's offense seemed to
start every possession from the shoulder of Airport Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday after Sunday in the NFL, the one great scorer does
not care how a team played the game _ he writes down only a W or an
L. In a league full of homely offense, winning ugly has become a
beauty contest.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the only sunshine on a gloomy and cloudy North Texas
day came from the postgame mouth of one Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a good football team, we've got to go out, take over a
tight game, and win it,'' the Cowboys' coach said. ``Today showed
we might be getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Cowboys are going anywhere come January, it will
obviously require much more offensive scoreboard production than
was displayed Sunday. Strangely enough, however, one of the most
positive moments of the season also came in this otherwise
offensive-wasteland of a game.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly unable to profit from prime field position, suddenly
Troy Aikman and Co. had none. They were backed up to the 16-yard
line in the waning seconds of the third quarter. A 9-6 Dallas lead
was as uncertain as Aikman's injured throwing-hand index finger.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's mere presence had already paid a dividend, although the
passing game was making little contribution. New York backed out of
the eight-man fronts it had used against Jason Garrett the last
time the teams met in September, which turned loose Emmitt Smith
for a very large day.
</P>
<P>
   And although backed up to the 16, what happened next was the
launching of a game-busting touchdown drive.
</P>
<P>
   In this 84-yard march, Aikman threw to six receivers, none of
them named Michael Irvin or Randy Moss. Think about that _ in one
critical and long drive, two theories died. One, that Aikman has to
have Michael Irvin to make the passing game work. Two, that the
Cowboys should have drafted Moss and his rap sheet.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest catches, not to mention sensational catches, of
the drive came from Billy Davis and Ernie Mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made the second receiver a nonconversation around
here,'' said Davis, also speaking for Mills. Billy, of course, only
told the truth, because that hot issue of the summer is no longer
even mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Like the special teams' commando he is, Davis ran a post over
the middle, and never flinched as he saw the ball and Giants'
safety Percy Ellsworth about to arrive one second apart. The
body-jarring hit from Ellsworth was heard in Duncanville. Davis,
however, immediately jumped up, ball in hand, and gave the
first-down signal. A sold-out Texas Stadium loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew (Ellsworth) was coming, but in a split-second, you make
the decision, do I or don't I?'' Davis said. ``To me, it's all
about thinking I will make that catch and thinking I will hang on
to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Two plays after Davis' 21-yard gain, Aikman went for it all on
another post route to Mills. A circus broke out with this catch. At
the 5-yard line, Ernie got one outstretched hand on the bullet,
then both hands, then somehow held the thing as he scooted along
the ground, untouched into the end zone. But the refs blew it,
marking him down at the 1. Two plays later, Aikman threw to a
wide-open Eric Bjornson for the game-is-over TD.
</P>
<P>
   As has been proved all season, the Cowboys don't have a second
receiver to offset the double-covered Irvin; they actually have two
in Mills and Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, by the way, had another great, clutch catch in the third
quarter that set up the go-ahead field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy came up to me (after the second one) and said, `Is Ernie
unbelievable or what?' '' Bjornson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have stressed from the start,'' Gailey said, ``is the
offense has to take advantage of what the defense is willing to
give us. If we aren't good enough to go to other spots on the
field, we aren't going to win games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Michael after the game I've never seen one guy given so
much respect (by the defense). They double-covered him the whole
way. Certainly, Troy loves to throw to Michael, but he sees what is
happening and has confidence in the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it came time to win Sunday, it was the ``other guys''
who made a touchdown happen, and also answered that
who-do-you-trust question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
