<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIDDY ERICKSON SHOWS OFF HIS MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As a veteran of Winter Olympics coverage, I can say
without fear of contradiction that for a few glorious moments
Sunday in the Kingdome, Dennis Erickson was just a triple toe loop
and a Playboy layout away from becoming the Katarina Witt of the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning, leaping, soaring, even offering a winsome smile, the
Seahawks coach fairly floated along the sideline after linebacker
Darrin Smith returned an interception for a touchdown and a 23-6
Seahawk lead.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson's performance wouldn't rate a gold medal, but since the
guy already had an anvil hanging from his neck, it nevertheless
bordered on the magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   During the run-up to the game, he was a career 0-7 against
Kansas City, as well as a fading 4-4 this disappointing season.
Erickson also was straining like hell to keep his team and his job
from flying apart.
</P>
<P>
   So when it dawned on him that he not only was winning the game,
but actually kicking the back pockets of his haughty rival, the
Chiefs' Marty Schottenheimer, Erickson acted like the kid who had
just vanquished the neighborhood bully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it, I love it, I love it,'' said linebacker Chad Brown
of his coach's gyrations. ``I watched the replay. He just let it
go. He was happy and enjoying it, which was good to see.''
</P>
<P>
   In his tenure, Erickson has displayed an awkward edginess to his
demeanor, sometimes seeming indecisive, sometimes too deferential
toward his players. It was as if he were still afflicted by
college-coach syndrome _ never quite sure he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   Schottenheimer, a forceful personality long on the details of
coaching, was exactly the kind of rival to feed that insecurity.
Ever since he reportedly said a few years ago after beating the
Seahawks that they were the most poorly prepared team he'd seen,
Erickson has wanted a piece of the guy, whether or not he admits
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat them like we did, having not beaten them since I've
been here . . .,'' Erickson said, smiling, voice trailing. ``It's
our eighth try, and we did it convincingly at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The 24-12 win not only brought the Seahawks back from the brink,
it provided the opportunity to kick a guy while he was down. The
Chiefs have lost four in a row, are 4-5 and Sunday outdumbed a unit
never revered for its mental acuity. The Chiefs' 17 penalties for
152 yards might have been the most damning single-game indictment
ever made against a Schottenheimer-coached team.
</P>
<P>
   The day's events presented such a role reversal that it seemed
almost Halloweenish _ the Chiefs showing up in Erickson masks and
Seahawk colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did to them,'' said Brown, ``the things they usually do to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Like scoring on the first possession. Like eating clock with
more runs than passes. Like capitalizing on mistakes. Like duping
the other guy into screwing up.
</P>
<P>
   On one offensive play in the second quarter, the Chiefs were
flagged for three fouls. Since there wasn't enough yardage in the
building to pay all the penalties _ and since the county
prosecutor's office is closed on Sundays _ the Seahawks accepted a
plea bargain of a 15-yarder for a chop block, as well as home
detention.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks were not eligible for sainthood this day either _
they had 13 penalties, not to mention two turnovers and only 89
yards of offense in the second half. As spectator entertainment,
the dreadfulness flirted with the monumental, dragging on so
insufferably that the time-elapsed clock switched from A.D. to B.C.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a win, one so bewilderingly easy that the Seahawk
offense took their 24-6 halftime lead into the locker room and left
it there with their brains.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, we lost our focus and played not to lose,'' said
wide receiver Mike Pritchard. ``We went back out there just trying
not to make mistakes that would put the defense in a bad position.
You can't play that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks haven't been in that position since the
season-opening, three-game sweep of the NFC Least, which now seems
a childhood memory.
</P>
<P>
   The last six weeks have been mostly a desperate grind of
failures by high-caliber people. Even the win in San Diego was a
tightrope walk over the shark pool.
</P>
<P>
   So to find themselves comfortably ahead of their most successful
rival was disorienting, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Chiefs have decayed so dramatically, it's hard to get a
read on the significance of the outcome. You might recall that the
first match between the clubs in Kansas City was conducted on King
Neptune's patio. All that was proven in that 17-6 mess was that the
Chiefs' gill-players were better than the Seahawks' gill-players.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs established that they are one of the poorer dry-track
teams in NFL history. If indeed the season proves the Seahawks have
been the better team all along, and still miss the playoffs by a
game, the fact that a Seattle team lost a contest because of
inability to handle rain will be an irony too great to bear.
</P>
<P>
   That's looking too far ahead. The here and now of the matter is
that the Seahawks won a game, they won in the AFC West and they
beat the bullies and their boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should ease those storm clouds over Kirkland,'' said Pete
Kendall, guard and part-time Harry Wappler. ``To be honest, things
were very tense last week.''
</P>
<P>
   The best part of all for those dressed in blue is everybody gets
to unpucker. I suspect the concussion has shaken windows up and
down Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
