<HEADLINE>
CSUN UNLEASHES FRUSTRATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ That wasn't a basketball game that took place at
the Matadome on Sunday, it was a two-hour group counseling session.
The Portland State players should have demanded the going rate for
shrinks for simply showing up for their exhibition game against the
CSUN women's team.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the Matadors' 103-72 shellacking of the Saints was
terrific therapy. For 10 days the Matadors had kept bottled up a
viperous mixture of emotions: abandonment, confusion, disbelief,
embarrassment, melancholy, resentment. Shaken by the arrest on
campus of their head coach, Michael Abraham, on drug-trafficking
charges and the forced resignations a few days later of two senior
athletic department officials, the Matadors insulated themselves
from the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   They ate together, laughed together, cried together and, most of
all, protected one another from the public's prying eyes. By
Sunday, the CSUN players were ready to unburden themselves to an
outsider.
</P>
<P>
   My, oh my, were they ever. The Matadors swallowed up the
sacrificial Saints like a tsunami. They led by 18 points after 11
minutes and by 27 at intermission. In the second half, they
continued to run so many circles around the Portland State players,
they nearly reached the record.
</P>
<P>
   Five more baskets, 10 more free throws or any combination
thereof and they would have tied the school mark set against UC
Irvine on Feb. 3, 1977.
</P>
<P>
   To put the record in perspective, it's older than all but two of
the CSUN players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took out a lot of aggression on (the Saints),'' said a
smiling interim head coach Frozena Jerro, who tried her level best
to keep the game in its proper context in the four days between her
promotion and Portland State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling myself, `It's just an exhibition game, it
doesn't count in the standings, it doesn't matter,' '' Jerro said.
</P>
<P>
   Like heck, it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game counted for so much more than wins and losses,''
Jerro was able to admit after all was said and won. ``It's a relief
to get a win under our belts. Just for team morale it was
important, after all the stuff that has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerro, the only one of Abraham's assistants who was with the
team in 1997-98, was named to take his place in a vote of the
players that carried the blessing of CSUN president Blenda Wilson.
She got the promotion on Wednesday and hadn't slept much since.
</P>
<P>
   Try as she might to count sheep, she kept seeing wolves. In her
darkest moments, she saw her own face at the door, baring fangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone through the whole gamut of emotions,'' Jerro said.
``I feel weird getting this promotion. So many people have been
hurt by what has happened, I can't feel good about benefiting from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is begrudging Jerro her break. In fact, many of her
fellow head coaches on campus could be found in the crowd of 462.
They came as a show of support for her, proving that the CSUN
family isn't nearly as dysfunctional as it has looked the past
couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the basketball team has never been more united. This
squad, with players from four different countries, didn't become a
true melting pot until it was thrown in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took what's been going on and we turned that negative into
a positive,'' said redshirt sophomore Tina Greer, who made her CSUN
debut a memorable one by coming within two steals of a triple
double. ``Before (Abraham's arrest), everybody was going through
the motions. But since then we've really pulled together. The
silver lining in the cloud is that we've all grown a lot closer.
We've got each other's backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer transferred in last year from Xavier because she desired
an up-tempo pace. Sure enough, she provided a positively pulsating
beat, assiduously pushing the ball upcourt on her way to a
10-assist, 14-point, eight-steal afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Edniesha Curry, whose pregame routine last season
included giving Abraham a hug, was herself mobbed by her teammates
after leading all scorers with 30 points in 29 minutes. She also
collected seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   Curry and Greer were the standouts, but everybody got into the
act. Twelve players logged at least seven minutes and 11 of them
scored at least four points.
</P>
<P>
   The result was breathtaking. Unless, of course, you were the
Saints, in which case it was asphyxiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad it didn't count,'' Jerro said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she laughed for the first time in a week and added, ``Oh,
but it did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
