<SLUG> BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNAP JUDGMENTS: SHOWDOWN FOOD FOR THOUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our Flutie Flakes are dying in the bowl. As the ultimate snack
of crunch time, they wilted Sunday. But we're starving for a hero,
so we rush to the cupboard for a box of Testaverde Toasties. Part
of a complete breakfast _ cereal, Big Tuna and a side order of
crow.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny might not be the toast of Broadway yet, but he certainly
ranks as the main man of the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Off-Broadway Vinny and the Jersey Jets sideswiped the
Doug Flutie bandwagon that's been carrying the Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
   This possibly pivotal AFC East matchup was promoted as a reunion
of Heisman Trophy-winning quarterbacks. Testaverde-Flutie were only
the second Heisman pair to meet in an NFL game. In 1977, Roger
Staubach and Jim Plunkett met in a Heisman battle that captured the
imagination of the nation. Yeah.
</P>
<P>
   But Testaverde and Flutie belong to another fraternity, the
Brotherhood of Doomed Quarterbacks (BDQs). BDQs include
quarterbacks who supposedly can't read a defense if it had been
written by Dr. Seuss (Testaverde) and those who might not qualify
for all of Disneyland's rides (Flutie).
</P>
<P>
   In short, quarterbacks who, according to the watchdogs of great
quarterbacking, couldn't thrive in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   When this season's midterms were graded, Flutie and Testaverde
were ranked 1-2 among AFC quarterbacks, and their teams were among
four tied for the AFC East lead. Their success had come at the
expense of younger quarterbacks who fit the league profile.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde, considered the duct tape of NFL passers, won
Sunday's round. He completed 22 of 31 passes for 258 yards and
three touchdowns. Flutie was 12 of 30 for 154. Two of his
screwballs were intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   But his bandwagon will be back on the road. How far it travels
depends on his ability to coax victory from his teammates. Ditto
Testaverde. We are happy to have been there for their first-half
run, an uprising from unexpected sources in the midst of an
otherwise dull NFL campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As stars, they've had more than a cup of coffee. They've had
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   __ Geography question:
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, East is east and west is East and even Scorsese
would be a long shot to establish any sense of direction.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has forgotten the three keys to good pro football are
talent, talent and location.
</P>
<P>
   In the crosshairs of this week's examination are geographic
cousins referred to as the ``AFC East'' and the ``NFC East.''
</P>
<P>
   We have no logistical problem in reconciling the NFL's concept
of the AFC East; its member cities all experience high noon at the
same time. And the teams are relatively decent with two completing
Week 10 at 6-3 and two others at 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   The division is as competitive as a room full of enterprising
mothers and one free-agent Beanie Baby.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFC East is misdirected on many levels. The combined
record is 17-28. Its prevailing bullies, the Dallas Cowboys, are
5-0 against divisional foes but 1-3 when playing real teams. Three
of the division's participating cities are in the Eastern time
zone, but citizens of two others _ Dallas and Tempe, Ariz. _ think
``EST'' is a form of yuppie voodoo.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals of Arizona are so off the beaten path their
defense could be known as the Gila Monsters of the Midway.
</P>
<P>
   The NFC West is worse.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical flight to a divisional matchup in San Francisco,
the Carolina Panthers, New Orleans Saints and Atlanta Falcons
absorb more jet lag than New York suffered during the halcyon daze
of Rich Kotite.
</P>
<P>
   We have a solution: Abolish divisions with directional names.
Through extensive research, we conclude the best adjustment could
be switching to divisions based on team nicknames. For example, the
Eagles, Ravens, Falcons, Cardinals and Seahawks would play in the
Audubon Division. The Jaguars, Panthers, Bengals and Lions would
make up the Garfield Division. The Redskins, Cowboys and Chiefs
would occupy the Politically Incorrect John Wayne Movie Division.
The Oilers, Bills, Chargers and 49ers are naturals for the Go For
Broke Division.
</P>
<P>
   But the toughest-to-define group would include the Raiders,
Buccaneers, Steelers and Packers and be known as the Pillage-Manual
Labor Division.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so we might be stuck with our current nonsense of direction.
But wouldn't it make sense to cultivate more geographic rivalries?
The NFL should consider it. If not, the future might offer another
directional alternative:
</P>
<P>
   South.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
