<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0311 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI     11-09 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REIGN HOME OPENER USHERS IN A NEW ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Scalpers were out on Mercer Street Sunday night. A
beautiful night in Seattle. No rain, only the Reign. And for the
home opener of this city's very own women's professional basketball
team, the Reign was a hot ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody selling?'' was the call on the sidewalk outside Mercer
Arena just before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was no.
</P>
<P>
   It was the right call, because inside the Reign players were not
only re-igniting the special lovefests that break out during home
games, they were creating a new image for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Call them winners.
</P>
<P>
   If this was the same team that did not win a single game in the
entire month of December last season, if this was the same team
that finished 15-29 and fifth in the Western Conference, then
Sunday night's near-sellout crowd had to be pinched to remember
those leaner, bleaker times.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening tip, it was clear that this is the best Reign
team in the American Basketball League's three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Alabama guard Niesa Johnson has all but turned
around this once confused and moribund team. The Reign finally has
a point guard who can run and penetrate and create, and Johnson put
it all on display Sunday, leading to a 106-86 victory over the San
Jose Lasers.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Reign never broke the century mark. This
season, it could become a habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great core group,'' Johnson said. ``There are some
great shooters, and they can reverse the ball well. The one thing
they were missing last year was a penetrator.''
</P>
<P>
   The return of last year's ABL rookie of the year, Shalonda Enis,
has ensured the Reign has an inside game to finish what Johnson
starts. And while Kate Starbird may not have added any real girth
to her bird-boned figure, she is confident again _ something that
should make the natural introvert smile and be happy with herself a
little more.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is we had so much fun out there. I remember
coming out in the second quarter and I had this big smile on my
face and thought this is the most fun I've had in a long time of
playing basketball,'' Starbird said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important in this new chemistry, the Reign has a coach
who seems to understand the difference between college hoops and
the women's pro game.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Holder, who replaced Jacquie Hullah halfway through last
season, has shown her charges a way to play an up-tempo game,
making them opportunists who can create and score in transition.
</P>
<P>
   It is a huge difference from the start of last season, when
Reign players looked like they were victims of too many film and
study sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Starbird and her cohorts weren't the only ones having fun. Mayor
Paul Schell was in the house. Sonics assistant coach Nate McMillan
and his family had front row seats. So did Sonic star Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   The Glove was on the cell phone, eating popcorn, chatting with
his pals. But he was there, spending his NBA-less nights supporting
the other home pro hoops' team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to play, but I'm sticking with the other players.
We're just looking to make sure we get a good deal,'' Payton said
of the NBA's hard-line lockout against the players.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his paycheck-less November, Payton was spending his
cash Sunday night _ all in support of a good cause. During a
halftime auction for an autographed Reign basketball, Payton got
into some serious nodding as he entered a bidding battle with
another, unidentified high-roller spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Payton barely flinched as the ball's price escalated in $50
chunks. He just kept nodding, all the way up to $700. And when it
came time to pay up, Payton just directed the Reign marketing
director to his agent, Eric Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll take care of it,'' Payton said, later telling the P-I
that despite his support, there is no truth the rumors that he
might be in the market to buy the Reign's operating rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gary's Girls? ``Not me,'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, sometime, all these big-picture issues will have to
be addressed. What the ABL needs is a better TV deal, which it
can't survive long-term without, especially when the WNBA is a
juggernaut with NBA money behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a miracle we're still here,'' ABL chief operating
officer Jim Weyermann said Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held off the greatest army in the world, the NBA, on just
bread and water. I think it's unbelievable. One day, everyone will
be able to look back at this as a real inspiration. The ABL
survived against all odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell about all that. For now, the Reign is off and
running. Basketball fans might just want to pack the house every
night.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-09-98 0217EST &QL; 
