<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0314 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-REIGN-SANJOSE-SPI     11-09 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-REIGN-SANJOSE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REIGN SETS SCORING RECORD IN HOME-OPENING ROMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Kate Starbird hasn't seen the movie ``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Reign's second-year guard, who came into the American
Basketball League from Stanford with considerable hype, put on a
scoring show at Mercer Arena Sunday night that resembled some of
those mythical ``Pleasantville'' players who made just about every
shot they attempted.
</P>
<P>
   Starbird had the feeling Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   She played the lead role in the Reign's home opener, matching
her career best with 25 points as the Reign made 34 of its 70 shots
in a record-breaking 106-86 victory over the San Jose Lasers before
a near-sellout crowd of 4,306.
</P>
<P>
   The Reign set a single-game franchise scoring record.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that we had so much fun out there,'' Starbird
said. ``The most fun in a long time. The most fun game since I've
been here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reign, the league's worst team last season, won its second
straight, and it was a dominating performance.
</P>
<P>
   With four starters scoring in double figures, the Reign built a
17-point halftime lead, 50-33. Then its only ragged stretch of the
game cost the Reign more than half of its lead in the third
quarter. But Kate Paye's 3-pointer pushed an eight-point lead back
to 11 near the end of the quarter, and San Jose (1-1) never got
closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle played with a lot of energy and adrenaline,'' Lasers
coach Angela Beck said. ``The big crowd and opening night really
helped them and we didn't answer the call. They controlled the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Starbird, who scored all nine of her points against the Colorado
Xplosion in the third quarter Friday night in Denver, had 11 in the
third quarter Sunday to help repel the Lasers' effort to catchup.
</P>
<P>
   But the Reign produced too much firepower from the inside and
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Starbird's torrid 9-for-13 shooting, center Val Whiting
scored 21 points and guard Niesa Johnson contributed 22 points, six
assists and four steals.
</P>
<P>
   A double-digit lead most of the way enabled Reign coach Tammy
Holder to play her entire roster. All 10 Reign players saw action
and nine scored.
</P>
<P>
   Starbird was in a comfort zone most of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way I like to play, an up-tempo game,'' she said.
``Up and down the court. That is more my game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of game that made her the college player of the
year at Stanford two years ago, when she averaged 20.9 points a
game. And the year before that, leading the Cardinal with a 20.9
average.
</P>
<P>
   An offense last season that stressed a half-court system
resulted in Starbird scoring 12.9 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a 25-point game at Long Beach, Calif., last November,
Starbird struggled while trying to fit into a controlled offensive
attack.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't adjust well. So the Reign did something to help.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a quick and clever point guard, was signed after the
Long Beach team folded and already is making the Reign a better
team. She penetrates, draws a crowd and dishes to a open teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a player like her last season,'' Starbird said.
``When she drives, they have to collapse and she kicks the ball
out. I was getting some wide open shots (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson didn't pass, she was getting hammered.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said after the Colorado game that either she had to slow
down and not surprise teammates with passes or wait until the front
line became more accustomed to her style.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson made just three of her eight shots, she
converted 15 of 18 free throws and reduced her turnovers from eight
in the regular-season opener to just three on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She utilizes what the team does well and adjusts quickly,''
said Holder of the third-year guard. ``We talked about having
better distribution and more scoring opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise for the Reign this season is that it hasn't
had to rely on the scoring of all-star forward Shalonda Enis, who
scored 11 points Sunday after a career-low 4 against the Xplosion.
</P>
<P>
   Holder isn't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we depended on (Enis) to do everything,'' Holder
said. ``This year, we have a more balanced attack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
