</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-ECONOMY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDURAN ECONOMY SWAMPED AFTER MITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT COLLIER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    LA CEIBA, Honduras _ Across the broad, fertile valleys of
northern Honduras, the banana republic has been given a wet,
violent burial.
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the Ulua to the Aguan rivers, the vast Chiquita and Dole
plantations have been almost totally destroyed by Hurricane Mitch,
which swept through the region more than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The waters unleashed by Mitch finally receded over the weekend,
leaving mud, destruction and the stench of decaying banana plants
for miles and miles.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras' huge banana industry _ which exports about $200
million worth of fruit annually, most of it destined for breakfast
tables throughout the eastern and central United States _ is
unlikely to resume production until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For a nation that depends on agriculture for nearly 30 percent
of its gross domestic product, it is a severe blow.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction has been replicated throughout Honduras, ranging
from prosperous shrimp farms on the Pacific Coast to the small
patches of stony mountain land on which hundreds of thousands of
peasants eke out a bare subsistence.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated 70 percent of the nation's crops washed away
or killed just before the annual harvest, analysts are asking how
Honduras will feed its people _ generous international food aid
will be required until next year's harvest _ and whether the
hurricane will leave the country any wiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mitch showed our vulnerability and poor management of our
natural resources,'' said Efrain Diaz, an agricultural expert with
the United Nations in Tegucigalpa, the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will force us to rethink the whole way the country's
agriculture and settlement patterns are structured. . . . It should
be the turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz and other experts say that although the hurricane was of
unprecedented ferocity, the damage was exacerbated by
deforestation, the absence of soil-conservation techniques and the
concentration of intensive, mechanized export farming in fertile
floodplains.
</P>
<P>
   But the experts and agribusiness leaders have reached no
consensus on how to reform the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we learn from this disaster, but I'm not sure we
will,'' said Jose Herrero, one of Honduras' top environmentalists
and president of the La Ceiba-based Cuero y Salado Foundation,
which works to protect rivers and estuaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must pay more attention to the delicate balance of
agriculture and a fragile ecosystem, rather than simply expecting
that modern, mechanized agriculture can combine with desperately
poor farmers in a way that won't make Mother Nature strike back.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-owned Chiquita and Dole say flood damage to their
plantations may be as much as $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Because the roots of banana plants die if they remain under
water for more than 48 hours, about three-quarters of the firms'
production has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras, which gave birth to the term ``banana republic,'' has
now been left without bananas.
</P>
<P>
   Similar damage is reported for the banana industries in
neighboring Guatemala and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is by far the worst damage to our operations since we
started in Honduras 100 years ago,'' said Francisco Romero, deputy
director at the headquarters of Standard Fruit Co., the parent
company of Dole, in La Ceiba, on the Caribbean coast.
</P>
<P>
   Chiquita announced Friday that it would lay off 7,782 workers _
nearly its entire field workforce _ and Romero said Sunday that
Standard Fruit will lay off most of its 8,000 field workers for at
least several months.
</P>
<P>
   Although Honduras has diversified its economy in recent years,
becoming less dependent on bananas, the losses are both devastating
and symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   Since Chiquita and Dole established huge banana plantations in
Honduras a century ago, the two companies have wielded a big stick
in the country's politics. They have made and unmade governments,
installed and deposed dictators, and frequently called in the army
to repress strikes by banana workers.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, it was said that the country's generals
alternated between favoring Chiquita and Dole, choosing presidents
loyal to one firm or the other depending on which one gave the
bigger ``donations'' that year.
</P>
<P>
   As democracy has taken root in recent years, the two
agribusiness giants have worked to soften their image. Their wages
now start at $170 per month, plus benefits, far above the national
average.
</P>
<P>
   Since the hurricane, both firms have carried out aggressive
relief operations, using their fleets of helicopters and boats in
search-and-rescue operations across the flooded plains, and sending
bulldozers, trucks and hundreds of employees to repair roads,
rebuild levees and distribute millions of dollars' worth of food.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Honduras, private agribusiness firms have carried
out what amounts to a sudden switch to charity work _ highly
unusual in Latin America, where corporations and the wealthy
generally shun philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   In the flooded plains by the Gulf of Fonseca, on Honduras'
Pacific coast, large shrimp and melon growers have flown in tons of
food aid to stranded rural dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   Company owners admit the relief work is mainly a
public-relations strategy at the beginning of what is sure to be a
long period of economic crisis and public discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is for people to gain hope from
seeing planes carrying aid in the sky,'' said Hector Corrales,
president of the Association of Shrimp Farmers in the southern city
of Choluteca.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our help won't be enough and may not reach them, but hope is
the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For many of Honduras' downtrodden workers and peasants, however,
the new corporate philanthropy means little.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a situation like this, we're just out of luck,'' said Juan
Carlos Molina, a banana union leader in La Ceiba. ``The workers
wind up carrying all of the burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're screwed by the government, then we get blindsided by the
hurricane, then the company lays us all off. We're always the
losers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
