A0489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     11-09 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Nov. 15.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The Djinn in the Nightingale's Eye: Five Fairy Stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By A.S. Byatt. Vintage International, $12.
</P>
<P>
   These fairy tales may be full of magic and quests, but they're
also spun from contemporary cloth as they explore the lives of
characters who feel imprisoned by their prescribed fate. ``Byatt is
a storyteller who could keep a sultan on the edge of his throne for
a thousand and one nights,'' Nancy Willard wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hunting Mister Heartbreak: A Discovery of America &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jonathan Raban. Vintage Departures, $13.
</P>
<P>
   This English author displays a quirky eye and restless energy in
his account of a two-year odyssey to American locales as varied as
Alabama, Seattle and New York, where he indulges in a full-scale
cultural deconstruction of Macy's department store. ``In an era of
jet tourism, he remains a traveler-adventurer in the tradition of
... Robert Louis Stevenson,'' Justin Kaplan wrote in these pages in
1991. ``He has a gift for vivid observation, description, anecdote
and personal encounter.''  &UR; Soft City &LR;  (Harvill, $12), an earlier
book by Raban that has just been restored to print, is both a sharp
portrait of London and its comfortable middle-class young in the
1970's and a spirited defense of urban life. ```Soft City' shows
how, in the midst of physical decay, a city can flourish by
fulfilling an elemental human need, the need to play out fantasies
of self,'' Richard Sennett said here in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Iliad &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Homer. Translated by Robert Fagles. Penguin, $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   This translation of Homer's tale of the Trojan War is marked by
free, cadenced lines and simple, direct language that resembles
real speech. ``His narrative has real pace, it presses onward,
leading the reader forward with an irresistible flow,'' Oliver
Taplin wrote here of Fagles in 1990. ``His version is imbued with
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Impeachment: A Handbook &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles L. Black Jr. Yale University, $6.95.
</P>
<P>
   In a guide written during the Watergate era but reissued in the
lengthening shadow of the Clinton impeachment hearings, a
constitutional scholar stresses the need for caution and common
sense as he outlines the process for removing a president from
office. In 1974 our reviewer, Mary Ellen Gale, called this an
``elegantly written, lucid, intelligent and comprehensive
handbook.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Springs of Affection: Stories of Dublin &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Maeve Brennan. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $13.
</P>
<P>
   These 21 tales by a former writer for The New Yorker who died in
1993 dwell on the small joys, hurts and unrealized dreams tucked
away in the red-brick houses of a single Dublin neighborhood.
``Brennan's book is full of small miracles presented in elegant but
simple prose,'' Jay Parini wrote in the Book Review last year. The
narrator of  &UR; An Irish Eye &LR; , by John Hawkes (Penguin, $11.95), is a
13-year-old orphan whose bizarre adventures include a romance with
an aging World War I veteran and enslavement by the mistress of a
manor house. In 1997 our reviewer, Liam Callanan, called this novel
``an engaging blend of genres and literary traditions ... that
ultimately becomes a kind of post-modern picaresque.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; My Brother &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jamaica Kincaid. Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $10.
</P>
<P>
   In reconstructing her brother's life and his death from AIDS in
their native Antigua, Kincaid refuses to romanticize her story,
choosing instead to follow the circular flow of her memory to
portray death as it really is, not as we might prefer it to be. The
result is ``a sustained meditation on the grinding wheel of family,
with mother always at the hub; on the countries of our past, both
real and emotional, which we have fled and in which we have felt
like strangers,'' Anna Quindlen wrote here in 1997. In  &UR; Daughter of
the Queen of Sheba &LR; , by Jacki Lyden (Penguin, $12.95), a National
Public Radio correspondent recalls growing up in the Midwest as the
daughter of a manic-depressive woman whose delusional behavior was
dazzlingly bold and exotic. Last year in these pages, Caroline
Knapp said Lyden succeeds in ``vividly capturing both the horror of
her mother's illness and the seductive, transporting power of her
insanity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dreams of My Russian Summers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Andre Makine. Translated by Geoffrey Strachan. Scribner,
$7.99.
</P>
<P>
   This French novel by a Russian emigree tells of how a remarkable
woman with a dual allegiance to her French past and her Russian
destiny endows her grandson with a sensibility that enables him to
endure life in the Soviet Union. ``Makine employs a highly poetic
voice to blend memory and imagination,'' Victor Brombert wrote here
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Planet Quest: The Epic Discovery of Alien Solar Systems &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ken Croswell. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $14.
</P>
<P>
   The history of extrasolar planetary astronomy is one of
frustration and false promises, but advances in the 1990s have
turned the field into an exciting growth industry. ```Planet Quest'
is of no practical use whatever ... but it is fascinating and
worthwhile nonetheless,'' John Durant wrote in these pages in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Leave It to Me &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Bharati Mukherjee. Fawcett Columbine, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   The heroine of this raucous road novel is a misfit adoptee who
sets off from Schenectady, N.Y., to California on a vengeful (and
ultimately lethal) quest for her true parents. She is ``a brilliant
creation -- hilarious, horribly knowing and even more horribly
oblivious,'' Lorna Sage wrote here last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
