<HEADLINE>
BESTSELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Nov. 15.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated bestseller list for paperback
books. Please see BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list and where
the book stood the previous week.) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Oct. 31,
1998, at almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000
other retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all
such outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of non-fiction can change from week to week,
reflecting changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE MACGREGOR GROOMS, by Nora Roberts. (Silhouette,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A patriarch takes steps to get his three
</P>
<P>
   stubbornly single grandsons married.
</P>
<P>
   2. CAT &AMP; MOUSE, by James Patterson. (Warner, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Alex Cross contends with two serial killers determined
</P>
<P>
   to take his life.
</P>
<P>
   3. TOM CLANCY'S POWER PLAYS: RUTHLESS. COM, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Martin Greenberg. (Berkley, $7.99.) America
</P>
<P>
   is imperiled by computer-based terrorism in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   4. DIVINE SECRETS OF THE YA-YA SISTERHOOD, by Rebecca Wells.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Perennial, $13.50.) Three generations of
</P>
<P>
   Southern women.
</P>
<P>
   5. WHAT LOOKS LIKE CRAZY ON AN ORDINARY DAY..., by Pearl
</P>
<P>
   Cleage. (Avon, $12.) Returning to her rustic hometown, a
</P>
<P>
   woman finds many changes since she left -- and romance.
</P>
<P>
   6. MIDWIVES, by Chris Bohijalian. (Vintage, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   Trouble, legal and moral, haunts a midwife who may have
</P>
<P>
   killed a woman while trying to save the baby's life.
</P>
<P>
   7. BELOVED, by Toni Morrison. (Plume, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Memories of her past haunt an escaped slave in
</P>
<P>
   post-Civil War Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   8. COLD MOUNTAIN, by Charles Frazier. (Vintage, $13.) A wounded
</P>
<P>
   Confederate soldier journey's home toward the end of the Civil
</P>
<P>
   War to meet and old love and a new world.
</P>
<P>
   9. HOMECOMING, by Belva Plain. (Dell, $6.99.) Members
</P>
<P>
   of an estranged family gather at the grandmother's
</P>
<P>
   estate at Christmastime.
</P>
<P>
   10. ONE TRUE THING, by Anna Quindlen. (Dell, $6.99.) A
</P>
<P>
   woman who cared for her fatally ill mother is charged
</P>
<P>
   with killing her.
</P>
<P>
   11. DECEPTION ON HIS MIND, by Elizabeth George. (Bantam,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) Probing the murder of a respected Asian resident
</P>
<P>
   of a British town.
</P>
<P>
   12. LITTLE ALTARS EVERYWHERE, by Rebecca Wells. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Perennial, $13.) An account of earlier experiences of
</P>
<P>
   members of the Ya-Ya sisterhood, first published in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE NOTEBOOK, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner Vision, $5.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A World War II veteran meets an old flame who is
</P>
<P>
   about to be married.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) THE ELUSIVE FLAME, by Kathleen E. Woodiwiss.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14.) An artist, destitue in Georgian London,
</P>
<P>
   manages to return to her native America.
</P>
<P>
   15. SERVANT OF THE BONES, by Anne Rice. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A dark angel seeking redemption journeys
</P>
<P>
   from Babylon to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NON-FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger. (Harper Paperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a
</P>
<P>
   crew of fishermen from Gloucester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley and
</P>
<P>
   William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis of the lives
</P>
<P>
   of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist's account of his ascent on Mount Everest
</P>
<P>
   in 1996, the deadliest season in history.
</P>
<P>
   5. ADVENTURES OF A PSYCHIC, by Sylvia Browne and Antoinette
</P>
<P>
   May. (Hay House, $12.95.) A psychic tells her life story.
</P>
<P>
   6. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) A celebration of life in the
</P>
<P>
   Italian countryside by an American poet.
</P>
<P>
   7. ALL OVER BUT THE SHOUTIN', by Rick Bragg. (Vintage,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) From poor white in Alabama to Pulitzer Prize-winning
</P>
<P>
   reporter: a memoir.
</P>
<P>
   8. CITIZEN SOLDIERS, by Stephen E. Ambrose. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $16.) The U.S. Army, from Normandy to Germany's
</P>
<P>
   surrender.
</P>
<P>
   9. A CIVIL ACTION, by Jonathan Harr. (Vintage, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit brought by Massachusetts householders against
</P>
<P>
   industrial polluters.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE VIRTUES OF AGING, by Jimmy Carter. (Library
</P>
<P>
   of Contemporary Thought/Ballantine, $9.95.) Reflections
</P>
<P>
   on the problems and rewarding opportunities of old age
</P>
<P>
   by the former president.
</P>
<P>
   11. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography
</P>
<P>
   of a man who survived his mother's abuse.
</P>
<P>
   12. INTO THE WILD, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of a young man whose obsession
</P>
<P>
   with the wilderness had a tragic end in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) THE COLOR OF WATER, by James McBride. (Riverhead, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A black writer and musician recalls his experiences growing
</P>
<P>
   up with his white mother in a Brooklyn, N.Y., housing project.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) ANATOMY OF THE SPIRIT, by Caroline Myss. (Three Rivers,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) Holistic medicine. (b).
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) CLIVE CUSSLER AND DIRK PITT REVEALED, by Clive Cussler
</P>
<P>
   and Craig Dirgo. (Pocket, $7.99.) The life and work of the
</P>
<P>
   author of many popular adventure stories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO, AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $6.50.) Ways to lose weight and achieve a healthy body.
(b)
</P>
<P>
   2. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE TEENAGE SOUL, II compiled by Jack
</P>
<P>
   Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen and Kimberly Kirberger.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspirational stories. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. PROTEIN POWER, by Michael R. Eades and Mary Dan Eades.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $6.50.) Two physicians offer a protein-rich, low-
</P>
<P>
   carbohydrate plan for losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   4. DON'T SWEAT THE SMALL STUFF ... AND IT'S ALL SMALL STUFF,
</P>
<P>
   by Richard Carlson. (Hyperion, $8.95.) How to enjoy life
</P>
<P>
   more and contribute to the world we live in. (b)
