<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Post-election picture of U.S. is (as usual) out of
focus
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elections are family reunions after a fashion, and the
obligatory snapshot from last week's catches the clan in its usual
disarray, complete with a scowling uncle or two, some perky moms
and a couple of kids blurry because they couldn't sit still. (Isn't
that Newty running off?)
</P>
<P>
   What the picture doesn't show is the family forming up to go
marching off on some great political toot, eternally the hope in
some of our more lurid ideological precincts. Rather, it finds us,
as usual, having things a bit of both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Movement conservatives can take at least small heart from a few
outcomes. Alaskans and Hawaiians voted to forbid gay marriage.
Whether that's constitutional is iffy as a matter of extruded legal
theory, but the political message is blunt enough. Gay rights
groups might do well to settle, for now, for trying to put full
legal parity into place for unmarried couples who apply for it. At
least potentially, that's saleable by an appeal to the electorate's
innate sense of fair play, without exciting the psychosocial alarms
the word ``marriage `` sets off.
</P>
<P>
   And Washington state, alas, killed affirmative action, voting to
put ``those people'' back in their place. If whites are to be kept
from misusing their majoritarian muscle to spike minority progress
state by state, affirmative action supporters will have to make
their case anew. Forgetful white folks need to be reminded why it
is in their own interests to keep affirmative action going until
black and Hispanic middle classes have had time to put a little
sustaining capital under themselves and don't depend only on
fragile incomes.
</P>
<P>
   The election displayed a nation with a surprising number of
progressive impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in two states enacted firm campaign-funding reforms, and
the two senators most associated with that effort nationally _ John
McCain, R-Ariz., and Russ Feingold, D-Wisc. _ were re-elected,
Feingold against a well-heeled opponent while himself shunning the
special-interest money he has been fighting to take out of play.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional pooh-bahs who dismiss funding reform as the
preoccupation of a meddlesome fringe will have a hard time
pretending next year that the issue died for all time when they
buried it this year. The mummy walks.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in three more states approved the medicinal _ it sez here
_ use of marijuana, legally dubious but interesting. Are policies
that refuse to make major legal and social distinctions between pot
and more dangerous drugs breaking down under the weight of a
generation that knows better?
</P>
<P>
   Resort to hackneyed right-wing wedge issues _ the gun-grabbers
are coming, gays are gonna get you, baby-killer abortionists are
after your daughter _ repelled voters in most races that featured
them. Has the religious right run its course? Ralph Reed, late of
the Christian Coalition, flopped like an out-of-tune diva in his
debut as a candidate consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's 1998 portrait shows that every second candidate was
not, as their opponents' commercials shrieked, ``too liberal for
(fill in the name of your state).'' And pictures, unlike political
ads, don't lie.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
