<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: In a French town, the meaning of Veterans Day
 &HT;    (For release Nov. 11, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today is Veterans Day, which means for most Americans that the
courts are closed and there is no mail delivery. In many areas,
schools are closed as well.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a youngster, the day was called Armistice Day. On the
11th of November at precisely 11 a.m., everything stopped for a
minute or two in remembrance of the horror that was World War I.
That was the day and time the armistice was signed ending what they
erroneously called the War to End All Wars.
</P>
<P>
   Then came World War II and the Korean War, and there were
millions more veterans to remember. In 1954, Congress changed the
name of the day to Veterans Day.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where we are.
</P>
<P>
   When I stress that the principal message today is that courts
and schools are closed and there is no mail, I say it with
considerable rancor. The observances of the real meaning of the day
that honors the men and women who served this country are too few.
I often wonder how many of those who benefit from the free day
observe its significance.
</P>
<P>
   It is a day of solemnity because even those who returned intact
from those wars gave what likely were the best years of their lives
in service to our country.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I think of Veterans Day, I cannot help but recall the
lady just above the beaches of Normandy, where the great invasion
took place in 1944. We like to say that the French never
appreciated our sacrifices in the two wars on their soil, but I am
one who does not accept that.
</P>
<P>
   And that's because of the lady.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the Seventies, I made what was, for me, a pilgrimage
to Omaha Beach. While I am not a veteran of World War II _ I served
during the Korean War _ I felt, and still do, that what happened in
Normandy on June 6, 1944 was the turning point of world history.
Those beaches, and the American cemetery above it, are consecrated
land. (If you saw ``Saving Private Ryan,'' you'll better
understand.)
</P>
<P>
   I stood on the same beach where those thousands of American dead
and wounded piled up years earlier and stared out to the sea. There
was a heavy fog that early morning and the mournful sound of an
unseen ship's horn completed a most melancholy, tearful moment
</P>
<P>
   Finally at grips with myself, I trudged, with my wife, above the
dunes and onto the streets of the little town of St. Laurent. To my
surprise, there were crossed French and American flags hanging from
all the lampposts _ and this was not on a day of particular
remembrance. It was just an ordinary summer day in a small French
seaside town where no longer were heard the ghastly sounds of
gunfire and human despair.
</P>
<P>
   The first person my wife and I encountered was a middle-aged
woman selling fruits and vegetables from a basket beneath one of
the lampposts. Thirsty, but not speaking much French, I pointed to
an orange in her basket. She offered it to me and I reached into my
pocket and offered, in turn, a selection of the French coins I had.
</P>
<P>
   She looked to my hand, then to my eyes. ``Americain?'' she
asked. ``Oui,'' I responded, not expecting what was to come next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Non!'' she reacted, clasping my other hand around the orange,
then closing my hand with the coins. She would not take my money
but I could have her orange.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell me the French don't remember us fondly. Not when I
can still recall that lady and those crossed flags.
</P>
<P>
   The moment was a Veterans Day in itself, far more meaningful
than a day off work, or no school. While I wasn't one of those who
fought their way off the beach and into St. Laurent, I was, in her
eyes, their representative at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   And I appreciated it. And I will never forget _ not her, not the
moment, not the meaning.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
