<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-COSMOS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE ELECTION OVER, IT'S BACK TO EXPANDING THE UNIVERSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has the last election analyst finally spoken? I hope so, because
you and I have much bigger fish to fry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The non-election news is that the universe seems to be not
simply expanding but doing so at an ever-growing rate. And what
Albert Einstein once called the worst blunder of his career _ his
proposal that there's a repulsive force that acts against gravity _
may turn out to be true after all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, I know that when I say a ``repulsive force,'' many of you
immediately think of Saddam Hussein or Jesse Helms and others. But
that's not it at all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I'm talking about some kind of bizarre source of energy
in the cosmos that seems to want to expand the vacuum between
planets and other celestial bodies, thus pushing them farther
apart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest news about all this strangeness comes from two teams
of astronomers who announced their findings at a recent workshop on
supernovas (which, like members of several old rock bands, are
dying stars) at the University of Chicago's Enrico Fermi Institute.
(No, Fermi was a scientist, not the old second baseman for the
Cubs. You're thinking, instead, of Emil Verban.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These scientists wrote up their findings in a recent issue of
``Science News,'' which you'll usually find at your grocery store
checkout counter between ``Bladder News'' and ``Skin Diseases
Gazette.'' Unless, instead, I'm thinking of ``Road Kill Gourmet
Digest.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, these astronomy teams (Do they have second basemen? I
don't know.) have been studying the brightness of distant, exploded
stars as a way of determining whether the universe is expanding,
contracting or static. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, no. That's not quite right. Everyone pretty much already
knows the universe is expanding. The question is whether there's
enough mass (and, therefore, gravity) in it to make it eventually
quit expanding and remain static or, eons from now, start to
collapse back in on itself the way old rock stars often do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The debate about which way the universe finally will go has been
going on for years, and some days the expansion proponents seem to
be winning while on others the contraction advocates seem to gain
the upper hand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have a personal policy against rooting for either side on the
theory that they're both wrong (along with the static folks). I
know it seems to be a logical impossibility that all of them could
be wrong, but amateur astronomers like me are allowed a fair amount
of latitude. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So the most recent study of the brightness of supernovas
indicates that we have what these two astronomy teams call ``an
accelerating universe.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, a forever-accelerating universe isn't exactly what
scientists have been expecting, so the astronomy teams who are
proposing this have been checking their work, looking for ways they
might be misreading the data. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found no systematic errors that could explain why it
is that it looks like we have an accelerating universe,'' says team
member Saul Perlmutter of the Lawrence Berkeley National
Laboratory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, you can bet the critics _ including the folks who don't
believe a word about the alleged Big Bang that supposedly
kick-started the universe some 13 billion years ago _ will be all
over this data, trying to figure out why it's wrong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I sort of hope the universe really is accelerating and that it's
at least partly due to Einstein's repulsive force. I know it's just
a personal bias, but I tend to think that guys with wacky-looking
hair are right more often than they're wrong. Well, except for Don
King and Ted Koppel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
