 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2497 - November 9, 1998   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2497 -- Nov. 9, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. TALES OF THE URBAN LEGEND The housewife who microwaved her
cat is just one of a host of urban legends. These stories have been
spread for decades by word-of-mouth (and now on the Internet,) and
rely on the use of what anthropologists call FOAF (friend of a
friend.) This article examines the sources of urban legends and
explains why they persist. By Katherine Lee. 1,000 words + photo.
____________________________________________________________ 2.
SHINTARO ISHIHARA INTERVIEW The Japanese politician Shintaro
Ishihara, 66, is one of the most prominent advocates of so-called
Asian values, along with Prime Minister Mohamad Mahathir of
Malaysia. Like Mahathir, he sees a Western (read U.S.) conspiracy
behind much of Asia's recent financial woes. Ishihara, a
nationalist and former LDP member of parliament, says in a
best-selling book, ``Declaration of War,'' that Americans used
their financial institutions to seek Japan's economic enslavement
after they were unable to compete with its manufacturers : tough
charges from a hard-nosed politician. From Der Spiegel. 700 words.
Q&AMP;A format. (English translation available.)
____________________________________________________________ 3. FOR
SPORTS FANS, MURDOCH TRUMPS DISNEY Sports is the ``battering ram''
of Rupert Murdoch's campaign for global media dominance. His latest
deal marks a triumph for Fox Sports Net TV against his rival
media-entertainment mogul, Michael Eisner, whose company, Disney,
owns ABC and ESPN. By Alan Deutschman. From The New York Times
Magazine. 2,000 words.
___________________________________________________________ 4. BE
CAREFUL WHAT YOU SAY ABOUT YOUR PLANTS -- THEY
</P>
<P>
   MAY BE LISTENING! Plants really do love music and respond to the
human voice. What's more, scientists now say they can smell, taste,
feel and even ``see.'' They use these abilities to protect
themselves from insects and from other plants trying to block out
their sunlight. They can also warn each other about impending
danger. Researchers want to learn more about plants' natural
defences and apply these secrets to commercial agriculture. From
Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. (English translation available.)
____________________________________________________________ 5.
HORSE SENSE The racing columnist, author and world-renowned
handicapper Andrew Beyer has found a way to make the odds work -
for himself as well as his many international followers. By Linda
Greenhouse. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length article
(3,100 words) and edited version available. 6. LICENSE TO KILL :
OSAMA BIN LADEN'S DECLARATION OF JIHAD A little-noticed declaration
of jihad by Osama bin Laden in an Arabic newspaper underscores the
Islamist's main grievance : infidel U.S. troops in Arabia. By
Bernard Lewis. From Foreign Affairs magazine. 1,500 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
WHAT'S DOING IN HAWAII Events, sightseeing, hotels and restaurants
in Hawaii. By Jocelyn Fujii. From The New York Times Way to Go!
1,500 words + photos + map.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
PINOCHET IN EXILE ``These past weeks,'' writes Tomas Eloy Martinez,
``I've been trying to step into Agosto Pinochet's shoes, trying to
figure out what must be going on inside him. ... The nastiest thing
Pinochet must be feeling right now is his total incomprehension of
why he was arrested. To his way of thinking, he didn't do anything
wrong : the blood, the exiles, the brute force, all those were
``necessary actions.''1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 9. A
WINE SNOB? MOI? Fine wine is a carefully crafted product that
deserves some appreciation. And it is a complicated subject; not
because wine snobs make it such, but because of the immense number
of grapes, places, vintages and styles of wine. Fareed Zakaria
gives a spirited defence of the wine snob. From Slate. 900 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 10.
VACATIONING AT HOME Family vacations are terrific - but not
hassle-free. However we all need a break and we love those
wonderful family vacation memories. We can do it all - by
vacationing at home. Here are some ideas on how to do just that. By
Kathy Sena. 600 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 11.
HELP YOUR BABY UP TO THE PLATE Is your baby ready for solids?
Follow the advice in this article for a smooth introduction to
first foods. By Hilory Wagner. From Child magazine. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 12.
BRAIN - THANK YOU FOR THE MUSIC Researchers in Hong Kong report
that music training in childhood may have long-term positive
effects on verbal, but not visual, memory. By Sara Abdulla. From
Nature News Service. 300 words. (N/A France and Spain. Embargo:
1800 GMT Wednesday, Nov. 11)
