<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make sure special feast doesn't lay a big egg
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For folks who don't often cook or are more used to
zapping the night's dinner in the microwave, Thanksgiving dinner
for kinfolks can be a traumatic experience. After all, those who
know you best are in the audience, and you are pretty sure a major
flop or success will be the topic of conversation in your family
for months to come.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, the traditional Thanksgiving meal is an easy one to
cook. And the Internet's World Wide Web offers plenty of help with
recipes and suggestions, even with ideas about what to do with all
the leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the obvious _ that Thanksgiving turkey. You
needn't search the many Web sites that offer tips for preparing
what has become the main entree for most families on the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   All you need to do is point your browser to http://www
</P>
<P>
   .butterball.com and you'll find more information than any human
needs to know about turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion is to click the link for the 10 Steps to a Picture
Perfect Turkey (or go directly to http://www.butterball.com/fall
</P>
<P>
   /10steps.html). We are talking detailed step-by-step directions
here, the kind of information that would let a man from Mars do a
terrific job roasting a turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a lot more to Thanksgiving than the turkey. In
fact, some of the side dishes are more likely to give you trouble
than the relatively foolproof turkey that you buy.
</P>
<P>
   And you'll need more than cooking directions. You may need some
ideas on specific dishes to prepare. That's where the next page
comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Go to Jgourmet'sThanksgiving Recipe Index at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .jgourmet.com/featured
</P>
<P>
   /thanksgiving/index.html and you'll find a feast of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a Thanksgiving turkey without a good stuffing
isn't really fitting holiday table fare. But most of us make
stuffings only a couple of times a year, so a little outside help
can come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive stuffing
</P>
<P>
   Your guests are almost certain to be impressed with the trendy
Corn Bread Stuffing with Sage, Sun-dried Tomatoes and Sausage that
you can prepare from a recipe on this page.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for a classy side dish, try the Carrots with Ginger and
Honey recipe. It's easy and quick to prepare _ and yet is something
a bit different for your holiday table.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us consider Thanksgiving to be the start of the holiday
party season. So it's likely you'll have guests dropping in during
the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   While most of them won't be there for the family dinner, you
will want something festive to serve. That's the value of the
Thanksgiving cookie recipes that you'll find at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .cookierecipe.com/cat
</P>
<P>
   /thanksgiving.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you prepare a big batch, because these cookies also
make nice gifts to leave behind when you visit others.
</P>
<P>
   There is no use tap-dancing around the next issue. We are all
mature people, and it's time to discuss the problem rationally.
Leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us end up with more turkey than we can eat. And after a
day or so of turkey sandwiches, the turkey problem becomes
pressing.
</P>
<P>
   There's a page that offers help: Wen's Thanksgiving 1997
Leftover Recipe Page at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.ultranet.com/(tilde)kaleidos
</P>
<P>
   /leftover.shtml. Don't get thrown by the 1997 in the title.
</P>
<P>
   After all, these are leftovers. And the art of making something
enticing using leftover turkey has not changed greatly over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the recipes you'll want to try is the one for Turkey, Corn
and Sweet Potato Soup. It adds a touch of Southwestern cuisine to
your leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
