<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Influential list spotlights Georgians
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than one-fifth of the people named in Digital South's
recent list of the 50 most influential people in Southern
technology are Georgians.
</P>
<P>
   Among those named are, of course, Charles Brewer, chairman and
chief executive, and Mike McQuary, president and chief operating
officer, of MindSpring. Also named is Bert Ellis, founder of
rapidly growing iXL Holding. Others named include Cam Lanier,
chairman of ITC Holding Co. ITC Holding provided much of the
capital that helped launch Internet provider MindSpring. Boland
Jones, founder of Premiere Technologies, and Relevant Knowledge's
Jeff Levy and Tim Cobb were also named.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shortage of advice about what PC to buy and the
latest guiding hand is provided by the current issue of ``Computers
Made Easy,'' a special quarterly issue of FamilyCircle and PC World
magazines. Among the magazine's recommendations are Dell's
Dimension XPS R400, the Mircon Millennia 400 Max and the IBM Aptiva
E5D. All of these models are in the $2,000 range. For computer
systems for $1,500 or less, the magazine recommends Compaq's
Presario 5150, the HP Pavilion 6330 and the CyberMax PowerMax H1,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Halloween has come and gone but LucasArts has released a new
computer CD game featuring a macabre character named Manny
Calavera. He's a skeletal looking guy in a white tux and he stars
in ``Grim Fandango.'' It's a role-playing game in which, as Manny,
you try to solve a variety of conspiracies in the Land of the Dead.
The CD features a score of Swing-era Bebop and Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Is no board game safe from computerization? Not if Hasbro
Interactive is involved. Its latest game is ``Girl Talk.'' Players
join an all-girl club. It's a role-playing game in which girls can
pick new identities and chat with computer generated characters.
Designed for girls age 8 through 12, ``Girl Talk'' retails for
about $30. It's available only for computers with Windows 95 or
later operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Quicken.com, one of the biggest online financial sites, has
added several more features in the past two weeks. Among them is
portfolio analysis, which helps consumers understand their
financial holdings in context. It includes pie charts and risk
return characteristics. Another new feature is stock search, which
lets users find stocks based on criteria they set. And then there's
stock evaluator. It lets users compare stocks and evaluate them
based on fundamental measures. You'll find this site at
http://www.quicken.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
