<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer ghost defies readers' explanations
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All Hallow's Eve has come and gone, I'm gorged with
candy scarfed up before those annoying little trick-or-treaters
could get it, and the ghost still resides in my computer, turning
it on at midnight every night.
</P>
<P>
   Since I reported this phenomenon, I've received several kindly
suggestions from readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your article suggests that you may have Norton Utilities
installed since you considered whether to call Norton or
Ghostbusters,'' one reader began. ``Norton may be the better
choice. These utilities have the ability to do things for you all
by themselves at a preset time _ which, of course, would include
turning on the computer if it is so capable. See whether that's
your problem.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not, because I'm waiting for the latest version of Norton
to install. Additionally, some guy named Peter Norton sent me a
message suggesting Ghostbusters would be the better choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is your computer is not shutting down but going into
a sleep, suspend or standby mode and wakes up at midnight because
of Microsoft task scheduler,'' wrote another reader. ``It comes
with Internet Explorer 4.0 and also with Windows 98. It does
periodic tasks such as defrag and scandisk when the computer is
idle for a period of time or on a regular schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   No luck. The computer's not sleeping, and I have neither
Explorer nor Windows 98 installed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I too noticed my computer coming on at odd hours even though I
had put it in rest mode,'' reports a third reader. ``I began
noticing that the computer only came on after my using the
telephone (the modem is connected to the same line). Perhaps, your
son's use of your wife's computer triggered yours to come on after
he went online _ that is if both computers use the same telephone
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Two computers are indeed using the same line, but mine is turned
off, not suspended or rested, and I can see no connection between
online activity and the machine coming on.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two possibilities to your problem. ... You may have
a problem with power management. Both the BIOS and Win 95 have
settings for this and sometimes they conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second takes an explanation. It might have something to do
with a new standard called Desktop Management Interface or DMI. DMI
is a tool for administrators of a network to get more productivity
out of a workstation. DMI allows a PC to be turned on a few minutes
before an employee arrives at work, thus saving valuable time lost
while booting the PC. DMI also monitors whether the cover has been
removed from the system and is used to track network activity.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't detect any conflicts in power management, and if I have
something called DMI on my computer I cannot find any trace of it.
If I did, I would swiftly expunge it. What kind of sweatshop wants
a computer to come on automatically a few minutes before John Q.
Public comes to work so he doesn't waste the company's valuable
time booting it up? Talk about Big Brother.
</P>
<P>
   The best, however, came in last.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was with great surprise that I read your article on Sunday,
10/25/98, and learned that I am not the only person with a computer
that cuts on at midnight! If you should ever find the reason, I
would be most interested. Shutting off the power seems to be the
only solution. Thanks!''
</P>
<P>
   You see? They're all around us. But the truth is in there
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
