<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Several sites trying to make sense of Microsoft trial
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The real trouble with the Microsoft trial is there is
no smoking gun, bloody glove, ransom note or tape recording to help
onlookers come down firmly on one side or the other of the Justice
Department's suit against the software monolith.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates has always been the man computer
geeks love to hate, but the trial is filled with ``he said, she
said'' charges and countercharges. For the totally confused and the
merely curious, many Web sites are keeping an eye on the suit and
trying to make some sense of it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no entity is following the trial closer than Microsoft
itself. The Microsoft Web site (http://www.microsoft.com) has a
special section titled ``Microsoft and the DOJ: What's Your
Opinion?'' Here, Microsoft makes clever use of media coverage of
the trial. Instead of attempting to defend itself via its public
relations department, the company shrewdly turns to pro-Microsoft
articles that have appeared in major newspapers such as The
Washington Post, The New York Times and The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   The most ironic section of the Microsoft site is titled
``Microsoft and the Freedom to Innovate.'' This section asks people
who won't earn in a lifetime what Gates made in the last half-hour
to write their elected officials about Microsoft's plight. It's
another interesting turn in a trial filled with ironies,
contradictions and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   There is also day-by-day trial coverage, but reader beware: The
trial coverage is unsigned, and therefore it's unclear if Microsoft
or a news organization is the author. The place for unabridged,
direct testimony is the Department of Justice Web site at
http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   /atr/cases/msindex.htm.
</P>
<P>
   The DOJ site also has a list of exhibits and Gates' testimony.
The forms are all in PDF format and must be downloaded to be read.
The Justice Department also invites users to e-mail comments on the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   One suggestion for the DOJ might be to publish some of the trial
documents so visitors can read them without downloading anything.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dry court documents and Microsoft's own defense
page, a number of journalists are working to make sense of the
trial. Michael Lewis provides color commentary for
subscription-only Slate, but his daily dispatches are also
available free of charge from the MSNBC site
(http://www.msnbc.com). MSNBC is also chock-full of all kinds of
information relating to the case, from daily reports to video, and
even a quick check of Microsoft stock prices. MSNBC Editor in Chief
Merrill Brown firmly states that the Web site, a joint venture
between Microsoft and MSNBC, is completely impartial in its
coverage of the trial. ``It's not an issue,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Business Week Online (http://www.businessweek.com) has partnered
with Court TV, an excellent way to attack the legal and business
sides of this complicated case. Susan Garland, Business Week's
Justice Department correspondent, reports on the trial in a clean,
uncomplicated style you don't need an MBA or a law degree to
understand. Garland and fellow Business Week columnist Mike France
also champion opposing sides in the commentary section. It's a
clever way to deconstruct the courtroom action, but also
illustrates the Microsoft glass at the moment is either half-empty
or half-full, depending on how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S NEW
</P>
<P>
   John Glenn Page: Check in here for everything you ever wanted to
know about the venerable Glenn, his shuttle mission, courtesy of
NASA.
</P>
<P>
   http://shuttle.nasa.gov/future/sts95/glenn.html
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Space Center: A flashy, well-organized home page telling
the story of U.S. manned space exploration from its humble
beginnings to the latest shuttle mission.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ksc.nasa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   FEMA.GOV: Federal Emergency Management Agency: If you're in the
middle of a natural disaster and your connection is somehow still
holding, this is the place to be. Although information for the
simply curious and calm browser can be somewhat buried, there are
many valuable and interesting pages to see.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.fema.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
