</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New crop of station wagons offers versatility, style, space
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Station wagons reached their glory days in the 1950s,
but decades earlier, they were conceived to fetch the elite from
the train station to a hotel or spa and provide adequate space in
the rear to carry everything from overnight case to steamer trunk.
</P>
<P>
   This was when those grand vehicles were clad in real wood. Even
today when an auto enthusiasts gets the chance to inspect a well
restored ``woody,'' it is a pure pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   But by the late '60s and early '70s, the station wagon had
become an icon of suburbia, and not always a flattering one. The
ugly image was parodied in the Chevy Chase movie ``Vacation,''
where the family car was a bizarre conglomeration of vehicles
painted a ghastly army green. The color fit; the station wagon had
become almost military.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, there's a new crop of wagons. The niche was
nearing extinction _ except for the popular Volvo wagon _ until
European manufacturers opted to give the concept an injection of
youth and vitality.
</P>
<P>
   European drivers love station wagons. Just like Americans, they
have lots to carry. But they don't have lots of road space. The
natural solution is a station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   There is a buffet of wagons in the marketplace. Looking for
elegance, luxury and style? Check out the Mercedes E320.
Resplendent with every option, including all-wheel drive, it can
take on the tasks of any highway sport-utility vehicle and still
fit under the portico at the country club.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a bit more of a traditionalist, Volvo offers wagons
in a variety of configurations from turbo-charged to all-wheel
drive, leather to sunroofs.
</P>
<P>
   If you need the space, but deep down you want a sports car, Audi
has a new Avant. If the Audi A4 is a sports car with a back seat,
then the Avant is a sports car with a back seat and a backpack.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with a $34,000 sticker price, but its corporate cousin,
the Volkswagen Passat GLS, offers most all of the same amenities
and performance in an almost nearly as attractive package at about
$23,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do these wagons offer great performance, handling and
style, they give superior fuel economy to sport-utilities and
better insurance rates as well. And it doesn't hurt a bit that they
are really cool cars.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers. Her
column is written exclusively for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net
</P>
