<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ham radio brings out the adolescent squeal in me
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the first time in nearly two years, I hooked my
ham radio station up to an antenna and _ in just seconds _ I was 13
years old again.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a licensed ham radio operator _ KQ4YA _ but because I lived
in apartments for the last three years, putting up an antenna
capable of transmitting wasn't practical. I recently bought a home
and moved in last week. Long before the pictures were hung, I had a
temporary antenna in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Ham radio has been a hobby, off and on, since I was 13 years
old. And each time I throw the switch and listen to the voices from
far away fade in and out of the static, I remember how my hands
used to tremble as I tuned my original radio station _ an old
Hallicrafters SX-99 receiver and a Healthkit transmitter. Both
companies are gone now and my ham radio now is a transceiver,
combining the functions of a transmitter and receiver, all in a
black box that isn't much bigger than a breadbox (if you're old
enough to remember what that is).
</P>
<P>
   But the thrill of ham radio doesn't depend on the type of radio
you use. The airwaves are one of the few parts of my world that
don't seem changed in modern and confusing ways. It's still very
much _ as I tune the bands _ like walking through a tropical forest
filled with birds. There are birdlike squeaks and squawks as I tune
past stations. And there are voices from around the world, other
amateur radio operators having conversations using an old
technology that hasn't changed markedly since the days of Marconi.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a particularly shy man, but it took me nearly half an
hour before I tried actually answering another station. But there
was a radio operator in Kentucky and, as I listened, he talked
about his job as a newspaper publisher. So I hit the transmit
button and called him _ sending my voice out over the air using
about the same amount of power it would take to illuminate a single
light bulb.
</P>
<P>
   I know it probably sounds crazy if you _ like me _ casually send
e-mail to acquaintances all over the world using the Internet, but
when that ham just a few states away answered my call it seemed
like magic that all of that was possible. And I was a tongue-tied
13-year-old again, babbling about the new house and the fact that I
hadn't been on the air in years.
</P>
<P>
   Each time I write a column about ham radio I wonder if I'm
whistling in the wind. A lot of people don't even know what we are,
confusing ham radio operators with CB radio enthusiasts of the
``good buddy'' variety. After all, there are only 600,000 licensed
amateur radio operators in the entire nation, so it's not strange
there's so much confusion about what we do and what the hobby is
about.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur radio surely isn't trendy. You're unlikely to impress
anyone at a party when you tell them about your new Yaseu FT-990
transceiver. Nor will crowds gather when you pull out a card
confirming a radio contact with a station in Bosnia. The way the
Internet bridges distances at the push of a button has taken away
some of the drama of talking to people in foreign lands. And the
ease of making a cellular phone call makes wireless communication
seem mundane.
</P>
<P>
   But we are not dealing with logic or even with something
practical now. Instead, I am talking about the magic of walking
into your spare bedroom and fishing out the voices of strangers
from the static. I am talking about the pure drama of hearing a
station in some distant country come back to you. And unlike on the
Net, you'll hear their voices and even _ in some cases _ literally
hear the background sound of the family dog barking in a parlor in
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Ham radio isn't for everyone. But I am surprised, each time I
write about it, to find there is still a heart tug for many that
hasn't been lost in the static.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to learn more about the hobby, point that
newfangled Web browser of yours to the home page of the American
Radio Relay League at http://www.arrl.org. That's the best-known
organization for U.S. ham operators. You'll find complete
information about licensing and the hobby itself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
