<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Passing NOx test often can be complex
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The term ``I/M'' test, commonly referred to as the
emissions test, really stands for ``inspection of maintenance.''
</P>
<P>
   Tailpipe gases measured during the test are just the end result
and verification of the maintenance a vehicle has received. You
should have found this to be true in the past two years when it
came your turn to test.
</P>
<P>
   If your vehicle received regularly scheduled maintenance
recommended by the manufacturer, it passed with flying colors. Even
the older or high-mileage well-maintained vehicles fared well.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, vehicles that had been neglected in upkeep
were rewarded with failed inspection of maintenance results. Their
owners were given the opportunity to spend all of their ``saved''
maintenance money and more on repairs necessary to get their cars
to pass, or at least waivered. It all boiled down to: ``If you want
to pass the test, you have to do the homework.''
</P>
<P>
   While the new I/M test being performed on older vehicles still
monitors maintenance, it also exposes problems in systems that have
no set maintenance schedules. The test for oxides of nitrogen _ or
NOx, the prime contributor to ground-level ozone _ has little to do
with how often you change your oil or your spark plugs. In fact,
your engine could be purring like a kitten and still fail the test
for NOx.
</P>
<P>
   NOx repair is a whole new ballgame for most mechanics. Although
the vehicle's emission control systems designed to control NOx have
been around since the mid-'70s, the old ``stationary vehicle''
testing techniques couldn't measure it.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the output of NOx is rarely related to
driveability. In fact, many older vehicles actually ran better when
the systems weren't working. Therefore, many systems long ago quit
working or have been disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors can contribute to NOx production, not all as
simple as repairing one system. There is a delicate balance
involved when correcting one problem but not creating another.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I talked about the $200 repair/waiver limit that many
people think is the maximum they need to spend to get their cars
patched up to get new tags. It's not, but many drivers whose cars
fail the test seem to think it is.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, NOx failure is not cheap. Verifying that a car's
emissions problems have been solved involves sophisticated _ and
expensive _ equipment.
</P>
<P>
   I know of several shops where the driveability/emission repair
mechanics are some of the best in the business. Their credentials
and training records are impeccable, and the shop has an admirable
repair track record. Most of the vehicles coming into the shop are
older, but the shop is not doing NOx-related emission failure
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   They could repair the cause of the failure with relative
certainty, but they do not have the equipment to verify the vehicle
will pass the emissions test when retested. For them, it doesn't
make sense to commit to an equipment investment of several thousand
dollars, when most of their customers expect to pay no more than
$200 for the repair.
</P>
<P>
   Those drivers, however, will find a way to get around the system
at minimal expense but without solving their car's problem or
helping to solve the ultimate problem, reducing pollution in metro
Atlanta. Less reputable shops can make repairs just good enough to
pass the test, and they will charge not much more than $200 for the
service.
</P>
<P>
   But finding anyone to fix cars _ and fix them right _ is getting
harder every day. It won't be long before the law of supply and
demand supersedes the law of the $200 waiver limit.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical Institute
and an ASE master automobile technician/L-1. Write her in care of
Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta,
GA 30302. Or send comments online to nora(at)admin2.dekalb.tec
</P>
<P>
   .ga.us or 2wrenchs(at) bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
