<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANK-LLOYD-PBS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBS offers story of Frank Lloyd Wright
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed until Nov. 10
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Frank Lloyd Wright'' Today and Wednesday at 9
p.m. PBS
</P>
<P>
   Revolutionary designs and a tumultuous life make Frank Lloyd
Wright one of the most intriguing figures of our time.
</P>
<P>
   A genius of towering intellect and towering ego, Wright designed
more than 800 buildings, including such breathtaking structures as
the Guggenheim Museum in New York and the legendary residence
Fallingwater in Pennsylvania. But his private life was marked by
scandal and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this overweening ego and soap opera of a private life
necessary in order to create great art?'' filmmaker Ken Burns mused
before TV critics when presenting his latest PBS offering, ``Frank
Lloyd Wright.'' ``It's something that always comes up when we study
the lives of great individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns' two-night, three-hour film lives up to the brilliance
we've come to expect of the man who gave us ``The Civil War,''
``Baseball'' and ``The Brooklyn Bridge,'' just to name a few. An
appropriate mix of life and architecture, the story is well told by
Burns and his long-time collaborator Lynn Novick, who shares
directing credit with him this time.
</P>
<P>
   Among the brilliant works by Wright that are highlighted in the
film are the architect's home and studio in Oak Park, Ill.; his
estate (Taliesin) and the Johnson Wax Building in Wisconson;
several of the trademark ``prairie houses'' and ``Usonian houses'';
the Imperial Hotel in Tokyo; and Taliesin West in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   When the camera flows through these buildings, lingering on
their exquisite lines and simplicity, the scenes are backed by the
music of Beethoven, Wright's favorite composer. The touch is subtle
and highly effective.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's influence on architecture at home and abroad was
profound, and Burns has taken great pains to point out the pros and
cons of this controversial artist. In the end, however, it is a
favorable but hardly fawning portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1867, Wright grew up with unhappily married parents. At
his mother's insistence, he studied architecture at the University
of Wisconsin until he dropped out to study with the great Chicago
architect Louis Sullivan. Claiming some of Sullivan's buildings on
his resume, Wright struck out on his own and, by 1900, had
established a successful practice, designing everything from homes
to synagogues to gas stations. A stickler for detail and control,
Wright insisted on designing everything in some of his houses,
including the dishes and napkin rings.
</P>
<P>
   As Burns points out, Wright lived beyond his means and rarely
met deadlines. But most of his clients loved him anyway. It was a
different story at home. In 1909 he left his wife and six children
for the wife of a married client. The scandal nearly ruined his
career, and he married twice more after similarly scandalous
affairs. Considered a has-been in his 50s, Wright founded a school
that, critics say, did little but exploit the young people who paid
for the privilege of working for him.
</P>
<P>
   The last two decades of Wright's life were his most prolific and
distinguished. He died in 1959 at the age of 91.
</P>
<P>
   Among those interviewed for the program are two of Wright's
sons, David and Eric Lloyd Wright, and Wright himself in audio and
video interviews. Especially telling is a self-absorbed, sometimes
haughty interview with Mike Wallace that aired on CBS. Compelling
commentary is supplied by architects and artists Philip Johnson,
Robert A.M. Stern and Maya Lin; writers Paul Goldberger and Brendan
Gill; biographer Meryle Secrest; and historian William Cronon.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway is the TV critic for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
