</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Americans have food prices to be grateful for
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This month, teachers will decorate their classrooms
with pictures of apples, pumpkins, nuts and other foods that
represent the end of the harvest. The cardboard cornucopia on the
bulletin board will remind young children to be grateful for this
country's abundant food supply.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these annual Thanksgiving rituals, we Americans remain
remarkably unappreciative of our highly efficient food growers, who
have drastically lowered the cost of eating. Waiting in the
checkout line, you'll hear a lot more griping about grocery bills
than expressions of appreciation for the low prices.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the truth? Are groceries getting cheaper, or are
consumers getting hit harder at the cash register?
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, both ``facts'' are true: Food has never been
cheaper, and Americans are spending more. The reason is that while
basic foods have gotten less expensive, our tastes have gotten more
extravagant.
</P>
<P>
   Beef provides a good example of falling food prices. The U.S.
Department of Agriculture says the average retail price for beef,
including all cuts, averaged $2.54 a pound in the first six months
of this year, down from $2.71 during the same period of 1997. The
National Cattlemen's Beef Association estimates that today, for
$10, a consumer could buy a pound of ground chuck, 1 1/4 pounds of
boneless top sirloin steak and 1 1/2 pounds of boneless chuck
shoulder steak, which would be enough meat to make dinner for a
family of four for three nights.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider what it takes to bring home that beef. The Bureau
of Labor Statistics says the average U.S. worker earns just under
$13 an hour. So even after taxes, it takes the average family man
just an hour of work to put meat on the table for three nights.
That is a fraction of the hours his grandfather had to toil to feed
beef to his children. During the Depression, families felt rich if
they could afford a small chicken for Sunday dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Think how much we will have to be grateful for at Thanksgiving
this year. Grocery stores in metro Atlanta already are running ads
offering name-brand turkeys for just 76 cents a pound. In other
words, the average Atlantan will work one hour to earn enough money
for a big, plucked turkey. Compare that with the hours one might
have spent a century ago to hunt, kill and clean a turkey for
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even though the price of beef, poultry, eggs, flour and
other simple foods has never been lower relative to work hours,
spending really is up. The Commerce Department reported last week
that consumer spending in September rose faster than incomes. That
meant shoppers had to reach into their savings or borrow money to
maintain their buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   So why are we spending so much? Because we aren't buying basics.
We are seeking out convenient foods that can be popped into the
microwave, as well as other products that make life easier or
better. But by choosing fancier foods and products, we are driving
up our shopping bills and encouraging manufacturers to give us
more.
</P>
<P>
   As part of this trend, Gillette Co. is introducing a toothbrush
with a rubberized handle and multicolored bristles. The price:
$4.99. Now when a shopper is rolling her cart down the dental care
aisle, she might grab four toothbrushes for her family. And that
will add $20 to her bill.
</P>
<P>
   Then she will complain about how ``groceries'' are getting more
expensive because of inflation. In reality, the only thing that has
been inflating is our desire for more convenience, style and
variety.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
