<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-SIDE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Riding the bus to prom? Don't make Cage puke
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Nicolas Cage had a traumatic high school
prom experience. Red-faced before they were famous Think you had it
tough as a kid? Consider the childhoods of these celebrities:
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Cage _ A not-so-rich kid attending the wealthy Beverly
Hills High School, Cage couldn't get girls to date him because it
meant riding the bus. When a beautiful girl agreed to go to the
prom, Cage cashed in a savings bond to rent a limosine. He was so
nervous though, that when he went to kiss her, he threw up. The
limo driver wouldn't let him back into the car because of the vomit
on his shoes and he had to walk home.
</P>
<P>
   Dolly Parton _ Parton grew up poor in Tennessee. When Dolly was
in grade school, her mother made a patchwork coat for her, tailored
from bright-colored scraps of material. Proud of the work of art,
Dolly couldn't wait to show off her coat at school. The kids
instead mocked her, saying it was nothing more than a bunch of
rags. She got the last laugh. Years later she turned the experience
into a song. Coat of Many Colors became her signature tune.
</P>
<P>
   J. Robert Oppenheimer _ A shy, sickly, intellectual kid, ``the
father of the atomic bomb'' was kidnapped at summer camp by fellow
campers and dragged to an icehouse, where he was stripped, beaten
and had his backside painted green.
</P>
<P>
   John Wayne _ Kids ridiculed Marion Morrison (his real name)
after he moved to California from Iowa because he was shy, skinny,
taller than the other boys and had a ``sissy name.'' They
repeatedly beat him up and called him ``little girl'' until he
filled out and began to play football.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
