</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHENKIDS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book offers look at celebrities as kids
 &HT;    WITH KIDS-SIDE
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The book ``When They Were Kids''
features hundreds of childhood anecdotes about celebrities such as
Dennis Rodman, Dolly Parton, Oprah Winfrey and Elvis Presley. Race
made difference for Burt YOUNG. One day, Reynolds was challenged by
the jocks to run a foot race against the best sprinter at Central
Junior High in West Palm Beach. Burt, running barefoot in front of
a crowd gathered at the football field, beat his opponent in the
last 5 yards. The result: He became a football player, lettered in
several sports. And everyone called him Buddy. The rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said in the book that while he'd like to think his success
was the result of luck and talent, he said it all might have worked
out differently for him if he hadn't won that foot race,'' Madigan
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's about as deep as the book strays into Freudian analysis.
(Yes, Sigmund Freud is here. He was the golden child of seven
offspring whose mother doted on him.) But Madigan said there are
some obvious personality traits that each notable displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of us are medically trained, but if I was playing
armchair psychologist, I'd say that all of the people in the book
had a lot of drive and ambition and success and a need to overcome
adversity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
