<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREIG10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kids can't catch up with idea of imitation mustard
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: My wise children don't believe there was
imitation mustard sold in the '50s. They say mustard is so
inexpensive, why would they make imitation? Your confirmation would
greatly be appreciated. _C.H.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Confirmed. But cost is not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Imitation mustard has always been with us _ even in the 1950s
when yellow mustard was about 20 cents a jar. Today, Rokeach
prepares it for those who love the flavor of mustard but cannot eat
mustard seed for religious or dietary reasons. Want to know more?
Contact the Mount Horeb Mustard Museum at (800) GET-MUST.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you furnish the address for C. Emily Feistritzer,
president of the National Center for Education Information? _Doris
J.
</P>
<P>
   A: This private research organization provides information on
alternative teacher certification. Write to Feistritzer at 4401
Connecticut Ave., NW, No. 212, Washington, D.C. 20008 or visit
www.ncei.com on the web.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During an episode of ``Law &AMP; Order,'' new assistant DA Abbie
Carmichael (Angie Harmon) quipped that her ``Longhorn pennant''
would look good on her boss' (Sam Waterston's) wall.
</P>
<P>
   Did I hear correctly? Was the Carmichael character written as a
University of Texas grad? _ Mark Weisman
</P>
<P>
   A: Always glad to help another ``Law &AMP; Order'' aficionado. (``In
the criminal justice system the people are represented by two
separate but equally important groups ...'') The Carmichael
character has been written to include a degree from the University
of Texas, verify the publicity folks for the popular show.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Harmon did not attend UT. Immediately after graduating
from Dallas' Highland Park High School, she hit New York City.
(Wouldn't you if, at the tender age of 15, you beat out 63,000
girls to win the national cover girl contest for Seventeen
magazine?)
</P>
<P>
   Q: My mom lost one eye to cancer and is having a great deal of
trouble with the other. She has just undergone her third laser
surgery and currently there is no improvement. She recently fell
again _ didn't see the curb, sprained her ankle, tore up both
knees.
</P>
<P>
   Where can I get information on seeing-eye dogs? I think she
needs far more help than a magnifying glass can provide. _Teri
Hurley
</P>
<P>
   A: Apparently the road to seeing-eye dogs is a long one _ in
both time and distance.
</P>
<P>
   The right dog has to be selected and trained with the person who
will be using the dog. Southwest Guide Dog Foundation in San
Antonio, at (210) 366-4081, is the only such school in Texas.
Training lasts about a month.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatives? Nancy Galloway, regional director with the Texas
Commission for the Blind (459-2544), suggests you call the
commission and ask for the ``counselor of the day.'' This
vocational rehabilitation counselor will visit with your mother,
find out what she feels she needs, and ``try to give her an
informed choice'' from among the variety of options available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For years I have looked for the clear plastic ``bubble''
umbrellas. They come down around your shoulders and block your head
from the wind and rain. Do they still make these? Where might I
order one? _Shannon R.
</P>
<P>
   A: The ultimate umbrella shop has these bubbles _ Uncle Sam
Umbrella Shop in New York. To order ($28 includes shipping), call
(212) 247-7163.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreigstatesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Due to
the number of inquiries, Jane cannot respond to every request.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Greig is a staff writer for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
