</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTTTOYS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A guide to the holiday season's hot toys
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS, LEGOROBOT
 &HT;    By Norma Martin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ 'Tis the season of Santa's elves: Kids are
making their wishes known. Parents are preparing to make their
purchases. Toy sellers are viewing their stock and checking it
twice, hoping to look in their retail crystal balls and learn the
answer to one of life's great mysteries:
</P>
<P>
   What will America's children beg for this year? What will be the
next Cabbage Patch doll or Power Rangers action figure or Tickle Me
Elmo sensation?
</P>
<P>
   For a hint at the frenzy that lies ahead, we turned to the
fun-masters who stock the toys.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the hottest toys will be _ surprise _ associated
with children's TV shows, such as Teletubbies or Blue's Clues. Of
course, there are the holiday sure-things: Barbie and Hot Wheels.
This year's Barbie wears a full-skirted, black velvety gown in her
annual holiday garb ($32.99), but for Barbie lovers who want a less
glamorous look, Harley-Davidson Barbie ($79.99) is out, complete
with faux leather attire and motorcycle helmet. This year's Hot
Wheels come with new race sets and a new, bigger vehicle that can
be taken apart and rebuilt into a monster-size vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest buzz is for a new fellow called Furby, a
winking, talking, giggling furry toy that costs $29.99.
</P>
<P>
   These toys are already selling, which is a good indication of
holiday heat. But for a hit toy to become a hot toy, it has to have
the buzz that turns into word of mouth that turns into sales, said
Jack Trout, a toy analyst with Trout and Partners, a marketing
strategy firm in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``People buy what other people are buying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, just because something is the fad toy of the season
doesn't mean anybody will want it next year. Just ask the makers of
the Cabbage Patch doll; the company eventually went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great ride up, just don't forget to get off at the
top,'' Trout said.
</P>
<P>
   However, some toys get a second chance. In Austin one of the
hottest items mentioned by merchants is retro: the yo-yo. But it's
a yo-yo for the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't your mother and daddy's yo-yo,'' said Jeff Hunt,
owner of KidGenius Toy Store in West Lake Hills.
</P>
<P>
   These are high-tech yo-yos, with ball bearings and clutches like
the Yomega X-Brain Yo-Yo ($9.25 and up) or the Pro Play 2000 Space
Yo-Yo ($4.95). These new high-tech yo-yos have viewable mechanical
parts and do everything but spin from the string by themselves.
Some yo-yos even cost $100.
</P>
<P>
   At Toy Joy in Central Austin, store manager Andi Miller
demonstrates a yo-yo that makes noises when it spins. It sounds
like a car crash. Then it sounds like lasers. It even sounds like
sirens. ``Yo-yos are going to be big this year,'' Miller said. ``I
think they'll be good stocking stuffers.''
</P>
<P>
   How are these early-shopping parents picking their holiday
surprises? Merchants say some are bringing their children in and
watching what they play with.
</P>
<P>
   At Over the Rainbow in West Austin, store manager Tish Martinez
said dolls will be big. The collectible Madame Alexander dolls
($69.95 and up) should do as well as the Corolle line that features
dolls ranging from lifelike infants to toddlers with all the
accessories. The newest is the Corolle Laughing Baby ($59.99), with
a soundtrack that sounds like a real infant.
</P>
<P>
   While baby dolls may appeal to younger children, parents of
young teens still can find something at the toy store. There are
robot-building kits, such as those by Robotix for $100, which
promises would-be engineers they can create a motorized dinosaur.
Or perhaps your teen would prefer the Rad Board, a skateboard with
a hinged front and back that transforms into a scooter ($69.99).
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, there's just too much high-tech under the
tree, and a parent has to opt for the tried and true.
</P>
<P>
   Trains are still a holiday favorite, Hunt said.
Remote-controlled train sets can start at $200. Younger children
can develop their love of trains with ones that run on wooden
tracks, such as those by Brio, which offers an eight-piece set for
$40.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something for everybody,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
