u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OZ-MEMORIES10-COX     11-09 1599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZ-MEMORIES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1939 movie still whisks its fans `somewhere over the rainbow'
 &HT;    By Julie Bookman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the young Judy Garland played Dorothy in ``The
Wizard of Oz,'' she couldn't have known she was making cinema
history _ that her movie would enchant generations to come, inspire
family traditions and evoke the strongest of memories.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine years after the original release, the digitally
spiffed-up film reopened in theaters across the country Friday, and
it's clear that Americans never tire of Dorothy's journey from
black-and-white to Technicolor.
</P>
<P>
   Take Wanda Vaughn, 37, of Riverdale. She figures she's seen the
film ``at least 150 times.'' Vaughn and her kids often sing ``We're
off to See the Wizard'' when they leave on a trip. And if a family
member does something dopey, he or she sings a few lines of ``If I
Only Had a Brain.''
</P>
<P>
   When the AJC asked readers for their memories of the movie, we
received about 200 calls _ many from folks who sang into the phone,
recited lines from the film, invited us to come see their ``Oz''
collections or told us the annual television broadcast of ``The
Wizard of Oz'' was among their most cherished childhood memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The annual Sunday night viewing on TV was every bit as
important to me as Christmas,'' said Mike Thompson, 39, of
Gainesville. ``The anticipation was unbelievable. We only had a
black-and-white TV, but my grandparents had a large color console.
So my parents would load me in the car, and we'd go over there.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us ate on TV trays while we watched. And you just
couldn't miss a minute, because it's all just one great scene after
another.''
</P>
<P>
   How to account for this movie's timeless appeal? Metro Atlantans
will tell you they love ``Oz'' because, because, because, because,
because ...
</P>
<P>
   The big screen
</P>
<P>
   BILLY JONES, 77, ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   I was at the Loew's Grand Theater for the very first showing of
``The Wizard of Oz,'' and I sat through it twice. I've been on the
Yellow Brick Road chasing down movie memorabilia ever since. I have
a fabulous collection of movie posters, plates, the original sheet
music, songbooks and much more.
</P>
<P>
   I've met Judy Garland, the Tin Man (Jack Haley) and Billie Burke
(Glinda the Good Witch) when she came to Rich's to sign books. I
met the Wicked Witch (Margaret Hamilton) when she was in Chastain
Park, and I fussed at her for being so mean and ugly to Dorothy.
</P>
<P>
   I flew to Las Vegas, where Debbie Reynolds showed me the Dorothy
dress she bought from MGM.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite part of the movie is when Judy sings ``Over the
Rainbow.'' When I go to the land of Oz, they're going to play that
at my funeral.
</P>
<P>
   A dime short
</P>
<P>
   FRANKIE DAVIDSON, 66, DECATUR
</P>
<P>
   I was in the first grade in Virginia when it first came out, and
it cost a dime to get in. I lost my dime at school, and so I
couldn't go see it and I cried all the way home.
</P>
<P>
   I did always feel sort of cheated, because I never did see it
until it came on TV. Now I can take my daughter and granddaughter
to see it on the big screen!
</P>
<P>
   Ham &AMP; cheese
</P>
<P>
   JANE GOODWIN, 45, LILBURN
</P>
<P>
   I had two sisters and one brother, and throughout the '60s we
had this one special night.
</P>
<P>
   My mother made ham and cheese sandwiches, wrapped in foil and
heated in the oven. It's the only time I ever remember having those
sandwiches. What a big treat to eat that supper on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Now we all live in different states, but when ``The Wizard of
Oz'' comes on, we call each other and say, ``Are the sandwiches in
the oven?''
</P>
<P>
   Flying monkeys
</P>
<P>
   DEBBIE AUTRY, 36, CALHOUN
</P>
<P>
   As a child growing up in Calhoun, I'd watch it with my younger
sister, Donna. She'd crawl in my lap and beg me to keep the flying
monkeys from getting her.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we are grown, she'll call me when the flying monkeys
appear, and we still talk each other through it, every time. I tell
her, ``Donna, those monkeys are not going to hurt you, and I would
never let anything hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Parallel lives
</P>
<P>
   JANIE C. WILLIAMS, 46, DECATUR
</P>
<P>
   I grew up in Atlanta and watched it every year on TV, always in
black and white.
</P>
<P>
   When I first saw it I was 5, and I thought that in some way
Dorothy's story paralleled my life. We had just got a little puppy.
And I was just going to kindergarten, out in the big world where I
would meet all sorts of different people, even some wicked people.
</P>
<P>
   But like Dorothy, I have to say it all ended up good.
</P>
<P>
   Lollipop Kids
</P>
<P>
   VIOLA JOHNSON, 39, SMYRNA
</P>
<P>
   I watched it every year as a kid in Baltimore. When Judy Garland
sang ``Over the Rainbow,'' I just wanted to be there with her.
</P>
<P>
   My niece and I always did the Lollipop Kids. She's moved around
over the years, but no matter where we both live, we still call
each other when it's on TV and imitate the Lollipop Kids over the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Stormy night
</P>
<P>
   PAM JOHNSON, 46, RIVERDALE
</P>
<P>
   I was 8 in 1960, and to my memory, this was the first time I saw
it. It was a stormy night, and we were watching it on our
black-and-white TV.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Wizard screamed at them to ``Go!'' and the Lion
ran down that long shiny hall and crashed through the glass, a
small living room window flew open and we all screamed and ran out
of the room. I'll never forget it.
</P>
<P>
   First snow
</P>
<P>
   MARIA PICO, 42, SANDY SPRINGS
</P>
<P>
   It's my fondest memory as a child in the early '60s. I grew up
on Long Island (N.Y.), and the first snow of the year came on the
night we watched it _ that happened about three years.
</P>
<P>
   I believed in the magic. I believed you watched ``The Wizard of
Oz'' and down came the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Answered prayers
</P>
<P>
   MARTHA SCHMIDT, 44, WOODSTOCK
</P>
<P>
   Being a preacher's kid in eastern Virginia, we always went to
church on Sunday nights, and the movie always came on on Sunday
night. Well, one year our prayers were answered because it snowed,
and church was canceled and we were able to finally watch ``The
Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   Purple Monkeys
</P>
<P>
   BILLY MURPHY, 40, PEACHTREE CITY
</P>
<P>
   We only had a black-and-white TV, but my older brother Bobby
went up the street to watch it on a friend's color set. During the
show he came running down the street to tell us the monkeys were
purple!
</P>
<P>
   I've probably watched it more than anyone else. I watched it so
much with my young daughter that the tape finally broke.
</P>
<P>
   Role model
</P>
<P>
   JERRY HAGERTY, 45, COBB COUNTY
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'60s there were no gay role models. I was around 11
or 12, and I just knew the Lion was my role model.
</P>
<P>
   He sings that he was born to be a sissy, he says he's just a
``dandy-lion'' and he uses a limp wrist.
</P>
<P>
   The movie told me it was OK to be gay. The Wizard told him he
didn't need to change because inside he was just as good as
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   There are other signs, too. There's the song, ``Come out, come
out, wherever you are,'' and the rainbow is a symbol of the gay
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The movie made me feel warm and fuzzy inside and helped me know
it was OK to be me. It's my all-time favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Real tears
</P>
<P>
   JOEY HUCKEBA, 44, CARROLLTON
</P>
<P>
   I always got really choked up when Dorothy said goodbye to the
Scarecrow. I would hide my tears or choke them back.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, I got to play the Scarecrow in a community
theater production. I drew on that real-life experience to play the
role, and I mustered up tears for every performance. Everybody told
me I was just as good as Ray Bolger.
</P>
<P>
   Oui, a misfit
</P>
<P>
   KNOX DEMMOND, 42, DEKALB COUNTY
</P>
<P>
   At Sandy Springs High School, I was in this group of theatrical
misfits. When I took French as an elective, the one thing I enjoyed
doing the most was translating the lines of the Wicked Witch of the
West: ``Je vous aurai, ma jolie, et votre petit chien, aussi!'''
</P>
<P>
   The Scarecrow's song has sort of been a theme of mine. I've
played it on the saxophone, and I've sung it under women's windows
to serenade them. It really works _ I've had the whole neighborhood
entranced.
</P>
<P>
   Ding, dong the witch is dead
</P>
<P>
   SHIRLEY BERRYHILL, 63, STONE MOUNTAIN
</P>
<P>
   My son Robert is a 36-year-old retarded young man. We watch it
every weekend, all weekend. He watched it five times last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When the witch melts, he dances around and cheers. It's Bobby's
favorite movie in the world. He's been watching it for 30 years,
and it's brought a lot of joy to his life that has been somewhat
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Their song
</P>
<P>
   LOUISE PRUITT, 75, LILBURN
</P>
<P>
   I was in my late teens in the Macon area and dating a very
special boy named Bill. On this one special night the song ``Over
the Rainbow'' came on his car radio _ and back then, a boy with a
car radio was really something.
</P>
<P>
   It became our song.
</P>
<P>
   To make a long story short, things didn't work out between us _
he went off to war and I married someone else. But I've always had
a special place in my heart for ``The Wizard of Oz'' because of
that memory and my connection with him.
</P>
<P>
   He never married. I visited his grave a couple weeks ago and I
stood there and hummed ``Over the Rainbow.''
</P>
<P>
   From the official Warner Brothers website:
</P>
<P>
   The Wizard of Oz made history by being the first movie to be
shown on commercial television annually. It first appeared on CBS
on Saturday, November 3, 1956, and last aired on Friday, May 8,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The film will still be shown on the Turner cable channels of
either Turner Classic Movies or Turner Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   Web address: http://www.thewizardofoz.com/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
