<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN10-COX     11-09 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Living, learning about diversity makes all the difference
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. _ Diversity is to be celebrated, I teach my
8th-graders. Differences make us interesting people to know.
Intellectually, they buy into it, but once in a while they ask some
tough questions. Questions for which I
</P>
<P>
   have no easy answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do people kill each other over religion?'' is always the
first one because they're learning about it in social studies. All
I can do is shrug and remind them of the comfort humans find in
similarities.
</P>
<P>
   How can I explain that all over the world people are being
murdered because they're a different race, or hail from the wrong
side of a border. Why do we kill for real estate? I've lived almost
65 years and I still can't figure that
</P>
<P>
   one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life isn't cheap,'' I remind them. ``This may well be the only
one we've got, so let's not blow it.'' Trite rhetoric for such a
serious question. I'm always ashamed because I have no answer. They
have the right to expect more from a teacher. Kids need examples -
so I try to explain diversity that way.
</P>
<P>
   I tell them about my old neighborhood and how I learned about
differences. I tell them about the Bruggemeyer family across the
street - a mother, father, two sons, and a dog named Skippy. And
how on gray winter Tuesday afternoons
</P>
<P>
   I'd watch Mrs. B. do the ironing on a padded board she'd prop on
two kitchen chair backs.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday mornings she'd scrub the kitchen floor and lay out
newspapers until it dried. Every evening at five she'd peel the
potatoes and put them in a pot of water on the back burner of her
Robertshaw gas stove. Then she'd make a
</P>
<P>
   cream sauce for the vegetables. Dinner was at six sharp. The
family always sat down with the first chime of the church bells at
Our Lady of Good Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Once, when my mom was out of town, I spent the night there and
in the early morning I heard Mr. B. in the bathroom, coughing. I'd
never heard anyone cough like that so I asked what was wrong.
That's how I learned about World War I and
</P>
<P>
   gas warfare. Mr. B. lived just long enough to see both of his
sons make it home from the next ``Great War.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sullivan lived next door to the Bruggemeyers. Whenever I'd
climb the stairs for a visit, she'd let me hold her life-size
Charley McCarthy dummy on my lap while I had cookies and juice.
</P>
<P>
   Next door to her lived the Sneiders - a young couple with a baby
named Tommy. Sometimes I got to hold Tommy on my lap. He was cute,
I remember, but I liked Mrs. Sullivan's dummy better - it didn't
wiggle.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Collister lived next to the Sneiders. Mr. Collister was a
streetcar motorman. They had beautiful flowers and the softest
grass I'd ever felt. They had a granddaughter named Kate who had
stopped growing when she was seven. That's how I learned about
diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Next door to them lived my best friend Carol. Her mom had a
wonderful smile. I hardly knew her dad. He was an eye doctor, and
early one morning he killed himself. That's how I learned about
funerals.
</P>
<P>
   Dickie Bartel lived on the corner. He was younger than I. His
mom was an artist. She died one winter. That's how I learned about
pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Tootie Wojahn, her mom and dad and two sisters lived around the
corner from the Bartels. Tootie's mom baked bread and sweet rolls
every Saturday morning. On school days I'd stop by for Tootie. I'd
get there early so I could watch Mrs. W. curl Tootie's silver-blond
hair with an iron that she heated on the stove. Just before the end
of the war, Tootie's oldest sister got married. There weren't
enough coupons to get special shoes for the wedding so she wore
</P>
<P>
   white bedroom slippers under her gown. My first wedding - and
somebody's dad asked me to dance.
</P>
<P>
   Two doors down lived the Donahue clan. Dr. Donahue, his wife,
and a slew of kids. That's how I learned about Catholics,
confession, and fish on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Kellys lived two houses down, the other way. ``Second-gear
Kelly,'' my mother called him because that was the only gear he
ever used on his '41 Ford. They had a mean little curly-haired dog
named Dandy that chased me the two
</P>
<P>
   blocks to school every morning, biting at my ankles. Mrs. Kelly
let me pick cherries from their back yard tree.
</P>
<P>
   In my old neighborhood I learned about birth defects - a lady
with a terrible limp and a deformed arm that she used to carry her
shopping basket on as she made her way to the corner market, and
another lady who was so clean her family
</P>
<P>
   had to use the toilet in the basement so they wouldn't dirty the
one upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``With understanding and knowledge we overcome our fears,'' I
tell my kids, ``so get out there and introduce yourself to someone
you've labeled `different' or
</P>
<P>
   `weird'. You'll learn something.'
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, some wiseguy stops by my desk after class and says,
``Hi, Ms. Schuett. I'm Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
