<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Tuesday, November 10, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ ATLANTA _ All Hallow's Eve has come and gone, I'm
gorged with candy scarfed up before those annoying little
trick-or-treaters could get it, and the ghost still resides in my
computer, turning it on at midnight every night. Since I reported
this phenomenon, I've received several kindly suggestions from
readers. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ The traditional Thanksgiving meal is an
easy one to cook. And the Internet's World Wide Web offers plenty
of help with recipes and suggestions, even with ideas about what to
do with all the leftovers. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ ATLANTA _ For the first time in nearly two years, I
hooked my ham radio station up to an antenna and _ in just seconds
_ I was 13 years old again. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ ATLANTA _ More than one-fifth of the people named
in Digital South's recent list of the 50 most influential people in
Southern technology are Georgians. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ OS 8.5, the latest version of the Apple
Computer operating system, represents another incremental step
forward for the Mac. By and large, OS 8.5 is a collection of small
but important tweaks. (Husted , Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates has always
been the man computer geeks love to hate, but the trial is filled
with ``he said, she said'' charges and countercharges. For the
totally confused and the merely curious, many Web sites are keeping
an eye on the suit and trying to make some sense of it. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ If you're one of the millions who didn't
see ``Titanic,'' the movie and didn't buy the video, the soundtrack
or the book, there's still at least one more chance to give money
to James Cameron this year. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   KRISTALL _ Sixty years ago the Holocaust began. On Nov. 9, 1938,
Nazi stormtroopers spread fear and terror across Germany,
vandalizing the homes and businesses of Jews, burning and looting
synagogues, desecrating cemeteries, brutalizing men, women and
children. The toll of the night's violence, which came to be known
as Kristallnacht, included 91 Jews killed, hundreds seriously
injured and thousands more humiliated and terrorized. This Monday,
a few of the survivors of Nazi tyranny share their memories of a
time gone mad during a program at The Temple, sponsored by the
Atlanta Jewish Federation. (Feinberg, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15-20.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VETS _ On the day before Veterans' Day, we talk with vets from
WWII-Korea. For 400,000 from WWII and many thousands from Korea,
this will be their last Veterans' Day. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-JAG-JOURNALISM _ TV series ``JAG'' does an episode about a
news network (ZNN, get it?) that broadcasts a story accusing the
U.S. military of using sarin nerve gas in the Gulf War against U.S.
scientists testing biological weapons for Iraq. As you might
expect, journalism fares none too well. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GREIG-COLUMN _ AUSTIN _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. My wise children don't
believe there was imitation mustard sold in the '50s. They say
mustard is so inexpensive, why would they make imitation? Your
confirmation would greatly be appreciated. (Grieg, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WHEN-KIDS _ Most of us only know famous figures because of the
extraordinary things they've done. Behind these achievements are
ordinary people with real childhoods. The new book ``When They Were
Kids'' explores the childhoods of more than 400 celebrities and
notables from history. (Houck, Palm Beach Post). WITH
ILLUSTRATIONS. 20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-SIDE _ Lists, quizzes and trivia about the childhoods of
famous people. Did you know Nicolas Cage threw up on his prom date
and had to hitch a ride home? Bill Gates claimed in the eleventh
grade that he'd be a millionaire by 30. Katharine Hepburn _ then
``Kathy'' _ called herself Jimmy and demanded to wear boys clothes
to school. (Palm Beach Post). 30-40. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-WRIGHT _ Ken Burns' two-part ``Frank Lloyd Wright'' starts
tonight on WGTV. It's a highly visual, highly intelligent detailed
profile (warts and all) that simply and effectively explains
Wright's legacy. (Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.5.
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
ETA: 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FRANK-LLOYD-PBS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Frank Lloyd Wright'' Today
and Wednesday at 9 p.m. PBS. Revolutionary designs and a tumultuous
life make Frank Lloyd Wright one of the most intriguing figures of
our time. (Holloway, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HOTTOYS _ A look at toys that are expected to be big sellers for
the holidays. (Norma, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
