<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PETE-WILSON (Sacramento, Calif.) _ For many California voters,
the election was about repudiating a Republican who wasn't on the
ballot: Gov. Pete Wilson. Wilson energized some wealthy and
well-organized opponents _ trade unions, Indian tribes and
teachers. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CONTRIBUTIONS (San Francisco) _ It's enough to pay the
annual salaries of 10,000 teachers, fuel the entire economy of
Micronesia for two years or build Bill Gates' pricey Seattle
mansion nine times over. Instead, the roughly half a billion
dollars raised for this year's California elections paid for nasty
TV ads, piles of glossy campaign mailers and an army of political
consultants _ at a spending rate that broke state records. By ERIN
McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-VETERAN (San Antonio) _ Roy Benavidez, 63, a retired master
sergeant in the Army's Special Forces, is in a San Antonio hospital
battling diabetes, anemia and a host of other illnesses. He hopes
to attend Veterans' Day ceremonies on Wednesday. By SIG
CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GRANDMOTHER-AUTHOR (Undated) _ Not long ago, while leaving a
store, Suzette Haden Elgin passed a group of boys. As she was
getting into her car, Elgin heard one of the teens say to his pals,
``Now that is what a grandmother is supposed to look like.'' Elgin,
author of ``The Grandmother Principles,'' remembers smiling to
herself. The teens were close, she said, but not quite right. Yes,
she had the requisite white hair and wrinkles, but she was wearing
slacks. By BARBARA KARKABI.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Look to the back yard to make holiday
wreaths. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LENOTRE-CHEF (Houston) _ At half-past five, Alain LeNotre is
taking a visitor through his family's 6-week-old culinary institute
when Patrick, his cousin, interrupts. Patrick, a celebrated chef,
speaks only French. ``He wants us to hear the bread sing,'' Alain
explains. Patrick cradles a baking sheet of baguettes so hot and
fresh that they do seem to sing their charms. Alain nods approval.
Patrick smiles and whisks them away. He has much to do before the
students descend. By CECILE HOLMES.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Now that advance boarding passes are a
relic, it's more important than ever for airline passengers to know
a good seat from a bad seat. There are differences _ even in the
same service class on the same plane. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CARIBBEAN (Undated) _ Mention the Caribbean to some
travelers, and the connotation is one enormous entity of similar
sun-drenched islands. But each island has a distinct personality.
Distinct appeal. Distinct topography. Even languages vary. Here are
island-by-island capsules detailing what makes each special. By
HARRY SHATTUCK and SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ How would you like to go
fishing with a guy who is a professional lie detector? You know
what that would mean? No more tall tales. No more stretching how
big the fish was, how many we caught, or where exactly we fished.
Most people are born honest, you know, but by the time they go
fishing, they usually get over it. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ ``By the year 2000, housewives
... will probably have a robot maid,'' an article in the New York
Times predicted in 1966. Little did they know there wouldn't be
housewives. This is an example of failed millennial predictions
collected in a little book called ``Uncle John's Indispensable
Guide to the Year 2000.'' By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEWS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The bloody demise of House
Speaker Newt Gingrich marks a wild reversal in the Capitol food
chain. When Gingrich decapitated the Democratic House leadership in
1989, a freshly resigned Speaker Jim Wright charged his executioner
with ``mindless cannibalism.'' Last week, Gingrich use the same
word to describe the half-dozen young Republican red-hots who
threatened to deny him their votes for re-election. By CHRISTOPHER
MATTHEWS.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Fifty years after the national
pollsters messed up in a big way, they are making the same kinds of
errors that gave polling a bad name in the Truman-Dewey race in
1948. To explain why they missed calling key races in 1998, they
trotted out alibis withered with age. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-METEOR (Beaumont, Texas) _ Our long national Newtmare
is over. Just two elections after leading the Revolution of '94,
the most dramatic takeover in modern American political history,
Newt Gingrich's career as House Speaker has fizzled out like a
meteorite plunging into the Okefenokee Swamp. And that's what
meteorites do. By THOMAS TASCHINGER.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PEACE (San Francisco) _ ``Democracy produces war'' may
sound like some Orwellian ``doublespeak,'' but that is the
predictable projection for ``Arab democracy,'' the oxymoronic
fantasy for repressive Arab regimes that is claimed will bring
peace to the Mideast, another reckless reach exceeding the
mediator's well-meaning grasp. By HALTON ADLER MANN.
</P>
