<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-SETBACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM SWEEPS AWAY GAINS OF A DECADE IN CENTRAL AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS AND RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ After enduring repressive civil wars,
military regimes, and corrupt governments, the little countries of
Central America finally started to savor the good life in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They tamed inflation and created jobs. They learned not to
rely on just one or two crops and the elixir of foreign aid. They
reined in armies and gave people a taste of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Then Hurricane Mitch barreled in, leveling houses, destroying
farms, and setting development back by years, if not decades.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This week, Nicaragua, El Salvador, Guatemala, and Honduras are
going about the task of rebuilding houses and roads, water mains,
and phone lines. But just as important, they are figuring out how
to tend to shattered families and mend fragile democracies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Nowhere are the problems more daunting than in Honduras, an
Ohio-sized country that has been sliced into independent
city-states separated by churning rivers the color of chocolate
milk.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; One out of every 1,000 Hondurans is dead or missing. One-fifth
of the population is displaced. Entire neighborhoods washed away,
and, as President Carlos Flores likes to say, ``it's easier to
count the number of bridges still standing than the ones that are
wrecked.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the wreckage has nothing to do with bricks and mortar.
In the capital, the energetic, well-liked mayor, Cesar Castellanos,
died in a helicopter crash Nov. 1 Castellanos, who called himself
``Fatty,'' was considered the likely next president.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Carlos Rivera, a businessman, stood amid the
whitewashed walls and red-tiled roofs of Tegucigalpa's historic
center. An earth-mover scooped up rocks and twisted metal that had
slammed into his mother-in-law's house as the Choluteca River rose
beyond its banks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Crystal chandeliers swung above his in-laws' mud-caked living
room. One wall had a hole wide enough for a powerboat. ``How does a
country start recovering from a mess like this?'' said Rivera,
whose family also lost a sporting-goods store.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Rivera graduated from Emerson College in Boston in the late
1980s, just as the Cold War was winding down and Honduras was
slipping away from Washington's powerful grip. Sensing the start of
an economic renaissance, Rivera opened three cigar shops in
Tegucigalpa. Throughout the city, other young Hondurans opened
restaurants, furniture stores, and boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; With money tight last week, Rivera had 5 percent of his usual
number of customers. It hardly mattered because there weren't many
cigars to sell; manufacturers didn't have gas for deliveries and
roads were impassable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In downtown Tegucigalpa, a gun-toting thief took advantage of
the turbulence and robbed Rivera's stepfather's delicatessen of
$2,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; And yet Rivera's family is lucky: None of their relatives were
injured as the hurricane stalled over Honduras for five days,
dumping as much rain as the country gets in a year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For decades, foreign corporations and the US government bought
and discarded Central American leaders like so many toy soldiers.
Until 1990, Honduras received $190 million in US aid per year _ a
straggering amount for a country that had fertile fields, good
ports, and fewer than 6 million people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; None of that mattered. Honduras was a staging ground for the
``contra'' war against Nicaragua's Sandinista government. The aid
has dropped steadily in the 1990s, to $30 million last year.
Honduras, which had relied on bananas and coffee, aggressively
started exporting melons, pineapples, and shrimp as well as
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In Nicaragua, meanwhile, many money-losing cotton fields were
plowed under and the country diversified to bananas, watermelons
and onions for export. From 1987 to 1997, agriculture in Nicaragua
has grown at an annual rate of 3.2 percent, according to the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In the northwest Nicaraguan town of Leon, Herman Pasillos had
been nurturing his sugar cane field, even whispering messages of
love and encouragement to the stalks. ``It's something I learned
from my grandfather, who was also a farmer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In less than one week _ the time it took Hurricane Mitch to
deluge the area with rain and start a mudslide from the Casita
volcano _ about half of Pasillo's 17-acre field was ruined.
Pasillo, 54, has to figure out how to feed his six children and
five grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Pasillo's problem will be the country's dilemma: How do you
start over when you have almost nothing?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In a leisurely conversation in Tegucigalpa on Thursday
afternoon, President Flores told Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston
about the complexities of rebuilding a country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; One of the most pressing problems is the lack of fuel to power
construction vehicles, buses, and water pumps, the president
explained. In order to bring in the fuel tankers, roads and bridges
must be repaired. But doing those repairs means using heavy
machinery, which requires fuel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It's a vicious circle,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Dr. Michael Collins, president of Caritas Christi in Boston,
saw the same phenomenon at a public hospital last week. The trauma
ward was filled with people with severe burns and head wounds. Two
children were bleeding profusely from hemorrhagic dengue fever _
something Collins had never seen outside of a medical textbook.
There was no medicine for a teenager doubled over with a kidney
stone; Collins gave the boy's mother $2 to buy painkillers at a
pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The hospital had a basic problem: no water for washing
doctor's hands, cleaning instruments, or laundering gowns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Mitch left something less palpable than damaged buildings and
mass graveyards: the peril of political instability in a region
that was just recovering from the damage caused by years of civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The danger is probably greatest in Nicaragua, which was ripped
apart by civil conflict from 1976 to 1990. Already, opponents
compare the government of President Arnoldo Aleman to the
dictatorship of Anastasio Somoza, which stole millions of dollars
in aid money after an earthquake hit Managua in 1972. So much money
vanished that Managua still has not been rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Relief workers say relations with the government are tense.
They have demanded assurances that donated food, clothes, and
medicines won't end up on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``We don't want to appear to exploit this situation,'' said an
opposition leader, former president Daniel Ortega, at his home.
``But I think the people are tired of this government's attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Catholic Church, not the government, will oversee efforts
to provide emergency shelter, clothing, and food, Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David L. Marcus reported from Tegucigalpa, Honduras, and
Richard Chacon reported from Managua, Nicaragua.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
