<HEADLINE>
GOODBYE, COLUMBUS _ FROM THE FIESTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone thought that Ohio State would have trouble winning the
national championship because of a team from Michigan. But who
would have thought that it would be Michigan State causing the
problems for the Buckeyes? Make that unranked Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   By posting a 28-24 victory over the Buckeyes in Columbus
Saturday, the Spartans caused several tremors in college football:
</P>
<P>
   _They knocked Ohio State from the No. 1 slot. It was the fourth
time since 1988 that an unranked team has upset a No. 1 team, and
the first time since Oct. 30, 1990, when Michigan State, again
unranked, upset No. 1 Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   _They all but eliminated the Buckeyes from consideration for the
national championship game in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _They probably knocked Notre Dame out of the Rose Bowl mix.
</P>
<P>
   _They ended any speculation about Ohio State quarterback Joe
Germaine possibly getting Heisman Trophy consideration.
</P>
<P>
   _They increased the national championship hopes for at least
five teams, all of which needed help and now have received it.
</P>
<P>
   _They put Ohio State in jeoprardy of getting shut out of the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in here with the attitude that we were the squirts in
the neighborhood who had to pick a fight with a bully,'' said
Michigan State coach Nick Saban, who now has the satisfaction of
spoiling not only Ohio State's season but Notre Dame's as well,
since the Spartans are the only team thus far to beat the Irish.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of national attention now is on Kansas State and
Tennessee, No. 1 in this week's polls (the Vols top the Associated
Press rankings, the Wildcats and Vols are tied in the coaches'
poll). There's also UCLA, and the looming presences of Florida and
Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Already the second-guessing has started in Columbus about Ohio
State coach John Cooper, whose record against Michigan _ one win in
10 years _ has haunted him.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate aftermath of the loss, Cooper was asked why, on
their next-to-last offensive series of the game and trailing by 12
points, the Buckeyes ran 12 consecutive plays on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's some really good second-guessing,'' said Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Tyson Walter had this response: ``I don't get
paid to think like that. I get paid to do what they tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Paid? Hmmmm. We know what he meant. At least we hope we do.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line for all of this is that unless there are some
major upsets in the next few weeks, Ohio State fans are going to
munch on roast Cooper as much as roast turkey over Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Safe and sorry
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The buzz from around the country over Boston College's near
upset of Notre Dame centered around the play selection in the final
series.  &UR; Mike Cloud &LR; . Mike Cloud. Mike Cloud. Just as the Eagles
did in their failed drive against Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Tom O'Brien  &LR; justifiably went with his best back. But it
could be argued that when a team is 3-5 and not expected to win,
one might take chances by throwing the ball, rolling out, or using
play-action, which would at least make the defense react.
</P>
<P>
   BC played it safe and lost, 31-26, which for the Eagles is
unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Big problems
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a shock: Syracuse lost a big game. When are the Orangemen
going to win a game when something is on the line? Saturday's loss
to West Virginia was almost predictable, not because West Virginia
was better but because West Virginia played better in a game it had
to win ... Say what you want about the softness of Wisconsin's
schedule, but the Badgers are taking care of business with a great
defense, which makes them dangerous. Saturday's 26-7 win over
Minnesota gives Wisconsin its best start in 97 years and basically
makes the winner of this week's game against Michigan the Big Ten's
Rose Bowl front-runner ... There's little question as to which the
best service academy team is this season. Air Force, the only team
in Division 1-A to score more than 30 points in every game, has
beaten Army and Navy, outscoring them by an 84-14 margin ... The
Southeastern Conference West is a mess. Arkansas and Mississippi
State are the only teams with fewer than three league losses ...
Pass defense has become an oxymoron at Washington. After Oregon
quarterback  &UR; Akili Smith  &LR; blitzed the Huskies for 442 yards in
Saturday's 27-22 victory, the total passing yards given up by the
Huskies in the last three games was a staggering 1,292 ... With
only UCLA and Washington State remaining, Washington is in danger
of its first losing season since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hookup 'Horns
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State showed that you can stop Texas running back
 &UR; Ricky Williams &LR; , &UR;  &LR; limiting him to 90 yards rushing, 114 below his
average. But the Longhorns, who are a solid 7-2, showed they can
beat you in another way, as quarterback  &UR; Major Applewhite  &LR; threw
for 408 yards and three touchdowns, one to Williams, in Texas's
37-34 win ... The bowl game we would love to see is UCLA vs. Notre
Dame. Considering the less-than-dazzling method with which both
teams have won games this year, such a meeting could go on forever.
Lowly Oregon State, which is now saddled with its 28th consecutive
losing season, had the Bruins all but beat half a dozen times
Saturday before UCLA came up with a wild 41-34 victory in the last
30 seconds ... Congratulations to Curry College and coach  &UR; Steve
Nelson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has taken a team coming off a winless season and
turned it into a six-win team.
</P>
</TEXT>
