<SLUG> BC-NIXON-PRECEDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT PRECEDENT TO CONSULT: NIXON IN 1974 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By the sixth day of the House Judiciary Committee's
impeachment debate during the summer of 1974, the weight of the
committee's task seemed to have sunk into its members' bones like
the fetid Washington humidity.
</P>
<P>
   They had already voted out three articles of impeachment against
President Richard M. Nixon. This extra exercise, assessing whether
Nixon should be removed from office for deliberately backdating a
huge and dubious tax deduction, seemed gratuitous to some,
including a peevish Trent Lott, who snapped, ``You may not like it,
but do you impeach a president for mere negligence in filing
personal income taxes?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet this debate, more punchy and angry than the solemn ones that
preceded it, could light a path that will lift the veil of
impeachment from another president, Bill Clinton. It turned on two
key legal issues facing the current Judiciary Committee: whether
the president must be impeached for breaking the law _ in Nixon's
case, the tax code _ and whether such a violation must bear on his
official, rather than personal, conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is scheduled to hear Monday from
constitutional specialists and to consider legal memos from its
members on what standards should be applied to Clinton. Many are
expected to draw on the one true precedent to this year's
impeachment effort: the '74 hearings.
</P>
<P>
   A Globe review of the transcripts and staff documents from the
Nixon impeachment battle reveals substantial evidence from both the
then-majority Democrats and the then-minority Republicans that
Clinton's most frequently cited offense, perjury, would not merit
impeachment under the '74 standards.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional standard of impeachment _ ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' _ is subject to multiple interpretations, and
critics of Clinton have long contended that a criminal violation by
a president merits removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1974, when a committee dominated by political opponents
of the president was called upon to set specific standards, it
pointedly rejected the notion that a violation of the law
automatically triggered impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The principal purpose of impeachment, the '74 committee decided,
was to remedy ``grave misconduct that so injures our constitutional
institutions and form of government as to justify impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The general applicability of the criminal law also makes it
inappropriate as a standard for a process applicable to a highly
specific situation such as removal of a president,'' asserted the
committee's majority report on standards of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the committee voted, impeachment should be limited to
a president's abuse of his official powers: ``In an impeachment
proceeding a president is called to account for abusing powers that
only a president possesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The minority report, prepared by the Republican staff for
members sympathetic to Nixon and reluctant to remove him from
office, suggested not only that Congress is not obliged to vote for
impeachment over an apparent criminal violation, but must exercise
``prosecutorial discretion'' and pursue only those offenses that
jeopardize the government. Even then, the Republicans contended,
Congress retains the power to ``waive or pardon'' the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Both reports set the stage for the '74 committee's bruising
debate over the articles of impeachment, conducted at first behind
closed doors and later in the full glare of television. Three
articles eventually emerged: one charging that Nixon personally
engineered the Watergate coverup, including the payment of hush
money; a second accusing the president of ordering the FBI and CIA
to investigate his political enemies; and a third citing his
refusal to respond to congressional subpoenas. A proposed article
dealing with the secret bombing of Cambodia was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the last proposed article, tied to Nixon's taxes,
that is most analogous to Clinton's alleged perjury. Just as
today's members must debate whether an offense arising from a
private lawsuit justifies impeachment, the '74 committee sifted the
arguments for removing Nixon over a serious tax violation.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Nixon's taxes had raised political hackles earlier
in the year: Nixon, seeking to reduce his tax burden almost to
nothing, tried to deduct hundreds of thousands of dollars for
donating a cache of official papers to a university. It was a
questionable tactic, but one that had allegedly been recommended to
him by his predecessor, Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Additional questions arose, however, when it was alleged that
the papers had not actually been given away before the tax
deadline, and that Nixon had knowingly fudged the date. It was one
of a string of questionable deductions claimed by Nixon, including
trying to write off the upkeep of his private vacation homes. In
all, Congress determined that Nixon underpaid his taxes by $432,000
plus interest.
</P>
<P>
   To partisan Democrats, like the populist Jack Brooks of Texas,
this seemed like an offense that struck home to millions of
Americans laboring under their own tax burdens.
</P>
<P>
   ``No man in America can be above the law,'' declared Brooks, a
personal friend of LBJ. ``It is our duty to establish now that
evidence of specific statutory crimes and constitutional violations
by the president of the United States will subject all presidents
now and in the future to impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet committee members quickly jumped on Brooks _ and the
critics, for the first time, included substantial numbers of the
heretofore unified Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Hogan of Maryland, a lawyerly Republican who had broken
with Nixon earlier, declared that the tax offense was improper
grist for the committee because it related to Nixon's private
affairs. Hogan quoted from the committee's report: ``As a technical
term, high crime signified a crime against the system of
government, not merely a serious crime. This element of injury to
the commonwealth, that is, to the state itself and to the
Constitution, was historically the criteria for distinguishing a
high crime or misdemeanor from an ordinary one.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley Mayne, a Republican from Iowa, whose narrow margin of
victory left him vulnerable to the anti-Nixon backlash, nonetheless
stood by the president: ``Even if criminal fraud had been proved,
and I think it clearly is not, then we would still have the
question of whether it is a high crime or misdemeanor sufficient to
impeach under the Constitution ... I certainly do not believe that
Madison and the framers of the Constitution had in mind any such
recital as we are hearing tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, many Democrats agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In a line that might have been scripted by one of Clinton's
defenders, Jerome R. Waldie of California _ a staunch Nixon
opponent _ nonetheless declared that impeachment must be reserved
for ``cases where there has been an enormous abuse'' of purely
presidential powers _ and the tax matter did not fit.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Owens of Utah, a former aide to the Kennedy brothers, also
decided that Nixon's alleged tax crimes were too minor: ``You don't
impeach for every offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Ray Thornton of Arkansas declared that an impeachment
inquiry ``is not a tax court or a criminal court nor should it
endeavor to become one.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee voted 26-12 against approving an article of
impeachment based on Nixon's alleged tax offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the '74 Judiciary Committee remain in Congress.
Lott is Senate majority leader. And one, William Cohen of Maine,
even serves in Clinton's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Most, including Hogan, Thornton, Waldie, and Owens, are long
forgotten in political circles, but this week, at least, their
words will ring forth like those of Madison, Hamilton, and
Jefferson _ in the mouths of Clinton's defenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
