<SLUG> BC-GUNS-ELECTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNS PROVE TO BE A LOADED ISSUE DURING ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like abortion and gay rights, guns are fast
becoming a wedge issue in electoral politics.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 campaigns, particularly on the East and West Coasts,
opposition to gun control was used in TV attack ads and even became
a litmus test for character in some of the most hotly contested
statewide races across the nation, political observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the fate of the ``Dangerous Dozen,'' a group identified
at the start of the campaign season by Sarah and Jim Brady as
hard-core gun-rights supporters. All were subject to attacks for
opposing measures such as the Brady bill and the assault-weapons
ban, and all but one lost his or her race.
</P>
<P>
   The group included Republican Senators Lauch Faircloth of North
Carolina and Alfonse D'Amato of New York, and gubernatorial
candidates Democratic Representative Glenn Poshard of Illinois,
California Republican Dan Lungren and Maryland Republican Ellen
Sauerbrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that guns are the number one issue in any race, but
that guns have become a baseline issue for winning candidates,''
said Robert Spitzer, author of ``The Politics of Gun Control.''
``What we're seeing is part of a long-term shift, where the
demographic base of support for guns is slowly disappearing, except
in the rural South and Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates read these losses as a sign that the tide
may be turning in their favor, particularly in statewide elections
where urban and suburban voters often outweigh rural voters. In
contrast, a wave of politicians friendly to the National Rifle
Association swept into Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, however, disputes the notion that support for gun
control is growing at the expense of gun rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pretty much where we were before. ... But at the state
level, I can find a lot of pluses,'' said NRA Executive Vice
President Wayne LaPierre. He pointed to two such victories _ one on
a referendum in Wisconsin on the right to bear and keep arms, the
other in gubernatorial races in a half-dozen states where winning
candidates ran on the issue of the right to carry a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, however, said that support for the right to carry a
weapon or bear arms is not about gun control, but rather a matter
of freedom, choice, or crime prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right-to-carry laws, for instance, are pitched to citizens who
feel vulnerable to crime and want a gun as a deterrent, but they do
not necessarily contradict the general desire for stronger gun
laws,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And although the House and the Senate are still controlled by
gun-rights forces, gun-control advocates say the results of
Tuesday's elections have given them a huge boost, particularly with
the election to the Senate of the nation's most outspoken advocate,
Representative Charles Schumer, a New York Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of a trend that will prevent the NRA
from going into certain states,'' said Kristin Rand, director of
federal issues for the Violence Policy Center, a Washington group
fighting for stricter gun laws. ``Psychologically, the way the
election played out was helpful to us, particularly because
everyone considers California a bellwether state.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates in both parties used guns as never before to stake
out a moderate posture, by painting their opponents as extremists
for failing to support gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Guns were prominent in so many races that Handgun Control, the
group headed by Sarah Brady, decided there was no need to fund ads
in tight races involving gun-rights opponents, unlike 1996, when
the group spent hundreds of thousands of dollars on campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``In race after race, in key battlegrounds, people took to the
airwaves to talk about gun control,'' said Bob Walker of Handgun
Control's Voter Education Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Democratic Governor-elect Gray Davis and Senator
Barbara Boxer pounded their opponents for not supporting
gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Schumer criticized D'Amato for opposing the
assault-weapons ban, just as Maryland's Democratic Governor Parris
Glendening did against Sauerbrey.
</P>
<P>
   And in Illinois, gun control played big in the gubernatorial and
Senate races and illustrated that this is a bipartisan issue.
Republican Governor-elect George Ryan launched a relentless attack
on Poshard's pro-gun position, said Tom Smith of the National
Opinion Research Center, a polling group at the University of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Using the same tactic, although without winning, Illinois
Senator Carol Moseley-Braun played her opponent's opposition to gun
control and abortion rights to help her close the gap in a race
that observers say otherwise would have been a resounding defeat
for her.
</P>
</TEXT>
