<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT EASY BEING LEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is for The Skinny People. You know who you are, you
toothpick-slender types who are perfectly healthy but who often are
greeted by the question, ``Lost weight?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Feeling OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Been sick?''
</P>
<P>
   It's for anyone who might have been a pudgy baby but who has
competed in the paperweight class since first grade, has endured
the wisecracks (``. . . vanishes when he turns sideways''), has
heard all the nicknames (``Spindleshanks,'' ``Pipe Cleaner'') and
has experienced the cruel rejections (like when the Bloodmobile
people assumed someone so thin couldn't possibly spare a pint).
</P>
<P>
   Some friends have recently said: ``You're the TV guy. Why not
pursue the Calista Flockhart-is-wasting-away story?''
</P>
<P>
   The easy answer is that Flockhart's waist is nobody's business.
She's a thin person who seems to have gotten thinner. It happens.
</P>
<P>
   To recap: Flockhart, the star of Fox's Monday night hit, ``Ally
McBeal,'' was photographed at the Emmy Awards in September wearing
a sleeveless, backless gown that had some observers saying ``wow,''
but not for the usual reasons. Hardly the fleshy, curvaceous sort
who could have sat for Rubens, the spindly Flockhart looked instead
as if she should have sat down to a platter of Reubens. And a side
of fries. And a shake.
</P>
<P>
   So do I, for that matter. But not being one who regularly
ventures out in sleeveless, backless evening wear (I get cold
easily), I so far have escaped the concern of those who might treat
me for an eating disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Flockhart wasn't so lucky. The buzz in Hollywood began
immediately after the Emmys, mainly because Flockhart looked leaner
than she did at the Golden Globes several months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   What on earth was the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the problem was lousy journalism. Not because someone
snapped Flockhart's picture. No problem there. She was fair game
and certainly wasn't trying to hide from the media.
</P>
<P>
   But, in short order, the ugly rumors began to fly, first on the
Internet and then in the so-called ``mainstream'' media.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you can be too thin. You can also be too nosy. A TV
station in New York eventually reported breathlessly _ and
erroneously _ that production of ``Ally McBeal'' was shutting down
because Flockhart had checked into a clinic.
</P>
<P>
   It was _ and is _ the sort of gossip we all love to spread. Was
she ill? Was she nuts? Was Hollywood forcing her to have
unrealistic expectations of how she should look? Traditionally
speaking, it was perfect fodder for the ``tabloids,'' which revel
in fantastic scenarios that play fast and loose with the truth. And
it was stuff that ``serious'' journalists would pay no attention
to, because speculation simply isn't journalism.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. Some serious journals jumped on the story because,
with the advent of Internet-generated ``news,'' there now seems to
be a dearth of editors with the courage to say, ``Wait a minute.
This isn't news. It's gossip, and we don't report gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   Flockhart, a stage actress well-regarded in New York but largely
unknown to TV audiences until last year, is only the latest victim
of this rush to bad (or no) judgment in newsrooms across the
country. Newspapers and, to some extent, TV stations used to call
the tune when it came to deciding what's news. Now they're often at
the tail end of the dance line, following ``stories'' that got
their start in someone's fertile (febrile?) mind and grew bigger
with each visit to an Internet chat room.
</P>
<P>
   With millions of people already chatting, some editors at
``respected'' institutions figure they'd better board the bus so as
not to seem too out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   I like to call it institutional insecurity, and it's
particularly virulent at TV stations whose newscasts are run by
people from the ``Entertainment Tonight'' school of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers are guilty, too. I'm proud that this one has seen fit
not to enter the Guess Calista's Weight sweepstakes, but there are
plenty of others that have decided her lack of heft is somehow
newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   So, anyone looking for the full-meal McBeal deal should look
elsewhere today. This is nothing more than a defense of Flockhart's
privacy and a declaration that, for some people, it's perfectly OK
to be thin.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad that Flockhart felt compelled to divulge her daily diet
to People magazine last week, but she probably decided she had
little choice. After radio stations began spreading the report that
she had checked into a clinic, the bad journalism was on a flaky
roll. It was Flockhart's turn to respond to the classic
when-did-you-stop-beating-your-dog type of question. Keep mum, and
she's presumed to be hiding something; deny the rumor, and she's
presumed to be hiding something.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, we skinny people don't have a lot of wiggle room when
it comes to weight loss. Still, our thinness may imply nothing more
sinister than a spunky metabolism and a genetic predisposition to
burn fat. And even when it does indicate something serious, such as
a digestive problem or an eating disorder, is it really a matter
for public speculation?
</P>
<P>
   We're a people obsessed with appearance, but, trust me on this:
Not everyone is trying to look like Calvin Klein's waif of the
moment. Some of us just happen to be skinny, no matter how many
slices of double-cheese pepperoni pizza we're inclined to wolf. We
have stiletto elbows that can cut diamonds, knobby knees that enter
a room several seconds before the rest of us. Our double-A heels
don't do well in loafers. Our bony wrists never met a watch that
didn't flop around.
</P>
<P>
   What's dumb _ and unhealthy _ is that some people who aren't
naturally thin are trying to be thin. That's lunacy. But blaming
Calista Flockhart for it, or suggesting that she has some global
responsibility to fatten up so others won't be inclined to emulate
her, is lunacy a la mode.
</P>
<P>
   This probably betrays my journalistic credentials, but I'm very
pleased when public people manage to keep their private lives
private. If they want to share their home lives with us, fine, but
I don't need to know who they're dating, hating or skating out on.
If they don't want us to know, I'm cool with it. Likewise, I'm not
interested in whether they're adhering to the precepts of the Food
Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, anorexia is serious. But where is it written that people in
the spotlight have an obligation to discuss their problems with the
masses? If Flockhart has a problem, I hope she gets help. But as a
string bean whose eating habits have been formed by 30 years of
deadlines that seem to fall right around lunchtime, I'm aware what
long hours and an irregular dietary regimen can do. Flockhart also
works in a business where good nutrition can fall prey to an
unforgiving schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Sensible people are able to make the necessary adjustments.
Sensible people also know it's silly to get caught up in the lives
of TV stars. Those who don't are the ones with a problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
