u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-09 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW FACE OF REPUBLICANISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a difference a day makes. On Monday, House Speaker Newt
Gingrich was telling associates that the GOP might gain as many as
15 seats in the House. Wednesday, Gingrich was scrambling to hold
onto his job, as angry Republican congressmen and party activists
schemed to throw him over.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott woke up Wednesday morning to
find many Republicans blaming him, by name, for the GOP's pathetic
performance on Election Day. Lott had killed any kind of tax cut
during the legislative session, fearing the president would recast
it as an assault on the Social Security system. His conversion was
immediate. ``The idea of an across-the-board tax rate cut could be
not only the fair thing to do for working Americans,'' Lott told
reporters Wednesday, ``it could be necessary to boost the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A day late and about $1,000 short,''said one midwestern
governor in disgust. Republican Senator Chuck Hagel of Nebraska
told The Washington Post: ``You can't win elections if you have
nothing to say. We are the majority party, we need an agenda to
work from and that is tied to leadership _ whether it requires a
change in the leadership remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The speed with which the GOP insurrection broke out was
symptomatic of the deep disquiet among the rank and file about the
Washington faces of Republicanism. Lott, Gingrich, Armey, and Delay
stare out from the television set without a trace of empathy.
Starr, Tripp, and Goldberg have become almost ghoulish; stuck in
some political version of the movie ``Groundhog Day.'' Every night
is scandal night. Voters were as sick of them as they are about it.
</P>
<P>
   It was an article of faith within the Republican congressional
leadership that the combination of the Lewinsky scandal, possible
impeachment, historical precedent, and the new demographics of
prosperity would compel a Republican sweep in this year's mid-term
elections. If all that didn't work, it was believed, the GOP money
machine would simply buy victory in states like Wisconsin, North
Carolina, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, every distinction was blurred, every substantive
issue evaded for imagined political advantage. Don't build it, the
GOP argued, and they will come anyway. Standing for nothing except
the enhancement of their privileged circumstances, Republicans
regarded the electorate as supplicants instead of constituents and
were rightly slapped for the arrogance of their pose.
</P>
<P>
   At roughly 9 o'clock Eastern time on election night, the locus
of power in the Republican Party shifted to Austin, Texas. Governor
George W. Bush had by that time been thoroughly briefed on the
breadth of his electoral triumph. Not only had he defeated his
Democratic opponent by more than 1.5 million votes (the largest
margin in the history of Texas politics), he had captured half the
Hispanic vote and one-sixth of the African-American vote as well.
The scope of Bush's victory left seasoned professionals in awe.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just that. It was that almost all of his allies
had won as well. Brother Jeb was now the governor of Florida.
Pennsylvania Governor Tom Ridge was reelected in a landslide. New
York Governor George Pataki, who through channels has said that he
would only run for president if Bush didn't, triumphed as the rest
of his ticket perished. Michigan Governor John Engler slaughtered
his opponent and let it be known that his next campaign would be
Bush's presidential run. Everywhere you turned Tuesday night, the
cards kept turning up with George W. Bush's face on it.
</P>
<P>
   It is the face that GOP activists, reeling from Tuesday's
disaster, now demand become the face of their party. It's not just
that he has solid conservative credentials and the inclination to
include. It's not just that he carries forward the brand name his
father did so much to burnish and inherits the network of his
family?s national connections. It's not just that has, on file,
18,000 names of $1,000 contributors (and from his brother Jeb, the
names of 5,000 more) who can bank $23 million with a single mailing
and a few thousand follow-up phone calls. And it's not just that he
has his father's iron discipline and his mother's easy charm.
</P>
<P>
   Buried deep within the national Election Day Voter Poll
conducted by the Voter News Service was a question about the year
2000 presidential election. It asked a sample of voters virtually
identical to the 1996 electorate which presidential candidate they
would support, Bush or Gore. Fifty-one percent said Bush, 39
percent said Gore. Those numbers, more than anything else, tell the
story of the next 18 months of GOP politics.
</P>
<P>
   It might be argued that I take this view because, by a happy
accident of birth, the brothers Bush are my first cousins. I don't
think so. Roger Ailes, the legendary GOP political consultant who
now runs the Fox News Channel, surveyed the situation late Tuesday
night: ``Big night for the family,'' he said. ``The old man's back
on top.'' What he meant was that the eldest son is rising.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
