<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0872 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CELLUCCI-BOS &LR;      11-09 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI, UNFAZED, SETS OUT ON A SEA OF DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Now for the hard part.
</P>
<P>
   After a tough campaign, Paul Cellucci has won the corner office
in his own right. But as the new governor formulates his agenda, he
looks down the corridor on some daunting odds.
</P>
<P>
   In the 160-member House, the ragtag Republican band numbers only
28.
</P>
<P>
   In the 40-member Senate, the GOP counts a scant seven senators,
nine fewer than William F. Weld had upon taking office in 1991, and
half the number needed to uphold a veto.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's no longer an accidental governor, Cellucci hopes
to cut taxes further, follow through on education reform, reinstate
the death penalty _ and rebuild his tattered party.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his lack of legislative support _ or coattails _ he
thinks his 50.8 to 47.4 percent win gives him a mandate, even on
controversial issues such as capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a bigger percentage win than Bill Weld and I got in
1990,'' Cellucci said in an interview with the Globe last week.
``We had a mandate then and I believe I have a mandate now.''
</P>
<P>
   But the legislative leadership clearly sees things differently.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Friday how he thought Cellucci would fare as governor,
Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham replied: ``I think the
question is the same as it is with the Patriots this Sunday: Which
one shows up?''
</P>
<P>
   In Birmingham's view, candidate Cellucci embraced goals that may
well prove mutually exclusive. ``On the one hand, he seemed to be
the world champion tax-cutter; on the other hand, he wants to be
the greatest friend in the country to the kids in our public
schools,'' the Senate president said. ``I am not sure both of those
priorities are going to be sustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of doubt doesn't seem to faze Cellucci, who noted
several times last week that the legislative leadership was
skeptical last year as well, when he first called for a tax cut of
about $1.5 billion. In the end, though the details were
significantly different from his plan, the tax cuts the Legislature
passed were worth about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran has made it clear he's
skeptical the state can afford another large tax cut. Further,
Finneran has indicated he won't go any further toward helping the
Patriots with a stadium, another Cellucci priority, and has
signaled he's prepared to do battle to keep the death penalty off
the books.
</P>
<P>
   That means the new governor will have to practice some serious
persuasion to move his priorities forward.
</P>
<P>
   And given the GOP's slim numbers in the Legislature, Brian Lees
of East Longmeadow, Senate Republican leader, says that for
Cellucci to succeed, he'll have to be ready to compromise with the
Democratic Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is, you have to reach out and you can't
alienate the leadership,'' said Lees.
</P>
<P>
   That's all the more true since Cellucci lacks an enforceable
veto, a key weapon for Weld in his first two years.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Cellucci is that this is not 1991, when
Governor Weld started off on rocky footing with legislative leaders
he had disparaged on the campaign trail. It wasn't until late
spring, after several bruising battles and months of heated
rhetoric, that Weld finally started to develop a decent working
relationship with top Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Despite issue differences, Cellucci is on cordial terms with
both Finneran and Birmingham. In his 15 months as acting governor,
he worked patiently as an insider, with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly brokered an agreement to reduce the unemployment
insurance levy businesses pay, pushed for and got an electricity
deregulation bill, signed an assault weapons ban and a brownfield
bill to expedite the redevelopment of polluted urban areas, and won
$1 billion in tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But most of those were issues in which the Democratic
legislative leadership shared Cellucci's priorities. On issues
where there was more strenuous disagreement, the acting governor
saw some of his priorities stall.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's election results were hardly counted before Finneran
had poured cold water on Cellucci's hopes for further tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an economy that is less than robust, something has to
give,'' Finneran said. ``You either slow the pace of reform or you
stabilize your tax base or cut taxes less aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham, too, makes it clear his priorities lie apart from
further tax-cutting, saying that even after the $1.7 billion
increase in education spending is fully phased in next year, yearly
increases of $100 million will still be required to assure adequate
funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is my first priority, and I will do everything, with
every fiber of my body, to see that that is achieved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others think Cellucci's penchant for playing the State House
insider could hurt his hopes to rebuild the Republican Party into a
viable force. They say the best way to elect Republicans is to have
a high-profile fight with Democrats on issues, and to take those
differences to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   That, essentially, is the path to power Newt Gingrich and the
congressional Republicans successfully pursued in 1994. It's the
course that Treasurer Joseph D. Malone advocated for the state GOP
in his own gubernatorial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It's a course Cellucci has little interest in pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I focus on results,'' he said. ``Once the election is over, it
is my job to work with whoever has been elected by the people of
this state to get some things done to benefit the people of
Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he and Weld had made essentially the same decision
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others were advising us to kind of have a scorched-earth
policy, beat up on the Democrats, and that would help us at the
polls in two years, and maybe it would have,'' he said. ``But I
believe our first obligation is to get things done for the people
of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   By any account, Weld and Cellucci had a successful first two
years. Still, in 1992, with Democratic presidential nominee Bill
Clinton running strong, the GOP took a drubbing in the state
Senate, losing seven seats _ and with those seats, the ability to
uphold a gubernatorial veto.
</P>
<P>
   But part of the reason for the Republican misfortunes in the
1990s may have been Weld's decision not to invest much energy in
the Republican State Committee. Lees thinks Cellucci will take a
much more active role.
</P>
<P>
   One other prominent Republican also predicts Cellucci will do
better than Weld at improving GOP fortunes: Weld himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the recruiting and grass-roots growth effort is
something Paul simply takes to much more naturally than I did,''
Weld said. ``Having started his political life as a member of the
Hudson Charter Commission and then a selectman and then a state
representative and then a senator, Paul is familiar with every rung
of the ladder. Having started as governor, I just wasn't as close
to the process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
