<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOUDS-WEATHER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIST'S HEAD IN THE CLOUDS _ TO RESEARCH THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As a troubled youth on the streets of postwar London,
Peter Hobbs was taken aside by a member of the British weather
service and introduced to the wonders of clouds in the hope that it
might help curb his delinquent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It did. And Hobbs has kept his head in the clouds since.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Peter Hobbs, University of Washington atmospheric
scientist and director of the UW's world-renowned Cloud and Aerosol
Research Group, celebrated his team's latest achievement with the
dedication of a ``new'' research airplane at Paine Field in
Everett.
</P>
<P>
   The UW's latest airborne laboratory is a refurbished 40-year-old
Convair 580 turboprop, obtained through government surplus, fixed
up and outfitted with sophisticated equipment to intensively study
clouds, airborne particulates and many other important players in
the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's new to us anyway,'' Hobbs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Husky One'' is the third plane for Hobbs' group, replacing a
Convair-131A. The first airplane obtained in 1970 was a World War
II Douglas B-23 formerly owned by Howard Hughes and now on display
at McChord Air Force Base in Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs' group of about 20 scientists is one of the world's
largest research crews focused on clouds and aerosols, tiny
particles that can remain suspended in air for long periods.
Aerosols come from sources such as fires, pollution, dust storms
and volcanos.
</P>
<P>
   Among the UW group's accomplishments was the first demonstration
of the effectiveness of color Doppler radar for tracking rainfall _
something weather forecasters now routinely use. The B-23 also flew
over the eruption of Mount Baker and, later, Mount St. Helens to
provide some of the first airborne studies of how volcanoes affect
the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The UW group has performed studies worldwide, including a flight
over the burning oil fields of Kuwait after the Gulf War in 1991
and a study of the global effect of smoke from the huge fires in
the Amazon Basin in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Western Washington might want to know why more rain
falls in some places. Hobbs' team has studied precipitation
patterns and the behavior of water in clouds _ from the microscopic
level to mega-storms _ to try to answer this deceptively simple
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter's work demonstrates the importance of making
observations and measurements in science,'' said Dr. Robert
Serafin, director of the National Center for Atmospheric Research
(NCAR) in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the difficulty and complexity of atmospheric science,
Serafin said, many researchers emphasize the use of computer models
and theoretical work. Hobbs, he said, stubbornly adheres to a more
direct method of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The UW is one of a few universities nowadays that operates its
own atmospheric research airplane. Most scientists who need
airborne research rent planes from NCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs believes this situation, combined with the focus on models
and theories, bode ill for atmospheric science. ``For an increasing
number of students, as well as research and operational
meteorologists, `reality' has become a numerical model output,'' he
said in a journal article.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many of the most interesting characteristics of the
atmosphere _ such as the ozone hole and lightning _ are not best
predicted or understood by models.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds still most interest Hobbs, of course. His ambitious
efforts to grow and maintain the UW's airborne lab all stem from
his teenage fascination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be on Earth if weren't for clouds,'' he said. Most
people recognize that life depends on water, but it is the cycle of
water driven by clouds and the atmosphere that really fuels life.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs, who joined the UW in 1963 intending to stay two years,
ended up staying put to develop his own cloud physics program. As a
teenager in London, he attended university lectures to find
scientists who could tell him what he wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled attending one lecture, ``Clouds, Rain and
Rainmaking.'' Hobbs approached the speaker and asked to join the
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to go away and get a degree in physics first,''
Hobbs said. So he did, spending years with his head in books until
earning a doctorate in cloud physics from the University of London.
He went back to the scientist and asked for a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't remember me, but he gave me a fellowship anyway,''
Hobbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Given his love of clouds, Seattle was a logical place to move
for postgraduate work. At the time, many universities and
government labs launched aircraft for atmospheric research. Hobbs
was offered a chance to start such a program at the UW.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the culmination of a long-held dream by Peter,'' said
Dr. Alvin Kwiram, UW vice provost for research, speaking at last
week's dedication. But Hobbs' lofty goal has been realized and
sustained not so much by dreaming as by his tenacity and successful
efforts to show the scientific value of conducting extensive
airborne atmospheric research, Kwiram said. He credited Hobbs for
his ``entrepreneurial'' talent at securing the funds and expertise
to fix up and equip an older plane for cutting-edge research.
</P>
<P>
   About $1.5 million was spent on the Convair 580, with money from
NASA, the National Science Foundation and the UW. B.F. Goodrich
donated paint for the plane, with a twin stripe in Husky colors.
The Boeing Co. also provided equipment and expertise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-09-98 1319EST &QL; 
