<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-09 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS COULDN'T DELIVER LOYALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts and California had two things in common for last
week's election: a strong, active organized labor force and a
viable Democratic candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   But California had one thing that Massachusetts did not: a
unified Democratic Party that strongly supported its candidate.
That, apparently, made the difference. Lieutenant Governor Gray
Davis was elected governor in California, and Attorney General
Scott Harshbarger lost in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor in California can be credited for much of
Davis's election-night strength, just as organized labor here,
especially the AFL-CIO, was largely responsible for giving
Harshbarger the surge that made the final count so close. Even
members of the media were impressed with the way labor's massive
phone banks delivered the message on behalf of Harshbarger to
hundreds of thousands of households across the state.
</P>
<P>
   But while some key Democrats, such as US Senators Edward M.
Kennedy and John F. Kerry, actively campaigned for Harshbarger, too
many others decided to look away.
</P>
<P>
   Take the reluctant manner in which House Speaker Thomas M.
Finneran and Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino endorsed Harshbarger.
Finneran barely lifted a finger on his behalf. Menino, according to
some Harshbarger supporters, did not have any of his troops out
actively campaigning for the Democratic candidate. In fact, one
Harshbarger strategist saw two of Menino's workers carrying
Cellucci signs in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harshbarger won Boston by 25,000 votes and also won
cities such as Worcester, Fall River, and New Bedford, his margins
were very small for a Democrat. With a little more help from local
Democrats, including Menino, he could have won Boston by the same
margin that Kerry did two years ago _ 65,000 votes. Harshbarger
lost the election by 65,000 votes. If he had carried just those
three other overwhelmingly Democratic communities by the same
margin Kerry did, Harshbarger would have won the election.
</P>
<P>
   Add to his problems the hollow endorsements of US Representative
Joseph P. Kennedy II, who dropped out of the gubernatorial race
earlier in the year, and US Representative Martin Meehan, who also
considered a run for governor this year. Although verbally
expressing their support for Harshbarger, Kennedy and Meehan were
virtually invisible when it came time to to actively campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, Secretary of State William Galvin should be
added to the list of non-helpers. While Galvin, by virtue of his
office, can say his role was limited to being an objective election
observer, others note that he is, after all, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   This lack of support for the Democratic nominee can be traced to
a problem within the state party that apparently is not as
pervasive among California Democrats _ jealously.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign, pundits wrote and voters read reports
of how Democratic insiders did not like Harshbarger because he was
not one of them. Moreover, he was disliked because he had
prosecuted some Democrats that were among, or friends of, these
insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Usually when a large political prize such as the governor's seat
is at issue, most party loyalists can put aside their small
differences and unite for the greater good of victory. But that did
not happen this year for reasons that had nothing to do with
Harshbarger's lack of charisma or the first debate performance.
</P>
<P>
   The real reason was that too many key Democrats simply did not
want Harshbarger to win. And their motivation may be simply that
they, themselves, appear to have aspirations to be governor.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, although he dropped out of the sweepstakes this year,
still is expected to consider another run in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, who considered a bid this year but apparently decided
that the time was not right, probably will again consider running
in four years.
</P>
<P>
   For Finneran, the governor's office appears to be a logical next
step after being House speaker.
</P>
<P>
   And Menino has to be at least contemplating it as a logical next
move _ as have many mayors before him _ especially after being the
first Boston mayor in recent history to run for reelection
unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   If these men are thinking ``governor'' in four years,
conventional wisdom suggests, they would prefer to challenge a
Republican in the final than a Democrat in the primary. In other
words, if Harshbarger had won last week, it is unlikely that any of
the current Democratic hopefuls would have taken him on four years
hence.
</P>
<P>
   While they may have had a common goal in helping to keep
Harshbarger out of the governor's office, none of these men have
anything else in common _ except, perhaps, their single ambition.
</P>
<P>
   These Democrats can plan to compete against each other for the
nomination in 2002. The winner, ironically, will be looking for the
kind of party support that was withheld from Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Democrats here can be each other's own worst enemy.
They would rather give in to petty self-interest than unite to
elect a governor.
</P>
<P>
   And there's another price that may be paid for failing to unite
behind a winning Democratic nominee: the loss of Massachusetts as
the site for the next Democratic National Convention. The site
selection committee is less likely to pick a state with a
Republican governor _ despite Menino's sales pitch on Boston's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   If Los Angeles is chosen as the site of the 2000 convention,
Governor Davis can thank his state's Democratic Party for making it
possible. He can also thank a few key Democrats in Massachusetts
for making that choice a lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
