<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWYER-KLAN-BOS &LR;      11-09 1363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-KLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK LAWYER MAKES A CASE FOR DEFENDING A KLANSMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va._ David Baugh is a black lawyer with a
cross-burning Klansman for a client.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Black is an Imperial Wizard of the Ku Klux Klan with a
black man for a laywer.
</P>
<P>
   The Klansman won't allow the lawyer in his house, and the lawyer
doubts he'd ever shake hands with his client.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, to hear them tell it, their working relationship is
unremarkable. They call it a triumph of a Klansman's colorblind
pragmatism _ no one doubts Baugh's legal skills _ and a lawyer's
colorblind passion for constitutional freedoms, including racist
speech by a client he calls evil.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Richmond, where Confederate president Jefferson
Davis lies buried just blocks from Baugh's office, and where old
wounds are passed down like heirlooms, not everyone sees it with
such cool detachment.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Virginia NAACP calls it an abomination, and a
black newspaper columnist has urged Baugh to quit the case.
Weighing in from Texas, a black lawyer who defended a Klansman
several years ago predicts ominously that Baugh will suffer for his
decision to take the case.
</P>
<P>
   The uproar began with Black's Aug. 15 arrest in rural
Hillsville, Va., under a rarely enforced 1960 state law. The US
Supreme Court struck down a similar St. Paul, Minn., ordinance in
1992 _ affirming First Amendment protections for not only speech
but also ``expressive conduct'' such as cross-burning. The Virginia
statute has remained untested.
</P>
<P>
   Black said the Klan rally was a private gathering of about 45
people. It ended with ``a cross-lighting ritual, like we do at
every meeting,'' to symbolically purify all those in attendance.
Had he known he faced arrest, Black said, he would have plugged in
a neon cross he uses when fire is impractical.
</P>
<P>
   Black faces up to five years in prison on the felony charge,
which next goes to court Friday for a preliminary hearing. That
date should mark the first meeting of Baugh and Black, who have
been dealing only by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh, a board member of the Virginia chapter of the American
Civil Liberties Union, volunteered to take the case, at no charge,
when no one else would represent Black. He isn't looking forward to
it, but he won't shy away.
</P>
<P>
   In a funky office in a residential Richmond neighborhood, Baugh
sits behind a desk with an explosion of papers and photos splayed
out before him. An old barber chair faces him (he sits there to
mellow out and listen to music), and a signed poster touting Hunter
Thompson for sheriff is propped in a corner. On the wall is a
framed greeting card from his wife, Joslyn, showing a hippo on a
diving board, looking down to a tiny bucket of water. The message:
``No guts, no glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Between swigs of Diet Coke, Baugh said his biggest concern is
that Black's case seems so winnable on constitutional grounds that
he is preparing doubly hard to make sure he isn't missing
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cross-burning is speech. This case is about the First
Amendment,'' said Baugh, 51, who resembles actor James Earl Jones,
down to the precise diction, the booming laugh, and the generous
girth. ``The Klan is a hate organization, and those people are
evil, evil people. But I don't have the right to gag them, and
neither does anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Baugh's estimation of who is evil does not stop
with Klansmen. ``The KKK hasn't had one-hundredth the negative
impact on constitutional rights, particularly rights of minorities,
as the existing members of the federal bench,'' he said, singling
out Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist for scorn.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh said the case gives him an opportunity to change
misperceptions about defense lawyers. ``When I defend a pedophile,
it doesn't mean I put on a raincoat afterward and run to the
playground,'' Baugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh came to Black's defense after a long record of challenging
authority, championing the Bill of Rights, and defending minority
rights. He was thrown out of college for a year for his role in a
civil rights protest. He later lost his job as a federal prosecutor
after questioning a judge over harsher sentences being given to
minority defendants. In his private practice, he has been jailed
for contempt after sharing some of his stronger opinions with
judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a strong advocate, and he takes his advocacy to the
wall,'' said his friend Jerry Zerkin, a fellow Richmond lawyer who
bails out Baugh whenever a contempt citation is issued.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh's hero is his father, Howard, now 78, a retired Air Force
colonel who flew 135 combat missions during World War II with the
storied, segregated Tuskegee Airmen. Baugh called his father, his
wife, and two daughters before taking Black's case. All gave their
assent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not defending this individual's ideology. He's not
helping the Klan so much as defending the Constitution,'' Howard
Baugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh said he had second thoughts only after hearing Black
explain his beliefs in an interview. ``It's easy for me to sit back
and say I defend the First Amendment. But when it breathes, when it
sweats, sometimes you think twice. There was some questioning on my
part,'' Baugh said.
</P>
<P>
   But that feeling passed, in part because Baugh believes he is
the best person to take the case. Baugh knows it would have been
more difficult for a white lawyer, out of concern that some would
wonder about the lawyer's hidden sympathies.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Black is thrilled to have this particular black
man representing him, though it has done nothing to change his
views, which are laced with racial epithets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got Mr. David Baugh as my attorney because he is a
professional, because he is a constitutional lawyer, and because he
is the most qualified,'' said Black, 50, a bounty hunter and
elected constable in Johnstown, Pa. In almost the next breath, he
added: ``I am not going to invite him to my home to break bread
with me because my Bible tells me that mixing leads to the
destruction of my race.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said he has suffered no backlash from fellow Klansmen:
``I'm the Imperial Wizard, and pretty much what I say goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Insisting he is a separatist, not a supremacist, Black then gave
a discourse on the Holocaust as fiction, how ``filthy Jews'' are to
blame for slavery, and how Africa remains home to naked cannibals
who, when sick, ``are going to some witch doctor with a bone in
their nose.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of statement that makes Salim Khalfani angry
that Baugh is Black's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stinks. It's really an abomination for someone like David
Baugh to represent someone in the KKK,'' said Khalfani, executive
director of the Virginia NAACP. ``Mr. Black should get someone of
his own ilk.''
</P>
<P>
   He was seconded by Michael Paul Williams, a black columnist for
the Richmond Times-Dispatch, who opposed Baugh's involvement under
a headline that called it an ``affront to ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   Baugh is not the first unlikely lawyer for a Klansman. Nearly 10
years ago, a Jewish lawyer in northern Virginia defended a KKK
member charged with violating a law forbidding adults from wearing
masks _ or hoods _ in public. He lost.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1993, Anthony Griffin, a black lawyer from Texas, was
fired as legal counsel to that state's NAACP when he defended a
Klansman for refusing to turn over his membership list. ``I know
this is going to hurt this man emotionally, financially,
professionally,'' Griffin said last week. ``But if you believe in
the Constitution, you have to stand in the breach and take that
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Baugh dismisses the warnings and the criticism. He is confident
that his reputation will protect him, and that criminals will still
seek him out. ``What, murderers are going to cop an attitude about
me defending a Klansman?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh has no illusions about changing Black. ``We're never going
to be buddies,'' he said. ``He's not going to have any great
revelation and neither am I.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people want to get us on the Montel Williams show and
have a `Kumbaya' moment. That is not going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
