<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0879 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-09 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRONIC PAIRING: GINGRICH-SLAYERS AND GOP'S LEADERS-IN-WAITING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Maybe now, especially now, Newt Gingrich ought to
get in touch with Hillary Rodham Clinton and acknowledge to her
that there is indeed a right-wing conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that it would do Newt in instead of Mrs. Clinton's
husband is perhaps a touch anomalous, but that doesn't make the
conspiracy any less real.
</P>
<P>
   The exquisite irony is that the leading forces to replace
Gingrich in the comically dysfunctional House of Representatives
are directly in conflict with the forces on his right that made
Gingrich's continued tenure (at least to him) impossible.
</P>
<P>
   This point has been mostly lost in the tumult following
Gingrich's toss of the white towel on Friday, just hours after
threatening with some success to slice the legs off opponents he
bitterly assailed as cannibals and blackmailers. It could use some
elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath of last week's Wake-up Call Election in the House
had been traditional grumbling for the first 48 hours. What changed
it was a move by a group of '94 freshmen on the far right that
Gingrich was absolutely correct in calling blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   The move _ the key players were movement conservatives Matt
Salmon of Arizona, Tom Coburn and Steve Largent (more about him
later) of Oklahoma, and David McIntosh of Indiana _ was a refusal
to vote for Gingrich as speaker next January.
</P>
<P>
   This group (at most fewer than twenty) did not have a prayer of
blocking Gingrich's renomination. The speakership, however, is a
constitutional office, requiring election by the entire House
membership; by vowing to vote ``present,'' the anti-Gingrich forces
could have blocked his election.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, by using all the powers of his office and party
position (and he had centralized most of them), Gingrich could have
bludgeoned the gang into submission. Ironically, by choosing to
quit, Gingrich may have blunted the true purpose of their
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence begins with the front-runner by far for next
speaker, Appropriations Committee chairman Bob Livingston of
suburban New Orleans, an architect of two measures the true-blues
love to hate _ the gigantic highway construction bill and the
catchall $520 billion spending bill that provided the bookends for
this year's astonishingly poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that, pork and all, both bills were on balance worth
enacting. The highway bill will more than pay for itself from the
proceeds of a stronger economy, and the spending bill was the worst
legislation imaginable except for all the gridlocking alternatives
to it. But merits are less important than the fact that
conservatives were deeply disillusioned by these acts of
governance.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the irony. Bob Livingston is not only a good and
affable guy, as well as a tough one, but he also believes deeply in
the coalition politics that produces legislation. Livingston has
truly odd ideas, including notions that this is not a monolithic
society and that 30-second advertising messages, no matter how many
zillions of dollars are behind them, are no substitute for the
actual legislation and policies to back them up.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston is very conservative, but with a difference, one
dramatically symbolized by his upcoming proposal to get Social
Security out of the federal budget so its current surpluses do not
mask the fact that the government continues to run an operating
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from being the right thing to do, the proposal is smart
conservative politics because it focuses attention on more
expenditures to cut, even if it lacks specifics.
</P>
<P>
   To put it mildly, the gang that got Gingrich will not quietly
settle for just that. Their ideological agenda has two points that
Livingston's probable ascendancy has not addressed _ massive tax
cuts and accompanying government-gutting, and renewed vigor on
social issue.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, their energies are directed toward Steve
Largent's campaign to unseat Gingrich holdover Dick Armey of Texas
as majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   On a superficial level, Largent's candidacy should be rejected
because his post-election analogy was as side-splitting as it was
absurd. To liken the Republican Party in Congress to the Titanic
that has hit the iceberg, and then to demand a change in crew is,
to put it mildly, to miss the point.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Largent is Gingrich without political sense.
He was one of the 17 House members who voted against permitting the
government to reopen after the disastrous, planned train wreck of
late 1995. He is a total privatizer on Social Security, and he is
down-the-line Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   That is why this contest is far from settled and why it remains
possible for another entry, like Representative Jennifer Dunn of
Washington, to emerge. And any notion of a Livingston-Largent
``team'' is laughable.
</P>
<P>
   That is also why two other Gingrich holdovers _ majority whip
Tom Delay of Texas and John Boehner of Ohio _ are trying to keep
their jobs in exchange for support of Livingston, and under the
thrilling banner of ``Enough Change.''
</P>
<P>
   The broader point, though, is that Gingrich's departure and
Livingston's emergence mask a deep, unsettled turmoil that will
continue for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
