<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !! 1/2 ``The Alarmist''   Black comedy about burlgar-alarm peddlers
who trigger the devices they sell to boost sales becomes too
disjointed as it expands into a take on the lethal arbitrariness of
the universe. Pluses: David Arquette's revved-up nerdy salesman,
Kate Capshaw's single mom who becomes his lover, Ryan Reynolds as
her hulking teenage son, who dishes out the most surprises. (R)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ! 1/2 ``Belly''  &LR; Celebrated video director Hype Williams makes his
feature debut with this terrible and sickeningly violent ode to the
thug life. Williams, who also wrote the script, tries to have it
both ways by capturing the horrors in loving detail, then
condemning them with heavy-handed speeches. It's a failed morality
play told in the most immoral way possible. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! 1/2 ``Living Out Loud''  &LR; Holly Hunter shines as a newly divorced
woman moving out into the nocturnal world of the unattached. Her
explorations include a friendship with her elevator man, Danny
DeVito, and the owner of a congenial nightclub (Queen Latifah).
Choppy and scattered, but Richard LaGravanese's directing debut
does include an adult viewpoint and an abundance of rich, bluesy
atmosphere. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! ``The Siege''  &LR; Hot-button topic _ Arab terrorists setting off
bombs in New York City _ is handled in superficial comic-strip
thriller terms, wasting Denzel Washington's righteous FBI agent,
Bruce Willis's rogue general, Annette Bening's mysterious CIA op,
and provocative visuals of the Army marching in to herd
Arabic-speaking Brooklynites into internment camps. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ! 1/2 ``Velvet Goldmine''  &LR; All the spandex and feathers and glitter
can't hide the fact that Todd Haynes's homage to '70s glam rock
runs a narrow gamut from dullness to nothingness. It rubs Jonathan
Rhys Meyers's David Bowie figure and Ewan McGregor's Iggy Pop
stand-in together, but produces no sparks. Christian Bale adds
little as the earnest reporter, digging out the story in ``Citizen
Kane'' fashion. Toni Collette, handed little to work with, gives
the others an acting lesson. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;   &UR; ``The Waterboy'' &LR;  A morality tale disguised as lowbrow comedy,
Adam Sandler's latest screwball affair follows dim-witted,
picked-on waterboy Bobby Boucher (Sandler) as he learns to
translate his pent-up rage into the language of a killer football
tackle. His insanely overprotective mama (Kathy Bates),
down-and-out coach (Henry Winkler), brutally abusive teammates, and
mean-spirited townsfolk are all redeemed in the bargain. There are
some genuinely funny one-liners; otherwise, the humor is largely
cruel and cliched. (PG-13) (Joan Anderman)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
