<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TEACHME-BOS &LR;      11-09 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TEACHME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEACHER'S LESSONS DON'T TRANSLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SANDY COLEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
TEACH ME! 
Kids Will Learn When Oppression Is the Lesson 
By Murray Levin 
Monthly Review Press, 152 pp., $23 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For 45 years, Murray Levin taught political theory at
Boston University, Stonehill College, and Harvard Extension School.
But in 1993, at age 70, he decided to explore a very different
educational terrain. He spent three years teaching history at the
Greater Egleston Community High School, an alternative school in
the city's Jamaica Plain neighborhood with a student body mostly
African American and Latino, students who had failed to learn at
mainstream schools.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Teach Me! Kids Will Learn When Oppression is
the Lesson,'' Levin chronicles his experience at the school he
refers to as ``a venue of last resort'' for the students whose
living environments present daily threats to learning.
</P>
<P>
   After months of frustration, Levin abandoned the textbook he had
thought his students would respond to: ``A People's History of the
United States,'' by fellow academic Howard Zinn. Students
considered it boring and refused to read it. Instead, he decided to
teach logic to students whose thinking was fragmented and
unfocused.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of textbooks, he used the study of the Cuban missile
crisis to discuss power struggles, uncertainty, and drawing wrong
conclusions that seem right. He dissected advertising and political
campaigns to show how they manipulate minds. He had students
role-play. He ate lunch with them and talked to them.
</P>
<P>
   The results were mixed. Students dropped in and out of his
class, sometimes showed up high or drunk, were unable to grasp the
significance of education in their lives, or were distracted by
abusive relationships or friends murdered in street violence.
</P>
<P>
   Levin says he intends the book to be ``an intellectual history,
an analysis of how black and Latino adolescents see the world ...
an account of their political and social theory, their perception,
their cognition, their despair and their attraction to
conspiratorial thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing this, he hopes to lay out a successful, unconventional
approach to teaching that will reach difficult students where they
live _ one that takes into account the conditions of poverty,
violence, drugs, and abuse that prevents them from learning by
traditional methods. It is a noble desire, and Levin explains
effectively why such an approach is needed. Unfortunately, his book
fails on many levels.
</P>
<P>
   Levin has taken a snapshot of a small group of black and Latino
students and used it to project a global image. These students so
hopelessly lost in despair and paralyzed by what they think the
white world is doing to them wrongly become representative of all
minority students living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the book consists of verbatim accounts of students
talking about how they view politics, history, poverty, violence,
and the causes of despair in their lives. Often that cause is white
oppression. Often the quotations are rambling, profanity-filled,
laced with broken English.
</P>
<P>
   Levin does this no doubt to show the fragmented thinking process
of the students he dealt with over a three-year period and to
illustrate the challenge he faced as a teacher. But the result is a
book that's an unpleasant struggle to read. It is not always clear
which student is speaking; none of the voices is distinctive or
individual.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, Levin's insistence on interpreting what a
student has just said comes across as insulting. He wants to allow
the students to speak for themselves, but he assumes they cannot be
understood. And though he praises the students' writing ability and
even includes some of their poetry, he continually points out that
their comments in class are ridiculous, even paranoid _ they
believe white people are trying to destroy minorities; they
theorize that the government created the AIDS virus to kill blacks
and Latinos and is involved in the drug trade for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, given the years he devoted to the school, Levin cared
about the frustrating mission of trying to make education work for
urban kids so often left behind. But that caring doesn't translate.
Instead, he projects the cold detachment of a scientist viewing
specimens through a microscope. &UR;  &LR; ``Teach Me!'' has a Professor
'enry 'iggins in the 'hood feel. His time at the Egleston school
may have been an interesting experiment, for him and for his
students. But his report on the experiment is not a plan for
change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
