<HEADER>
A0896 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-09 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR THE FUTURE TO PASS BY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``By the year 2000, housewives ... will probably
have a robot maid,'' an article in the New York Times predicted in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   Little did they know there wouldn't be housewives.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 2000 ... rayon underwear will be bought by chemical
factories and converted into candy,'' Science Digest predicted in
1967.
</P>
<P>
   Little did they know we wouldn't wear rayon undies and we'd eat
Skittles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that (in 2000) the Republican Party will pick a
nominee that will beat Bill Clinton,'' Dan Quayle said in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Little did we know that Dan Quayle is still trying to walk with
one foot in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   All these failed millennial predictions are in a little book
called ``Uncle John's Indispensable Guide to the Year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The book was created by John Javna, a former dollhouse maker,
one-time street musician and home-publisher with his Bathroom
Reader's Press. Javna hit the big time and the top of the New York
Times best-seller list in 1989 with ``50 Simple Things You Can Do
To Save The Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Javna's millennium book took five years to compile. He started
before it was practical to do such research on the Internet. Hey,
that's the future for you.
</P>
<P>
   His little book includes every tidbit you need to know about the
millennium. It should do pretty well, but I hate to predict
anything. A week ago no one would have predicted apocalypse for the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People couldn't even predict the home computer, even in the
late '60s,'' Javna said when I called him at his home in Ashland,
Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I loved the best,'' Javna said, ``was this guy in
1950 who wrote an article in Popular Science about how all the
furniture in living rooms would be made of plastic, with a drain in
the middle of the room so you could hose it all down.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds good to me, especially since I never got a robot maid.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to mock failed predictions. Javna likes the ones that
came true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into this because 100 years ago there were
science-fiction writers who were predicting the future, and it
showed how far we've come. John Elsbeth Watkins predicted hot and
cold air spigots. They do exist, and now we have the joy of simply
turning on heat or air-conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins wrote his millennium predictions in Ladies Home Journal
in 1900. He foresaw ready-cooked meals and ``cameras connected
electrically with screens at opposite ends of circuits, thousands
of miles at a span.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 1888 best-seller ``Looking Backward,'' set in a Utopian
2000, Edward Bellamy not only predicted television, he predicted
golf on television. So it wasn't a perfect society. But he also
predicted no unemployment, no wars and no lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Bellamy missed almost as badly as Dan Quayle, but the last
century was a more hopeful time than the present, despite all the
advances we've made.
</P>
<P>
   As author Gail Collins wrote (as quoted in Javna's little book):
``Looking backward from Bellamy's future, the saddest thing is not
that we have failed to create the utopia he imagined, but that we
have stopped dreaming up utopias of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, we dream up disasters. We have the year 2000 computer
problem, and UFO panics on the eve of the millennium. ``People are
approaching this with fear instead of thinking how cool it is to be
alive at this time when we've progressed by all these great
inventions,'' Javna says.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred years ago there were no antibiotics or electricity.
Maybe that's why people loved the future so much.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem? Forget it. ``We've been Y2Ked into submission
at this point,'' Javna says.
</P>
<P>
   Will the millennium bring apocalypse? Naah. Julius Caesar made
Jan. 1 the start of the year for no good reason. And our 2000 will
be 4698 in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of what we regard as our foundations is arbitrary,''
Javna says. ``The reality is that there is no foundation holding us
up. We hold ourselves up.''
</P>
<P>
   We won't hit the millennium like Wile E. Coyote running off a
cliff and suddenly looking down. Instead, Javna says the turn of
the millennium offers us a unique observation point for looking
backward and forward.
</P>
<P>
   Most seers only predicted the future as far as 2000, so we'll be
out there having to make one up.
</P>
<P>
   Javna's book is a trivia book, but it's not trivial. Consider
the story of the most important influence on Americans' vision of
the future, the animated TV show ``The Jetsons.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question is: How come we don't zip around in little
Jetson flying cars? The answer is, we could have.
</P>
<P>
   The creators of ``The Jetsons,'' William Hanna and Joseph
Barbera, got the idea for the Jetsons' car from a magazine article
about inventor Paul Moller, who had invented a thing called the
Skycar. It flew, but never really flew because of the Federal
Aviation Administration and an $800,000 price tag.
</P>
<P>
   So you see, the present in 1962 influenced how we saw our
future. And the future also held weird nostalgia for ``The
Jetsons'' and a bad movie version.
</P>
<P>
   These are the things you can learn from a little book. You can
sit there in the bathroom thumbing through it and get a sense that
time is an arbitrary idea _ except, perhaps, for anyone who is
waiting to use the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-09-98 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981109.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WOODS-BOS &LR;      11-09 1768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE MAINE'S GREAT WOODS ON THE CHOPPING BLOCK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For about what it cost to buy the Prudential Center in downtown
Boston, three companies purchased 10 percent of the state of Maine
over the last month, powerfully demonstrating the new fragility of
one of America's most enduring and famous forests, the North Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike more urban states that routinely turn to government to
protect prized natural resources, Maine has relied on private land
owners for generations to keep people from making permanent homes
in the forests that cover two-thirds of the state. But now, as
distant corporations buy and sell the woods like trading cards,
many worry that the old `timber baron' system is breaking down.
</P>
<P>
   In four head-spinning weeks, 2.5 million acres of the Maine
woods _ from the unspoiled shores of Moosehead Lake to the banks of
rivers where Henry David Thoreau once canoed to forests below
mile-high Mt. Katahdin _ were sold to private firms for $555
million. That's a bargain, considering the Prudential complex alone
sold for $546 million last summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Along the way, one seller largely rebuffed an ambitious state
bid to protect thousands of acres that were sold.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners, Plum Creek Timber Co. of Seattle, J.D. Irving of
New Brunswick, and McDonald Investment Co. of Alabama, quickly
pledged to preserve the woods for loggers and outdoor enthusiasts
alike. But few believe this is business as usual: Plum Creek
markets remote lands for exclusive homes, and some believe that
this is the beginning, not the end, of the sale of the Maine woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has been caught unawares,'' said public policy
professor Richard Barringer of the University of Southern Maine,
noting that the state had only $3 million in its primary
land-purchasing fund when the forest sales started. ``And the
message has not been lost on the other (major land) owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining a growing chorus of environmentalists, editorial
writers, and Gov. Angus King, Barringer said the state needs a
large fund for land protection or it risks being left on the
sidelines as private land owners decide the fate of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The myth of the Maine woods is a very important part of the
consciousness of this state. Were it to get broken up, people would
be quite upset,'' said Barringer, who as state planning director in
the 1980s was instrumental in past land purchases.
</P>
<P>
   But ``public lands'' are fighting words in parts of Maine,
especially in rural areas where people make their living from the
woods. To many of them, public land is a place where logging is off
limits and park rangers limit their hunting, snowmobiling, and
other outdoor recreation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to really press strongly for no bond issue (for land
acquisition) because this is totally out of hand,'' said Mary Adams
of Garland, the state's leading property rights activist. ``The
environmentalists want (development limits) or outright ownership
of land, because, once it's in state hands, it's in
environmentalist hands. They control state policy.''
</P>
<P>
   While support for bonds to protect open space is almost like
kissing babies for Massachusetts politicians, sentiment is divided
in Maine. A statewide survey in early October found that 44 percent
of residents would vote for a $50 million bond to protect public
land, but 34 percent would oppose it. But, with Adams's history of
come-from-behind victories, public land supporters know they will
have a fight on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The massive land sales in Maine tap a deep fear among
environmentalists dating to the real estate boom of the 1980s, when
developers carved up tracts of forest across northern New England
to make way for condos, private estates or just to make a quick
buck. The 26 million acres of forest from Maine to eastern New York
is the largest tract of undeveloped land east of the Mississippi
River, and they worried that the so-called Northern Forest would
become a second-home market for affluent city dwellers just a few
hours' drive away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most dangerous man in the woods is not a man with a
chainsaw, but a man with a lawnmower,'' warned an editorial in the
Maine Times in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   So far, with a few exceptions, fears of development remain
unrealized. Maine economist Lloyd Irland estimates that only about
one to two percent of the Northern Forest will be subdivided for
development by the time the 1990s end, most of that on land held by
small-scale owners rather than by the big industrial land owners
who own most of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things the environmental community is talking about just
isn't happening. It's all hype,'' said Dan Corcoran, a forester at
Bowater Inc. paper company in Millinocket. ``You don't have miles
of shoreline development going on. If anything, we've established
conservation easements (that restrict development). We have better
management.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Northern Forest is in some ways more vulnerable today
than it was when the debate began. Despite much talk about
protecting the woods, government and private conservationists have
purchased or otherwise protected less than 1 percent of the forest
since 1990, leaving the vast majority of acreage unprotected and in
private hands.
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, state officials have done little to acquire or buy
development rights on the 14.2 million acres of Northern Forest in
private hands, protecting just 898 acres through the Land for
Maine's Future program.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Northern Forest itself is a far less stable place
than it was just 15 years ago, as local land owners have been
replaced by multi-national corporations that have few ties to the
region.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Great Northern Paper was one of the most powerful
companies in the state in 1983, with 4,200 employees at its paper
mills in the Millinocket area and 9 percent of the state's land
area to its name. In those days, the chief executive lived in
Millinocket among his employees and boasted that the company's land
was its security for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Great Northern has been bought out twice, its
workforce has dropped to 1,700, and the current owner, South
Carolina-based Bowater, plans to close its antiquated Millinocket
mill if it can't find a buyer soon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bowater is using its once-sacred land to raise cash
after spending more than $800 million to buy Canadian and Korean
paper companies this year. First, the company sold a million acres
to Irving for $220 million, then, last week, it sold another
656,000 acres to McDonald for $155 million. In two weeks, Bowater
had dismembered Maine's biggest land empire.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup of these large tracts is precisely what
environmentalists fear, since it may open the door for developers
to break off hilltop, waterfront and other valuable parcels for
development, turning property purchased for $200 an acre into home
lots worth tens of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Irving and McDonald officials express little
interest in real estate. Irving, now the state's largest land
owner, has been more controversial for its logging practices, while
McDonald has hired highly regarded Wagner Forest Management of
Lyme, N &UR; . &LR; H &UR; . &LR; , to take care of its new land.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wagner chief executive Hank Swan said he wanted to work
out a plan with the state to sell development rights on key land
such as the West Branch of the Penobscot River, made famous by
Thoreau's writings on the Maine woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to invite a couple of conservation organizations to
provide us not only with technical expertise but also some ideas on
how we can develop a unified conservation protection plan,'' Swan
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Though conservationists were relieved at Swan's approach, many
Mainers were still shocked at the lightning speed with which the
Maine woods had been sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been used to having the ownership of these lands be
pretty static for long periods of time,'' explained Mark DesMueles,
director of the Land for Maine's Future program. ``This has been
sort of a healthy wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists were most alarmed at the October sale of a
million acres in the Moosehead Lake region belonging to South
Africa Pulp and Paper, or SAPPI, to pay off the debt the company
incurred buying a European paper company.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. King had proposed to preserve tens of thousands of acres,
getting upfront money from private groups, but SAPPI rejected most
of the offer, only agreeing to sell development rights on 1,908
acres along Moosehead Lake and other places.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, even though buyer Plum Creek has a resume that
includes substantial conservation work on its western lands,
conservationists were disturbed that the company does develop some
of its property. The company's web page, for instance, offers
lakefront land in Montana for development.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long will it be before Maine's special places are listed
on Plum Creek's website?'' asked Julie Wormser of the Wilderness
Society in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   King, a longtime public land supporter who was overwhelmingly
re-elected last week, is now making land protection a priority of
his second term, suggesting he might support a $45 million bond for
land, though others want $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to renew our ability to acquire, from willing sellers,
important conservation and recreational lands that may otherwise be
lost forever,'' he said in late October.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate is likely to be polarizing. Conservative
activists such as Adams oppose any land bond at all, while a
Massachusetts-based environmental group, RESTORE: The North Woods,
is pushing for a 3.2-million acre national park that would include
much of the former SAPPI and Bowater lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those situations (when) history moves in a
quantum leap ...like the Berlin Wall coming down,'' said Jym St.
Pierre of RESTORE, calling for the state to take bold action to
protect the forest.
</P>
<P>
   King administration officials acknowledge that the governor has
his work cut out for him, but they say the events of the fall may
have shocked Mainers into taking action, especially if King makes
it clear he doesn't want to create a big park.
</P>
<P>
   Senior King adviser Sue Bell said he will try to strike a
balance, preventing development while encouraging forest
industries. That won't please Adams or RESTORE, Bell concedes, but
``Maine's history has been an accommodation to various values in
the forest...It's been a place where people recreate as well as
work,'' and King wants that to continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
