<SLUG> BC-MATTHEWS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GIANT KILLER BECOMES A GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The bloody demise of House Speaker Newt Gingrich
marks a wild reversal in the Capitol food chain.
</P>
<P>
   When Gingrich decapitated the Democratic leadership in the House
of Representatives in 1989, a freshly resigned Speaker Jim Wright
charged his executioner with ``mindless cannibalism.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the same man accused of devouring his way to power in
1995 accused party rebels of those very eating habits. ``They're
hateful,'' Gingrich said of the half-dozen young Republican
red-hots who threatened to deny him their votes for re-election as
speaker. ``They're cannibals!''
</P>
<P>
   With that word, the speaker of the House carved an epitaph for a
brand of flesh-eating politics that he _ more than anyone else _
created. No one who has watched his rise and fall would question
his or his defeated predecessor's choice of words: ``cannibalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich won and held the nation's highest legislative office
chewing on the bones of his rivals, championing the raw appetites
of his allies. In the end, he lost it the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine and a half years ago, Jim Wright, in his second term as
speaker, stood in the well (of the House) and decried what he
called the `mindless cannibalism' that had forced him to resign,''
recalled Mark Johnson, who was Wright's spokesman in 1989. ``He was
referring to the partisanship that had taken over the House that
had made everything a zero-sum game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did Newt Gingrich say (Friday) in his conference call? He
referred to the `cannibals,''' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich had caught and destroyed Wright for a book deal that
violated House ethics rules. Now he has been consumed by a long
series of embarrassments that climaxed last year with a formal
reprimand for his own ethics infractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The similarities between their tenures is unbelievable,''
Johnson noted with ironic satisfaction. ``They were both very
strong-willed, top-down leaders. They both had book deals that got
them in ethical trouble. And they both lost the support of their
caucuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Former California Rep. Tony Coelho, who as House Democratic whip
fought Gingrich in the 1980s, called Gingrich a victim of his own
take-no-prisoners brand of politics. While past leaderscould rely
on strong personal ties to other lawmakers to stay in power once
they got there, Gingrich depended entirely on his own ferociousness
rather than the comradeship of his political allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt had tremendous respect among his colleagues for his
intellectual skill and his strategic skill. He didn't have the
personal depth of relationship. When he got nicked, there was no
depth to go to,'' Coehlo said.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting Gingrich with former Democratic House Speaker Thomas
``Tip'' O'Neill, who was a ``man of the House'' rather than an
ideologue, Coehlo noted, ``Tip didn't get respect for his strategic
ability. A lot of people really didn't like him. But a lot of
people would go through a fire for him. When he got in trouble, you
had people who went out and smelled it out and never permitted a
real fire to build.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gingrich's problem is that he brought this on himself,''
Johnson said. ``He created all this partisanship. He created the
cannibalism. In the end, his party decided that he got them the
majority, but there have been two elections in a row where they've
lost seats. He was never the best messenger, but he was a
visionary. That kept the Republicans together. He proved in this
last year that he lost that. So he had no redeeming quality. There
was no reason to keep him.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Christopher Matthews, the administrative assistant to House
Speaker Thomas O'Neill's from 1981 to 1987, is the Washington
bureau chief of the San Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
