A0903 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-09 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEWEY DEFEATS TRUMAN, REDUX 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Fifty years after the national pollsters messed
up in a big way, they are making the same kinds of errors that gave
polling a bad name in the Truman-Dewey race in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   To explain why they missed calling key races in 1998, they
trotted out alibis withered with age. In a number of contests, they
simply failed to poll right up to election time, thus missing
changes in voter opinions. In others, they made assumptions that
were false.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion surveying, comprehensively and conscientiously
done, is a valuable tool providing information that would not be
otherwise available. Exit polls are especially useful for revealing
the motives of people who actually voted.
</P>
<P>
   Polling deserves better from its practitioners than it got in
this year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   The news media that push these polls on the public are far from
guiltless. Their readers and viewers are entitled to accurate
information, which is the reason for publishing these polls in the
first place. Given the poor performances by many pollsters this
election, the media ought to demand their money back and apologize
to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   The electorate stood conventional predictions and past practices
on the head, permitting the party that holds the White House to
retain or expand its congressional representation. By doing so, the
people also set up sign posts pointing to resolution of the effort
to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   What the public confirmed by their votes, and their explanations
of them, is that impeachment is not the fitting punishment for
Clinton's offenses. They also expressed views that he should be
rebuked in some manner.
</P>
<P>
   However, the congressional censure that the American public
appears to favor is running into some scholarly concerns. Seems
that there is no constitutional authority for the Congress to
censure the president, unless he waives his rights.
</P>
<P>
   That puts the ball back into the court of the House Judiciary
Committee, which is considering impeachment. The partisan nature of
the Republican handling of this issue backfired on the party in
last week's election. The partisanship was reinforced two days
later by the actions of Rep. Henry J. Hyde, who heads the Judiciary
Committee. Hyde, R-Ill., is routinely ballyhooed in news accounts
as the epitome of fairness and non-partisanship. To prove just how
wrong news accounts can be, he unleashed 81 questions on the
president. To these questions, the chairman of a congressional
committee demands from the president of the United States yes or no
answers, never mind that many don't lend themselves to such a
response. In his supposed effort to be non-political, Hyde also
apparently overlooked consulting the Democrats on his committee.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's the way to run an impartial investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of asking the president leading questions, the Judiciary
Committee's first order of business would seem to be to find out
just how good an investigation independent counsel Kenneth Starr
carried out for the $40 million he has spent.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence is piling up that he may have broken several laws
several times over, and a federal judge has ordered a special
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A nonpartisan effort, which an impeachment process warrants,
would first seek to establish the validity of the laundry list of
charges that the Starr investigation has patched together.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the very case that provides the foundation for
Starr's charges is coming apart. Paula Corbin Jones, in her
relentless pursuit of as much money as she can lay her hands on,
has now alienated her second set of lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Having ostensibly begun all this in an attempt to recover what
she said was her good name, which she jeopardized in the first
place by going public with an old complaint, Jones has abandoned
seeking an apology from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Her ideological soulmates in turn have cut her loose, because
they find her appetite for money too strong.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton should forego any further attempts to reach an
out-of-court settlement. This case, already dismissed once as a
happening that did not constitute an offense in law, should go the
distance in the courts. Jones' case is no more viable in the
appeals court than it was the first time a judge heard her
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Can there be any doubt remaining that the Jones case from the
first was about money, notoriety and political theater? Is it not
clear that the charges against Clinton emanate from this failed
case? For all its intrinsic weaknesses, the Jones case has served
the independent counsel as his only mechanism to snare the
president. If he has any other goods on the president, he has
failed to produce them. Consequently, the Judiciary Committee's
task would not appear to be too complicated.
</P>
<P>
   With the Jones case imploding, and Starr's dubious investigative
tactics, there is every reason to wrap up the impeachment hearings
speedily. Everyone on the Judiciary Committee should be concerned
how history will remember what they do.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-09-98 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
