<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-WASSERSTEIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WENDY WASSERSTEIN ILLUMINATES WOMEN'S DILEMMAS, COMPLEXITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SARAH V. SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playwright Wendy Wasserstein was in Boston recently for one of
the final performances of her latest play, ``An American
Daughter.'' Its star _ a doctor, public health expert, and mother _
is nominated for surgeon general, but scandal follows when it's
revealed that she once skipped jury duty because her life was so
busy.
</P>
<P>
   Globe editor Sarah V. Snyder recently talked with Wasserstein
about women, politics, and motherhood. Following are excerpts from
their conversation:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In ``An American Daughter,'' the nominee for surgeon general,
a mother, is asked questions by a TV interviewer zanily different
from anything a man would be asked. Do you think we are close to
the time, or far from it, when a mother and father running for
public office would be treated identically?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think women are always asked personal questions. I don't
know if they always will be. It must be human interest. ... I'm
always asked about, `Is your mother upset you're not married?' `Are
you going to adopt a child?' I truly don't think that Edward Albee
gets asked (such questions) ... of course he's older, but I doubt
whether my colleagues get asked these questions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. ``An American Daughter'' features a successful, beautiful
20-something feminist author, Quincy Quince, who strikes the older
women as clueless about the complexities of mixing family and
professional life. Who does she represent to you?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No one in the specific, not a certain person. But I also
think there's a certain arrogance, it comes to me later in life,
that some people ... they think that there's an ability to organize
life, some sort of key. You just have that key, and you'll sail
along and make none of the mistakes everyone else made. We said to
our mothers, `You just lived at home in the suburbs; you don't
know.' The Quincy Quinces can look at us, and say, `Boy, you guys
didn't know. You guys are earnest and sentimental. Forget it, babe!
You don't know how to take of yourself while I, Miss Quincy Quince,
do.'
</P>
<P>
   She has no wisdom. What she has is, she knows how to operate.
What's scary about the world ... how you operate, how you position
yourself, is that Miss Quincy Quince is going to do great. That's
the point of view of the author anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This same character announces that she intends to `write two
more books, start her family, then enter public life.' But her
mattter-of-factness makes it a laugh line. Do you think a talented
young woman even in this day and age is still foolish to think she
can have it all?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. With some wisdom, you think about what your child's like;
it's possible you'll have an ill child. Or you get ill. Or your
husband loses his job, or The Boston Globe merges. Who knows? You
don't know at all. It's very nice for her, but life doesn't work
that way. She's totally clueless. `Her plan is the right plan.' Who
the hell knows?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some professional women cringed at older feminist characters
in ``The Heidi Chronicles'' and ``An American Daughter'' who
discover they are unfulfilled because they don't have children.
Isn't this an old-fashioned view of women?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You know, I think what's hard is, whether things are
old-fashined, or politically correct, or unpolitically correct, you
have to go to who's the character there. If Judith wants a child,
it's hard to say that's not legitimate, to want a child. Some do,
some don't. I don't believe it's not an issue. You have to decide,
or consciously decide not to decide. ... It is of issue in life,
for men, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has any professional woman said to you, ``I have been able to
accomplish exactly what I hoped, both as a parent and a
professional''?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. My sister died at age 60. You know ... who knows? I certainly
know older women who look back at their lives and say it's been
good. I also know a lot of people who have regrets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But you would say, of combining high professional
accomplishment and children, one doesn't obviate the other?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. One doesn't obviate the other, but I think it's really hard.
It's just hard. One, because it's a hell of a lot of amount of
work, and people should be alowed to sit around a little bit. I
like to sit around. I think it's really nice. And people should
have friendships and things not necessarily ... not toward
something. Every minute not raising children or working shouldn't
have to be spent lifting weights to escape osteoporosis. It's all
oriented toward something. The numbers would show it's hard for
women, or there would be more women CEOs and in politics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Obviously women in their 40s today grew up with much
different attitudes than their mothers. Do you think girls in their
teens today will be as different from us as we were from our
mothers?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Probably. I know girls in their 20s ... I have many nieces, I
have one, a junior at Harvard, Pamela. I have three other nieces,
who got married in their 20s. They wanted to be sure they were
married. So, you know, that's great; they're in love, and married
lovely guys, and that's great. But it has to do with character as
well. I meet a 9-year-old girl I can tell is a creative child, and
whatever road she goes on will be somewhat similar to mine, not
mainstream, even if it's a totally different world. I think, `I
know you.' And there are little Quincy Quinces being born out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you ever get the feeling that an incredible amount of
potentially creative, artistic, or professional-accomplishment
energy among women gets permanently diverted by children?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No. I think about that. I wrote ``The Heidi Chronicles'' when
I was 36, which would have been the time I might have had children.
The great thing about women is, they do things at different times
in their lives. One of my favorite women in politics is Nita
Loweyfrom Westchester ... a congresswoman, raised three children.
First she lived in that great world of volunteers; they run the PTA
and this and that. And then at 48 or 50, she ran for Congress.
She's a great congressperson. She knows about children and
education and breast cancer and is extremely effective. And I think
what's good about women is, if you have children, then in a sense
it broadens your life so what you bring to your work, or columns,
is a larger sense of the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. It can be hard when you're with very young children, though,
minding them on the stoop for instance, to think you'll ever
achieve professionally what you would have otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think it may be that that person doesn't write their play
when they're sitting on the stoop, but four or five years later.
I'm in the process of possibly adopting a child. But I'm old. I
think, can I do this? I did this other thing, and that was great,
and I'll never have to look back and say, I didn't get to do it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Would ``The Heidi Chronicles'' have been written if you'd
been busy with children?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You don't know. It depends on the personality. Maybe as an
artistic endeavor, it just had to get written.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. And maybe a different play would have been written.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. Maybe a different play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
