<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-METEOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S NEWTMARE IS OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By THOMAS TASCHINGER  
 c.1998 Beaumont Enterprise  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAUMONT, Texas _ Our long national Newtmare is over.
</P>
<P>
   Just two elections after leading the Revolution of '94, the most
dramatic takeover in modern American political history, Newt
Gingrich's career as speaker of the House of Representatives has
fizzled out like a meteorite plunging to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what meteorites do. They blaze brilliantly for a
time, but after their fuel is used up and their force is spent,
they quickly fade to black.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was such an entity. The congressman from Georgia had
the drive and imagination and guts to do something that many people
thought couldn't be done _ install a Republican majority in the
House. His ``Contract with America'' will go down in history as one
of the best package of reforms ever to scrub Congress, one that was
perfectly in tune with the public's pent-up desires.
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake about it, America needed Newt's coup. Even
many Democrats will acknowledge that their party had become flabby
and arrogant after 40 years of controlling the House. They were
passing bills the people didn't need (frequently laden with pork
and red tape) and refusing to pass bills that voters did want
(balanced budget, term limits, and so forth). Like a quarterback
who'd thrown too many interceptions, they needed a sit-down and
should be better for it when they inevitably regain the House.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who had richly earned nicknames like the ``Gingrich
Who Stole Christmas'' was never able to make the transition from
bomb-throwing back-bencher to elder statesman. The same tactics
that worked when he was a little-known minority leader _
scorched-earth campaigns and ruthless fund-raising _ were
inappropriate once he had stormed the palace. The public began to
see Nasty Newt as an annoying wonk who never seemed to shut up and
never seemed to learn from his increasingly frequent mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Newt's nemesis _ another big ol' gray-haired Baby
Boomer from the South _ had his own laundry list of personal flaws.
But Bill Clinton was smarter and slicker than Gingrich. His style
wasn't as harsh, and he could seamlessly reinvent himself or walk
away from earlier gaffes in a way that Gingrich never could match.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he didn't try. The speaker was a brilliant man, and
after he'd do something dumb like whine about having to leave Air
Force One by the back door, he'd listen intently to advisers who
told exactly how he'd blundered and what he needed to do to
recover. But within weeks _ or days _ another Newtron Bomb was
dropped on American politics, and the same cycle of repentance and
regeneration started over.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Newt had become exactly what he'd railed against in
the '80s. The federal budget passed (barely) last month had several
major spending bills balled into one unfathomable mess, including
$20 billion in appropriations shamelessly classified as
``emergency'' to get by the balanced budget requirements of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   What it didn't have was the things that differentiate
conservatives from liberals _ tax cuts, school vouchers, less
government. As last week's election results showed, if voters have
a choice between traditional Democrats and wishy-washy Republicans
who try to act like Democrats, they'll choose the real thing every
time.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice if Republicans could hope that the
post-Gingrich era will be as successful as the first part of Newt's
rule, but that looks doubtful now. Although many Americans believe
Gingrich to be the poster boy for right-wing extremism, in truth
he's the voice of reason compared to some of the zealots who want
to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Bob Livingston, the thoroughly
undistinguished Republican congressman from Louisiana who is the
front-runner to succeed Gingrich. Livingston, who almost left
politics two years ago, has a dull, flat speaking style ... except
when he loses his temper (which he does frequently) and begins
shouting and waving his arms like a man being electrocuted. Unless
Livingston can grow into the job _ and he has nowhere to go but up
_ practice saying ``Speaker Gephardt.''
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways Gingrich's reign of terror was fun while it
lasted. He grabbed American politics by the scruff of the neck and
shook some sense into it, and that's something that puppies,
children and congressmen need from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Farewell, Newtie; we barely knew ye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Taschinger is opinions editor of The Beaumont
Enterprise, P.O. Box 3071, Beaumont, Texas, 77704; e-mail
ttaschin(at)beaumontenterprise.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
