<HEADLINE>
DEFINING `DEMOCRACY' IN THE MIDDLE EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HALTON ADLER MANN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Democracy produces war'' may sound like some
Orwellian doublespeak, but that is the predictable projection for
``Arab democracy,'' the oxymoronic fantasy for repressive Arab
regimes that is claimed will bring peace to the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   Democracies do not declare war on each other, not proximate
democracies. Certainly, there are abundant examples proving this
maxim. But in the Mideast, maxims _ except perhaps ``the enemy of
my enemy is my friend'' _ cannot survive its history's hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   Without Anwar Sadat's autocratic and dramatic foray for peace
with Israel, Egypt would never have made such momentous history.
But without democratic freedoms and parties in Egypt that would
have defeated such rapprochement, the former Nazi supporter Sadat
and the former Irgun terrorist Menachem Begin both evolved to
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Would such a stunning overture for peace have been realized in a
democratic Egypt where fundamentalist Islamic fanaticism threatens
to destabilize its presidential dictatorship, the same terrorists
who murder tourists and Coptic Christians and who assassinated
Sadat?
</P>
<P>
   Would a democratic Jordan with its Palestinian majority have
made peace with Israel without the unilateral decision of its
supreme monarch, King Hussein? Unconditionally, no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy'' in such countries that have been alien to the
impulse decades longer than Israel has been an independent,
democratic nation would never have recognized its right to exist
and respected its territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
   This is the paradox that has made the Mideast peace process,
torn by terrorism, stalemated by historical hatred and belligerent
beliefs, even potentially viable.
</P>
<P>
   Israel at 50 years must be celebrated for arriving there against
the odds and the enemies surrounding it and for making peace with
them, returning captured land after repulsing wartime attacks.
Jordan at 50 must be censured for not creating a Palestinian state
during the 20 years _ 1947 to 1967 _ it controlled the destiny of
Trans-Jordan, the West Bank Palestinian homeland whose agony over
protracted percentage disputes prevented the progress of peace
until the recent agreement in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Diaspora that preceded Palestine's 1947
partition and followed it for decades replicates the Jewish
antecedent. Every Arab nation reduces Palestinians to pariah
status. Egypt, intent on recovering the Sinai oil fields after the
Yom Kippur War, did not demand the return of Gaza and its
Palestinian population. Kuwait banished its Palestinians during the
Persian Gulf War. In the Arab world, Palestinians, like the
Diaspora Jews, are the lepers of the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   Those whom fortune has forsaken in lands hostile to hope were
never welcome anywhere their travails and travels took them,
suffering persecution, inquisition and ghettoization.
</P>
<P>
   If Israel had not existed for the past 50 years, would a
Palestinian state? Would Gamal Abdel Nasser, King Hussein and Hafez
Assad have permitted it? Would they have allowed the secure and
secular fantasy of ``Arab democracy'' in nations that subjugate
women to the role of chattel and suppress the rights of their
citizens? Could peace have been produced from such a tyrannical
trio without a symbiotic, democratic partner _ Israel?
</P>
<P>
   Let the land that is the Palestinians' be given to them as it
was given to the Jews of Israel. Let them revoke their evil
covenant to destroy Israel, let the terrorism be terminated and let
us have peace from this time forward, forevermore.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Halton Adler Mann is a San Francisco journalist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
