<HEADER>
A0915 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      11-09 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PART OF WINDFALL SHOULD GO TOWARD RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a 46-year-old single woman and have been working for one
year as an independent contractor in real estate. I will make
$25,000 this year, and expect to earn $40,000 next year. I have a
$45,000 IRA invested in New England Value fund, Class A, $16,000 in
a money market fund, $3,500 in Nicholas II fund, and $1.400 in the
Domini Social Equity Trust. I add $50 a month to the Domini fund. I
also have an investment cooperative apartment in the North End of
Boston, where there is eight years left on a $30,000 6 percent
mortgage. I net $600 a month from the rent after paying the $378
mortgage payment and the $150 cooperative fee. I have just
inherited $125,000 and need suggestions. I don't mind risk.
</P>
<P>
   S.R., West Falmouth, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You don't give full details on your investment in the coop
apartment, but it certainly sounds like that move is generating a
better return for you than other investments are likely to do.
</P>
<P>
   Since your career is in real estate, and I presume you have a
good deal of expertise there, why not park half of the inheritance
in a money market fund until you can find a second investment
property which looks like it will perform as well as the first has
apparently done?
</P>
<P>
   As for the remaining $62,500, my suggestion is invest it to
buttress your retirement savings. If you haven't made your IRA
contribution for this year, I suggest you do so using a Roth IRA,
which will put a portion of your retirement savings on a tax-free
basis.
</P>
<P>
   For next year, when you anticipate higher earnings, as a
self-employed person you can switch from IRA savings to a Keogh
plan, which will allow you to put away more than the $2,000 annual
limit for traditional and Roth IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   If you set aside the money for that, you might be left with
about $55,000 or so to invest. If you are sure that you want to put
this money aside for retirement and won't have any call on it until
you reach age 59 1/2 or later, you might want to put some or all of
it in a variable annuity account. These are basically hybrids of
mutual fund investing and insurance. In this case, the insurance
level is minimal, but it sufficient for these plans to qualify as
tax-deferred investments.
</P>
<P>
   Most major mutual fund companies offer variable annuities which
track their most popular funds, and they tend to produce annual
returns that run about 1/2 of 1 percent lower than those of the
funds they emulate _ the returns are lower because of the cost of
insurance. But many people find that surrendering a half percent of
investment return is much more attractive than facing the tax
liabilities inherent in non-deferred holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you decide to go with a variable annuity or taxable
accounts, if these are to be retirement savings, I suggest you lump
them together in your mind with the existing IRA, seeking to create
an overall portfolio with about 50 percent of its assets in a solid
large-cap fund such as the position you already have in New England
Value.
</P>
<P>
   As for the remainder, I'd suggest you divide it evenly into four
additional sectors to balance the portfolio. I'd suggest you put 12
1/2 percent each in an overseas fund, a mid-cap fund, a small-cap
fund, and a health care sector fund. If you were investing with
Vanguard, for example, you might select the Vanguard Mid-Cap Index,
the Small-Cap Index, the International Growth, and Specialized
Health Care funds. With Fidelity a similar portfolio might consist
of its Mid-Cap Stock, its Low-Priced Stock, its Overseas, and its
Select Health Care funds.
</P>
<P>
   If you view your positions in Nicholas II and Domini Social
Equity Trust as retirement savings, since Nicholas II is a mid-cap
fund and Domini a large-cap fund, you could include those amounts
when you're working out the dollar allocations.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to view all of your investments except the money
market fund as retirement savings, you would have a total of
$109,300. Thus you'd want a total of $54,650 in the core large-cap
positions (Domini and New England Value) and about $13,650 in each
of the other sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you'll want to establish these positions as carefully
you would be if you were looking for a real estate investment.
Therefore, with the exception of the IRA and Keogh investments, I
would adopt a 36-month dollar cost averaging program.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you follow the suggestions above, with $55,000
earmarked for long-term investments, I'd begin by putting all but
$1,645 in a money market fund. With the $1,645, you would make your
first fund or variable annuity investment. The each month you would
target a similar amount to one of the funds; with this pace,
assuming 5 percent average returns from the money fund, you would
spread the investments out over 36 months, and in the process you
would reduce the risk you'd face in the event of a short-term
market downturn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. At age 64 and semi-retired, I am about to sell a house and
move into a condo. The proceeds of the house sale will not fully
pay for the condo, and I have the choice between seeking out a
15-year mortgage or cashing in some investments and buying it
outright. If I were to buy outright, it would have not have a
detrimental effect on the income I need to derive from my
portfolio. Which is better?
</P>
<P>
   D.M., Southborough, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In general, my point of view is that in time you will find
that now will shape up as a good time to take a mortgage and a bad
time to have too much of your money tied up in investments that are
dominated by the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But to address your specific question, I must first face
another: How is the money in question invested?
</P>
<P>
   If it's taxable stock accounts or vehicles that track the stock
market in general, I think I'd sell and buy the place outright. On
the other hand, if these are tax-deferred fixed-income investments,
it's likely that your returns from them will be very close to the
amount you would pay for a 15-year mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   When you then tally in the tax benefit of taking the mortgage _
deducting the interest expenses _ the chances are overwhelming that
you'd be better off taking the mortgage. As a variant, you could
move an amount of your tax-deferred portfolio that's equal to the
mortgage amount from stocks to a solid fixed-income investment such
as a GNMA fund and then take the mortgage; you would get the same
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a column that ran here on Oct. 18 you discussed minimum
distributions based on the life expectancies of the owners and
beneficiaries of an IRA. I have read that another option called
``term certain'' is available. By this method, the owner and the
beneficiary establish their life expectancy. If it's 22 years, they
withdraw 1/22 the first year, 1/21 the second year, and so on until
the account is emptied in the 22d year. Is this true, and if so,
which method is better?
</P>
<P>
   J.H., La Mirada, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Briefly, the advantage of using the method I described, which
the IRS calls the recalculation method, is that the required
minimum distributions are smaller, and the owner will never be
required to empty out the account entirely. The term certain method
is indeed an allowed option (as is a third approach called the
``hybrid'' method).
</P>
<P>
   The disadvantage of the recalculation method, as described in
J.K. Lasser's ``Your Income Tax'' guide, is that if your spouse is
your beneficiary and dies first, you must then recalculate the
mandatory withdrawal amount based on your single life expectancy,
resulting in higher withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when you die, the secondary beneficiary will have to
receive the entire balance by the end of the year following your
death and pay taxes on the entire amount.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, when an IRA that has been established with a term
certain sequence of withdrawals and the beneficiary is not a
spouse, the person who inherits the account will be required only
to maintain the sequence of withdrawals that was initially
established under the term certain plan.
</P>
<P>
   So which is better? If all depends on your individual needs and
tax situation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
