<HEADER>
A0916 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WOLFE-BOS &LR;      11-09 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WOLFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG, BAD WOLFEAN YARN OF RACE, POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
A MAN IN FULL 
By Tom Wolfe. 742 pp. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $28.95. 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; With his hyperactive reportorial gifts, his Old Richmond
sensibility, and his Ivy League imprint (don't forget that PhD from
Yale), Tom Wolfe never seemed content with merely having blown open
the backwaters of American journalism. No, he insisted on taking
that big-mouthed brilliance into the realm of fiction, where lurked
even wilder swamplands. If he'd already pontificated on real-life
subjects from modern art to the space race, think what
possibilities lay in the motherlode of invention! So Wolfe, at
midlife, decided to go after the Zeitgeist via urban realism.
Unlike a lot of his characters, he emerged from the '80s intact,
his ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' a flawed but wildly ambitious
ride through the mannered minefields of New York. What the novel
lacked in emotional dimension, it made up for in unmitigated
chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   Thackeray and part ... well, Tom Wolfe: the hilariously But if
Tom Wolfe always longed to be our Zola, what he got instead was
part Thackeray and part ... well, Tom Wolfe: the hilariously
astute, high-octane chronicler of social mores in the modern age.
And what he's given us with ``A Man in Full'' is a Big Ol' American
Novel _ a rollicking collision of the New South, old money,
politics, race, and ``bidness,'' in a fin de siecle climate of
excess and absurdity. It's as smooth and fast-talking as a room
full of cattle ranchers (and with just as much potential for bull).
Some of it is brilliant. Some of it is farcical, and suffers from
Wolfe's reality-obsessed neglect of his characters' inner lives.
But the man's finest powers of description are in full supply in
this novel, which is, more than anything else, geographically
dazzling. He slams you through the high-gloss buffoonery of Atlanta
banking and real estate, takes you inside the cruelties of a
northern California prison, then deposits you within the
anachronistic confines of a Georgia quail-shooting plantation.
Whatever its more intricate failings, ``A Man in Full'' is blessed
with full-throttle momentum; there is scarcely a moment in the
novel that isn't _ wicked Wolfe _ damnably absorbing.
</P>
<P>
   The advance hype on ``A Man in Full'' has been considerable
(and, some might say, ingenious); what other novel in recent
history has sold a gazillion copies even before it hit the stores?
Along with the publicity, of course, has come the ensuing media
overkill, so that the deluge of plot summations in print almost
short-circuits the act of reading. But this is actually a book most
enjoyed scene by scene, without any preconceived expectations. It's
a series of gorgeous set pieces, the overall design being a moral
suspense tale that only resolves in the novel's final pages. With
Wolfe (a literary pointillist if ever there was one), it's always
about the cumulative effort: Just as in ``The Right Stuff'' all
those incredible details were supposed to lead to liftoff, the
layering of moments and nuance here creates a vastly realized map
where all the dots connect.
</P>
<P>
   The master of this particular universe is an old Southern boy
named Charlie Croker, a poor kid who made good on the football
field at Georgia Tech, then went on to become one of the overnight
barons of the Atlanta real estate boom. His bluster and
testosterone bumping up against age (60) and frailty (a bum knee, a
waning sex drive), Charlie has built an empire he hoped would
protect him forever. He has an air-brushed second wife not even
half his age, a 29,000-acre recreational ranch that would stagger
the likes of Donald Trump, a set of invincibly reactionary politics
that screens out everything but other rich white men. He's headed
for a major fall, in other words, that old-Georgia hubris ensuring
a plunge toward the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie's arrogance as a developer now has him facing
bankruptcy, and one of the minions affected by his troubles is a
young man named Conrad Hensley, who works in the freezer warehouses
of Croker Global Foods on the outskirts of Oakland, Calif. When
Charlie's belt-tightening forces layoffs at the company, Conrad _
23 and the father of two _ is on the streets. What follows is a
stunningly depicted Dantean journey through the decidedly un-chic
hinterlands of the Bay Area, where generosity and decency are no
match for meanness and bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the inimitable Charlie, Conrad is probably the best
character Wolfe has ever given breath. (Tellingly, he's also
conceived with the most tenderness and the least irony.) The
rebelliously upright son of two aging hippies, Conrad only wanted a
piece of the old-fashioned American dream _ and finds himself
instead in the Santa Rita Rehabilitation Center, the victim of what
life can hand you when you're on the losing end of a Charlie Croker
mishap. With Conrad's brutal undoing juxtaposed against Charlie's
fall from gracious society in Georgia, it's only a matter of time
before these two star-crossed souls will converge. But first there
are the requisite stratospheric subplots, enabling Wolfe to create
a few collision courses among modern art, inner-city race
relations, the back alleys of the banking industry, and the decline
of Southern decadence.
</P>
<P>
   At the alleged center of ``A Man in Full'' is a rich young white
woman's accusation of date rape against Fareek Fanon, a black
football star. She's the daughter of one of Charlie's cronies; he,
a surly, in-your-face athlete who made it out of Atlanta's slums,
and who now has the monied interests of Georgia Tech behind him.
It's an Old South, save-our-daughters story Wolfe must have found
irresistible, though in many ways the dilemma itself is peripheral
to the minor charactors and events it sets in motion. Considered
the embodiment of affluent, Georgia-cracker provincialism, Charlie
is handpicked by the politically brilliant black mayor of Atlanta
to speak out on behalf of Fareek; if he does so, his creditors'
threats promise to recede. By setting up this somewhat creaky plot
device, the novel pits Charlie's desperation against the flicker of
his humanity _ and also delivers an intricate racial saga involving
old-boy racism, the myriad cultures of black Atlanta, and the
Realpolitik of the New South.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention a guy (Roger White II, called Roger Too White by
his less-apologist black brethren) who, with his custom-tailored
wardrobe, gets to show off Wolfe's sartorial splendor. The king of
external detail, Wolfe revels in a kind of descriptive fecundity,
and certainly ``A Man in Full'' is brimming with it: the exquisite
architecture of old Atlanta; a quail hunt on an autumn morning; a
$1,250 sugar bowl, belonging to Charlie's ex-wife, that speaks
legions about its owner's background and insecurities. Some of the
finest moments in the novel are guided by this richness of
specificity, from a terrifying get-the-guest ``workout'' session
with Croker's bankers to a breeding between his prize stallion and
mare at the ranch (guests are invited to watch). And Conrad's stint
in prison is as powerfully rendered as anything Wolfe has written.
Still, at times such lushness threatens to eclipse the more
intimate spheres of fiction. Spending paragraphs on the dimensions
of Charlie's dressing room, for instance, Wolfe will almost forget
to mention that his protagonist has an infant daughter. That choice
of focus may be intended to suggest Charlie's parental failings,
but it has the result of accentuating Wolfe's inattention to the
emotional realm.
</P>
<P>
   The more depressed Charlie became in ``A Man in Full,'' the more
I liked him. And herein lies one of the successes of Wolfe's
efforts. He's written a sendup of the South, but he's done so as a
native Southerner who got far enough away to see the place with
hawk-eyed realism _ to see its ludicrous posturing, its poignant
humility, its sugar-coated iniquities and suicidal gentility. ``A
Man in Full'' is less showy than ``The Bonfire of the Vanities,''
but it's a better novel, partly because the world it evokes _
beyond its Atlanta high-rises and its perfectly manicured lawns _
is such a heart-and-soul fortress that Wolfe himself couldn't put
it into words. But he got it all.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his signature satire, in Wolfe's hands everybody's
guilty of something: of parsimony, solipsism, failures of the
heart, the usual idiotic blunders called human error. But ``A Man
in Full'' has a tenderness about it, even an idealism, that's new
to Wolfe. The ending of the novel has problems; as with the
too-neat epilogue of ``Bonfire,'' Wolfe doesn't know how to let his
characters go without inventing forced solutions for their ongoing
dramas. But even if you can't bear the introduction of a Greek
philosopher (Epictetus) to tie things together (there goes that
closet scholar again), you have to admire the hope such a ploy
represents. If any quality emerged alongside Wolfe's
take-no-prisoners intelligence in his previous work, it was a
too-cool heart that bordered on cynicism. That's nowhere in sight
in ``A Man in Full,'' which is as wide as the Mississippi,
firecracker smart, and _ dare we say it? _ sometimes even kind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
