<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SUCCEEDS IN PAINTING MICROSOFT AS A BULLY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the landmark antitrust case against Microsoft
Corp. in its fourth week, the government has offered abundant
details to show that the world's best-known software company is
also a marketplace bully. But the government still has significant
work to do to prove that Microsoft broke any laws.
</P>
<P>
   Three senior officials from well-known companies have testified
so far, all relating &UR;  &LR; stories of how Microsoft tried to strong-arm
their firms by offering special access to Microsoft's nearly
ubiquitous &UR;  &LR; Windows software _ or by denying them access.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape Communications Corp.'s chief executive said that
Microsoft proposed that the two companies split the market for
Internet browsing software, and implied it would deny Netscape
important Windows technical information if it did not agree. Had it
taken place, such a market division would have hampered Netscape's
growth. It would also likely have constituted illegal collusion
between competitors.
</P>
<P>
   An Apple Computer Inc. executive said Microsoft wanted Apple to
promote its browser and not Netscape's. Microsoft's alleged threat:
it would end production of office software for Apple computers,
which would make them far harder to sell.
</P>
<P>
   And a senior official of America Online Inc. said that his
company agreed to use and promote Microsoft's browser, and to
downplay Netscape's. Microsoft's inducement: it would give AOL a
prominent place on the opening screen that Windows users see when
they turn on their computers.
</P>
<P>
   If borne out through the rest of the trial, these tales could
help convince US District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson that
Microsoft uses Windows illegally to crush its competitors.
Ultimately, the Department of Justice and the 20 states joining the
lawsuit want Jackson to limit Microsoft's power to use Windows to
manipulate its competitors, though they have not yet spelled out
exactly how that should be accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Under antitrust laws, owning a monopoly is legal. But it is
illegal to use a monopoly to injure companies trying to create new
competition, or to use monopoly power to push into new markets.
</P>
<P>
   The range of evidence offered so far has surprised some
antitrust specialists following the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has put in a pretty strong case so far. Over
the summer, as this came to a head, I wouldn't have predicted it
would be this strong,'' said Lisa Wood of the Boston firm Nutter,
McClennen &AMP; Fish.
</P>
<P>
   Windows is the leading operating system for personal computers.
It controls a computer's basic operations and helps it runs games,
spreadsheets, word processors and other applications programs.
Companies that sell computers need a license from Microsoft to sell
Windows with their machines, and companies that make applications
programs want Microsoft to share technical details of the latest
upgrades of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Given its large market share, Microsoft's tactics with Apple,
AOL, and Netscape are evidence that the Redmond, Wash., software
company is using its power to muscle competitors, said Robert
Doyle, a former Federal Trade Commission lawyer now with the firm
Arent, Fox in Washington. ``If they had a 30 percent market
position in operating systems, you could conclude that Microsoft's
threats weren't very viable ... But they've got 90 percent or 80
percent, and that gives Microsoft some leverage in getting what
they want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, in which the judge has limited each side to 12
witnesses, has a long way to go. Only three of the government's
witnesses have been called so far, and less than two hours of the
20-hour deposition by Microsoft chairman Bill Gates have been
aired. Ultimately, the court might see as many as eight hours of
that deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has not called any of its witnesses. And one strong
argument that it has made is that Netscape's software is still
popular and easy to find, despite Microsoft's alleged efforts to
crush the company.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government has not begun to argue several required
aspects of its case. Generally, antitrust specialists said, the
government needs to prove three elements to win:
</P>
<P>
   _That Microsoft has monopoly control of the market for operating
system software used on personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   _That Microsoft used its monopoly power to defend that monopoly
or to push into new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   _And that Microsoft's actions prompted higher prices, slower
innovation, or less competition in the software market, or that
they otherwise hurt consumers.
</P>
<P>
   With the Apple, AOL, and Netscape testimony, the government has
mostly addressed the second element. But it has barely begun to
offer evidence on the first and third elements. For those portions
of the trial, the government will lean heavily on the work of
economists.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Falk, a legal adviser to Microsoft rival Oracle Corp. and
to a trade alliance that favors the antitrust action, said that it
may not be difficult to show that Microsoft's actions harmed
consumers. If the government can prove that Microsoft intentionally
warded off competitors to maintain its monopoly, then the law
presumes consumers were injured.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
