<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981109.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0940 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-2     11-09 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 WASHINGTON: ... were injured.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Wood, the Nutter, McClennen &AMP; Fish lawyer, said that is only
true of older and more familiar markets. Because software is a
newer, less understood market, courts may be hesitant to impose
controls on Microsoft unless the government offers solid economic
evidence to show the company harmed consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is saying, `We are not trying to maintain a monopoly
or to stifle competition. We are trying to produce good products,
to pursue consumer good and consumer value,''' Wood said. ``The
government needs to show more of why consumers don't enjoy as much
innovation or as good prices as they could have.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the government likely cannot prove that Windows is a
monopoly merely by citing its 90 percent market share. &UR;  &LR; It will
need economic data to counter Microsoft's claims that its hold on
the market is incomplete and insecure.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it should not be punished merely because computer
buyers have decided its product is the best available. Moreover, it
says that any smart person with a little capital can design a
product that dethrones Windows. A true monopolist would not have to
relentlessly improve Windows to hold market share, and it would be
able to charge higher prices for Windows than Microsoft does.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the government, in the ongoing antitrust
trial, has made headway in arguing that Microsoft's Internet
browser should be marketed as a separate product from Windows.
Microsoft's practice of bundling the two products _ and including
the browser for free _ severely hurt Netscape's ability to win new
customers.
</P>
<P>
   In June, an Appeals Court backed Microsoft's practice of selling
the two products as one. But Wood and Doyle said the government, in
the current antitrust case, has presented evidence suggesting that
Microsoft combined the two products to hurt Netscape, not to help
consumers. That evidence was not presented to the Appeals Court. It
could persuade Jackson, the district court judge, to rule that the
two products are improperly linked, and allow him to be upheld on
appeal. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, however, saw one significant problem with the
government's case so far. It has spent too much time attacking
Gates's credibility, he said. It has spent too much time trying to
show that Gates, in depositions, tried to mislead the government
about his knowledge of Microsoft's tactics against Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is personalizing the case too much,'' Doyle
said. ``That could prove detrimental in the long run. They should
focus on the behavior of the company rather than on the
personalities of the individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLAIMS AGAINST MICROSOFT AND ITS RESPONSES
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the Microsoft trial enters its fourth week, the following
claims have been made by witnesses and attorneys in the case:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David Boies, lead attorney for the Justice Department &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claim: Microsoft illegally used the monopoly power of its
Windows software to crush competitors. This strategy comes directly
from chairman Bill Gates, who lied about it in depositions.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft response: The company is not a monopoly. It competes
aggressively but legally. Demonizing Gates does not amount to proof
of anticompetitive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
James Barksdale, chief executive, Netscape Communications Corp. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claim: Microsoft illegally tried to carve up the browser market
and implied it would deny Netscape important Windows technical
information if it did not agree.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft response: Netscape account is ``fantastical.'' No
market division was offered or occurred. Netscape distributes
millions of copies of its browser, showing that Microsoft has not
crushed it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Colburn, senior vice president of business affairs,
America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claim: Microsoft offered to build easy access to AOL's on-line
service into Windows _ if AOL would dump Netscape's browser in
favor of Microsoft's. AOL agreed because the offer was too good to
pass up.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's response: AOL chose Microsoft's browser for its
better technology. AOL and Netscape were also colluding to hurt
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Avadis Tevanian Jr., senior vice president of software
engineering, Apple Computer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claim: Microsoft threatened to end production of crucial office
software for Apple computers if Apple did not promote Microsoft's
browser. Microsoft also tried to bully Apple to abandon an
important ``multimedia'' software product.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft response: The browser deal was part of a larger
investment in Apple to help shore up the troubled company. The
multimedia charge is false.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates (by videotaped deposition), chairman, Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Claim: He had no knowledge of attempts to bully Netscape or to
divide the browser market.
</P>
<P>
   Government response: Internal company e-mails show otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOURCE: Globe research &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
