<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0943 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-09 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUTIE CAN'T PULL OUT A TROPHY WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Did somebody say, ``Vinny Flakes''?
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe ``Vinny Pasta.'' Whatever. What we do know is that
Sunday's game had nothing to do with the 1984 Heisman Trophy
winner. It was all about the 1986 winner, his big plays and his
team's decisive 34-12 victory in an AFC East showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde of the Jets was so good, and his team's triumph
so complete, that he was given the ultimate tribute by coach Bill
Parcells. He got to watch the final five minutes or so standing on
the sideline wearing the obligatory baseball cap as ex-Patriot Ray
Lucas performed mopup duties. Hey, with 22-for-31, 258-yard,
three-TD numbers, he had earned the star treatment. He even had an
18-yard scramble, if you can believe that.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Bills' Doug Flutie, there was never even a hint of
mania. He was rendered boringly mortal by a Bill Belichick-inspired
Jets' defense that limited him to 12-for-30 passing, 154 yards, and
two interceptions, and which, more important, kept him out of the
end zone, sometimes despite some pretty nice field position.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, it had to be the defense, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not according to Buffalo coach Wade Phillips. ``They didn't show
us anything we didn't expect,'' said Bum's Kid.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie agreed _ almost. ``I can't say it was any one specific
thing,'' he said with a shrug. ``They put some pressure on me. I
had to get rid of it. They made plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about the situation a little more, Flutie did
acknowledge one thing. ``They did run a 4-4,'' he said. ``That was
a look we hadn't seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was the Jets' defense or the Bills' lack of offensive
execution, the end result was a touchdown-free game for the Bills.
And there were chances. Good chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills came up with three Jets turnovers in the first half,
out of which the visitors fashioned 3 points. This is a formula for
failure in the National Football League. No none will argue that
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we didn't take advantage of three turnovers in the first
half,'' pointed out Phillips, ``that was the difference in the ball
game. Then I thought we lost our poise a little in the second
half.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense got us some turnovers in the first half,''
confirmed Flutie, ``and we wound up with field goals instead of
touchdowns. We had our opportunities early, and we didn't take
advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie has gotten full credit for all the good Buffalo
happenings during the previous five weeks, so he must be ready to
accept a lot of the blame for this sorry offensive performance at
Giants Stadium. He was limited to little bursts of energy. He was
never able to sustain any offense for his team. He never ran away
from anybody. He never made any chicken salad out of chicken
excrement. He was an ineffective NFL quarterback, period. And he
knew it.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the ball over at the Jets 38 (following an interception
on Testaverde's first play from scrimmage), the Jets 37, and the
Jets 49, the best Flutie and the Bills could generate was one Steve
Christie field goal. In one particularly unproductive stretch
overlapping the end of the second quarter and the first five
minutes of the third, Flutie had a killer interception followed by
back-to-back three-and-outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough day,'' Flutie said. ``I've gone five years
since I had one of these games.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst transgression was an interception that came with 27
seconds remaining in the half. The Jets were leading, 10-9. The
Bills had the ball at their 40. On first and 10, Flutie tried to
connect with Eric Moulds, but Otis Smith got there first. Vinny the
QB hit Dedric Ward for 25 _ one of his many big plays for the
born-again signal-caller _ and John Hall nailed a 43-yard field
goal. That was a very bad juxtaposition, and Flutie was ready to
assume full responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one ball I wish I had back,'' Flutie declared. ``I
didn't lead him enough. It would have been a big gainer if I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is used to the idea that most outsiders now regard all
Buffalo games as Flutie morality plays, which doesn't mean he has
to like it. When the mentor began to reflect on this game, he saw a
lot more problems than an unproductive quarterback. In fact, 12
points and no touchdowns notwithstanding, Phillips was more
concerned about something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was horrible,'' he said. ``It was absolutely
horrible on third down and fourth down.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that the Tuna, as he always does, went for
it on fourth down when given half a chance. There was a
fourth-and-6 at the Buffalo 35 with the Jets leading by a 20-12
score late in the third quarter. Vinny hit Keyshawn Johnson for the
needed 7 yards, and five plays later he hit Wayne Chrebet for a
12-yard TD pass to put the game completely out of Buffalo's feeble
reach.
</P>
<P>
   Both the losing coach and the losing quarterback had nothing but
good things to say about Testaverde. As for the losing QB's own
self-appraisal?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad day,'' said Flutie, ``but I'm going to keep
swinging. Nothing's going to change. I'm going to let it fly. I'm
not going to fold up the tent. I don't accept losing very easily.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 36, and there is nothing he can take with a loss. ``You
look at the film and you correct your mistakes,'' he said. ``But
you can correct your mistakes with a win, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows very well who the next opponent is, but he says it's
not going to be a big deal because it's in Rich Stadium and not in
Foxborough, Mass. He knows that if he doesn't play better than he
did Sunday, the anti-Flutie bill of particulars once again will be
rehashed. It will be a what-have-you-done-for-me-lately deal as
long as he plays on this side of the border, even if he's supposed
to be the starter for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches can change their minds, too,'' said Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
