<HEADLINE>
A PINCH OF HUMILITY IS NOW IN THE RECIPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ This time, maybe just in the nick of time,
they seemed to get it. Unfortunately for them, they really had to
get it before they finally got it, but at least when the debacle
was over Sunday no one was in denial anymore in the New England
Patriots' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   No one. Not after this. And maybe that will save them from
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``From almost every opportunity we had early on, we couldn't do
anything,'' coach Pete Carroll said after he stood stunned on the
sidelines and watched ``the most talented team in the AFC East'' be
destroyed by the Atlanta Falcons, 41-10. ``There is no place to
look here where there is any bright spot. There's no silver lining
here in any manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a horrific display of football. That's where we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   That is indeed where the Patriots are this morning. They are 5-4
and fighting to keep afloat coming off a performance so horrific
their coach used that word twice to describe it.
</P>
<P>
   They are 5-4 and back in the pack and no longer _ they can only
hope _ a team believing they are the most talented in the AFC East,
as they have been described so often by so many people that they
actually began to believe it despite having no evidence to support
that besides talking heads on TV saying it and empty heads in
newspapers writing it.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, they were a team in denial. They were slapped
around by the Denver Broncos in a game far closer to a blowout
(remember how it started off 17-0?) than a 6-point loss yet
believed they'd been competitive when in fact some of their best
players had been their own worst enemies.
</P>
<P>
   They lost to the Jets and the Dolphins and said they just needed
to make a few more plays when they had consistently made none,
denying the evidence of who they were that was in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   Then came last week's game in Indianapolis. It was a game that
Drew Bledsoe and a handful of his teammates saw for what it was. It
was not a victory. It was an escape.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most of the young men in their locker room insisted they
were all right. They said there was no reason to panic. They said
they hadn't played their best football yet. They knew they were
better than they seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Falcons came to town Sunday and destroyed the myth of
the Patriots' assumed superiority. Atlanta destroyed the lie that
they were the most talented team in the AFC East and made them face
reality, which simply is that they are a good team like a lot of
good teams in the NFL today. They are a team that can win _ or lose
_ any game, any time, depending on if they are prepared to kick and
scrap and fight on every play. Every play, not half of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're not that talented,'' Bledsoe said in a whisper
late Sunday, long after the locker room had been all but abandoned.
``I don't know what the attitude of individual guys was after the
Colt game, but I knew then we were going to have to continue to
raise our level of play if we wanted to win. We didn't do that, so
you get what you had today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Injuries are not an excuse to play the way we played. We kind
of rolled over for them today.''
</P>
<P>
   They rolled over. They got pummeled. They took a beating. They
got mugged. They were lambasted. They ... well you get the picture,
but most of all, it was another game against another elite team
(say what you will, the Falcons are 13-4 in their last 17 games) in
which they were destroyed in a hurry, down, 28-3, by halftime in
part because of a coaching blunder when Carroll opted to go for it
on fourth and 2 at the Falcon 13 with the score already 21-3 and
his team floundering and in need of any kind of success.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking the chip-shot field goal just to calm the
waters, he went for the score and got one _ a 71-yard fumble return
by Atlanta defensive end Chuck Smith after Bledsoe was sacked by
Lester Archambeau and the ball popped loose. It was all over after
that with 30 minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field goal didn't look that significant at the time,''
Carroll said. ``As you look at it now, we would have loved to have
it because that play was an enormous play in the game. I just
thought we had a chance with a couple of yards there to go ahead
and make a first down. We thought we had a good call. We thought we
could make it. We went in with that thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they thought wrong, which is fitting because for too long
the Patriots have been a team that thinks wrong. Self-confidence is
a good thing. Self-indulgence is not. And these Patriots have
indulged themselves with their personal delusions all summer and
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has come to this. It has come to a moment when no one can
deny any more what their old mentor used to say. You are what you
are, and this morning they are 5-4 and a battered team.
</P>
<P>
   But, just as they were not as good as they seemed when they beat
the Kansas City Chiefs, 40-10, a month ago, they are not as bad as
the team that made a 61-point reversal of fortunes Sunday, losing
by 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, like a drunk who has to hit skid row to know he has a
problem, the New England Patriots hit bottom and saw what they'd
become. They are a team in trouble but also one that can play
better than it has the past month if each one of them will resolve
to take care of his own business and accept responsibility for his
actions every play. Not on the big plays but on all the plays,
because you never know when the biggest play will come.
</P>
<P>
   They are a team that needed to acknowledge, as Lawyer Milloy
jokingly did last night, ``It's time to panic.''
</P>
<P>
   What he meant is not that panic was the solution. What he meant
was that it was time to stop talking about how talented they are
and show it. It is time to realize they are not good enough to win
if they make mistakes, not good enough to win if they commit
lame-brain penalties, not good enough to win if they line up in the
wrong spot or play the wrong coverage or end up with their blockers
all standing up while their running back or quarterback is lying
down, not good enough to win if they can't manage the clock or
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They are not the Broncos or the Vikings or the Packers. Frankly,
at least for the moment, they are not even the Jets. They are who
they are, a team that needs to understand just how hard it is for
them to win every Sunday because there is not much difference
between this most talented team in the AFC East and everybody else
in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, at last, they seemed to understand that. Nothing could
gloss over what happened this time. No one could deny the obvious
any more. Most important, no one tried this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody here expected it to be this way,'' said Willie Clay.
``Sometimes, when you have some success, you assume things are
going to happen for you. They haven't, so right now we're lacking
in confidence. Our confidence is shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is embarrassing. It's shocking. We never thought we'd be
on this side of the ball. It's now or never, in my eyes. Panic has
been here already. A few more games like this and there won't be
panic. It'll be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, for the first time, the Patriots really seemed to get
it. Now we'll see what they do about it, because it's not too late
... unless it's already over. Only the real Patriots, whoever they
are, can decide that.
</P>
</TEXT>
