<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-$ADV30-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR-JOY-ADVISORY. 
 COMPASSION FOR A 'LEFTOVER' CHILD 
 FOR USE FRI., OCT. 30, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
 
 EDITORS: Here is a repeat of a Dr. Laura column for clients needing
it to finish out the month, plus a sample of a new column from New
York Times Special Features: Dr. Joy. See advisory slugged By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: I just got married and my husband's 7-year-old
daughter hates me. Do I have to take abuse from her just because I
married her dad? _ Detroit
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Of course she hates you, and if you were in her
position you'd hate you, too. You not only dashed her childish
fantasy that her mom and dad would get back together, but in her
mind you've stolen her dad from her. Even if the two of you were
terrific friends during the courtship, now that it's for real it's
all different. If her dad was silly enough to spring your marriage
on her, both of you owe her an apology.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is she's only 7; the bad news is that ``leftover
children'' from the man's first marriage are a major cause of
breakup of the second marriage.
</P>
<P>
   If you can remember being 7, you will have a huge advantage with
this little charmer. She's hurt and afraid and confused. She needs
to know that her dad still loves her, that you're not trying to be
her mother and that you're not going to be the wicked stepmother
she's heard about in bedtime stories and from her friends and
Grandmother. Try to be an auntie or a big sister. If you can be
patient, kind, understanding when she feels you're her rival, you
probably will have a very good friend when she's old enough to
appreciate that you didn't try to become her mother at a time she
felt the world had caved in on her.
</P>
<P>
   And I bet you'll find yourself with a happy marriage and a
husband grateful that he didn't have to choose between the two of
you.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I try to be a good guy, treat women right, be
sensitive to their feelings and needs, but they always go for the
bad guys instead and think I'm a wimp. I'm ready to change, but
where can I find bad-guy lessons? _ Toronto
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: The question is more where you can find
stop-feeling-sorry-for-yourself lessons. Be who you really are in a
relationship _ your best, truest self, right from the beginning.
Don't pretend to be some half-baked macho fantasy notion of how you
think ``real'' men act. No bad-guy lessons for you _ just a clearer
sense of who you are and how you can be comfortable. A teensy bit
of gentleness and a drop of excitement thrown in can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I'm concerned about my 9-year-old granddaughter. Her
parents _ my son John and his ex-girlfriend Jan _ broke up 18
months ago. Since then Jan has abused drugs and been with abusive
boyfriends. She has never worked and has made a mess of her life.
Now my granddaughter has become nasty, unappreciative, irritable
and just a pain in the neck. She's become a miniature Jan! What can
I do? _ West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: If you think Jan is an unfit mom, you're obligated to
get your granddaughter out of there. If not, stay out of it. Sounds
like your granddaughter could use a hug rather than criticism. Tell
her you love her and bite your tongue when you feel like saying
``If only you weren't such a monster'' or ``You're just like your
mother!''
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I'm 50, and my mom treats me like a 4-year-old. No
matter what the topic of conversation, when I suggest anything, she
tells me I'm wrong even before I finish. If I hold my ground, she
gets mad. Once she stopped speaking to me for six months because I
disagreed with her! When I try to ignore her, I feel like someone
stuffed a sock in my mouth. _ Seattle, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Take the sock out of your mouth and create a brand-new
relationship with your mom. You mother is belittling you _
literally trying to make you little, so she will still be the mom
and you will still be the child. It's the only relationship she
knows how to navigate with you. That's why it's up to you to
change.
</P>
<P>
   Identify new stuff she likes to do. Movies, museums, gardening _
anything as long as it's new and different. Then, do those things
with her. Together you'll find new topics of conversation and build
a friendship instead of a mother-daughter tug-of-war. Then when she
snipes at you, say to her exactly what you'd say to a friend: ``I
love you, but putting me down won't work for us as adults.'' As
soon as you refuse to play, there's no more game.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, NY 10168.
Questions of general interest will be answered in this weekly
column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters cannot be answered
individually.
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1998 by Dr. Joy Browne Distributed by New York Times
Special Features
</P>
