<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING HEADWAY ON A LIE-PROOF FISHING TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How would you like to go fishing with a guy who
is a professional lie-detector?
</P>
<P>
   You know what that would mean? No more tall tales. No more
stretching how big the fish was, how many we caught, or where
exactly we fished.
</P>
<P>
   That could be very difficult, I thought, as we boarded the boat
for our trip in San Francisco Bay recently. Most people are born
honest, you know, but by the time they go fishing, they usually get
over it.
</P>
<P>
   But not Jim Adams of Concord, Calif. He's been running polygraph
tests for 19 years, including testing the winners of fishing
tournaments. ``One time I caught a guy who claimed to have won a
bass tournament,'' he recounted. ``He failed the lie-detector test,
then was exposed to have a limit of fish that had been previously
caught, hidden in a cage underwater.''
</P>
<P>
   Now we're in for trouble, I thought, as we headed for Tiburon
along the Marin shore, overcast and with a light wind out of the
south. Adams, 54, looked over at his dad, Earl Adams, 83, smiled,
and I wondered, ``What if they administer truth serum?''
</P>
<P>
   What brought us together was the San Francisco Examiner's
outdoor quiz, which appears in the newspaper in first Sunday of
December. Earl was the grand-prize winner of last year's contest,
one of a best-ever 86 people who answered all 10 questions right,
then drawn for a fishing trip with the Sturgeon General, Keith
Fraser, and me.
</P>
<P>
   But Earl has had some health problems, first requiring
open-heart surgery, from which he emerged in excellent shape, then
being diagnosed with osteoporosis, a bone problem in which his back
is often very sore and continually stiff. Under doctor's orders, he
was not allowed to fish for sturgeon, especially not the giants
that we have occasionally hooked in San Pablo Bay. How big? Like 7
feet long, maybe bigger. Cannot tell a lie.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, joined by son Jim ``the polygraph man,'' we headed
out in Fraser's 24-footer into the Bay, for striped bass instead of
sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
   After scheduling difficulties, we finally were out.
</P>
<P>
   But there was that south wind. A light rain. The full moon. The
start of minus low tides. Green water turning murky. And then there
was a recent rain, which freshened the Bay and inspired a large
migration of striped bass out of San Francisco Bay and upstream to
Suisun Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The previous three days on the boat, there were 42, 30 and nine
stripers caught, a downward trend. But even then, I noticed Jim
Adams a bit skeptical at these numbers, but hey, Cannot tell a lie.
</P>
<P>
   We let our lines out, trolling Worm-Tail jigs along the shore,
our trip timed for the top of the tide when the water has its best
clarity, and Earl told us about his life, his marriage of 58 years
with his wife, Shirley _ ``It will be 60 years in the year 2000'' _
retiring in the Bay Area, how proud he was of his five sons and
daughter, and grandchildren. And he explained how he had got all 10
questions right while Jim, the expert in the family, had missed
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim pretty much got most of the answers for me, but we
couldn't agree on that one question, the one about what was the
worst of the falls while skiing,'' Earl said. ``Jim thought it was
`biff,' my wife picked `face plant' and I put down `yard sale.'
Then Jim picked up the Sunday paper and saw I'd won the grand
prize. We couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, I'd had one bite, nobody else even a touch. It
was looking grim. Cannot tell a lie.
</P>
<P>
   We tried all our favorite spots. Tried every trick. Nothing. An
hour later, with the outgoing tide now causing the water to lose
much of its clarity and turn murky, the prospects were now bleak.
</P>
<P>
   We turned a corner on a shoreline point, and suddenly: Bang! I
got a jolt on my rod, and a moment later, had one. I passed the rod
to Earl. He grabbed ahold, and braced himself in his seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's strong,'' Earl announced, ``pulling real hard. Might need
some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Jim was ready to take over, Earl turned the fish, and
tussled away. It darted, powered down to the bottom, then skirted
the boat on a lateral run. Earl just kept reeling, his eyes like
laser beams, and brought it aside. He wanted the fish released, and
with a flip, the striper was off the hook, and disappeared into the
briny green of the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   To our shock, that turned out to be the only fish of the trip.
So Fraser and I set up a return outing, this one for Mr. Sturgy,
where Earl's grandson, Charlie, could also take part. On the way
in, I explained to Jim, his built-in lie detector now cranked up on
instinct, just how good the fishing has been, and how we had just
missed by a few days some of Bay's best fishing of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we were out there were so many bass that we had
to fight them off the boat with the oars,'' I explained. ``I hooked
one that was so big, that the first time it jumped, the level of
the Bay dropped 2 feet. The next time it jumped, a boat fell in the
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, Cannot tell a lie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
