<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR HELPS DEFINE ROLE OF GRANDMOTHERS 
 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BARBARA KARKABI 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, while leaving a store, Suzette Haden Elgin passed
a group of boys.
</P>
<P>
   As she was getting into her car, Elgin heard one of the teens
say to his pals, ``Now that is what a grandmother is supposed to
look like.''
</P>
<P>
   Elgin remembers smiling to herself. The teens were close, she
said, but not quite right. Yes, she had the requisite white hair
and wrinkles, but she was wearing slacks.
</P>
<P>
   With a twinkle in her eye, Elgin explained: ``In my day,
grandmothers would have never gone out in public in slacks. In
fact, most might never have even owned any.''
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that when a woman became a grandmother, no matter
what her age, she looked and dressed the part. That time has long
since passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, grandmothers are corporate lawyers, out exploring
jungles or being novelists, artists and every conceivable thing,''
said Elgin, author of ``The Grandmother Principles'' (Abbeville
Press, $18.95). ``But you can still be a true grandmother. It is
not nearly as important that you contact your grandchildren four
times or 150 times a year as that they know when they are going to
hear from you and you stick to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Grandmothering, Elgin believes, is not about how you cook or how
you look. It's about being a person who is consistent. The
grandmother's role is increasingly important in an age when
everything changes rapidly, she said; instead of ``warehousing
older women,'' we should view them as vital parts of the community.
</P>
<P>
   At 62, Elgin is a loving and experienced mother of five and
grandmother of 10. Her grandchildren, ranging in age from 6 months
to 16, live as nearby as 30 minutes from her Arkansas home and as
far away as New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was in my late 40s when I became a grandmother for
the first time. I was absolutely thrilled,'' Elgin said. ``I have
sort of been a grandmother from birth. I have always adored babies
and children and stray dogs. I have never worried about this
problem of being old. I think people are reluctant to be
grandmothers because they have this stereotype in our culture that
grandmothers are old women, and we have a negative attitude toward
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a devoted grandmother, she is a linguist and the
author of 34 books, including 12 science-fiction novels, a number
of linguistics textbooks and a series called ``The Gentle Art of
Verbal Self-Defense'' (Wiley &AMP; Sons, $11.25). So when Elgin's
publisher approached her about writing a book on grandmothering,
she said she felt qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the book came from my own experience as a mother and
grandmother in every kind of crazy situation you can imagine,''
Elgin said. ``I have had every kind of experience, from truly the
depths of poverty to relative privilege, and raising children in
all of these situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been a working mother and a widow. I have had
rebellious adolescent children who got in trouble. I have had
squeaky-clean children who never got into any trouble. I have had
sick children and well children. I've seen the gamut. I have had
divorce in my family and multiracial grandchildren. I really don't
think there's anything I have not had to deal with. I guess that
was my good luck, because I was then ready to write this book.''
</P>
<P>
   When Elgin looked to see what was available on grandmothering,
she found little of practical value: a rather scholarly work on the
role of grandmothers in society and a book on long-distance
grandmothering. She dug up old-fashioned books on how to churn
butter and get stains out of a linen christening dress. Then there
were the trendy guides on theme parks to visit with your
grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   What Elgin envisioned was a more practical book, ``a system or
philosophy of grandmothering that every woman could adapt to her
own situation.'' She initially titled her work ``The Portable
Grandmother.'' She hopes it will help women who never had a
grandmother as a role model and single women struggling to raise
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many young mothers now with no one to turn to in a
tragedy,'' she said. ``Or to turn to and say, `Mom, show me how to
do this.' I don't pretend that a book is going to show them how to
do it, but at least it can say to them, `In situations like this,
here's how you think about it, and here are some things you can
do.' And I can tell them that it will get better.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Elgin focuses on emphasizing to grandmothers
the importance of their role in keeping the modern family together.
She also offers information for grandmothers raising their
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   She derived her ``grandmother principles'' from situations in
which she found herself again and again during her years of
grandmothering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you learn the rules of golf, and you can play on any
course at all,'' she said. ``And I figured there were rules for
grandmothering that would work no matter how bizarre the situation.
When I came to one of them, I would call it a grandmother
principle. The publisher decided to pull them out in a chart.''
</P>
<P>
   One principle: Somebody has to be the grown-up. One of the
hardest things for grandparents to learn, Elgin said, is that when
a family is grieving and in despair _ whether it's because someone
died or went to jail or got pregnant _ someone has to be the
grown-up and get everyone through it. Generally, Elgin said, it is
the grandmother who takes on that role.
</P>
<P>
   In her down-to-earth style, she tells grandmothers how to
publish a family newsletter, prepare a family history and hand it
down, stay in touch via e-mail and Web TV, take over a household
for a 24- or 48-hour emergency, deal with difficult relatives,
mediate family disputes and teach a child to crochet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the kind of practical things that older women have
learned how to do,'' she said. ``Younger women would have no reason
to know these things. Where would they have learned?''
</P>
<P>
   Elgin has some strong words for women who are reluctant to take
on the grandmother role, either because they don't want to be
perceived as old or because after raising their own children,
they're too busy for grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them, `You are going to be sorry, because if the
grandmothers do not get in there and help produce children who are
independent and self-sufficient, it will boomerang,' '' she said.
``The grandmothers will end up having to support them, and there
will go our golden years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think it is the place of older women to extend
themselves to grandmotherless families. Frankly, we have abdicated
our role. Every other culture has grandmothers who automatically
look after these things.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
