<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENOTRE-CHEF-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
COOKING WITH CLASS: LeNOTRE FAMILY SHARES CULINARY EXPERTISE 
 
By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ At half-past five, Alain LeNotre is showing a visitor
through his family's 6-week-old culinary institute when Patrick
LeNotre, his cousin, interrupts. Patrick, a celebrated chef, speaks
only French.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants us to hear the bread sing,'' Alain explains.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick sweeps into the classroom of the Alain and Marie LeNotre
Culinary Institute. He cradles a baking sheet of baguettes so hot
and fresh that they do seem to sing their charms. Alain nods
approval. Patrick smiles and whisks them away. He has much to do
before the students descend at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Biochemists. Cattle breeders. Financial planners. It doesn't
matter what their day jobs are. At night, students come from near
and far to the institute, about five minutes north of downtown
Houston. Leisure Learning cooking classes offered by the LeNotres
draw people who enjoy taking classes in which even amateur cooks
feel like chefs.
</P>
<P>
   The institute offers four levels of training in day and evening
classes. Courses range from those designed for beginners to
advanced classes for full-time chefs, the institute's real target,
as well as periodic seminars and refresher courses.
</P>
<P>
   Alain and Patrick LeNotre were reared to expect the best of the
best in any culinary arena. They inherited their love of cooking,
baking and teaching from their grandmother, Eleonore, one of
France's first female chefs early in this century. Alain's father,
Gaston, and Patrick's father, Marcel, continued the family
tradition. Gaston LeNotre is one of the fabled names in the French
culinary world.
</P>
<P>
   Roaming through the new school, Alain stops periodically. He is
checking, always checking. Are the floors clean? How are the
cheesecakes doing? Is the ground-floor cookware and utensil
boutique _ a paradise of top-of-the-line French products _
well-stocked? His culinary expertise is extensive. Even more
impressive are Patrick's chef credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But in their kitchen even novice cooks are treated with respect.
</P>
<P>
   The LeNotres stress good teaching, transmitting to others,
whether professional or amateur, the best culinary methods with
skill, patience and more than a pinch of savoir-faire. For
professional students, the institute even offers courses in the
French language at no extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups get a chance to study with the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken cooking classes in Paris and New York,''
30-year-old biochemist Mykel Ngo says at a Leisure Learning class
as he chops and minces vegetables for bouillabaisse. His brown eyes
dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this? This is the best. It's more hands-on. Most of the
other classes, you get to taste and then go home when you're done.
Here, you sit down (after class), and they serve you.''
</P>
<P>
   Students aren't the only ones who are happy about the school.
The LeNotres are delighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked about the school for so long ...,'' says Marie
LeNotre. ``So now that it becomes a reality, it is very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The new school, at 7070 Allensby off Interstate 45, is 14,000
square feet of gleaming stainless-steel kitchens, steam-convection
ovens and refrigerators so big a family could eat Thanksgiving
dinner in them. Much equipment was donated by commercial sponsors,
Alain says, noting those companies hope chefs trained at the
institute may someday order the same equipment for restaurant
kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to be delivered early this month was the ice-cream machine,
a necessity for Alain, a master chef in pastry, chocolate candy,
ice cream and catering.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston institute is modeled on the LeNotre family's
successful Ecole LeNotre Paris. Alain LeNotre, a native of
Normandy, founded the Paris school in 1970, when he was working
with his parents, Gaston and Colette LeNotre.
</P>
<P>
   Alain and his wife, Marie _ a native of Athens, Greece _ moved
to the United States in 1981, settling in Houston. They were
working with LeNotre Paris to extend the family's international
franchise of bakery cafes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, they started their own company, opening a bakery in
Houston, operated independently from LeNotre Paris. They became
well-known for their culinary creativity, catering and pastries,
and their retail outlets became familiar sights in upscale Houston
shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
   Those outlets closed when the buildings were demolished, Alain
says, and now the wholesale bakery and catering operation continues
as a separate company, managed from offices at the Culinary
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Marie LeNotre, who has master's degrees in public health and
creative writing, functions as the institute's marketing guru.
Neither Alain nor Marie teach regularly, although both assist if
needed.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's professional-chef program, with day and night
class schedules available, offers two tracks: The first combines
cooking and catering, the second baking, pastries, chocolate and
ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs may enter training at one of three basic levels. ``Level 1
is to make sure they like the profession,'' Alain says. ``Level 2
is to prepare them for entering the work force.''
</P>
<P>
   After Level 3 in the cooking sequence, students earn a sous-chef
to cuisine diploma. After Level 3 in the bakery sequence, they earn
a sous-chef patissier diploma. Advanced courses are offered at
Level 4.
</P>
<P>
   The training is not cheap. Tuition ranges from $325 for a
one-week, three nights per week, evening course to $7,500 for the
full 10 weeks in the daytime program or 20 weeks in the evening
program. The evening program takes longer because students attend
only three nights per week, rather than five days per week.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, which has 14 professional students now,
recommends that beginning chefs complete at least the first two
levels before seeking professional employment. Chefs seeking
advanced training may attend on a per-week basis, or sign up for
advanced seminars offered periodically.
</P>
<P>
   Not all students dream of working as chefs. Some are simply
determined to learn to really cook. Evening students in the
professional classes include an attorney, a salesclerk and a
businessman. Day students come from all walks of life. Two
students, a brother and a sister, are studying while preparing to
open a restaurant in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Classes are limited to 10-15 students to ensure that training is
hands-on. The institute has four full-time and four part-time
teachers. There are plans for different chefs to be employed as
teachers so that students learn fresh approaches. In addition,
expert chefs periodically will be used. For example, beginning in
January, chef Nicole Routhier, an expert in French and Vietnamese
cuisine, will teach a series of 10 Leisure Learning classes on
Saturday at the institute. International cuisines to be explored
range from Japanese to Italian.
</P>
<P>
   The Leisure Learning classes cost $55 per three-hour class. Each
is usually part of an ongoing series, held on weeknights or
Saturdays. Students sign up for one class at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The institute also offers continuing-education opportunities for
professional chefs and a technical-assistance center for
restaurants, food-service companies, cruise lines and related
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Institute students will learn some of the 700 recipes brought to
the institute by Patrick LeNotre, an award-winning cuisine, bakery
and pastry chef who earned fame as an executive chef at two of the
family's restaurants in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick's recipes range from basic sauces, stews, soups and main
dishes to Normandy eel cooked in an apple-cider base and
bouillabaisse made with an entire blue crab ground by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Students may learn to create an Eiffel Tower from chocolate or
to prepare caramelized fig tarts.
</P>
<P>
   And those who decide to pursue such pleasures professionally
should find a wide-open market.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for new chefs has been high and is expected to continue
to grow. A restaurant industry association projects that U.S.
restaurant sales will exceed $320 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   With sales increasing, the LeNotres see a corresponding increase
in the need for professional chefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already know (we will succeed),'' says Patrick, with Alain
and Marie translating. ``Because of the kind of students we have
here, there is a potential to train great chefs in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Chef training is expanding to include more women, he says, as
courses offered for amateurs attract more men. Both reflect
cultural trends in France and the United States in which more men
are doing the family food shopping and preparation and more women
are studying to become professional chefs.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's flexible class schedule and rapid training are
attractive to students, says S. Michael Hirsch, manager of career
development and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes us unique from some of the other fine culinary
schools is they're on an academic track and we're on a purely
skills track,'' says Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   Professional-level classes are more intense than Leisure
Learning courses, Patrick LeNotre says, but he tries to offer
important tips to both groups. Although he is quieter than his
cousin and doesn't usually join amateur students for dinner after
class, he likes teaching them.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere is ``convivial, sympathetic and relaxing,'' he
says, and professional enough to attract people who really love to
cook or want to learn how.
</P>
<P>
   In three short hours, students such as Ngo, the biochemist,
prepare a meal of several courses typical of the cuisine of a
particular region of France. One week there will be flounder a la
Normandie and Marcel Proust, with the oyster, shrimp, mushroom,
mussel, apple cider and cream sauce the author favored.
</P>
<P>
   Another class will celebrate Provence, with an emphasis on a
complex lamb stew seasoned with eggplant, carrots, anchovy fillets,
garlic, onion, roasted red and green peppers and more.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Oliver of New Ulm drives 90 minutes to attend Leisure
Learning classes at the institute. She loves French food. She's
traveled to France. She's building a home with a fantastic kitchen.
She works long, hard hours on her ranch. Cooking is the other side
of life, a time to ponder and learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I feel very creative,'' Oliver says, jotting
notes in her recipe folder.
</P>
<P>
   In class, the inexperienced and the seasoned amateur explore
French cuisine in full chef regalia. They mix, chop, slice, fillet
and sear under the watchful eyes of Patrick, Alain and Marie
LeNotre and other school staff.
</P>
<P>
   Most are a little awed by Patrick. He was voted French Chef of
the Year by French culinary critics. His cookbook, whose French
title translates as ``The Secret Recipes of Patrick LeNotre,'' has
sold well. He has cooked for the president of France and the
emperor of Japan. He has worked with some of the greatest French
chefs, including Paul Bocuse and Roger Verger.
</P>
<P>
   Alain and Marie LeNotre, who would like to see the school go
national, want to publish a cookbook that is accessible to
Americans cooking at home. They're thinking about a series of
how-to cooking videos.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick concurs, but his focus is on the kitchen and on his
periodic return trips to France. He loves his work, but he misses
his wife, Raymonde; his teen-age daughter, Caroline; and his son,
Olivier, a law student. Every four months, he returns home for two
weeks. Next year, his family will move to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In the Leisure Learning classes, Patrick is gracious and
understanding but also precise and meticulous. Alain and Marie
translate in the amateur classes; other instructors assist in the
professional courses.
</P>
<P>
   Alain notes that amateur students use the same equipment as
professional students _ except for the knives. ``Too many people
cut themselves in those first classes,'' he says. ``So we switched
to smaller ones.''
</P>
<P>
   As the class prepares strawberries for a dessert, Patrick
LeNotre demonstrates how each strawberry should be gently washed
with a pastry &UR;  &LR; brush. Never, never, never dunk the berries under
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of like a James Bond martini,'' one participant whispers.
``Stirred, not shaken.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
