<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK TO BACK YARD FOR HOLIDAY WREATHS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the harvest season, gardeners can gather colorful and
textural natural materials to assemble wreaths, swags or
arrangements for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the simplest wreaths you can craft at home are the
grapevine wreath and the pine cone wreath.
</P>
<P>
   To make the vine wreath, scout for muscadine grapevines in the
woods. Wind and wrap the fresh vine in a circle, and leave tendrils
for texture and interest. The wreath will dry hard and last for
years. The grapevine wreath is handsome on its own, but you easily
can add or subtract ornamentation such as dried flowers, seed pods,
berry-laden boughs or ribbon. Often these elements can be woven
into the wreath, eliminating the need for a hot-glue gun.
</P>
<P>
   A pine cone wreath will also last for years. Gather numerous
cones of varying sizes. Cut the bottoms off the cones, then use a
hot-glue gun to attach those of uniform size, each pointing
outward, around the outside of a heavy-duty Styrofoam ring.
Assemble another circle of cones of varying sizes, then create an
inner circle with smaller cones that are relatively uniform in
size. Spray the wreath with varnish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Natural harvests &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Use your imagination to spruce up a wreath base, whether
homemade or purchased, with natural collections from the woods or
garden. You might borrow ideas from books or catalogs that carry
wreaths crafted from natural materials.
</P>
<P>
   Evergreens can be used for holiday decorations in grapevine
wreaths or attached to wire, straw or Styrofoam forms. Tuck small
clusters of greenery such as boxwood, bundled with wire or florist
tape, into wreath bases or attach with florist pins if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Greenery is often just outside the back door. Holly, Leyland
cypress, juniper, pine, eleagnus, asparagus fern, holly fern,
nandina, boxwood, magnolia, pittosporum, aspidistra and ivy are
subjects for holiday creations.
</P>
<P>
   Pine cones, magnolia seed pods, lotus pods, poppy pods,
butterfly weed pods (spray the silk with hair spray as it begins to
pop from the pod), sweet gum balls, acorns, pecans, moss, rose
hips, cattails, jack-in-the-pulpit, moss and berries from
pyracantha, tallow and holly can be used for ornamentation. Wrap
bundles with florist tape and attach with florist pins or hot glue
as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Ears of corn, bean pods, artichokes, pomegranates, loquats,
lemons, apples and pineapples (the symbol of hospitality) up the
visual appeal, as well. Florist picks can be used to secure fruit
and vegetables to a wreath.
</P>
<P>
   While fresh flowers can be allowed to dry in place in an
arrangement, those with long stems will often sag as they dry,
destroying the lines of your creation. Therefore, those with short
stems work best.
</P>
<P>
   Many gardeners like to dry flowers and herbs to create
long-lasting decorations. Mexican bush sage, yarrow, dusty miller,
celosia, gomphrena, goldenrod, ornamental grasses, rosemary,
oregano and thyme are often bundled and dried.
</P>
<P>
   Air drying is a simple method of preservation. The South Texas
Unit of the American Herb Society makes these suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   Pick materials for drying in late morning. Avoid rain-soaked or
dew-covered blooms. Flowers are brightest when they first open.
Pick flowers just before they peak, when they are fully formed but
the centers are still closed.
</P>
<P>
   Do not dry outside. Flowers fade and green turns brown in our
humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Use rubber bands on bunches, as they will adapt as the material
shrinks as it dries.
</P>
<P>
   Hang small bundles upside down on clothes hangers. Hang in a dry
location with good air circulation. Avoid exposure to sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Drying time depends on the original moisture content of the
plant material and the size of the bundles. Usually, the process
takes several days. Stems will snap easily when drying is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Spray final designs with hair spray to discourage shedding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tools &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These tools, available from a florist, nursery or crafts store,
will make crafting natural decorations easier: garden clippers;
glue gun; florist pins; wooden florist picks in 3-, 4- and 6-inch
lengths; floral tape; ribbon (wired kind more easily shaped); and
wreath forms
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suggested reading &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Dierks' ``Everlasting Harvest'' (Sterling Publishing,
$16.95); Betsy Williams' ``Potpourri and Fragrant Crafts''
(Reader's Digest, $24.95); and Quentin Steitz's ``Decorating With
Texas Naturals: Grasses, Pods, Vines, Weeds'' (University of Texas
Press). &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-09-98 1406EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
