<DOCNO> NYT19981109.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1001 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-09 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOW YOUR SEAT BEFORE YOU FLY 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While planning a European excursion earlier this year, I debated
whether to use upgrade certificates _ a precious commodity for any
frequent flier _ to secure a business-class seat with an
economy-class ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The free booze and more food weren't important to me. The film
library was no lure; I prefer to sleep across the Atlantic. And at
5 feet 7, I don't need extra leg room. My eventual decision to
upgrade was based on one factor: Being somewhat spacious in girth,
I appreciate a wider seat.
</P>
<P>
   What a surprise! I've felt less cramped in economy class. And no
wonder. Upon return, I was perusing the September issue of Business
Traveler Magazine and learned that the Delta Airlines MD-11
business-class seat I occupied, while generous in leg room, is only
18 inches wide. According to the same study, Continental
BusinessFirst seats are 20 inches wide. Some aircraft feature even
wider seats.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the real pinch: A similar Business Traveler magazine
study of long-haul economy classes, published in May, found that
Delta MD-11 seats in that compartment are 19 inches wide _ as
spacious as any surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   If these studies are accurate, I used valuable upgrades to
secure a seat 1 inch narrower than I had originally booked in the
back of the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More changes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delta has subsequently announced plans to follow Continental's
successful policy of combining first and business classes on
trans-Atlantic flights. That should result in more comfortable
seating.
</P>
<P>
   But I relate my predicament because the November and December
holiday seasons represent the busiest travel periods for infrequent
fliers. Maybe they can profit from my mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Whether we travel once a year _ or once a week _ we share a
common bond in that we appreciate comfort at 35,000 feet. And not
all airplane seats are created equal.
</P>
<P>
   Did you realize, for instance, that middle seats _ no aisle, no
window _ comprise 32 percent of all available seats aboard an
American Airlines DC-10? But only 13 percent of the seats on
American's Boeing 767 are in the middle. Many passengers aren't
aware that up to 10 percent of the seats on some aircraft don't
fully recline.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures were published in the October issue of the monthly
Consumer Reports Travel Letter as part of a study of coach classes
in wide-bodied aircraft aimed at discovering ``The Worst Seats in
the Sky ... and How to Avoid Them.''
</P>
<P>
   The report identified an estimated 77,000 undesirable seats _
specifically, nonrecliners, middles and seats near bathrooms where
long lines form _ on 800 jumbo jets operated by 11 airlines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Letting travelers know &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Reports Travel Letter is urging airlines to make
specific information available to travelers. The publication
credits Houston-based Continental for adopting a policy to equip
reservations agents with knowledge about seat-recline on all jets.
It also encourages passengers to ask questions about specific
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Even when traveling on narrow-bodied, single-aisle aircraft _
more uniform in their design _ passengers can enhance their
enjoyment by acting on priorities: Request a window seat if the
view is important, an aisle if you want easier bathroom access or
shoulder room. Inquire about sitting in an exit row, where leg room
is substantial (although airlines often hold these rows until they
can ensure that occupants are physically able to assist in case of
an emergency).
</P>
<P>
   Passengers must be more assertive today in stressing their
preferences. Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   Advance boarding passes that show seat assignments became relics
a few months back. Security measures now require airport check-in
for photo identification. Electronic ticketing is growing in
popularity. Because airlines figure advance passes no longer
represent time-savers for the traveler or gate agent, they ceased
issuing them.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, most airlines still permit us to reserve seats weeks ahead
of a flight. Travel agents and telephone reservations agents just
don't always bother to remind us of this significant option. This
is especially important for families: I've seen numerous instances
recently when Mom, Dad and the kids arrived at a gate without seat
assignments and were separated.
</P>
<P>
   For information about subscribing to Consumer Reports Travel
Letter, call 800-234-1970.
</P>
<P>
   For information about subscribing to Business Traveler magazine,
call 800-726-1243. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
