<DOCNO> NYT19981109.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1005 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CARIBBEAN-6TAK     11-09 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CARIBBEAN-6TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL-CARIBBEAN-6TAKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
and SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many travelers, the Caribbean extends a mystical lure. We
fantasize about sun-drenched beaches, turquoise seas, underwater
adventure, sipping rum punches on a pirate boat.
</P>
<P>
   And all that does indeed beckon _ and reward _ vacationers.
</P>
<P>
   But too often we tend to dismiss this region as one entity, one
vast archipelago with a common background and common culture and
common attractions.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, each island has a unique personality reflected in its
people, its language, its history, its topography, its natural
wonders, its cuisine, its everyday way of life. Except for a bond
with the sea, Curacao is no more akin to Puerto Rico than Vermont
is to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Though the great majority of Caribbean residents are descendants
of Africans, varying influences _ British, Dutch, French, Spanish,
East Indian and countless others _ have shaped their cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Individual islands also vary widely in size: Cuba, the largest,
encompasses more than 4,000 square miles; Saba covers only 3 square
miles. And in appearance: Mountains in the Dominican Republic soar
two miles into the sky; the highest elevation on Barbuda is 150
feet. We discover a lush rain forest on Martinique, desert cactuses
on Aruba.
</P>
<P>
   We dive into a coral wonderland on Bonaire, shop in exclusive
French boutiques on St. Martin, hike and camp in a national park on
St. John, seek out exotic birds on Trinidad and Tobago and exotic
spices on Grenada, walk the cobblestone streets of a 500-year-old
town on Puerto Rico and bathe in a ``drive-in volcano'' on St.
Lucia.
</P>
<P>
   Planning a trip to ``the Caribbean'' that satisfies specific
priorities can require extensive planning. Today, in a special
Houston Chronicle Travel section, we provide island-by-island
capsules that offer perspectives on the region's diversity.
Included are telephone contacts and Internet addresses for islands'
tourist boards. Another good source for information is the
Caribbean Tourism Organization: Call 212-635-9530; or access
www.caribtourism.com. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Access will become easier Dec. 15 when Continental Airlines
begins daily nonstop jet service between Houston and San Juan,
Puerto Rico. Continental already offers twice-weekly nonstop
service between Houston and Aruba; Cayman Airways flies three times
weekly to Grand Cayman Island. Other islands are usually accessed
via Miami or Atlanta. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANGUILLA
</P>
<P>
   Location: 190 miles east of Puerto Rico and five miles north of
St. Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 35 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 9,660.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Eastern Caribbean dollar. U.S. dollars are accepted
almost everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   History: Arawak Indians long inhabited the island; the English
arrived in the mid-17th century. Anguillans actually rebelled
against independence in 1967, demanding to be reinstated as a
British Crown Colony.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful and uncrowded white sand beaches and crystal blue
waters.
</P>
<P>
   A slow pace. No large cruise ships permitted. No casinos.
Evening entertainment concentrated in the island's fine _ but
expensive _ restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Caribbean's plushest and priciest resorts,
Malliouhana and Cap Juluca.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-553-4939. Access www.net.ai.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Commuter planes arrive from San Juan. Ferries
operate frequently from Marigot on St. Martin; trips are about 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: For a treat off the beaten path, make reservations
for lunch at Koal Keel in an area known as ``The Valley.'' Beyond
the stellar Caribbean cuisine, where else will you find a bed
adorned with lace in the center of a courtyard?
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: A great escape for those who prefer water sports
and good food over historical landmarks and shopping, especially if
money isn't a serious concern.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIGUA
</P>
<P>
   Location: North of Guadeloupe and east of St. Kitts and Nevis.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 108 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 67,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English (with a unique Antiguan accent).
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Eastern Caribbean dollar. U.S. dollars are accepted
almost everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   History: Christopher Columbus arrived in 1493, but Spanish and
French explorers moved on and English colonization began in the
1630s.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials tout 365 beaches _ one for every day of the
year. All are open to the public. Numerous bays entice sailors and
other boaters; late April brings an international yachting
festival.
</P>
<P>
   About half the population lives in St. John, the capital and
major cruise port.
</P>
<P>
   Obligatory tourist stops include Nelson's Dockyard at English
Harbor; Admiral Horatio Nelson, who arrived in 1784, was among
several military leaders to use this secure area as a home base for
his fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Lodging options are varied and satisfy most budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Forming one nation with Antigua are Barbuda, situated 25 miles
to the north, and the tiny Redonda nature preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 888-268-4227. Access
www.antigua-barbuda.org.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Nonstop flights from Miami, New York and San Juan
serve Antigua. Most major cruise lines stop for a day.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Antigua suffered extensive damage from Hurricane
Georges, but most of the tourist infrastructure is now fully
operational.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Antigua has emerged into a favored tourism
destination not only with Americans but with the British and other
Europeans who arrive daily on wide-bodied jets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARUBA
</P>
<P>
   Location: in the southern Caribbean about 15 miles off the
Venezuelan coast.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 70 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 82,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Dutch. But English, Spanish, Portuguese and a local
dialect known as Papiamento also are spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Aruban florin or guilder. U.S. dollars are accepted at
most locations.
</P>
<P>
   History: Indian settlements date back at least 1,000 years.
Spanish explorers arrived in 1499. The Dutch took possession in
1636, yielded to the English in 1805 but regained control 11 years
later.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   An island of varying personalities _ a ``resort row'' of huge,
modern hotels and casinos along lovely Palm Beach at one extreme
and hidden coves and rocky passes at the other, with a desert
landscape at the center.
</P>
<P>
   For sports-lovers: Windsurfers from all over North America
gather here; golfing hazards on an 18-hole course include live
goats.
</P>
<P>
   Oranjestad, the largest city and cruise port, is clean and
picturesque with Dutch Colonial-style architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Ample nightlife includes about 10 full-scale casinos and 100
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-862-7822. Access www.aruba.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Continental Airlines offers two nonstop flights
weekly in each direction between Bush Intercontinental Airport and
Aruba.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Aruba's official tree, the divi-divi, serves as a
compass for anyone needing directions. Because of constant trade
wins, the divi-divis always point southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Aruba represents one of the most satisfying
Caribbean destinations. Despite its 2,000-mile distance from
Houston, nonstop flights make it a convenient getaway, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BAHAMAS
</P>
<P>
   Location: 60 miles east of Palm Beach, Fla. (technically not in
the Caribbean but commonly aligned with that region).
</P>
<P>
   Size: More than 700 islands and 2,000 cays with a land mass of
5,382 square miles scattered over more than 100,000 square miles of
the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 278,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English, with a musically Irish/African accent.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Bahamian dollar. U.S. dollars are accepted almost
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   History: Populated by the peaceful Lucayans for 500 years before
Columbus' arrival in 1492. Enslaved and shipped to work in the
Hispaniola gold mines, the Lucayans were extinct just 25 years
after the Spaniards' arrival. Pirates and Puritans followed in the
1600s. During World War II, the Duke of Windsor, formerly the king
of England, lived in the Bahamas as governor. The islands earned
their independence from Britain in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Boasts 1.6 million overnight visitors each year, and another 1.7
million day-trippers ferried in by no fewer than 10 cruise lines.
</P>
<P>
   Bustling beaches, glitzy casinos and a Disney-esque
marine-themed resort called Atlantis.
</P>
<P>
   Pink flamingos, the showy national bird, are 50,000 strong on
the island of Inagua, an out island _ or Family Island, as Bahamas
tourism officials prefer _ that also is home to the Morton Salt Co.
</P>
<P>
   Fantastic costumes and vibrant music are at the heart of
junkanoo celebrations on Boxing Day (Dec. 26) and New Year's Day.
These colorful extravaganzas celebrate freedom and Bahamian
culture. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Tourist information: Call 800-422-4262. Access
www.interknowledge.com/bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Nonstop flights are available from many U.S.
cities, including Miami and Atlanta. Most major cruise lines make
calls at Nassau or Freeport.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Watch sunset from The Cloister, a relocated
14th-century French monastery once owned by newspaper mogul William
Randolph Hearst. The Cloister is located in the gardens of the
Ocean Club, a pricey resort on Paradise Island, but, as ``Frommer's
Portable Bahamas'' (Macmillan, $9.95) reports, admission to the
gardens is free.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Nonstop action, family friendly. Definitely not gay
friendly. Out islands offer the seclusion and peace, but few
amenities. Nice selection of lodging for all budgets.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BARBADOS
</P>
<P>
   Location: 118 miles southeast of St. Lucia.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 166 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 258,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Barbados dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: Barbados was colonized in 1627 by the British, who had
uninterrupted control for 300 years. The Bajans earned their
independence in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Home of Mount Gay, the world's oldest distiller of rum. This
island also is where the word ``rum'' originated.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred religions are represented here. Among the
sanctuaries is the oldest Jewish synagogue in the Western
Hemisphere. It dates from 1654.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling hills, cricket matches and polo ponies recall the
island's long history with Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Surfers risk their necks and boards at Bathsheba Beach.
</P>
<P>
   American tourists risk their necks driving on the left in a
moke, a locally manufactured electric car that is no bigger than a
golf cart.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-221-9831.Access www.barbados.org.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Nonstop jet service is available via Miami and
New York; frequent flights arrive from Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Hot jazz and cool ocean breezes are on tap Jan.
13-17 at the Barbados Jazz Festival. Among the featured performers
will be Kenny G and Earth, Wind and Fire. Call 888-227-2236.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Tourism has a long history in Barbados. George
Washington visited in 1751; it was the future president's first and
only international trip. His most memorable souvenir: a case of
smallpox. Today the island gets high marks for its sophistication,
welcoming citizenry and fine dining. But be warned, it is not a
budget destination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BARBUDA
</P>
<P>
   Location: 25 miles north of Antigua.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 62 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 1,200.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Eastern Caribbean dollar. U.S. dollars are accepted
almost everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   History: Like Antigua, settled by the British in the 1630s.
Politically merged with Antigua in 1860.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Notable for wildlife sanctuaries, especially for seabirds;
birders come to admire magnificent black frigatebirds (whose mating
season is August-December) that have 8-foot wingspans and soar up
to 100 mph. Local fishermen can assist in facilitating close-up
observation.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 underwater wrecks lure divers, but diving is
difficult and facilities limited; filling tanks on Antigua is
recommended. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Hotels are limited and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 888-268-4227. Access
www.antigua-barbuda.org.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Commuter flights and boats arrive from St. John
on Antigua.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Like Antigua, Barbuda suffered damage from
Hurricane Georges; consult a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: This is one of the Caribbean's most unspoiled
islands. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BONAIRE
</P>
<P>
   Location: About 45 miles north of Venezuela and east of Aruba
and Curaao in the chain commonly known as the ABCs (with Aruba and
Curaao).
</P>
<P>
   Size: 112 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 11,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Netherlands Antilles florin or guilder. U.S. dollars
are commonly accepted.
</P>
<P>
   History: Much like Aruba: The Dutch took control back from the
British in the early 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   With its entire coastline a living mass of coral, Bonaire is
regarded as one of the world's premier sites for scuba diving and
snorkeling.
</P>
<P>
   Washington-Slagbaai National Park serves as a preserve for
iguanas and exotic birds; about 170 bird species have been
identified here.
</P>
<P>
   No worries about crowding from thousands of cruise passengers;
only small ships dock here. Despite recent hotel development,
Bonaire remains a quiet retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-266-2473. Access www.bonaire.org.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Air Aruba offers connecting jet service from
Miami and other U.S. gateways via Aruba; Continental offers nonstop
service between Houston and Aruba, where connections are available.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Bonaire is one of only four places in the world
where flamingo colonies breed. More than 10,000 flamingos call this
island home.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: This is the Caribbean's No. 1 destination _ and one
of the world's best _ for those who relish underwater exploration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH VIRGIN ISLANDS
</P>
<P>
   Location: 60 miles east of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Size: More than 50 rocks, islands and cays with a total area of
59 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 13,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: Discovered by Columbus in 1493, it was a favorite
hideaway of buccaneers such as Henry Morgan and Blackbeard. A
member of the Commonwealth, BVI became self-governing in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Just says no to mega-size cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   Deadman's Bay on Peter's Island typifies the laid-back and
lonely bathing beach.
</P>
<P>
   Neverland for sailors, who can explore isolated inlets, picnic
on palm-fringed beaches and then dock for an evening of reggae and
rum.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-835-8530. Access
www.bviwelcome.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Take a flight from San Juan on Puerto Rico (or
from one of another half-dozen Caribbean islands) or ferry over
from the U.S. Virgin Island of St. John, which is less than two
miles from Tortola, BVI's largest island.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Are you the host with the most (money)? Consider a
vacation on Necker Island, owned by billionaire Richard Branson.
The 74-acre island boasts a Balinese-style house with panoramic
views, swimming pools, a white-sand beach and a fine European chef.
You can invite as many as 23 guests, which just about equals the
number of staff that will be at your service. Prices start at
$13,000 per day for up to seven guests. Access
www.neckerisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Times are changing in the British Virgin Islands.
While these islands will never match the welcome mat put out by
neighbors St. John and St. Thomas of the U.S. Virgin Islands, the
BVI is working on its infrastructure to lure more tourists,
particularly from the United States. Go now so you can bemoan the
changes on your second visit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAYMAN ISLANDS
</P>
<P>
   Location: South of Cuba and west of Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Grand Cayman is 76 square miles, Cayman Brac 15 square
miles and Little Cayman 11 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 32,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Cayman Islands dollar. The U.S. dollar is widely
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding scuba diving and snorkeling.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Mile Beach on Grand Cayman is lined with high-quality
hotels and condominiums
</P>
<P>
   Tortuga Rum Cakes, available in George Town (the largest town
and cruise port), make distinct gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to a turtle farm on Grand Cayman can observe turtles of
all sizes and ages _ and even hold them.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 713-461-1317 or 800-346-3313. Access
www.caymanislands.ky.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Cayman Airways offers three round trips weekly
between Bush Intercontinental Airport and Grand Cayman.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: If you are told to go to Hell on Grand Cayman,
don't take offense: A jagged rock formation known as ironshore is
named Hell, and it even boasts a post office where you can get mail
stamped from Hell.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: The Caymans, a major banking center, are clean and
virtually crime-free; residents have a high literacy rate and
standard of living and are among the most courteous in the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CUBA
</P>
<P>
   Location: 90 miles south of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 42,803 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 11 million.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Cuban peso.
</P>
<P>
   History: Cuba was discovered by Columbus in 1492, but Spain did
not begin to colonize until about 1511. The United States aided a
Cuban rebellion against Spain in 1898, and the country earned its
independence in 1902. A revolution in 1959 followed many years of
dictatorial rule in Cuba. Fidel Castro, the revolution's leader,
then instituted a communist system of government.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 416-362-0700. Access www.cubaweb.cu.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: It is not illegal for Americans to visit Cuba, but
it is against the law to spend money there because of a trade
embargo that has been in effect since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CURAAO
</P>
<P>
   Location: 35 miles north of Venezuela and 42 miles east of
Aruba.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 174 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 170,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Dutch and Papiamento. English is widely spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Netherland Antilles florin or guilder.
</P>
<P>
   History: Curaao has been the administrative capital of the ABC
islands (also including Aruba and Bonaire) since the Dutch arrived
in 1634.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Shares the same beautiful turquoise waters as sister islands
Aruba and Bonaire; diving is excellent, but beaches aren't an
asset.
</P>
<P>
   In capital city of Willemstad, the waterfront is lined with
beautiful Dutch gable houses bathed in pastel colors; it's easy to
imagine being in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Famed for Curaao liqueur; distillery tours are available on
weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   A ``seaquarium'' introduces more than 400 varieties of tropical
fish, sponges and corals.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-270-3350. Access
www.caribtourism.com on the Internet and follow instructions for
information on Curaao.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: American Airlines offers connecting service
between Houston and Curaao via Miami. Continental has twice weekly
service between Houston and Aruba; Air Aruba serves Curaao from
Aruba.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: From Islands magazine's December issue (available
on newsstands for $4.95): The latest curiosity is the Curaao
Ostrich and Game Farm, where 600 of the world's largest birds strut
their stuff. Most are raised for export.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: A Dutch influence _ on food, architecture and
lifestyle _ shows here more than on any other Caribbean island.
Wide-bodied jets arrive daily with tourists from the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOMINICA
</P>
<P>
   Location: 52 miles northeast of Martinique.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 290 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 72,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English, but you'll also hear a French Creole patois.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: East Caribbean dollar. U.S. dollar accepted almost
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   History: Columbus named the island in 1493. It was colonized by
the French in the 18th century and taken over by the British in
1815. Independence came in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Pure-blood Carib Indians still live in an area known as the
Carib Indian Territory on the northeast corner of the island.
</P>
<P>
   365 rivers and hundreds of waterfalls, but just 700 guest rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Not known for beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti is the only Caribbean country poorer than Dominica.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 212-475-7542.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Flights arrive from Puerto Rico and a half-dozen
other Caribbean islands. Ferry service is available from Martinique
and Guadeloupe.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: A rigorous, half-day hike steers visitors to the
Boiling Lake in Morne Trois Pitons National Park. This volcanic
chimney is the largest of its kind in the world. Creating a
200-foot-wide lake that boils in the middle; it's only about 190
degrees around its rim.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Dominica is the destination for the adventurous
ecotraveler who shuns nightlife and creature comforts for the
opportunity to hike rugged mountain trails, spy rare birds in the
rain forest or explore an underwater volcanic crater.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOMINICAN REPUBLIC
</P>
<P>
   Location: Occupies two-thirds of the island of Hispaniola (with
Haiti covering the other third) between Puerto Rico and Cuba about
800 miles south of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 30,000 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Dominican peso.
</P>
<P>
   History: Oldest European settlement in the Western Hemisphere;
Columbus' first landing in the New World was here in 1492. Governed
at times by France, Spain, Cuba and self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   About 250 miles of sparkling beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous moderately priced all-inclusive resorts, especially
popular with Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme poverty in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   Widely varied topography, with Pico Duarte the highest mountain
in the Caribbean at 10,400 feet; national parks cover 10 percent of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 888-374-6361 or 212-768-2481.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: American Airlines offers connecting service
between Houston and Santo Domingo via Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: From ``Fodor's Exploring Caribbean'' (Fodor's,
$19): ``Dominicans use abundant native fruit to make exotic and icy
milkshakes known as `bastidas.' Flavors include `pina' (pineapple),
`china' (orange), `lechola' (pawpaw) and `guanabana' (soursop).'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bottom line: The island's poverty, crime and unreliable power
sources are factors to consider when planning a trip; those who
visit are rewarded by a rare combination of historical and natural
wonders. Some areas, including the Punta Cana resort region, were
badly damaged by Hurricane Georges. Consult a travel agent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   GRENADA
</P>
<P>
   Location: 90 miles north of Trinidad in the southern Caribbean,
part of a three-island nation that also includes the tiny islands
of Petit Martinique and Carriacou.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 133 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 96,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Eastern Caribbean dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: Discovered by Columbus on his third voyage in 1498.
First settled by French. Ruled alternatively by French and British.
Declared independence from the British Commonwealth in 1974.
Subject of first modern coup in the English-speaking Caribbean in
1979 by Maurice Bishop, who had ties to Fidel Castro's Cuban
regime. Controversial U.S. military intervention in 1983 has led to
regular democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   The island of spice _ nutmeg, mace, cocoa beans, cinnamon,
allspice, bay leaves, cloves and more. Vendors sell packets of
spices at bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Anse beach, one of several lovely stretches of sand.
</P>
<P>
   Picturesque landscape of mountains, valleys and streams.
</P>
<P>
   Popular with hikers; trails of varying difficulty lead into rain
forests, along cliffs, past waterfalls and through lush gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-927-9554.Or access
www.grenada.org.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: American Airlines offers connecting service via
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: From ``Fodor's Exploring Caribbean'' (Fodor's,
$19): ``It was on Grenada that the Caribbean rum punch was
perfected (when a planter sprinkled nutmeg into his guests' glasses
at a party in 1813).'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bottom line: Don't let images of the 1980s U.S. military action
dissuade. Those who enjoy hiking or otherwise escaping into natural
paradises will find Grenada accommodating. Wonderful aromas enhance
the ambience on the Spice Island.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GUADELOUPE
</P>
<P>
   Location: 140 miles southeast of St. Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Two islands totaling 530 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 385,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: French. English is spoken only in the major resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: French franc.
</P>
<P>
   History: Discovered by Columbus in 1493, Guadeloupe was first
colonized by the French about 1635. The settlers, however, were
ill-equipped for tropical life and growth stagnated. Emboldened by
the French Revolution, the islanders asserted their independence,
abolished slavery and opened the door for British occupation. Bad
call. French forces were sent to restore order and oust the Brits.
More than 4,000 Guadeloupians lost their heads on the guillotine.
The British were to invade Guadeloupe once again in 1810, but
surrendered the island back to the French in 1815.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Characteristics: &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Islanders vote in France's national elections and are entitled
to French social benefits.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million visitors each year come for a Jekyll-Hyde
experience: peaceful countryside and lively resort areas.
</P>
<P>
   Nude beaches and black-sand beaches are popular and abundant.
</P>
<P>
   Once designated by Jacques Cousteau as one of the top 10 dive
spots in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-391-4909. &UR;  &LR; Access www.fgtousa.org.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Nonstop flights from Miami and direct flights
from New York. Frequent commuter ferry service operates between
Martinique and Guadeloupe.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: A short but memorable flight or a ferry crossing
will take you to two of Guadeloupe's most exceptional experiences:
the satellite islands of Iles des Saintes and Marie-Galente.
Visitors will discover windmills, fishing villages, sheep farms,
unspoiled beaches and charming but rustic accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: A diverse experience: French croissants, creole
cuisine, vibrant beaches and zouk music.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HAITI
</P>
<P>
   Location: Occupies one-third of the island of Hispaniola between
Puerto Rico and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 10,714 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 6 million.
</P>
<P>
   History: The first 40 European settlers, left by Columbus in
1492, died. Later, African slaves endured decades of torture at the
hands of French colonial masters before rebelling in 1804,
declaring independence and forming the world's first black
republic.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 212-697-9767.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: As recently as the 1960s, Haiti's beautiful
beaches, varied topography and arguably the finest handicraft and
native art in the Caribbean made it a popular tourist destination.
Now it is the Western Hemisphere's poorest country, seriously
overcrowded and wracked with political instability. Tourism is not
recommended. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; (MORE) &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA
</P>
<P>
   Location: 90 miles south of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 4,243 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English, mon.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Jamaican dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: The motto ``Out of many, one people'' describes the
island's history as much as it reflects its diversity. The Arawak
settled as early as A.D. 700. Christopher Columbus showed up in
1494.Spaniards began colonizing about 1510. The English invaded
about 1655. Slavery allowed Jamaica to develop into the world's
largest sugar producer. It also led to centuries of strife, pain,
rebellion and death. Slavery was finally abolished in 1874. Jamaica
earned its independence in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Birthplace of Bob Marley and James Bond.
</P>
<P>
   A plethora of all-inclusive resorts and hot honeymoon hideaways.
</P>
<P>
   River rafting, ballooning, diving, mountain biking, horseback
riding, sport fishing, swimming, hiking, snorkeling. Just how many
vacation days do you have?
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-526-2422.Access
www.jamaicatravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Air Jamaica serves both Montego Bay and Kingston
from U.S. gateways that include Atlanta, Chicago and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Quirky Negril was once ``the'' place to be, but
Palm Beach (Fla.) Post travel writer Cheryl Blackerby is telling
tourists to head to the east coast: ``Port Antonio is the place to
enjoy the real Jamaica: to hike the mountains and cool off in a
waterfall, to ride a bike down the winding roads of a 5,000-foot
peak, to wander the countryside and meet people accessible only by
steep, muddy trails.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Jamaica has gotten a bad reputation for its crime
rate and pushy peddlers. But its stunning beaches and cheerful
populace can't be beaten. This is a destination for the adventurer,
nature lover and sun worshiper. Like its rum, Jamaica is
intoxicating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARTINIQUE
</P>
<P>
   Location: Between Dominica to the north and St. Lucia to the
south.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 425 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 360,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: French and Creole. English is spoken in most tourist
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: French franc.
</P>
<P>
   History: Except for brief English occupancies, the French have
ruled since 1635. In 1946, Martinique became a French Department
and in 1974 an Overseas Region.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   One of the most fertile Caribbean islands.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of species of tropical plants in the Jardin de Balata.
</P>
<P>
   A museum featuring paintings done by Paul Gauguin over a
two-year period when he lived here.
</P>
<P>
   A charming French creole ambience.
</P>
<P>
   Good shopping bargains on French imports such as perfume,
cosmetics, crystal, china and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Caribbean's most picturesque capital cities,
Fort-de-France, with a yacht-filled harbor and mountainous
backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most popular islands for cycling and hiking and
favored for most water sports. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Tourist information: Call 800-391-4909. Access
www.martinique.org.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Most flight connections are via San Juan;
frequent commuter service operates between Martinique and
Guadeloupe.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: From Islands magazine's December issue (available
at newsstands for $4.95): ``The sole survivor of the eruption of
the Mount Pele volcano in 1902, which killed 30,000 in St.-Pierre,
was a prisoner named Cyparis who was protected by thick dungeon
walls. He later became an attraction in the Barnum and Bailey
circus.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: With numerous assets and 4,000 hotel rooms,
Martinique takes a more ambitious approach to tourism than its
neighbor, Guadeloupe; visitors arrive daily from France on nonstop
jumbo jets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONTSERRAT
</P>
<P>
   Location: 27 miles south of Antigua.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 39 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Not recommended as a destination because of
volcanic activity and resulting damage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEVIS
</P>
<P>
   Location: 2 miles southeast of St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 36 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 9,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: East Caribbean dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: Another of Columbus' discoveries, Nevis was in the
center of more than 150 years of sparring between the French and
British. Britain won the island outright via the Treaty of
Versailles in 1783. Then in 1983, Nevis was awarded independence
from everyone except St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics: &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Independent-minded. In an August vote, islanders narrowly
defeated a secession move that would have ended its alliance with
larger neighbor St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   No casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Gracious colonial charm oozes in plantation houses-turned-inns.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-582-6208. Access
www.stkitts-nevis.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Air connections for Nevis invariably include
Puerto Rico or St. Kitts. A 10-minute flight or a 45-minute ferry
ride connects St. Kitts and Nevis.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Nevis boasts one of the best golf courses in the
Caribbean. The Four Seasons' scenic 18 holes were designed by
Robert Trent Jones Jr. The course reaches up toward 3,232-foot
Nevis Peak and down to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: According to ``Fielding's Caribbean'' (Fielding,
$19.95): ``No one seems to move faster than a ceiling fan in Nevis,
and following a lavish gourmet dinner in a history-filled
plantation home, your dreams may well be about the luscious array
of tropical fruits that will grace your breakfast buffet in the
morning.'' Mmmm, nice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUERTO RICO
</P>
<P>
   Location: 1,045 miles southeast of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 1,650 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 3.5 million (1 million in San Juan).
</P>
<P>
   Language: Spanish and English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: Long ruled by Spain, Puerto Rico was handed to the
United States in the 1898 Treaty of Paris. In 1917, residents were
granted U.S. citizenship. In 1952, the island became the only
member of the U.S. commonwealth to receive its own constitution and
government.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Old San Juan, the city's historical district, restored to its
500-year-old splendor. El Morro and San Cristobal forts still stand
guard over pastel-colored buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Large and vibrant hotel-casinos line beaches near San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   El Yunque, a spectacular rain forest, makes for enchanting
explorations; look for the rare Puerto Rican parrot with its green
and blue plumage and red headmarkings.
</P>
<P>
   Ponce, the second largest city and center of culture and the
arts.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-815-7391. Access
www.discoverpuertorico.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Continental Airlines will begin daily nonstop
service Dec. 15 between Bush Intercontinental Airport and San Juan.
Nonstop flights already serve San Juan from several U.S. cities,
including Atlanta and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Even if you are only in San Juan for part of a day
in connection with a cruise, secure a walking-tour map of Old San
Juan, readily available near the port dock, then take off on
cobblestone streets and alleys to discover historical forts, art
galleries, museums and homes featuring Spanish architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: There are so many diverse attractions, including
beautiful beaches and luxury resorts, that ordering brochures in
advance is essential to maximum enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SABA
</P>
<P>
   Location: 28 miles south of St. Maarten.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 5 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Dutch, but English is spoken everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Netherlands Antilles florin.
</P>
<P>
   History: Became another notch on Columbus' belt in 1493. First
settled in 1640 by the Dutch, but went on to change hands more than
a dozen times. Dutch took undisputed and final claim to Saba,
pronounced Say-bah, in 1816.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics: &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Sees less than 25,000 visitors annually.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half the islanders _ both black and white _ have the same
last name: Hassell.
</P>
<P>
   But no hassles here on this ultra laid-back island. Also no
beaches, casinos, discos or fancy dining rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Its best-known ``exports:'' &UR;  &LR; Saban lace and 151-proof Saba Spice
liquor.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Tourist information: Call 800-722-2394.Access
www.turq.com/saba.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Air service is available from St. Maarten. Flight
time is about 15 minutes. Or take a catamaran from St. Maarten.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: If you've got the thighs for it, Saba offers
terrific hiking. Try the steep, 1,064-step trail that cuts through
the rain forest on the way to the top of the appropriately named
Mount Scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: There is only one real reason to head to this tiny
Caribbean jewel: scuba diving. Diving here is not recommended for
the beginner, as it is as challenging as it is rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. BARTHELEMY
</P>
<P>
   Location: Only a few miles southeast of St. Maarten.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 8 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: French.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: French franc.
</P>
<P>
   History: All but unexplored by Europeans until 1637, St. Barts
or St. Barths (as it is commonly known now) is so tiny that it
became a secret hiding place for pirates. It has been a French
dependency of Guadeloupe since 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the most chic, exclusive and expensive island in the
Caribbean. Known for luxury-oriented and intimate accommodations;
the largest hotel has 76 rooms.
</P>
<P>
   More French than Creole, with almost 100 percent employment and
high literacy.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual among Caribbean islands in that the population includes
few blacks; early slave ships passed St. Barts by.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent beaches, considering its size.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 202-659-7779. Access
www.st-barths.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: 19-seat commuter planes serve St. Barts from
nearby St. Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: We won't spoil the fun with details, but suffice it
to say that the landing approach by plane is an experience you
likely won't soon forget.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: This is the place for travelers who want to be
pampered, relish privacy and enjoy French food and flair _ and who
aren't on a tight budget.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. CROIX
</P>
<P>
   Location: southernmost of the U.S. Virgin Islands, southeast of
Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 82 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: Controlled by seven conquerors over the past 250 years;
purchased with St. Thomas and St. John by the United States from
Denmark for $25 million in 1917. U.S. citizenship was granted
natives in 1932; the U.S. Virgin Islands is now a self-governing,
unincorporated territory.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Buck Island Reef National Monument, an uninhabited island just
off shore and the only underwater national monument in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   A strong Danish influence still evident in Christiansted and
Frederiksted, the main towns.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-acre rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   Best cycling destination among the U.S. Virgin Islands. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Tourist information: Call 800-372-8784.Access www.usvi.net.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: American Airlines offers connecting service via
Miami, Delta via Atlanta; several daily flights arrive from San
Juan.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Christopher Columbus' named these islands _
including what is now the British Virgin Islands _ for the
legendary 11,000 virgin followers of St. Ursula.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: For travelers who enjoy the remote feel of St. John
and the good shopping and accommodations on St. Thomas, St. Croix
makes a good compromise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. EUSTATIUS
</P>
<P>
   Location: 25 miles south of St. Maarten.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 11.8 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 2,200.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Dutch, but English is spoken everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Netherlands Antilles florin.
</P>
<P>
   History: During the late 1700s, St. Eustatius, first colonized
by the Dutch in 1636, was one of the most prosperous islands in the
Caribbean. It was a trading center with more than 8,000 residents.
Its demise was hastened by British plundering and the emancipation
of the island's slaves, which ruined the agricultural industry.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Lovely beaches where swimming isn't advised; and great places to
swim but with no sand in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Island is known as Statia by everyone except guidebook writers.
</P>
<P>
   Like its neighbor Saba, St. Eustatius is casino-, disco- and
pretense-free.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: 800-722-2394.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Air service is available from St. Maarten. Flight
time is about 17 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: The ruins of more than 250 ships are believed to
rest untouched in Oranje Bay. Along the shore at Oranjestad, be on
the lookout for blue beads. The five-sided beads originated in
Holland and probably were used for trade with Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Early to bed, early to dive. When you return home,
you'll be tan, well-rested and still have some money in your
wallet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. JOHN
</P>
<P>
   Location: Two miles east of St. Thomas in the U.S. Virgin
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 16 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: Basically the same as St. Croix.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Almost two-thirds of the island _ and 5,600 acres of underwater
territory _ make up the Virgin Islands National Park. Main reasons
to visit include camping and hiking on well-preserved nature
trails. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Idyllic beaches and coves.
</P>
<P>
   Trunk Bay, celebrated for its 225-yard snorkeling trail but
often overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-372-8784. Access www.usvi.net.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Ferry service is offered daily from St. Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Even if you have only a half-day during a cruise,
it's worthwhile making the boat ride from St. Thomas to St. John
and taking an island tour; most cruise lines schedule excursions,
with several sightseeing options.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: The bustle of St. Thomas seems far removed once you
arrive on St. John. Instead of ducking past hordes of overly
aggressive panhandlers, the biggest challenge here is waiting for
wild donkeys to cross the road in the national park. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ST. KITTS
</P>
<P>
   Location: 65 miles west of Antigua.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 68 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 32,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: East Caribbean dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: St. Kitts was a base for Caribbean colonization for
both the French and the British, who had joined together to battle
Spain and then cohabited peacefully on the island for several
decades. After the ``friendship'' faltered, the French booted the
Brits off the island following the siege of Brimstone Hill
Fortress. St. Kitts was returned to the British via the Treaty of
Versailles in 1783. In 1983, St. Kitts and Nevis were allied as an
independent federation.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Fascinating petroglyphs createdby the native Caribs, who were
massacred in the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   Black beaches of volcanic sand on the island's northern end
contrast with its sugar-colored shores to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar, coffee and cotton are still cash crops.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-582-6208. Access
www.stkitts-nevis.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Daily flights leave San Juan as well as other
islands such as Antigua, St. Thomas and St. Maarten. A 10-minute
flight or a 45-minute ferry ride connects St. Kitts and Nevis.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: If you wake up to sparkling clear skies here, head
immediately to the Brimstone Hill Fortress, which is perched 800
feet above the sea. Built of volcanic rock with walls as thick as
12 feet, the fortress offers both a view of 18th-century military
life and sweeping Caribbean vistas.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: This is the escape for the tired, the stressed and
the early riser. More bustling than its neighbor Nevis, but that's
not saying much.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. LUCIA
</P>
<P>
   Location: Between Martinique and St. Vincent in the eastern
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 238 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Eastern Caribbean dollar. U.S. currency is widely
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   History: Occupied for centuries by the Arawak and then the Carib
Indians, St. Lucia was settled by the British in the early 17th
century. The British and French exchanged control 14 times before
the 1814 Treaty of Paris designated the island as a British Crown
Colony. St. Lucia is as an independent member of the British
Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Among the lushest and prettiest Caribbean islands, with a dense
tropical rain forest, fertile green valleys, towering mountains and
numerous banana plantations.
</P>
<P>
   The Pitons, twin peaks that rise directly above the sea along
the southwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   The hot mineral baths of La Soufriere, a rare ``drive-in
volcano,'' and a nearby multicolored waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   Remote bays and inlets _ some reachable only by boat _ and good
diving.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-456-3984. Access www.st-lucia.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: American Airlines offers connecting service
through Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Don't waste much time in Castries or Soufriere, the
largest cities; this is an island made for exploration _ preferably
on foot if time and energy permit.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: St. Lucia is one of the Caribbean's most beautiful
islands; Mother Nature is the real attraction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. MAARTEN/ ST. MARTIN
</P>
<P>
   Location: 190 miles east of San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 37 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 32,000 on the Dutch side, 28,000 on the French side.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Dutch on St. Maarten, French on St. Martin. English is
widely spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Dutch guilder on St. Maarten, French franc on St.
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   History: Dutch and French settlers found the island to their
liking. A treaty in 1648 divided the land: According to legend, a
Dutchman and Frenchman stood back to back, then raced in a circle
around the island until they met again face-to-face, thus
establishing the boundary. The same legend holds that the French
side is slightly bigger because the Frenchman drank only wine and
was faster than his gin-guzzling Dutch counterpart. Others contend
that the Dutchman was distracted by a French woman. St. Maarten is
now part of the Netherlands Antilles; St. Martin is a commune of
Guadeloupe.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Two cultures on one small island; there are no restrictions or
checkpoints in crossing the border.
</P>
<P>
   A faster pace on the Dutch side, home to Philipsburg, the main
cruise port (overcrowded when several ships are anchored offshore),
and several casinos.
</P>
<P>
   A Continental flair on the French side: Marigot is among the
Caribbean's most charming small towns, dotted with bistros and
creperies; its colorful marina is jammed with expensive yachts. At
first glance, Grand Case resembles any other one-street village by
the water, but some call it the restaurant capital of the
Caribbean; more than 20 eateries serve an international
smorgasbord.
</P>
<P>
   An emphasis on water sports and shopping, not sightseeing or
historical attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Notable for fine resorts, especially La Samana, which resembles
a Moorish Mediterranean village and occupies 55 secluded acres on
the French side.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: For St. Maarten: Call 800-786-2278; access
www.st-maarten.com. For St. Martin: Call 202-659-7779; access
www.st-martin.org.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: American Airlines provides connecting service via
Dallas or Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: This is the place to be if you are short on laundry
money: Orient Beach on the French side is the Caribbean's most
popular clothing-optional beach; topless bathing is OK at many
other beaches. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bottom line: Perhaps no other island has experienced such a
rapid growth in tourism over the past two decades. While this led
to the construction of many new hotels, restaurants and shops,
Caribbean connoisseurs bemoan the loss of an unspoiled ambience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. THOMAS
</P>
<P>
   Location: 75 miles east of Puerto Rico, 2 miles west of St. John
and 40 miles north of St. Croix in the U.S. Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 32 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   No other Caribbean island caters so openly to cruise ships; as
many as 10 per day in peak season dock or anchor at Charlotte
Amalie.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds can be intense in the downtown area, especially on peak
cruise arrival days. Vendors, taxi drivers and panhandlers have
become increasingly rude and aggressive in recent years. But
shopping bargains abound, and as on the other U.S. Virgin Islands
duty-free allowances are higher.
</P>
<P>
   Much-photographed Magens Bay is stunning in its beauty; tours
will take you there and back.
</P>
<P>
   A good diving destination, with numerous companies vying for
business.
</P>
<P>
   A wide range of lodging options, from budget-conscious
accommodations to luxury resorts _ many rebuilt or refurbished
following extensive hurricane damage in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-372-8784. Access www.usvi.net.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Delta Airlines offers connecting service via
Atlanta, American via Miami or Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Cruise passengers can avoid the crowds of downtown
Charlotte Amalie and still find good bargains at a large shopping
complex within walking distance of the ship's docking location.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: This is the Caribbean's most commercial island and
certainly a top shopping destination. Those interested in other
pursuits are advised to bypass Charlotte Amalie and head toward
Magens Bay or other scenic outposts away from the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. VINCENT AND THE GRENADINES
</P>
<P>
   Location: 61 miles south of Martinique.
</P>
<P>
   Size: St. Vincent is 133 square miles; the 32 islands that
comprise the Grenadines have a combined area of 17 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 119,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English and French patois.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: East Caribbean dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: Tenacious Carib Indians were able to keep European
intrusion at a minimum until the mid-1700s. The British finally
gained control of St. Vincent in 1763 and ruled the island almost
uninterrupted for 200 years. St. Vincent and the Grenadines
officially earned their independence in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   Captain Bligh of the mutinous Bounty introduced breadfruit trees
to St. Vincent in 1793.
</P>
<P>
   St. Vincent boasts the oldest botanical garden in the Western
Hemisphere. It was established in 1765.
</P>
<P>
   Beach lovers should head for the Grenadines.
</P>
<P>
   There's a yacht happening in the Grenadines, 7Vhere
island-hopping has become an art form. The chain is dotted with
secluded beaches and private-island resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-729-1726; or access www.vincy.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Flights are available to Kingstown, St. Vincent
from Puerto Rico, Barbados and Grenada. In addition to inner-island
flights, regular ferry service connects St. Vincent with the
Grenadines' Bequia, Canouan, Mayreau and Union islands.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Want to taste the good life? Pool your money with
some friends and take a whirl around the islands on a chartered
yacht. You can go bare-bones or plush, for a day or a week. Every
day will be a picnic, every night a laid-back party.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: While plenty of people use St. Vincent as just a
springboard to the pretty Grenadines, you'll be well-rewarded if
you give the island a little of your time. It offers plenty of
natural sights such as attractive waterfalls, exotic gardens and
the volcano La Soufriere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRINIDAD &AMP; TOBAGO
</P>
<P>
   Location: Trinidad is seven miles off the eastern coast of
Venezuela and 22 miles from sister island Tobago.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Trinidad is 1,864 square miles; Tobago is 116 square
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Trinidad and Tobago dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: Caribs, Columbus, Spanish, French, British _ yada,
yada, yada. Earned independence in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   It's all here: tropical rain forest, savannah, mangrove swamp,
marsh and semi-deciduous forest.
</P>
<P>
   Birthplace of the steel drum band.
</P>
<P>
   Perching place of more than 600 species of butterflies and 430
species of birds, both North and South American.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-748-4224 or 888-595-4868. Access
www.visittnt.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Flights are available from Miami and New York to
Port of Spain. The Tobago airport serves flights coming from Puerto
Rico and Trinidad, the latter a 25-minute journey. A five-hour
ferry ride is another option.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: The islands' location just off the coast of
Venezuela puts them south of the hurricane belt and makes Trinidad
and Tobago a good island destination for travel during storm-prone
months.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Go for a vacation of contrasts _ exotic and
bustling Trinidad and peaceful and soothing Tobago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TURKS &AMP; CAICOS ISLANDS
</P>
<P>
   Location: 575 miles east of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 40 islands covering 193 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 14,000.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   History: An influx of British loyalists abandoned the States for
these islands after the U.S. declared its independence. These new
settlers set up cotton plantations that were doomed to fail. The
islands were designated a British Crown Colony in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics: &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Islanders call themselves ``Belongers.''
</P>
<P>
   The uninhabited island of East Caicos is popular with nesting
sea turtles because of its superb 17-mile beach and its abundance
of mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find a stoplight on any island.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist information: Call 800-241-0824. Access
www.ttg.co.uk/t&AMP;c/index.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Direct air service is available out of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Insider tip: Plan your diving trip between the months of
December and April and you may be treated to an underwater
symphony. More than 2,500 humpback whales pass through this
archipelago, and their whale song often can be heard by divers.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: &UR;  &LR; Life is slow, breezes constant and clothing
modest. Another great diving destination with some distinguished
high-end resorts such as the Grace Bay Club on Providenciales and
the Meridian Club on Pine Cay. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
