<HEADER>
A1018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-1110-     11-09 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-1110-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINESE TROOPS DETAILED TO RENOVATE TIANANMEN SQUARE
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 400 words.
 &HT;    With photo placed in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Scores of troops of the People's Liberation Army were
at work Monday in Tiananmen Square, this time breaking up paving
rather than demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation is for next fall's celebration of the 50th
anniversary of the Chinese communist revolution. But the big
question hanging over the soldiers' labor is precisely when they
will finish the estimated seven-month face-lift in relation to a
less festive anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Will Tiananmen Square reopen before or after the 10th
anniversary of the pro-democracy demonstrations that were crushed
on June 4, 1989, some diplomats wondered Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Until now Chinese authorities have forbidden any commemoration
of the protests that began in Tiananmen that May and ended in a
scattered series of bloody confrontations. A closure of the square
continuing into next June would make the prohibition easier to
maintain in an important anniversary year, one that well might
tempt some Chinese to mark the sad events of a decade past.
</P>
<P>
   However long it lasts, the closure that began last week has
surprised tourists for whom a visit to Tiananmen Square is normally
a key component of seeing Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a part of history,'' said Emanuel Washington, 38, an
electrical engineer visiting this week from Freemont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see what it was about, where the students were
(demonstrating). This is a disappointment,'' said Washington, who
said he was surprised to be barred from entering the square.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation of Tiananmen Square was announced on Oct. 31, and
dozens of canvas-topped Army troop trucks were spotted in the
square in the middle of last week.
</P>
<P>
   All day Monday, uniformed military and state security officers
guarded the entrances of the new, sky blue sheet metal wall that
surrounds nearly all of the square. Only authorized persons and
vehicles could pass into the broad expanse of Tiananmen Square,
covering more than 100 acres, that until now has been open to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   At about seven feet high, the wall also limits ground-level
viewing of the roughly 500 soldiers in green fatigues and some
civilian workers who already have busted up large portions of the
concrete brick plaza, creating jagged holes and tall piles of
rubble peeking above the wall.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Why did the Chinese government choose to assign the job to
soldiers?
</P>
<P>
   A score of phone calls by the Cox News Service failed to find
the answer. The information or propaganda offices of the city
government, the Beijing City Construction Group, the Tiananmen
Square Management Committee and the Beijing Committee of the
Communist Party -- all of which were purported to have
responsibility for the repairs -- said they could not answer.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the sensitive nature of the square prompted leaders to
assure no one would sabotage the work. Perhaps the army has the
right equipment and manpower. Or maybe the price is right.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers have not been seen laboring at the multitude of other
construction/renovation projects underway in Beijing in preparation
for the big 50th birthday of ``New China'' that falls on October 1
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The official news agency Xinhua reported earlier this year that
Beijing had begun ``67 giant projects'' estimated to cost $14
billion to mark the anniversary. They range from subway expansion
to new sewer lines to refurbishing the Great Hall of the People and
the Museum of the Revolution, both located on Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   At the square, the cement bricks in an area of 170,000 square
meters are to be replaced by granite ones, the loudspeaker system
is to be revamped, and lighting improved. A new fountain with laser
lights will be added, Xinhua said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
