<P>
   GINGRICH AFTERMATH
</P>
<P>
   GOPAC _ WASHINGTON _ Newt Gingrich speaks to GOPAC Monday night
on his future and the future of the Republican Party. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Will move late. Gingrich not skedded to speak unitl about 9
p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKER _ Chris Cox (R-Calif.) withdraws from race for House
Speaker, leaving Rep. Bob Livingston (R-La.) a shoo-in for the
GOP's top leadership position in Congress. But other GOP leaders
are drawing opponents, including NRCC chair John Linder. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CONGELECT _ Question and answer with Georgia Secretary of State
Lewis Massey on when special election to fill Gingrich's seat would
take place; nonpartisian nature of the election; qualifying; and
who pays for it. (Pruitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER _ A look at the diminished clout of the Georgia
delegation with Gingrich's resignation and what happens to the pork
for Gingrich's home district of Cobb County? (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKMAN-COLUMN _ In ancient Israel, Hebrew priests would place
their hands on the head of a goat and pile all of the tribe's sins
and transgressions on the animal. Then they would banish the
scapegoat to the wilderness, carrying all of their problems with
it. It's not going to be that easy for the Republicans. Last week
they piled all of their problems on the head of Newt Gingrich, and
on Friday they banished him to the political wilderness. But his
exile does not lessen or diminish the Republicans' underlying
predicament. (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved in (k) commentary category.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ House Judiciary subcommittee holds its hearing on
what's an impeachable offense. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV _ Rep. Henry Hyde's committee held hearings Monday
with legal experts testifying about the grounds for impeachment.
May be interesting or not. AJC TV Critic Phil Kloer will monitor on
CNN,/C-SPAN. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Tentative/on merits. If a story develops, it will move in
the (l) Lifestyle category.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION-HOGS _ WASHINGTON _ Environmental concerns about
livestock farms escalated into a major political issue in several
states this year, and the big losers across the board were hog
farmers. Voters approved rigorous regulations and restrictions for
hog farms and pressured candidates to change their position on
regulating hog farms. They even voted out hog farmer Sen Lauch
Faircloth, R-N.C., who was portrayed by opponents as an
anti-environmentalist. As the large environmental groups count
their successes, hog farmers fear this growing national trend could
put them out of business. (Moscoso, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Continuing spot coverage of the
Microsoft antitrust trial. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MARBURG _ WASHINGTON _ Researchers at the U.S. Army Medical
Research Institute of Infectious Diseases, the Army's primary
center for research on matters involving chemical and biological
warfare and terrorism, announce Tuesday that they have successfully
immunized monkeys against Marburg virus, a deadly form of
hemorrhagic fever related to Ebola. The Army researchers used a
pair of proteins snipped from the virus to create a DNA vaccine
that stimulated immunity without causing disease in the animals.
The work raises hope that eventually vaccines can be used to
protect military troops and maybe civilians from at least some of
the weapons of bioterrorism. (Nesmith, Cox News Service 500)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN _ BEIJING _ Scores of troops of the People's
Liberation Army were at work Monday in Tiananmen Square, this time
breaking up paving rather than demonstrations. The renovation is
for next fall's celebration of the 50th anniversary of the Chinese
communist revolution. But the big question hanging over the
soldiers' labor is precisely when they will finish the estimated
seven-month face lift in relation to a less festive anniversary.
Will Tiananmen Square reopen before or after the 10th anniversary
of the pro-democracy demonstrations that were crushed on June 4,
1989, some diplomats wondered Monday. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 1 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-EURO _ PARIS _ The French government is launching a
publicity campaign on Tuesday, Nov. 10, to inform their public
about the Euro's advent. It is an indication of the level of
awareness throughout the European community about the impending
unified currency _ which is surprisingly low. (Developing.)
(Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SMOKE _ MIAMI, Fla., _ A tobacco CEO and scientist turned
whistlblower testified Monday in Florida's tobacco trial. Bennett
Lebow joins William Farone, former research chief for Phillip
Morris, on the stand in the $200 billion suit against tobacco
makers filed by sick Florida smokers. Farone has testified in other
trials that cigarette makers targeted teens. Tobacco attorneys, in
turn, accuse him of seeking revenge for getting fired. Lebow, head
of Liggett Group, has already admitted the industry hid trade
secrets. Other tobacco attorneys say the concession was financially
motivated and he's just trying to avoid being skinned like the rest
of them. (Staletovich, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TRUTH _ ATLANTA _ Emory University visiting professors Wole
Soyinka, Nobel prize winning playwright from Nigeria, and Desmond
Tutu, Nobel Peace Prize winner, tonight debate the merits of
justice vs. reconciliation in the aftermath of their nations'
upheaval. (Graham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Will move late. Debate skedded to start about 7 p.m. EST.
</P>
