<SLUG> BC-SWISS-JEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE THE CUCKOO CLOCK, ANTI-SEMITISM IS AN OLD SWISS TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The recently settled controversy over how much Swiss
banks owe the relatives of Jewish depositors later killed by the
Nazis has unleashed a strong wave of anti-Semitism in Switzerland,
according to a new report.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting aspects of the report are that it was
compiled by an official Swiss government agency and that it admits
anti-Jewish sentiment among the Swiss was already widespread before
the dispute erupted. In fact, the Commission against Racism said
anti-Semitism is ``endemic'' among all classes and goes back a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   This comes as little surprise to journalists, including me, who
in reporting on the so-called Holocaust gold debate received
patently anti-Semitic letters from Swiss nationals accusing us of
being part of a Jewish conspiracy. One letter that I received
declared that Swiss bankers were honest, unlike ``the Jew, Meyer
Lansky, who was the banker to the Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   The official report noted that during the debate over the banked
funds ``a wave of anti-Semitism manifested itself in letters to
Swiss newspapers, hate mail to Jewish organizations and incidents
in which individual Jews were insulted and ostracized.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Semitism achieved a ~~``high level of social
respectability,'' according to the report, because it appeared to
be in accord with what many prominent Swiss people, including some
politicians, believed. Jean Pascal Delamuraz, a former president of
the Swiss Confederation, for instance, publicly described the
action of Jewish groups to recover the money as ``blackmail.''
</P>
<P>
   Major Swiss banks finally agreed in July to pay $1.2 billion to
the claimants after initially contending that those with a right to
the funds were paid off long ago and later offering much smaller
amounts than the sum eventually agreed to. The $1.2 billion was
judged to be comparable at today's prices to the total of Jewish
deposits before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Although Switzerland likes to portray itself as a haven for
anti-Nazi refugees during the war, thousands of Jews fleeing German
Fuhrer Adolf Hitler were turned away at the frontier. The report
said the underlying cause was popular antipathy to Jews, an
attitude that it conceded ``goes back centuries.'' Some officials
who tried to help Jewish refugees were fired from their jobs, the
study added.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bankers' agreement was reached, antagonism toward Jews
has mounted, the report stated. Opinion polls show anti-Semitism
still on the rise, it noted, with many Swiss believing the banks
should not have ``capitulated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
