<HEADER>
A1061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MITCH-HONDURAS-HNS &LR;      11-09 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-HONDURAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPORTUNITIES SEEN FROM RUIN OF MITCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ By erasing entire communities from the
map, Hurricane Mitch changed the face of Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   In a land where life was already calamitous for thousands of
poor families, Mitch came as an end-of-the-millennium apocalypse, a
disaster that hit just as the country was struggling to its feet.
</P>
<P>
   According to an editorial in the Tegucigalpa daily El Heraldo on
Saturday, Honduras' losses were worse than the total material
damage caused by civil wars in nearby Guatemala, El Salvador and
Nicaragua in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the disaster suffered by the Honduran people is
worse than what any (Central American) nation suffered in
decades,'' said Jose Alejandro Arevalo, president of the Central
American Bank of Economic Integration.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Mitch _ which killed an estimated 6,000
Hondurans, left 1 million homeless and destroyed 70 percent of
agricultural lands _ the country could face famines, epidemics and
social uprisings, said Manuel Torres Calderon, a Honduran political
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts worry that the disaster could strengthen the hand
of the military after 15 years of civilian rule and leave Honduras
even more dependent on foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is an emerging sense that an opportunity
is at hand to right some historic wrongs and design a blueprint for
a better Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Efrain Diaz argues that reconstruction must include
everything from improved urban planning to environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the chance to remake the country with an eye on the
future,'' he said. ``We need a new mentality, a new attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet true nation-building in Honduras, Diaz and other analysts
say, requires more than new roads, bridges and factories to replace
those destroyed by Mitch. It requires fundamental political and
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about making things the way they were before the
disaster,'' said Pablo Carias, a sociologist at the National
Autonomous University of Honduras. ``The nation must seize the
moment to break with the humiliating past.''
</P>
<P>
   This Tennessee-sized country of 5 million has been wracked by
corruption, coups and economic stagnation _ all of which have
helped turn Honduras into the third poorest country in the
hemisphere, behind only Haiti and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Since independence in 1821, Honduras has gone through
rebellions, civil wars and changes of government. A series of
military rulers gave way to a democratically elected president in
1983, but the military remains a dominant force.
</P>
<P>
   Although Honduras was never seriously threatened by guerrilla
groups, the country became a staging ground in the 1980s for
Washington's efforts to topple Marxist revolutions in Nicaragua, El
Salvador and Guatemala. In exchange, Honduras received more than $2
billion in U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Honduras was home to the largest CIA station in
the world as well as three armies _ those of the Hondurans, the
Americans and the U.S.-backed Contra rebels fighting in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Critics took to calling their homeland ``the U.S.S. Honduras.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, much of the aid was squandered. And when the Cold
War petered out, so did much of Washington's interest in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. aid to Honduras dropped dramatically, but analysts say the
belt-tightening did some good. Partly because the Honduran military
no longer enjoys unconditional U.S. support, its size and influence
have dwindled, and civilian government has solidified.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the government said, ``We're helping the United
States in their fight against (communism), so pay us,' '' said Leo
Valladares, head of the the National Human Rights Commission.
``Now, we know we have to open up to the world and not just depend
on Uncle Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   The devastation wrought by Mitch, however, could force Honduras
to pass the hat for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a huge setback in terms of Honduras' ability to make
decisions and to act as an independent, sovereign nation without
being so reliant on the United States and the international
community,'' said Susan Peacock, a Honduras expert at the National
Security Archive in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The scramble for disaster aid has led to unseemly bickering,
even as the dead are being counted. Several newspapers have
complained that Honduras will lose aid dollars to Nicaragua, unless
President Carlos Flores does a better job of articulating the scope
of the damage here.
</P>
<P>
   Some Hondurans believe the Clinton administration, which has
announced about $70 million in relief assistance for Central
America, should do more.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to U.S. largesse during the Cold War, a recent
newspaper cartoon depicted a stingy Uncle Sam handing out a few
dollars to a hurricane victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is strange,'' the victim says. ``In the '80s, you gave a
lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' says Uncle Sam. ``But you can't compare Mitch to the
communist menace.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more radical suggestions from both Honduras and
Nicaragua is that governments and banks ought to forgive the
countries' foreign debts or engage in debt swaps for hurricane
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras spends about 30 percent of its national budget just to
pay the annual interest on its $4 billion debt. Between January and
October, Honduras spent $245 million on debt-service payment, an
amount that could pay for a new road system in the
hurricane-ravaged capital of Tegucigalpa, Torres said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the inevitable snags in the civilian
government's relief effort are bound to weaken President Flores,
who took office in January. Any such shortfalls could provide an
opening for the military, said George Vickers, executive director
of the Washington Office on Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras' army has been weakened by the elimination of the
draft, the transfer of the police force to civilian control and
revelations about army-linked death-squad activities during the
1980s. At the same time, however, recent civilian governments have
come under scrutiny for corruption and for their failure to combat
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even under normal circumstances, the ability (of the
government) to deliver services is extremely weak,'' Vickers said.
``The military will try to leverage that to their advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The efficient handling of disaster aid will be vital to
maintaining a level of national unity in the coming months, said
Valladares, the human rights commissioner. Another key is to
promote the sort of citizen solidarity and good will that Hondurans
have shown the many victims of Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mitch was a disaster, but it left behind a united family,''
said Marta Bonilla, an Interior Ministry official. ``It made us
reflect a lot. We have to stick together all the time, not just
during tragedies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Otis is a free-lance journalist based in Bogota, Colombia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
