<DOCNO> NYT19981109.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1108 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OMBUDSMEN-HELP-HNS &LR;      11-09 1997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OMBUDSMEN-HELP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CONFLICT ARISES ON THE JOB, MANY TURN FIRST TO THEIR
OMBUDSMAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are like corporate den mothers with a soothing presence,
big shoulders to cry on and a box of tissues at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   Their offices are discreet and located far from the offices of
power _ some having private exits.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, perhaps, they are independent operators,
reporting directly to the president or chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   They are company ombudsmen, and they are there to help.
</P>
<P>
   Long a fixture on university campuses and on some newspaper
staffs, ombudsmen are now making their way into corporate offices,
resolving personality conflicts before they reach the boiling
point, settling disputes over pay or helping to determine if an
employee has been terminated unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike union shop stewards or human resources managers, they
represent neither a union nor a company. The ombudsmen, created to
avert expensive employment lawsuits, pride themselves on
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Shell Oil Co., Chevron Corp., Halliburton/Brown &AMP;
Root, Texaco and the Houston Independent School District all have
ombudsmen.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the issues ombudsmen handle don't seem like major
problems to most people, but for the individuals involved, they
are, said the HISD ombudsmen, Harold Trahan and Richard Timmons.
They listened to 1,600 concerns last year from 1,300 individuals.
</P>
<P>
   For example, two coaches at different schools spent two days in
mediation because one was angry with the other for supposedly
stealing his star players. Another time, the ombudsmen helped
broker a truce between two employees who wanted to park in the same
parking space.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth F. Schaumburger, one of five ombudsmen for Chevron and
the only one in Houston, had a recent case in which two employees
who had to work together stopped talking and communicated only by
e-mail. It took three sessions and a lot of tears to reach a
resolution, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many issues, however, are more serious and can make the
difference as to whether an employee keeps or loses his job.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Annie Sandles.
</P>
<P>
   Sandles is a 59-year-old smoker who has trouble blowing into a
Breathalyzer. When the HISD bus driver was chosen for a random drug
test recently, she passed the urine test but couldn't get enough
air into the Breathalyzer.
</P>
<P>
   Sandles, who couldn't get behind the wheel of her bus until she
passed the entire drug test, got a special Breathalyzer clearance
from her doctor. Sometimes that sort of exception takes a while to
work its way through a bureaucracy, during which time the employee
wouldn't be paid. This time, however, it was smooth sailing.
</P>
<P>
   After a phone call to the ombudsman at the request of Sandles'
union leader, she was back driving her bus that very evening.
</P>
<P>
   The ombudsmen accelerate the process, said John Bland,
international representative of the Transport Workers Union of
America Local 261 in Houston. They make school officials move a
little faster and can get things done.
</P>
<P>
   About 95 percent of ombudsmen come from within a company, so
they know the culture, unwritten rules and power structures that
are generally hidden from outside view, said Carole M. Trocchio,
executive director of the Ombudsman Association in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   They're also neutral, representing neither the interests of the
company nor the interests of employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask: ``Who pays you?' '' said Wilber Hicks, an
ombudsman for Shell's Resolve program. ``If you're paid by Shell,
how can you be neutral?''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said he explains that it's in their job description to be
neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just defended the company, then no one would come to
us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The same with employees _ if the ombudsmen took the employees'
side, managers would have no confidence in them.
</P>
<P>
   HISD has an identical code of neutrality that governs its
ombudsmen, but one union leader believes that it renders the school
district's ombudsmen rather ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   They're very helpful with minor insurance problems when no ego
is involved, but when it comes to handling a real conflict between
a teacher and an administrator, the ombudsmen don't have any power,
said Gayle Fallon, president of the Houston Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   They can commiserate all day with you but they can't hand down
enforceable decisions, she said. And by the time a teacher works
her way through the ombudsman process, she may exceed the time
during which she is allowed to file a grievance, Fallon said.
(Teachers have 30 days in which to file a grievance.)
</P>
<P>
   Fallon also complained that administrators aren't forced to deal
with the ombudsmen if they don't want to. She said there aren't any
penalties for a manager who doesn't participate in the program.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon said the program was put in place to replace unions. But
the ombudsmen aren't advocates for employees, she said, and don't
have the credibility they need to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Trahan and Timmons said the ombudsmen's office has been open for
three years and they seek out opportunities to meet with school
district employees to let them know they're available. But they
can't go to a school unless they're invited.
</P>
<P>
   Some administrators aren't too excited when they hear it's the
ombudsman on the other end of the phone, Trahan said. But once they
see that the ombudsman can help, they are usually cooperative, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   An ombudsman adds another level of review, so a person feels
he's had his day in court with someone who has no interest in the
outcome, said Joe Rosse, associate professor of management at the
University of Colorado at Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the decision stays the same _ for example, a co-worker
gets to keep his choice assignment _ the employee who complained
feels better, said Rosse, who specializes in employee-satisfaction
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a bit of research shows that if an employee believes a
particular system is fair _ in choosing who is laid off, for
example _ the employee will be able to handle the unfavorable
decision better than if he believes it is arbitrary.
</P>
<P>
   The adoption of an ombudsman program has been a real sea change
for some companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, people at Shell worried about retaliation if
they complained about employment practices, said Shell ombudsman
Walter Krudop.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company is trying to change the culture to make it
more relationship-driven, and that includes bringing conflicts to
the fore. But employees are still understandably unsure whether top
company officials really want employees to come forward, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a while to build up trust, but as people hear through
the grapevine that the ombudsmen are helpful at resolving conflicts
in a confidential way, there will be even less hesitation about
coming forward, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ombudsmen are confidential and zealous about protecting the
information they receive. Unless an employee asks the ombudsman to
pursue a complaint, the information must remain confidential.
</P>
<P>
   That includes complaints of sexual harassment or race
discrimination _ if the employee doesn't want to make a formal
complaint or pursue the problem, there's nothing an ombudsman can
do.
</P>
<P>
   HISD's ombudsmen make an exception to that code of
confidentiality if an employee indicates a child is being abused or
there is evidence that an employee may harm others, Timmons said.
</P>
<P>
   About once a year, they get a call from a secretary that someone
is highly agitated and needs someone to talk to, so Timmons or
Trahan rush over.
</P>
<P>
   To keep that confidentiality, ombudsmen are keen to ensure their
clients' privacy and go out of their way to make it difficult for
visitors to be spotted. Consequently, the HISD ombudsmen's offices
are located in an office building several miles away from the main
administration office and can't be seen from any school.
</P>
<P>
   Each ombudsman has a private door leading out into a hallway, so
clients who don't want to be spotted can dash out and leave the
building through a back staircase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meet people in airports, hotel lobbies and restaurants,''
said Schaumburger. He said he was at a meeting in which he sat next
to a former client, who didn't even acknowledge his existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a lonely job,'' said Schaumburger. His office is
sandwiched in with a hodgepodge of Chevron offices, such as one for
medical services, and the health club. It's hard to figure out who
has come to see which department, he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to lunch with you, quipped Shell's Hicks and
Krudop, for fear people will think you're discussing a workplace
problem.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, ombudsmen know a lot of very interesting gossip but
tend to be very diplomatic. The ombuds, as they are called at
Shell, just smile when they're asked for some really good stories,
with names deleted of course.
</P>
<P>
   While ombudsmen keep confidential information close to their
vests, they do make reports that list the types of issues that
they've handled, with no names attached.
</P>
<P>
   A key part of the job is to identify for the president ``threads
of similarities'' before things get out of hand, such as a rash of
sexual harassment complaints, Schaumburger said.
</P>
<P>
   That confidentiality, which has been the trademark of ombudsmen,
has been challenged recently in court.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court in St. Louis ruled last year that an
ombudsman at McDonnell Douglas Corp. (now part of Boeing Co.)
couldn't keep his records secret in a case involving a manager who
had a dispute with his supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The employee who had complained to the ombudsman later filed an
age discrimination case and sought copies of the ombudsman's
records.
</P>
<P>
   The company sought to keep the records secret, citing ombudsman
privilege, but the appeals court ruled the records must be turned
over to the employee.
</P>
<P>
   While the decision isn't binding on judges in other parts of the
country, it does open the door for employees and their lawyers to
obtain a wealth of information about personnel practices from the
corporate ombudsman.
</P>
<P>
   Before the decision came down, John Delaney said he believed
that corporate ombudsman programs would really take off.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of the McDonnell Douglas decision, Delaney, a
professor of management at the University of Iowa, said companies
are taking a second look at the value of an ombudsman if their
confidentiality can't be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   While many companies started their ombudsman programs to solve
potential legal problems before they turn into expensive lawsuits,
it's hard to get a handle on exactly how much companies save by
using them.
</P>
<P>
   Several employees have said they would have filed a lawsuit
without Shell Resolve, said Krudop, but it's hard to say whether
that's really true.
</P>
<P>
   Shell is undertaking a study to determine how much money it is
saving in legal fees, which is hard to do because it can't turn
over its records of individuals, even to an independent third
party, Krudop said.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, it is considering conducting a companywide survey
that will ask people who have used the program for their
confidential input.
</P>
<P>
   While the jury is still out, Krudop and Hicks are proud that
since the introduction of its ombudsman program 18 months ago, the
number of employment-related lawsuits that have been filed against
Shell has fallen drastically _ about 90 percent. Shell requires its
employees to use the ombudsman program before they file a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The ombudsmen at HISD figure their program saves $685,000 a year
in legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   Timmons said it's hard to estimate who would have sued had they
not had a chance to meet with the ombudsmen, but the ombudsmen go
through their cases each year and try to make their best guess.
</P>
<P>
   They figure each federal court case avoided saves $150,000, and
each mediation they handle saves $800 in outside mediation fees. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-09-98 1459EST &QL; 
