<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     11-09 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following Science
Times stories for papers of Tuesday, Nov. 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATER-USE (Undated) _ In a little-noticed but potentially
historic environmental turnabout, federal analysts report that
Americans' use of water declined by about 9 percent from 1980 to
1995 _ even as the United States' population grew by 16 percent
over the same period. By William K. Stevens. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTARCTICA-WOMEN (Undated) _ Life is vastly different these
days in Mactown, as its inhabitants call McMurdo Station, the main
American base in Antarctica. As a thousand or more scientists and
staff return to ``The Ice'' for another season of work in the
austral summer, about a third of them are women. By Cornelia Dean.
With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-DRUGS (Undated) _ Medical researchers have long
done experiments either in vivo, in living organisms, or in vitro,
in glass or test tubes. Now they are starting to work in silico, or
in computers. In a marriage of biotech and high tech, computers are
cataloging and analyzing the massive amounts of data being
discovered about human genes. By Andrew Pollack. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRAIN-CELLS (Undated) _ Officials of the National Institutes
of Health are seeking legal advice as to whether the congressional
ban on fetal research applies to the primordial human cells that
were isolated and grown in the laboratory for the first time last
week. At issue is whether the many university biologists who depend
on Federal money will have access to a research field rich with
medical promise. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DEBATE-FUTURE (Undated) _ Paired essay: Reports of the end
of science are greatly exaggerated. By John Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DEBATE-LIMITS (Undated) _ Paired essay. The more we know the
less there is to discover: We are near the end of science. By John
Horgan.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHIPWRECK (Lake Huron) _ Long before Titanic mania,
searching for shipwrecks was the passion of David Trotter, the most
prolific shipwreck hunter in the Great Lakes. Over the last 22
years, he has found nearly 70 ship skeletons in Lake Huron, Lake
Superior, Lake Erie and Lake Michigan. By Pam Belluck. With photo
and map graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH &AMP; FITNESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ It is now possible to determine a
person's propensity for fracture far in advance and offer
preventive treatments for most people at risk of developing
osteoporosis. A guide to spotting risks and what to do about them.
By Jane E. Brody. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-POLIO (Undated) _ Dr. Nancy Frick, one of the world's
foremost experts on the long-term psychological effects of
childhood polio, describes herself as absolutely Type A, driven to
succeed almost to the point of exhaustion. She is the director of a
research group, Harvest Center in Hackensack, N.J., which focuses
on the study of post-polio syndrome, a very late, totally
unexpected, painful and fatiguing effect of paralytic and
nonparalytic polio that struck some 1.63 million Americans in the
1940s. By Holcomb B. Noble. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-EATING-HABITS (Undated) _ A study suggests new theories
on why and when people eat. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-WOMEN-MUSCLES (Undated) _ When the history of women's
bodybuilding is written, 1998 will emerge as the year that the
weights tipped in favor of its old nemesis, femininity. What has
happened this year might have seemed, to some, inevitable. Fitness
competitions, slenderized versions of women's bodybuilding, have
eclipsed the bulked-up muscle shows in participant and audience
popularity. By Marion Roach. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-MALARIA (Undated) _ Biologists have taken a first step
toward cracking the code of the parasite the causes malaria and
using the information to explore all the deadly organism's
biological weaknesses. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-GENDER (Undated) The Society for the Advancement of
Women's Health Research released an analysis of disease and disease
treatments showing significant differences in how men and women
fare. The society, a Washington-based advocacy group that has
championed the study of gender-based biology, identified the 10
most important findings in the field to date including the fact
that women are three times more likely than men to develop one or
more autoimmune diseases. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STANDARD FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Short takes: Though gluttony is cited in
the Bible as a sin and a sign of moral weakness, religious people
in the United States are more likely to be overweight than
nonreligious people, researchers from Purdue University have found;
like tilting a pinball machine, leaning on the rails of a stair
climber comes with a penalty _ even if it's just for a short rest;
how to deal with images of youth and alcohol on television. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Why can't you tickle yourself? By C.
Claiborne Ray.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-WATCH (Undated) _ News, notes and short takes from the
world of science and health. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
