A1146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-09 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPRISED VICTORS GOT TURNOVERS AND RAN WITH THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They thought they could win, but never like
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think it would happen this way,'' said Atlanta coach
Dan Reeves of the 41-10 beating his team gave the Patriots Sunday.
``But we did the two things we had to do to win. We ran the ball.
We got turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   It was easy for Atlanta because the Patriots played like they
didn't care, according to several veteran Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   It was also easy for Atlanta because they had a better game plan
than the Patriots, taking advantage of New England's injury
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When No. 88 (Terry Glenn) doesn't play for them, that makes a
big difference in their offense,'' said safety Eugene Robinson.
``They have no one to go to right away with the ball. We thought we
could handle their wide recievers. We played against Henry Ellard
and knew what he could do. And then we didn't think the other kid
(Tony Simmons) could take advantage of what we were going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted to do is start by stopping their wide
receivers,'' said Falcons defensive coordinator Rich Brooks. ``Our
cornerbacks did a great job. This forced Drew Bledsoe to hold on to
the ball longer, and when he did our pass rush was able to get to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted heat on Bledsoe,'' said Robinson. ``We wanted him to
move in the pocket, because when you make him move, he doesn't
throw as well as when you let him stand still.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our corners shut down their wide receivers. Then we kept on
blitzing, and they had to keep Ben Coates in to block. When we did
that, they tried to throw quick to the running back (Robert
Edwards), and that didn't work. So there really wasn't anywhere
they could go with the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offense was shut down. With New England's top
receivers out with injuries, Bledsoe had no one to throw to right
away, and the Falcons roared after him all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the most we have blitzed any team in the two
years I've been here,'' said linebacker Cornelius Bennett, the
former Bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got good pressure on Drew. When I saw them keeping Coates
in to block, then I knew we had them. I've played against them
enough to know that when you take Coates out of the game, no matter
how you do it, you have them beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' offense also had answers for whatever the Patriots'
defense tried to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in here expecting to play against the best defense we
played all year, and it didn't happen,'' said Falcons quarterback
Chris Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a crazy game. We had the lead on them so fast, it
changed how we thought it would go. It was big for us to get a play
all the way to their 1-yard line,'' Chandler added about his
39-yard pass to Bob Christian on Atlanta's first possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when our defense got a turnover and we scored right away
to go up, 14-0, we thought we could score some points. Not 35
points. I never thought we could score five offensive touchdowns
against these guys here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots appeared to have stacked their defense to stop the
running of Jamal Anderson. Even with that, they couldn't stop him.
With his running game going, Chandler had fun taking apart the New
England secondary with his play-action passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seemed to double-cover Tony Martin's side of the field a
lot,'' Chandler said. ``They rolled their coverage that way. So I
went to Terance Mathis. He's a good receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said the Falcons weren't picking on one person in the
secondary, although it looked like they feasted on Chris Canty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran the play, and took what was open,'' he said. ``The
plays we made to the tight end (O.J. Santiago) came off some
bootleg action, and we got him up the field to make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had no running game. Edwards carried 10 times for
11 yards. ``He played like he was hurt,'' said Bennett. ``He didn't
seem to be running as hard as he did earlier in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was sacked five times, and it seemed like he was knocked
down 20 more.
</P>
<P>
   However, the most negative stat about the Patriots involved the
defense. This is where they were supposed to be stout this season,
and where they have disappointed most.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, the Patriots had given up 111 passing first
downs. No other team in the league had given up 100. In fact, the
league average was 82.8.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the same weakness was evident. The Falcons threw just 25
passes, but had 14 first downs through the air. The Patriots will
be 30th and last in the league once again, and it is a problem that
has to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
