<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Nov. 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (Moving in ``i'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-WATER (Miapur, Bangladesh) _ Special Report:
Bangladesh is in the midst of what some experts say could be the
biggest mass poisoning in history. Dangerous levels of arsenic have
been found in the ground water, entering millions of people as they
drink from a vast system of tube wells. Most of these hand-operated
pumps are 10 to 20 years old, about the same time it takes the
arsenic to do its lethal work, killing with one of several cancers.
By Barry Bearak. With map graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ELECT (Rosh Haayin, Israel) _ Peace isn't the only issue
in Israeli politics: The campaign leading up to municipal elections
on Tuesday has been unusually virulent, revealing the ethnic rifts,
clan rivalries, corruption scandals and turf wars that govern local
realities. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-MILITARY (Jakarta) The head of Indonesia's armed
forced says the military will reduce its role in the nation's
politics. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-PINOCHET (London) _ Gen. Augusto Pinochet's lawyers
present their case as the hearing continues on the appeal of the
ruling that Pinochet's arrest was illegal. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KRISTALLNACHT (Berlin) _ The 60th anniversary of
Kristallnacht reveals the tensions between the German government's
attempts to look forward and the tug of the terrible past. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (Moving in ``w'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Eighteen constitutional scholars
debate what constitutes impeachable offenses before the House
judiciary subcommittee. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKER-LIVINGSTON (Washington) _ Rep. Christopher Cox of
California bows out of race for speaker of the House, leaving Rep.
Robert Livingston of Louisiana uncontested in the bid to replace
Newt Gingrich. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON-PROFILE (Washington) _ Man In The News profile of
Rep. Robert Livingston. By Katharine Q. Seelye. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-ABORT (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno announces
a nationwide inquiry into possible links between the recent violent
incidences at abortion clinics. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Supreme Court declines to hear school
voucher case from Wisconsin, allowing the state to continue its
program of providing payments to families to send their children to
parochial schools. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRIVILEGE (Washington) _ Supreme Court rejects White
House request to reconsider secret service and attorney/client
decisions won by Independent Prosecutor Kenneth Starr. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JONES (Washington) _ Newly released documents show that
the judge in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case tried to
persuade her lawyers that she should settle with President Clinton,
and offered to speak to Jones, contending a jury was unlikely to
find in her favor if the suit went to trial, By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (Moving in ``a'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (Washington) _ Flush from a victory in
Washington State, where residents voted to ban state-sponsored
affirmative action programs, Ward Connerly, the California
businessman who bankrolled the effort, said he may start similar
drives in Florida, Michigan and other states. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-REACT (Los Angeles) _ In more than two dozen
interviews with black Americans from school children to blue collar
workers, historians, writers, retired hat makers, legal scholars,
radio talk show hosts, teachers and others, the brouhaha about the
release of DNA evidence that Jefferson had fathered at least one
child with Hemings was more vindication than revelation. By Donald
Terry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (Moving in ``f'' news file) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Washington) _ Developments; details later. By
Steve Lohr and Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   CITICORP (Undated) _ Steven Black, global head of equities at
Salomon Smith Barney, has resigned, marking another change in the
top management at the Citigroup unit. By Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-LAYOFFS (Undated) _ J.P. Morgan is reported to be
preparing to lay off 700 employees, about 5 percent of its staff.
By Timothy J. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   CLARIANT-MERGER (Undated) _ Clariant and Ciba Specialty
Chemicals agree to merge in a $6 billion share swap, creating the
dominant company in the global specialty-chemicals industry. By
Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   GM-ALCAN (Detroit) _ General Motors signs a 10-year,
multibillion-dollar agreement to buy substantial amounts of
aluminum from Alcan. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-BANKRUPTCY (Undated) _ Dow Corning files its long-awaited
bankruptcy reorganization plan, three and one-half years after the
company filed for creditor protection because of thousands of
breast-implant lawsuits. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   GPU-POWER (Undated) _ General Public Utilities sells 23 power
plants to Vivendi of France for $1.67 billion. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS (Moving in ``k'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Boston) _ Commentary by Anthony Lewis.
</P>
