<HEADER>
A1158 &Cx1f; ttg-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-KIDS &LR;      11-09 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-KIDS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KID GAMES  

</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN    
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a neat little idea for youngsters for a playtime
experience at the computer: Tonka's Workshop (Windows 95/98; about
$40). It's a collection of plastic workshop tools _ saw, plane,
hammer, screwdriver, drill and spray-paint can. They're housed on a
plastic case that straps to the computer's keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Using a tool causes a key lined up beneath it to be pressed.
Kids use this no-tech interface to help Tonka Joe onscreen as he
guides them through building various projects in his workshop and
performing fix-it chores in the barn, storage shed, pickup truck,
tree house and cellar. It's designed for children ages 3 and older
and works with nearly any keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   While the projects sound complex, building them is not. A few
swipes of saw cuts a sled from a piece of board. Twist the
screwdriver a couple of times and the runners are bolted in place.
Press the spray can lever a few times and the project is complete.
</P>
<P>
   For its oversimplistic approach to the tool shed, Tonka Workshop
has drawn some reviews that imply Hasbro Interactive (the
publishers) should be taken out behind the wood shed. True, the
can't-make-a-mistake world of Tonka Joe's tool bench isn't going to
win any awards from the carpenters down at the union hall who never
had the luxury of an ``undo'' button.
</P>
<P>
   But it's for young kids, for goodness sake, who want to hammer,
pull and twist. The not-so-favorable reviews have come from the
general computing press. The reviews from organizations that cover
children's software specifically have been much more favorable.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the kids seem to enjoy the program, even if saws
never cut a crooked line or threads never strip. The old
carpenter's advice of ``measure twice, cut once,'' need not apply
in Tonka Joe's workshop.
</P>
<P>
   And to a youngster, that's just fine.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call tollfree, 800-400-1352; Web site,
www.hasbro-interactive.com
</P>
<P>
   Who Knows Jack?
</P>
<P>
   The message on the outside of the box containing HeadRush, a
trivia game for the younger generation, says the game is, in so
many words, ``not for geezers.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the purchaser knows the names of the South Park
characters, along with other timely, seldom worthwhile,
information, he or she might want to consider another trivia game.
</P>
<P>
   This one (Windows/Macintosh; about $30) is from Berkeley
Software, which has a line of trivia software under the ``You Don't
Know Jack'' title. Company officials said the younger crowd was
shying away from the line, which covered ``crusty old '70s
trivia,'' in the words of one company executive.
</P>
<P>
   So the ``You Don't Know Jack'' concept was kept, but given
additional graphics and a ``coolness factor,'' a company
spokeswoman said. It also has more than 550 questions offered in a
variety of formats, and allows three players to compete with each
other or a computer opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Questions are introduced by cartoons. Sessions have a break for
the ``game show'' fictitious sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   And to appeal to the younger audience, the CD contains one audio
track from three bands recording on Mercury Records: Motorbaby, 2
Skinnee J's and Swirl 360.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. His
recent computer columns are on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/business/tech/)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-06-98 1617EST &QL;
</P>
