<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981109.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1166 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAVEMASTER-COX     11-09 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVEMASTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    DESCENDANTS OF SLAVES HONOR ANCESTORS' SLAVEMASTER
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Janet Jacobs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Defying political correctness, descendants of
Panola County, Texas, slaves are dedicating a historical marker to
the slavemaster who brought their families here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird that black people would want to do a marker on a
slavemaster,'' admitted Barbara Jefferson-Bonner, a Panola County
historian specializing in black history. ``Slavemasters are
supposed to be mean and cruel, but he wasn't that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The marker will be dedicated for Spearman ``Major'' Holland, who
brought Bonner's family here as slaves in the 1840s.
</P>
<P>
   Holland Quarters, a predominantly African-American community, is
four miles north of Carthage in Panola County. A former plantation,
the community has been home to generations descended from Holland's
slaves. Panola County is 35 miles southeast of Longview, on the
Louisiana border
</P>
<P>
   According to intensive research by Bonner, Holland was known for
his generosity toward his slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great guy. He cared for his slaves in a unique kind
of way,'' she said. ``When Spearman left here, he left his
thousands of acres to his slaves, who were ancestors of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Path to history
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's search into Spearman Holland began with her own family.
A dedicated genealogist for more than a decade, Bonner found three
generations of men in her family named after Spearman Holland and
his brother, Bird Holland.
</P>
<P>
   ``You run across several different things as you're doing
research,'' Bonner said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's sources included census reports, family Bibles, tax
records and other legal documents, as well as interviews with ``the
old heads,'' as she calls community elders.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner said she particularly questioned why former slaves would
name their children after a slave owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``A slavemaster was a slavemaster,'' Bonner said. ``He could be
good, bad or indifferent, but I definitely wouldn't name my
children after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in going through and listening to the elders and the
records, he was a great man,'' Bonner said. ``That was proved
because they continued to name their children after him and his
brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``And these were the blacks naming their children after the
slavemaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Lives of contradictions
</P>
<P>
   In addition to leaving his land to his former slaves, Holland
also was reputed to be a kind man while slavery was in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the slaves would complain about family members they'd
been separated from, he would find them and buy them,'' Bonner
said. ``One woman who didn't have any family, he bought her a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just trying to make sure he had all his families there,
and of those, he wanted them to be happy,'' Bonner explained.
</P>
<P>
   Holland was born in Virginia in 1801 and traveled to East Texas
by way of Carthage, Miss. A wealthy man involved in politics,
Holland was elected to the state Legislature and represented
Harrison County, which encompassed what is now Panola County, in
the Convention of 1845 and in the first Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Spearman and his family) were deep into politics,''
Bonner said. ``Their slaves cared for the land while he was away.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories passed down through the years recounted that when
Spearman came home after a trip he would bring back gifts for
everyone on the plantation, including the slaves, Bonner said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Civil War, Spearman served as a captain in the Texas
State Troops, Fourth Brigade. After the war, Holland and his family
moved away from East Texas, and Holland left the land ``to those
who had worked it,'' Bonner said.
</P>
<P>
   The gift of land
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been word of mouth through the family how we got the
land,'' Bonner said. ``It was so much land, blacks weren't supposed
to have that much land.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a type of caretaker relationship developed, where the
former overseer who had worked for Holland kept the land in trust
for the ex-slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner found records showing sales of large pieces of land from
the overseer to former slaves for amounts as little as $1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the nine families who came here, all of them had a piece,''
Bonner said. ``It happened to people who just deserved a piece of
the pie, and they got that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1867, the freedmen changed the name of their community from
Holland Plantation to Holland Quarters, but they still sought a way
to repay Holland, Bonner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they could do for him was to name our children after him
and remember,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bird's legacy
</P>
<P>
   The Holland generosity wasn't limited to Spearman, according to
Bonner's research. Spearman's brother, Bird, was known to buy
slaves just to give them their freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1850, Bird bought three young male slaves from Spearman
and took them north to be educated at Oberlin College in Ohio. One
of the former slaves, Milton Holland, went on to join the Union
Army during the Civil War and was the first black Texan to be
awarded the Medal of Honor. Another of the former slaves, William
Holland, became a Texas state legislator after the war. He
introduced the bill to create what is now Prairie View A&AMP;M
University.
</P>
<P>
   Bird Holland, who had been Secretary of State in 1861, joined
the Confederate army and was killed in the Battle of Mansfield in
1864.
</P>
<P>
   Marking history
</P>
<P>
   The idea to request a historical marker for Spearman Holland may
have seemed odd on the surface, but it has some logic, said Emily
Bell, historian with the Texas Historical Commission, the panel
that approves and creates historical markers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unusual, but not terribly surprising to me that the
descendants of ex-slaves would request the marker,'' Bell said.
``He gave the land that started the town. So in a way, he's the
founder of their town.''
</P>
<P>
   The marker was submitted to the state last spring and finally
approved in August. One of the members of the review board wrote
that the story was ``heartwarming.''
</P>
<P>
   Historical markers don't just mark significant places, Bell
said, they also indicate things of human importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the reasons he should have a marker is to tell
those human stories,'' she said. ``This will tell people there was
that relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Slavery was a way of life, Bonner said. ``It wasn't always as
bad as people thought,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By adding to history, the descendants of slaves show that their
ancestors were more than just victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``To add to history is a great thing,'' Bonner said. ``We're
doing our part.''
</P>
<P>
   Because she was unable to find where Holland is buried, the
marker, which should arrive next year, will be placed in the front
yard of one of Holland Quarters' most respected elders -- Annie Lou
Rayson-Lister. Lister taught school in Holland Quarters for 32
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the oldest living teacher that had taught at Holland
Quarters,'' Lister said from her daughter's home in Dallas. ``I was
reared in Holland Quarters, and I taught everybody in Holland
Quarters, just about. Mothers, grandmothers and
great-grandmothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lister said the fact that the marker was to honor a former
slavemaster does not concern her.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it doesn't bother me,'' Lister said. ``It's perfectly all
right with me. ``I've always heard about the slaves that he had,''
Lister said. ``When slavery was abolished, he got up and left and
gave that land to the slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've ever heard was that he was good to his slaves,''
Lister said.
</P>
<P>
   In doing the work, Bonner said she believed she was contributing
to a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like reliving the lives of my great-great-grandparents
and wishing it didn't have to be this way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they're watching and saying, 'You're doing a good
thing.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
