<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1170 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETE-WILSON-HNS &LR;      11-09 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETE-WILSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIONS TEAMED UP ON WILSON TO DEFEAT GOP HOPES IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ For some California voters, last week's
election was about repudiating a Republican who wasn't on the
ballot: Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Although he walked a pragmatic path during his eight years as
governor and will leave office with the vast majority of voters
feeling good about the state, Wilson energized some wealthy and
well-organized giants _ trade unions, Indian tribes and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Targeting Wilson as much as the Republican candidate for
governor, Dan Lungren, unions spent more than $33 million to help
elect Lt. Gov. Gray Davis to succeed Wilson, who was barred by law
from running for a third term. The unions set up hundreds of phone
banks, dragged people to the polls, mailed literature to millions
of voters and walked precincts.
</P>
<P>
   The spillover, analysts believe, helped Davis and other
Democrats sweep the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a happy night for Latinos, for union members ... and
pretty much everyone Wilson has managed to anger in the past four
years,'' Gary Segura, assistant professor at Claremont Graduate
University, said of Tuesday's election.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat for California Republicans may put a dent in Wilson's
ambition to become his party's nominee for president in 2000.
Another potential Republican candidate for the presidency, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, won by a landslide Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, the nominal head of the Republican Party in California,
was rarely seen campaigning for Lungren. Instead, he spent the
second-to-last week of the campaign traveling in other states to
help other GOP candidates _ and boost his own national stature.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked how much responsibility Wilson should take for
the GOP debacle in California on Tuesday, gubernatorial spokesman
Sean Walsh said: ``Virtually none.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's efforts to restrict political activities by labor
unions and end affirmative action had nothing to do with the
impressive Democratic showing, Wilson administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said trade and teachers unions already were energized by
the Davis campaign. He said the unions, which contributed $7
million to the Davis campaign, smelled a victory after Lungren
faired poorly in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the Lungren campaign, Wilson's people say, had
more to do with the attorney general's inability to reach moderate
and women voters. In addition, Walsh said, the polls showed that 70
percent of Californians believed the state was headed in the right
direction after eight years under Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're leaving office, that is a phenomenal record'' to
leave for Lungren, said Walsh, noting that Davis frequently aligned
himself during the campaign with Wilson as a way to demonize
Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson had two favorite targets while governor: the
rank-and-file trade and state employees' unions, and the California
Teachers' Association. Those groups worked overtime to defeat
Republicans and help elect Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever union members in May and June phoned potential voters
in the primary election, they had two messages: Defeat Proposition
226, the ballot initiative that would have restricted political
lobbying activities by unions; and vote for Davis. That same
momentum carried into November, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But no single issue rallied workers more than Wilson's decision
to change the state's overtime rules, union officials said. Under
the old regulations, which had been in place for 125 years, workers
qualified for overtime after working 8 hours in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Industrial Welfare Commission, acting at Wilson's
behest, changed the regulations so that overtime could be paid only
after working 40 hours in a week. One estimate showed that
California workers lost $1 billion in wages because of the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a move toward more nonpartisanship, and in fact
some percentage of our membership votes Republican,'' said Art
Pulaski, executive secretary of the California Labor Federation.
``But even among those who vote Republican, Wilson has managed to
alienate them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 290,000-member California Teachers' Association, a longtime
Wilson opponent, spent at least $6 million fighting Wilson's
Proposition 8, which would have required teacher competency tests
and created school councils to influence curriculum. They outspent
Wilson 7-1, and the measure was readily defeated.
</P>
<P>
   There was evidence anti-Wilson sentiment ran beyond just unions.
</P>
<P>
   California tribes paid for 6 million pieces of anti-Wilson
campaign mailers that helped motivate Hispanics to vote for
Proposition 5, which allows Las Vegas-style gambling on Indian
lands.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans made some gains among Hispanics this year,
the party still hurts from the dramatic drop in Hispanic and
minority voting because of Wilson's support of Proposition 187,
which cut off services to illegal immigrants, and Proposition 209,
which banned affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Where Republicans could count on 40 percent of the Hispanic vote
before Wilson backed Proposition 187 in 1994, exit polls show
Republicans got only about 18 percent this election.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect, Wilson's politics on immigration, Latinos, and
ethnic issues in general were the political equivalent of running
up a big credit-card debt to have a party, with no thought to what
happens when the bill comes due,'' said Jim Shultz, executive
director of the Democracy Center, a nonpartisan public policy
institute in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson became the favorite figure of scorn this election in
millions of pieces of Democratic mail to Hispanics and union
workers. Democrats printed 2,000 ``Adios! Pete Wilson!'' bumper
stickers. Davis' Spanish-language television commercials were about
Wilson, without saying his first name or that he was governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-09-98 1524EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
