<HEADER>
A1202 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWINS-LIVES-1500(2Tak     11-09 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWINS-LIVES-1500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE OF TWO LITTLE BOYS WHOSE LIVES DIVERGED YEARS AGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The picture sits on top of the china cabinet in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   It is a black-and-white picture, so you can't tell which of the
babies has brown eyes and which has blue. They look almost
identical.
</P>
<P>
   They look so much alike that their mother slicked up a wave of
hair on one of the boys' heads. All their lives, people looked at
them and assumed they were close. But I know differently. I know
what happened to them.
</P>
<P>
   I know those boys were never as close as they are in that
picture.
</P>
<P>
   I know, because one of them is me.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He asked me to stick around but I said I had to go.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I saw my brother, Barry, we talked on the back
porch of the house where we grew up, in the mountains of Virginia.
Barry sat in the corner of the porch, and I leaned against the
wall, under a window.
</P>
<P>
   We were little boys in matching pajamas when we stood tiptoe on
the other side of that window to see whether a blanket of snow had
covered the picnic table. We were inseparable then, lugging two of
everything wherever we went: two cap guns, two stick horses, two
bicycles we pretended were cars.
</P>
<P>
   We rode beside the river, where the pavement ended and you could
let go of the handlebars and coast, no hands, forever it seemed,
nothing behind you but a plume of dust.
</P>
<P>
   My brother was the quarterback, the Little League hitter, the
wrestler. He was the one who caught hepatitis after eating
tadpoles; the one who swallowed Granny's nitroglycerine pill; the
one who kicked over Mrs. Davis' jack-o'-lantern. I was the one who
watched. I was the one on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   When I was10, the doctor told my parents I cried at night
because I had something called Legg-Perthes disease. My hip bone
was crumbling. He said I couldn't keep up with my brother because
the bone was dying.
</P>
<P>
   I came home from the children's hospital in a metal brace that
ran down my legs like the letter A. For the next few years, a
distance grew between my brother and me as he ran ahead and I
hobbled behind. He left me standing in the outfield, ankle-high in
dandelions and weeds, waiting for a ball that never came.
</P>
<P>
   It took me years to forgive him for that.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't forgive him until after he died.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the time we went to high school, the brace and the crutches
lay in the attic, gathering dust, but it was too late. We were
changed.
</P>
<P>
   My brother spent Friday nights under stadium lights or on a
wrestling mat. I spent mine in the bleachers or in the parking lot,
drinking beer.
</P>
<P>
   At our high-school graduation, we sat side by side, the
difference between us then as real as the space between our chairs.
I kept tapping my legs, anxious to leave. He sat still, content to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   The town we grew up in was so small that we told people we were
from another, but nobody had heard of it, either. Our dad was a
third-generation coal miner who lost his father to black lung
disease and his grandfather to a mine collapse. He gave 35 years of
his life to a dark hole inside a mountain so we wouldn't be like
him. But Barry didn't want to leave.
</P>
<P>
   He was the one who dated the same girl for three years; the one
who blew off college recruitment day; the one who wanted to spend
the rest of his life in a coal-mining town in the mountains of
Virginia. I was the one who wanted out.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My brother was a big shot in high school, a state champion
wrestler, a senior on the homecoming court, but two hours from
home, at the biggest university in Virginia, he was just another
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   I knew something was wrong when I found him in the dorm room we
shared with the door locked, the blinds closed. He lay on the
bottom bunk, his back toward the door. It was the middle of the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get it,'' he told me. ``You don't know what it's
like to be so depressed you don't have the energy to roll over.''
</P>
<P>
   He left 110 Lee Hall at the end of his freshman year and moved
back in with Mom and Dad.
</P>
<P>
   I stayed. If people made fun of my hillbilly accent, I lost it.
If people never heard of my hometown, I never mentioned it again. I
was ashamed of the mountains and the mines; I wanted to be like the
kids who grew up in Baltimore and D.C., who smoked and drank and
knew the Metro line schedule.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't find time to make it home for summer breaks.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mom passed him on the highway while she was running errands. She
knew he was supposed to be in class at the community college so she
turned around, suspicious. He'd already taken the pills by the time
she got home.
</P>
<P>
   Barry wrote each of us a note. He said he loved us, that he was
sorry and that we weren't to blame. Then he swallowed 64
anti-depressants.
</P>
<P>
   The next time, a note lay on the bed in the middle room.
</P>
<P>
   It led Dad to the road by the river, where we rode our bikes and
fished for redeyes and shot pop cans off tree stumps. It was just
getting dark when Dad found him in the woods, by the river, with a
shotgun. Dad talked him into coming home.
</P>
<P>
   They were asleep the third time, when Barry knocked on their
bedroom door, crying and holding up a bloody wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Mom found him in the garage on his fourth try, lying on the
cement floor with his head beneath the exhaust pipe. The engine was
running.
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatrist diagnosed Barry as ``schizoaffective,'' lost
somewhere between schizophrenia and depression. He said Barry was
born with a chemical imbalance, and his brain didn't make enough of
the chemical seratonin.
</P>
<P>
   Once, I visited him in the mental hospital where he spent weeks
and sometimes months. On a Sunday afternoon, while we walked around
the parking lot, Barry made jokes about his escape.
</P>
<P>
   He twirled a finger beside his head when telling me about some
of the other patients. He talked about an old man who was committed
for buying four cars in one day. The psychiatrists put the man on
so much medication that his mania was reduced to baby steps. Barry
called it The Thorazine Shuffle. He did a mean imitation.
</P>
<P>
   My brother could be a funny guy.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The house was full of people by the time I got there. I flew to
Virginia and met my baby sister at the airport. Her husband drove
us back through the mountains to the house where we grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Lights were on in every room. People stood outside in the
shadows, and more people were inside. Mom and Dad were in the
living room. Mom was on the couch, Dad on the floor at her feet,
holding her hands.
</P>
<P>
   They met on a blind date, in a bowling alley. She quit her job
at the Ben Franklin Five &AMP; Dime after they got married. He got a
job in the coal mines.
</P>
<P>
   They moved into a rented trailer until they saved up enough
money to buy a trailer of their own. They married in January and
had a family by the end of the year. The twins came early, on
Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Brown-eyed Barry came first. Blue-eyed me came 15 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   The house where we grew up is full of our pictures, even now. It
seems there are pictures of us in every room.
</P>
<P>
   When people came for the funeral, they looked at the images _ on
the wall and on the TV and on the china cabinet. In awkward
moments, they asked whether I knew the moment when Barry died.
``Don't twins feel something?''
</P>
<P>
   I told them I knew when Dad called me on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Barry was getting over a bad cold, but he still wanted to go on
a trip the county mental health department planned for the next
day. He took a friend's pain pills to sleep better.
</P>
<P>
   The pain pills and his anti-depressants were toxic together.
They slowed down his heart, filled his lungs and caused his entire
body to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   He was living alone and seemed to be getting his life together.
All he wanted was a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   He never woke up.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My brother Barry died on Sept. 24, 1993. He was 27 years old.
</P>
<P>
   He is buried on a hillside, under an acorn tree so tall it
reaches over a goldfish pond at the base of the hill. Dad taught us
to drive in this cemetery when we were 15.
</P>
<P>
   This is what I think about, sitting on the bench beside his
grave.
</P>
<P>
   I think about the paisley tie I picked out to bury him in and
the salesclerk who felt so sorry for me that she didn't know what
to say so she cried, too.
</P>
<P>
   I think about how we started out as twins but ended up more like
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   I think of how I spent the first half of my life wanting to be
like him and how he spent the last half of his life wanting to be
like me.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's too bad we grew apart. I think maybe there was
nothing we could do about that.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
