<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is the Medical Tribune News Service budget for Monday,
November 9, 1998. The service, distributed by the New York Times
Syndicate, is a consumer version of the Medical Tribune newspaper
for doctors.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about this daily package of health-news
articles and features, contact Bob Farnell at farnellb &LR; nytimes.com,
or phone him at 800-535-4425.
</P>
<P>
   TEMPERATURE-HEART-MED -- DALLAS -- People with heart disease may
want to check the weather forecast before heading outdoors,
according to a study presented here at the annual meeting of the
American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings, released Monday, suggest that changes in
temperature and atmospheric pressure may be related to an increased
risk of heart attack in men. (350 words)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MARIJUANA-MED -- Widespread voter acceptance of the
possible benefit of legalizing marijuana for medical uses may set
off another round of debate over the value of smoking pot. (600
words)
</P>
<P>
   ARTHRITIS-TREAT-MED -- SAN DIEGO -- Breakthrough treatments for
rheumatoid arthritis will be the subject of a press conference here
Monday at the annual meeting of the American College of
Rheumatology. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   DIET-DRUG-MED -- DALLAS -- A new study is the first to attempt
to define who is at risk of heart problems from taking the
once-popular diet-drug combination fen-phen, which was pulled from
the market last year after reports linked the medications to
heart-valve defects. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   GENE-THERAPY-MED _ DALLAS _ Investigators speaking here Monday
at the annual meeting of the American Heart Association will
discuss the latest research in using gene therapy to grow new blood
vessels in the legs and heart to re-route blood around blocked
arteries and to prevent the re-clogging of blood vessels after
surgery. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   TREAT-CHOLESTEROL-MED -- DALLAS -- Elderly men and women with
normal cholesterol levels may be able to lower their risk of a
heart attack with drug therapy, researchers are expected to report
here Monday at the annual meeting of the American Heart
Association. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
