<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Monday, Nov. 9, 1998     
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file these stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about Houston Chronicle
sports stories, please call the Houston Chronicle Sports
Department, 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: CONGRESS-SPEAKER; MITCH-REFUGEES; MITCH-HONDURAS;
MITCH-NICARAGUA; OMBUDSMEN-HELP; and BKN-NBA-LOCKOUT.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACHMENT-DEFINITION (Washington) _ Legal scholars and
historians disagree in their testimony before a House Judiciary
panel trying to define what is an impeachable offense. But the
argument may turn into an academic exercise because of turmoil
within the GOP House leadership and the public mood against
impeachment. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-CLINTON (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rejects President
Clinton's appeals to let Secret Service agents and government
lawyers refuse to answer questions about possible criminal conduct
by Clinton and other government officials. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEAKER (Washington) _ California Rep. Christopher Cox
withdraws as a contender to succeed New Gingrich, apparently
clearing the way for Rep. Bob Livingston of Louisiana to become
speaker of the House. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-LEADERSHIP (Washington) _ In the game of musical chairs
among House leaders, the race for the majority leader's seat
appears to pit incumbent Richard Armey of Texas against challengers
Steve Largent of Oklahoma, Jennifer Dunn of Washington and J.
Dennis Hastert of Illinois. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MITCH-REFUGEES (Tololar, Nicaragua) _ Stumbling across the
hardening moonscape of mud that was once her village, Maria Elva
Bran let out a subdued but satisfied yelp as she spotted a bit of
good fortune. She leaned toward the earth that had become a grave
for thousands of her neighbors and pried loose a small ear of corn.
``What luck,'' Bran said. Such mercies sustain millions of people
whose lives were sundered by the storm known as Mitch. By DUDLEY
ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   MITCH-HONDURAS (Tegucigalpa, Honduras) _ By erasing entire
communities from the map, Hurricane Mitch literally changed the
face of Honduras. In a land where life was already calamitous for
thousands of poor families, Mitch came as an end-of-the-millennium
apocalypse, a disaster that hit just as the country was struggling
to its feet. By JOHN OTIS. (Already filed).
</P>
<P>
   MITCH-NICARAGUA (Managua, Nicaragua) _ When President Arnoldo
Aleman went on television to donate his own money to hurricane
victims, he pointedly handed over the check with his right hand.
``I don't do anything with the left,'' he joked, referring to his
stance against the leftist Sandinista National Liberation Front,
which was voted out of office in 1990 after years of civil war. By
DUDLEY ALTHAUS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OMBUDSMEN-HELP (Undated) _ They are like corporate den mothers
with a soothing presence, big shoulders to cry on and a box of
tissues at the ready. Their offices are discreet and located far
from the offices of power. Most importantly, perhaps, they are
independent operators. They are company ombudsmen, and they are
there to help. By L.M. SIXEL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Trying to figure how to get out of
an impeachment process the voters don't want, House Republicans are
discovering an old military truism _ it is easier to start a war
than end one. Even so, Democrats have suffered a blow with the loss
of their most useful bogeyman, Newt Gingrich. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-JEWS (Paris) _ The recently settled controversy over how
much Swiss banks owe to the relatives of Jewish depositors later
killed by the Nazis has unleashed a strong wave of anti-Semitism in
Switzerland, according to a new government report. Among the most
interesting points is the admission that anti-Jewish sentiment
among the Swiss was already widespread before the dispute erupted.
By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-LOCKOUT (Undated) _ An update on the stalled
negotiations between the National Basketball Association and the
players union as the lockout drags into the second week of the
regular season. By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
