<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMY-VETERAN-HNS &LR;      11-09 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-VETERAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR HERO BATTLES AILMENTS BUT REMAINS DEVOTED TO DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Vietnam War veteran Roy Benavidez paused while
talking of his storied past and thought about the future. He
squeezed his right eye shut and grimaced.
</P>
<P>
   A long, high-pitched moan pierced the silence of his hospital
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God!'' Benavidez cried. ``Where are they (the nurses)
at?''
</P>
<P>
   The stump that used to be his right leg was the obvious source
of his pain, and the blood that pooled at the base of a heavy
plaster cast was a reminder of his grim reality.
</P>
<P>
   At 63, Benavidez's memory is fuzzy. The strength that sent the
retired master sergeant to the Army's Special Forces and later
carried him to a miraculous recovery after stepping on a land mine
in Vietnam is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Brooke Army Medical Center here amputated his leg
last month as diabetes threatened to trigger a fatal infection.
</P>
<P>
   Benavidez spent the days before Veterans Day in a San Antonio
hospital battling diabetes, anemia and a host of other illnesses _
all of which remind him of the day 30 years ago when a swarm of
North Vietnamese troops left him with more than three dozen scars.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Americans will gather Wednesday for
ceremonies nationwide honoring the more than 1 million veterans who
have died in battle since the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   A Green Beret and longtime resident of El Campo, Texas,
Benavidez received the Medal of Honor from President Ronald Reagan
in 1981 for saving eight fellow Special Forces troops.
</P>
<P>
   Benavidez recalled the battle in dreamlike fragments. He can't
say how many times he was clubbed, shot or stabbed. But he defied
the enemy and the odds, determined to rescue his comrades and then
recover classified documents from the body of a dead team leader.
</P>
<P>
   Today he is fighting again.
</P>
<P>
   Without detailing his illnesses, nurse Lainey Klingemann said
Benavidez was battling back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got medical problems that are very involved and each
complicate each other,'' said Klingemann, a nurse at Northeast
Methodist Hospital in San Antonio, where Benavidez began therapy
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They almost feed on each other to challenge his quality of
life,'' she said. ``It's a dynamic effect because they are all
interacting with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Pain from surgery is but one problem. He still can feel his feet
and toes in the leg he lost, a sensation known as phantom pain.
</P>
<P>
   Therapists also must help him regain lost upper-body strength.
During an interview, two people lifted Benavidez on several
occasions so he could shift in a wheelchair and be more
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his failing health, Benavidez wants to sell his book,
``Medal of Honor: A Vietnam Warrior's Story.'' He hopes to inspire
children and see Hollywood filmmakers recount his experience, much
as they did with World War II hero Audie Murphy in the 1955 movie
``To Hell and Back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood never has done a movie about a Hispanic war hero, and
youths need role models, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to be an American,'' Benavidez said. ``I'm proud to
serve my country, serve it well. I'm proud of being rewarded for a
job well done, and for my country to give me the benefit and
opportunity to advance in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Born Aug. 5, 1935, in the tiny South Texas community of
Lindenau, Raul Perez Benavidez was a sharecropper's son who barely
knew his parents. Salvador and Teresa Benavidez died a year apart,
leaving him and a younger brother, Rogelio, to live with an uncle,
Nicholas Benavidez.
</P>
<P>
   His family worked from dawn to dusk as migrant farm workers who
toiled in sugar beet and cotton fields from West Texas to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Though he went go to school for a few months, Benavidez said he
spent more time at harvests than in the classroom and only finished
the eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by racial discrimination, Benavidez vowed to master
English and find a way to get ahead. He found it in the Army, where
he earned his high school diploma, saw some of the world and earned
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his assignment to airborne school in 1958 that ``woke
me up'' and fueled a new ambition to ``become a soldier and be the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Benavidez said: ``I was just picking up a
paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Benavidez adopted the motto, ``duty, honor, country,'' and began
living it.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of May 2, 1968, three months into his second tour
of the Vietnam War, he made history.
</P>
<P>
   A North Vietnamese regiment surrounded a dozen soldiers from his
unit during a secret mission in Cambodia. Three helicopters trying
to save the men came under heavy fire and were unable to land.
</P>
<P>
   When he became aware of the situation, Benavidez thought of
three friends trapped in the fire zone and bulled his way onto a
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got on that 'copter, little did I know we were going to
spend six hours in hell,'' Benavidez said.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after jumping off his helicopter in a clearing, he
suffered wounds to the right leg, face and head while charging
through heavy enemy fire.
</P>
<P>
   Benavidez repositioned team members so they could give cover
fire for the helicopters. He then carried half the wounded troops
to nearby aircraft. But his battle had only begun.
</P>
<P>
   Benavidez recovered classified documents from a dead team leader
and then guided wounded troops from a downed aircraft and set up a
defense line.
</P>
<P>
   As the enemy gained strength, he called in airstrikes, directed
fire from helicopter gunships and provided first aid to a wounded
soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Bleeding from new gunshot wounds to the thigh and abdomen, and
hit in the back by grenade fragments, Benavidez was clubbed in the
head while leading a second extraction.
</P>
<P>
   In hand-to-hand fighting that ensued, he suffered wounds to his
head and arms before killing his adversary. He later cut down two
more enemy soldiers as they rushed toward a helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Then Benavidez made one last trip. He looked for classified
documents and carried more wounded to a waiting helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many times I was stabbed,'' he said. ``All I
had was wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the fighting, Benavidez, a devout Catholic, made the
sign of the cross so often his arms ``were going like an airplane
prop.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite new wounds, the ailing Benavidez still hears the call of
duty. He wants to continue inspiring children to stay off drugs and
get an education, a mission he would gladly undertake.
</P>
<P>
   Failure isn't an option, he said. ``Quitters never win and
winners never quit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
