<HEADLINE>
STUDY LINKS FOOD DESIRE TO MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (af)  
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hopeful of finding clues to a better understanding of obesity
and other disorders, scientists have long been interested in why
people start and stop eating.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, researchers have assumed the answers have to
do with physiology: caloric content, taste, and the functioning of
brain centers involved in hunger and satiety.
</P>
<P>
   A new study, however, suggests that cultural context _ in
particular the memory of when a person last ate and how much was
consumed _ plays an equally important role.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Rozin, a psychologist at the University of
Pennsylvania, and his colleagues studied meal regulation in two
patients with amnesia so severe they had virtually no memory of
events occurring even two minutes before.
</P>
<P>
   The patients, men whose long-term memory centers in the brain
had been damaged by illness, could not remember whether they had
just eaten a meal. When the researchers offered them a second
lunch, 10 to 30 minutes after they had eaten a first, the patients
consumed the additional food happily.
</P>
<P>
   Both patients also began to eat a third meal, presented 10 to 30
minutes after the second was finished. One of the men, called R.H.
by the researchers, ate much of the third lunch and, 20 minutes
later, announced that he planned to ``go for a walk and get a good
meal.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, when two control subjects were offered lunch a
second time, Rozin said, they replied, in effect, ``What are you,
crazy? I just ate.''
</P>
<P>
   The control subjects indicated on a rating scale that they were
less hungry after eating. But R.H.'s hunger ratings dropped only
slightly after a meal, and by the next meal had returned to their
original levels.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the study, Rozin said, indicate that ``a lot of
things that control what and how much people eat have nothing to do
with the state of nutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
