<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR AN ARMISTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) A 
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As they try to figure out how to punt gracefully in
an impeachment process the voters don't want, House Republicans are
discovering an old military truism: It is easier to start a war
than to end one.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP election debacle stripped the congressional debate over
whether to impeach President Clinton for lying under oath about
adultery of its major constitutional pretensions, exposing it for
the purely political exercise it has always been.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee is going through the motions of
examining the differing ways of defining impeachable offenses. But
the Constitution is vague and the experts who are testifying
contradict one another. In any case, they will have less influence
on the outcome of the hearings than the election has already had.
</P>
<P>
   GOP enthusiasm for bringing down a popular president in defiance
of public opinion essentially evaporated when the much-anticipated
Republican gains never materialized. Although many partisans are
stuck with their previous pious positions, some have been
sufficiently evasive to claim they are only now making up their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   No consensus for an alternative Clinton penalty has yet emerged,
although a toothless censure is often mentioned. But what once
seemed a sure committee impeachment vote now is anybody's guess,
and a full bipartisan House recommendation that the Senate try
Clinton is quite unlikely. There is, in any case, not a prayer that
a Senate trial would muster the required two-thirds majority to
impeach.
</P>
<P>
   With House Speaker Newt Gingrich's abrupt departure, Judiciary
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde is expected to run his hearings in
orderly fashion when Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr appears next
week. Hyde is now free to protect his own reputation as a judicious
fellow without being pressured by Gingrich, who had been directing
the scenario backstage.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's least radical Republicans are also free to do
their own thing, rather than Gingrich's thing. And Democrats who
once might have caved can discover newly stiffened spines.
</P>
<P>
   What Starr says could potentially tip the committee against
Clinton, but that too seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The two most singularly unpopular public figures in America are
Gingrich and Starr, both of whom had recent approval ratings below
20 percent, mostly because of voter distaste for their pursuit of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek reports in all seriousness that Starr is frantically
trying to come up with fresh sinful behavior to shock the nation _
lies to conceal a lipstick-stained towel in the Oval Office, for
instance, or another charge against picked-upon Webster Hubbell,
the former associate attorney general who stubbornly persists in
refusing to sell out Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr will need more than such pettifoggery to convince us
at this late date that he has impeachable goods on Clinton not
previously disclosed. He had his primary shot with his official
report. If he has more hot stuff, why didn't he include it?
Whatever happened to Whitewater, the travel office firings and the
oddness about the FBI files? If Starr knows something awful, why
didn't he say so before?
</P>
<P>
   There are also all those questions about Starr's own conduct,
from improper grand jury leaks to a mysterious failure to fully
inform Attorney General Janet Reno about his contacts with
right-wing Clinton enemies and Paula Jones' defense team. Not good.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La, the conservative pragmatist who is
slated to replace Gingrich as speaker, virtually made it official
that Clinton will get at least partially off the hook. Livingston
acknowledged that Congress is influenced by public opinion when it
thinks about whether to impeach a president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have certainly indicated in the polls that
they don't see it (lying about sex) as an impeachable or
dismissible offense, and that would have to be considered in the
political arena,'' Livingston said in a television interview. With
the GOP vote that will seal his new power still some days away, he
tactfully hedged his comments in order not to appear soft on the
president, adding that Clinton must answer to the voters somehow.
</P>
<P>
   But Livingston is not an ``impeach now, impeach forever''
fruitcake like Gingrich and Georgia Rep. Bob Barr. Gingrich had to
go because he kept stoking the fires under the president beyond a
point the voters thought reasonable. Such a relentless assault had
worked to bring down Democratic Speaker Jim Wright, but Clinton
proved a tougher bird than Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the impeachment issue is out of the way can there be
true bipartisan cooperation in Congress. Livingston knows this, and
is willing to go along. Hooray.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who felt Clinton should resign because there seemed
no other civilized way to avoid two years of constant bickering may
now reconsider our position. The voters have provided the prod. It
is up to Congress to respond sensibly, or go the way of Gingrich in
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Censure the bum in the White House, shift the dialogue to real
national issues and get on with the business of governing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
