<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-09 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1302 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ANTARCTICA-WOMEN-     11-09 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANTARCTICA-WOMEN-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A STRUGGLE, WOMEN WIN A PLACE `ON THE ICE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Ill., Minn.)   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By CORNELIA DEAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   McMURDO STATION, ANTARCTICA _ Twenty years ago, when Julia
Uberuaga first began working in Antarctica, she was one of only a
few women among hundreds of men. They stared at her, or leered at
her, or otherwise let her know she was unwelcome on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried myself to sleep more than one night,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Mathews, a microbiologist then at Hunter College, remembers
being ``pretty well beset by men'' when she did research at McMurdo
for a few seasons in the late 70s and early 80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a nuisance,'' she said. ``They were all over the
place. There were some that would never stop going after you.''
True to her biologist's calling, Dr. Mathews devised a taxonomy for
the Antarctic male: there were the predators, who lurked at every
turn, the scavengers, who usually were considerate enough to wait
for a signal before pouncing; and herbivores, who apparently wanted
nothing to do with women.
</P>
<P>
   The women's usual response, Dr. Mathews said, was to link up
with one man. He would keep the others away.
</P>
<P>
   Life is far different now in Mactown, as its inhabitants call
McMurdo Station, the main American base in Antarctica. As 1,000 or
more scientists and support staff return to ``the Ice'' for another
season of work in the austral summer, about a third of them are
women.
</P>
<P>
   Like the men, they are drawn by the wild beauty of the
landscape, the idea of living at one of Earth's last frontiers and
the chance to contribute to scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, they are bringing profound change to one of the
most unusual outposts of American society. And they have made
McMurdo a kind of laboratory for watching what happens when an
all-male group is gradually infiltrated by the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   When it was established by the Navy in 1956, McMurdo had all the
charm of a frontier mining camp. Buildings were a hodgepodge of
strictly utilitarian Quonset huts and sheds, painted in the
military palette of gray or green and plunked down, seemingly at
random, on volcanic soil devoid of even a blade of grass. Social
life centered around alcohol, lots of it, and the first few women
to visit were protected by military guards.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it looks much the same. But there are women in offices
and research labs, driving trucks, managing remote field sites and
even, like Ms. Uberuaga, operating heavy earth-moving equipment.
And they seem to be accepted, confident and at ease.
</P>
<P>
   To researchers like Charles Moskos, a professor of sociology at
Northwestern University who has studied military organizations, the
change is a matter of numbers. As more and more women join an
organization, he said, there is a ``tipping point'' when its
atmosphere changes.
</P>
<P>
   In the military, he said, the point is somewhere between 15
percent and 20 percent of the group. Then, he said, ``women are no
longer regarded as abberant people who have to be treated with kid
gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, many of the issues involving women in remote
outposts relate to sex, and not just to sexual relations. For
example, Moskos said, when there are only a few women around, men
may feel free to make off-color jokes, and the women may feel
pressure to laugh at them.
</P>
<P>
   Or, he went on, ``if there are only a few women, trying to
maintain modesty looks like extraordinary perks given to them.''
All that starts to change at the tipping point, he said. ``A more
civil culture develops.'' The women begin to censor their own
behavior, and men keep other men in line.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he and other social psychologists say, the presence of
women seems to encourage men to behave better toward each other.
Past the tipping point, for example, men get into far fewer fights.
</P>
<P>
   This change is good, because ``aggression is one of the major
things you can't tolerate'' in the isolation of Antarctica, said
John Nicoletti of Lakewood, Colo., a psychologist who headed the
team evaluating the men and women who spent this winter (summer in
the Northern Hemisphere) on the ice. ``The presence of women adds
normality,'' he went on. ``It's less like a wilderness experience.
It mimics regular society where there are rules and you have to
follow them.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in social code has probably been accelerated by the
change in McMurdo's mission since the end of the Cold War. Until
then, the base was primarily a military outpost where some
scientific work also went on. Today, it is a research establishment
run by the National Science Foundation and administered by a
private contractor, Antarctic Support Associates. Almost everyone
works as a scientist or in support of scientists.
</P>
<P>
   And social life no longer revolves around Navy liquor rations.
</P>
<P>
   Women were almost totally excluded from Antarctica until about
30 years ago. The first woman to set foot on the continent was
Caroline Mikkelsen, the wife of a Norwegian whaling captain, who
landed with him at the Vestfold Hills, on the Antarctica peninsula,
in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   The first women to winter on Antarctica were also accompanying
their husbands, on a private expedition in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, though, the nations that ran Antarctic programs
officially banned women, supposedly because the rigors of the
continent were too great for the women and the rigors of providing
separate bathroom facilities were too great for the program
administrators. It was widely acknowledged, however, that the real
reason was fear of sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though other countries, notably Chile and the Soviet Union,
gradually allowed more and more women into their stations, the
United States' Antarctic programs were all-male until 1969, and it
was not until 1974 that American women wintered over at McMurdo,
two among 128 men.
</P>
<P>
   One was Mary Alice McWhinnie, the first woman to head scientific
operations there, and the other was her assistant, Sister Mary
Odile Cahoon, a teaching nun from St. Scholastica College in
Duluth, Minn. Barbara Land described their first winter in her
book, ``The New Explorers,'' (Dodd, Mead, 1981). ``Both the Navy
and the NSF were still a little uptight about having women at
McMurdo for the winter,'' Sister Odile told her. ``I am sure they
felt more comfortable having a couple of maiden aunts test the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The first women at the South Pole arrived in 1969, in a Navy
plane. So that none could grab credit for being the first woman at
Pole, the six left the plane together, walking down its rear cargo
ramp arm in arm. But women did not stay overnight at the polar base
until 1971 and it was not until 1979 that a woman wintered there.
</P>
<P>
   But it is only within the last few years that there have been
enough women at the United States' Antarctica stations to make a
big difference. When women first arrived on the Ice, the Navy Shore
Patrol was still making regular sweeps to rescue men who had fallen
down drunk, so they would not freeze to death in the McMurdo
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty rough place,'' said Rebecca Johnson, an author
who first visited Antarctica in 1991, as part of the NSF's Writers
and Artists program. ``There were three bars,'' she recalled,
``When I came back in '94 one of those that had been the
hardest-driving had been converted into a gym and what had been the
Officers' Club had been converted into the Coffee House.'' Today,
it is a popular after-work spot for wine, cheese, capuccino and
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the base store still stocks liberal supplies of
beer, wine and liquor, and plenty of people enjoy a cocktail or two
after work. But social life is not limited to drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are literally so many things to do you can't decide,''
said Amy Madden, who tended bar there until February. ``You can
work out in the gym, and there are aerobics, skiing, hiking, bingo,
karaoke, ceramics.''
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke, she was knitting a cap, her first project in
Stitch-n-Bitch, an organization of about a dozen women (and two
men) that met regularly to do needlework. There are groups for
writers, musicians and even Bible study.
</P>
<P>
   As researchers, women have participated in or led studies of the
diet of the penguin, how fish keep from freezing, the life cycle of
microscopic worms and a host of other research subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are women lab managers, more women involved in every
aspect,'' said Professor Diana H. Wall of Colorado State
University, where she directs the Natural Resource Ecology
Laboratory. Dr. Wall has been doing field work since 1989 on
microscopic worms that live in Antarctic soil.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere for women has definitely improved since then, she
said, primarily because there are more of them both at McMurdo and
in field camps. ``There is a comfort level,'' she said. ``You can
talk to them about things you would not necessarily want to talk
with men about. The women don't have to be so macho.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from research, women fill all kinds of support jobs at
McMurdo, South Pole and Palmer Station, the other main American
bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women seemed to break in first in supply,'' said Stanley P.
Wisneski, who runs McMurdo and several outlying installations for
Antarctic Support Associates this year, his 13th season on the Ice.
``From that point, once they did get here, maybe if they were
already a trades person they could move into those spots.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, there are women working as machinists, carpenters,
heavy equipment operators and ``fuelies,'' the people who drive the
big white ``fuel mule'' delivery trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Abbott, the manager of helicopter operations, began
working on the Ice, as people there call Antarctica, as a janitor
in the 1985-86 season. At that point, she said, ``there were 26
women and hundreds of men.''
</P>
<P>
   Mactown was a mess, with trash everywhere, she recalled, and
``you felt leered at, looked at.'' Today, the base is scrupulously
neat, and as she dispatches the helicopters that ferry scientists
and supplies to and from remote field camps, most of her colleagues
are women. At age 46, she thinks of this job as her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of fought it for a while,'' Ms. Abbott said. But when a
boyfriend wanted her to settle in New Zealand, she resisted. This
year found her back at work in her cramped office, off the storage
area for helicopter parts and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny day, light reflected off the Ross Sea ice, is
blinding. That's the way Ms. Abbott likes it. On sunny days, the
helos (pronounced HEE-lows) fly on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   As in more normal environments, some of the people working here
develop romantic attachments. With at least two men for every
women, women here do not languish for lack of suitors. But like
everything else, romance is difficult in Antarctica, even in the
relative civilization of McMurdo.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to date here,'' said Anne Vick, who arrived a
few weeks ago for another season running the Mechanical Equipment
Center, where generators and other equipment is kept in shape.
</P>
<P>
   There are regular movies, but people view them from
straight-back chairs in the galley. Couples can leave the base for
a stroll, but only if their survival skills have been checked out.
And, at least in the summer season, there is never any romantic
twilight. Unless it is raining or foggy, the sun shines with the
same lurid brightness 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to socialize,'' Ms. Vick said.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, almost everyone lives in a dormitory and
in the summer season almost everyone has a roommate. ``If one
person has a roommate who leaves town you can get several shifts,''
Ms. Vick said. ``One guy goes into the field so his roommate's
girlfriend comes over, then her roommate's boyfriend comes over.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are even rougher in remote camps, and not just because of
their isolation. A leaflet issued to women offers a warning ``about
doing it in the field,'' noting that that no one is as clean in
camp as back at Mactown, and that pregnancy means an immediate
flight home.
</P>
<P>
   The guide also offers how-to tips for using a device that some
women say has vastly improved their lives in the primitive cold of
remote camps: an anatomically contoured funnel and extension hose
that _ almost _ allows women to urinate like men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secrets of success are proper positioning of the funnel and
insuring you have a good seal between it and your body,'' the guide
says.
</P>
<P>
   But many women say they never use it because if it is not
positioned exactly right they can end up wet, a potentially
disastrous problem. Anyway, Ms. Johnson said, ``you quickly lose
all sense of embarrassment in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite changes that have made Antarctica more inviting to
women, it will never seem like home. Even in McMurdo the ratio of
men to women is wildly out of balance and there are no old people,
no children and no pets.
</P>
<P>
   For some who come to the Ice, that is fine. ``There are some
people who (italics)want(end italics) to be away from home,'' Ms.
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wisneski said, about half to two-thirds of the workers
return each year. ``Wanderers,'' he calls them.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Ms. Vick, 27, fits that pattern. She had worked on the
Ice in the 1993-94 season, and then earned a master's degree at the
Scott Polar Research Institute at Cambridge University. By 1997,
she was living in Manhattan, in the West Village, and working for
the Hearst Corp., on the international editions of magazines like
Esquire and Harper's Bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   She took a job in marketing, but she hated it. ``I thought,
`it's time to go back.' I missed the people and the life style.
There is such a fantastic communiuty of women here _ interesting,
motivated, savvy women in very non-traditional roles.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, after some travel, work in Greenland and an
exhibition of her Antarctic photographs in New York last summer,
she returned again.
</P>
<P>
   Other women, like Ms. Uberuaga, simply fall in love with the
place.
</P>
<P>
   It was her mother, an employee of the civilian contractor then
running services at McMurdo, who suggested that she try a season in
the Ice in 1979. ``In those days if you recruited someone they
would pay you a $50 bonus,'' Ms. Uberuaga recalled wryly.
</P>
<P>
   She was 24 that first year, and she worked as a laborer. There
were only a handful of other women. ``This was a big bastion of
masculinity and military conservatism,'' she said. ``I had a
million critics.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Uberuaga stuck with it, in part because she loved the
landscape and the outdoor life but also because her supervisors
held out the promise of promotion that, over the years, she won.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Ms. Uberuaga ran an earth-mover with a 16-foot
blade, working on the site for a new fuel tank. She has become so
skilled on the big machine that she could smooth the tank base to
within a fraction of an inch, and she is proud of it. ``It's a very
diverse and interesting job,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With Antarctic Support Associates providing housing, food and
even clothing, Ms. Uberuaga's expenses are few. Like many of her
co-workers, she works from October to February in Antarctica,
saving enough to support herself the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a house in the mountains in Idaho,'' she said. ``It's
paid for, it's right on the river. Everything I have is paid for. I
just have a great life.''
</P>
<P>
   But she is 43 now and, although there is no formal age limit for
working in Antarctica, she realizes that at some point she will no
longer be able to pass the required physical exam. ``I am very
attached to the landscape here and yet there will be a day when I
can never come back,'' she said. ``That makes it so poignant.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she said, a friend she met at McMurdo decided not to
return for another season. A few months later, Ms. Uberuaga
recalled, she received a letter from her. ``Halfway through the
Montana winter she was dreaming of the Ice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
