<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, Nov. 10. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
warnken(at)nytimes.com  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (Moving in ``i'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-WATER (Miapur, Bangladesh) _ Special Report: Tens of
thousands of Bangladeshi villagers are dying as the country
struggles against what some experts say could be the biggest mass
poisoning in history. Dangerous levels of arsenic have been found
in the ground water, entering millions of people sip by sip. By
Barry Bearak. With map graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ELECT (Rosh Haayin, Israel) _ On an international level,
Israelis engage in bare-knuckled diplomacy. Nationally, they duke
it out with invective-laced rhetoric in the Parliament. But it is
on the municipal level where they really take off their gloves, and
the campaign season that culminates in Tuesday's local elections
has been as dastardly as it gets. Take the case of Yigal Yanai,
candidate for mayor, victim of the dirtiest of tricks. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECONOMY (Brasilia) _ In late August, as South America
panicked that Brazil's economy would follow Russia's into default,
the Government here scrambled for ways to protect the country's
shrinking foreign reserves. But as the government hoists the banner
of austerity, the gap between the Government's calls for sacrifice
and its spending practices appears striking. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (Moving in ``w'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Constitutional scholars on both
sides of the impeachment debate told members of the House Judiciary
Committee Monday that a compromise outcome such as a vote to
censure President Clinton had no basis in the Constitution and
could dangerously weaken the presidency. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKER-LIVINGSTON (Washington) _ Representative Robert L.
Livingston of Louisiana locked up the votes to become Speaker of
the House, while Republicans turned their attention to the contest
to be majority leader, the second-ranking position. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON-PROFILE (Washington) _ Man In The News profile of
Rep. Robert Livingston. By Katharine Q. Seelye. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court Monday sidestepped for
the time being the looming national debate over whether taxpayer
funded vouchers may be used to send children to parochial schools
as the justices let stand a lower court ruling upholding the
constitutionality of such a program in Milwaukee. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (Moving in ``a'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSLIM-SCHOOL (Undated)_ Across the country, Islamic schools
like Al Noor that offer religion and Arabic classes along with a
standard academic curriculum are expanding and flourishing, with
many becoming over-subscribed so quickly that principals are
scrambling for money to build more.
</P>
