A1344 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LENNON-CD-REVIEW-TEX     11-09 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENNON-CD-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGINE, ANOTHER JOHN LENNON BOXED SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Lennon could seem simultaneously to be both cynic and
enthusiast. That's what we have to be when considering ``The John
Lennon Anthology,'' a newly released four-CD boxed set from Capitol
Records consisting mostly of studio outtakes, snippets of
conversation, midst-of-composing song snatches, and a few live
performances that haven't appeared on previous albums.
</P>
<P>
   Cynicism first: We already have an ``official'' Lennon boxed
set, plus a couple of greatest-hits packages. Most fans already own
one or two versions of his best-known solo tunes, plus a good
sampling of everything else. In the booklet that accompanies this
new anthology, Yoko Ono occasionally interrupts her own whining
about how she and John were misunderstood to reiterate how these
new CDs show fans the John she knew, how John's entire body of work
is important, and how the songs on this set are ``the ones John
wanted you to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question: If he wanted us to know them, why were
they never released during his lifetime?
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible not to suspect that Ono has assumed her
occasional role of still-grieving widow in hopes of squeezing a few
more millions out of Lennon's musical corpse. If ``The John Lennon
Anthology'' sells respectably, don't be shocked if Yoko comes up
with some more long-lost outtakes John wanted us to know, too.
</P>
<P>
   But having said that ...
</P>
<P>
   It is also true that any Lennon fan, rabid or casual, will find
a lot to like about ``Anthology.'' Even the most casual throwaways
have something entertaining to offer, and hearing alternate takes
on Lennon classics like ``Jealous Guy'' and ``Whatever Gets You
Thru the Night'' is not only interesting but exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The CDs are beautifully packaged, with each heavy-cardboard
fold-over sleeve illustrated with Lennon drawings (weak-of-heart be
warned _ some are pretty racy), and careful booklet annotation
about what was recorded where and when and with whom. Individual
CDs celebrate distinct portions of Lennon's solo career _
``Ascot,'' with a focus on his first two albums; ``New York City,''
at once the most uneven and the most fascinating, with seven live
cuts from various benefit concerts; ``The Lost Weekend,'' dominated
by Lennon's chaotic collaboration with demented production genius
Phil Spector; and ``Dakota,'' with songs culled from Lennon's final
years, when he celebrated marriage and fatherhood above rock
stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Just about any multiple-CD boxed set contains some bloat. We
could have done without a few of the studio conversations between
Spector and Lennon; outtakes of ``Slippin' and Slidin' '' and
``Peggy Sue'' contribute nothing to the preservation of Lennon's
own musical legacy. But nearly everything else is meat, not fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ascot'' will probably please the most listeners. Much of the
breakthrough, right-to-the-bone tunes from ``John Lennon'' are
reintroduced as works in progress, and there is a generous sampling
from the more accessible ``Imagine'' album. ``Jealous Guy'' is
especially engaging; so, in a nastier sense, is listening to Lennon
craft ``How Do You Sleep?'' a song meant to libel ex-Beatle buddy
Paul McCartney.
</P>
<P>
   Many of ``New York City's'' tracks were labeled hedonistic dreck
as soon as they were issued back in the '70s. ``New York City,''
``Luck of the Irish'' and ``Attica State'' are more interesting now
as social nostalgia than as rock-your-socks entertainment. But
there's a stunning live version of ``Imagine,'' with Lennon
explaining that he's playing it on acoustic guitar because his old
band broke up and he hasn't got a new one yet, and there are fun
demos of ``I'm the Greatest'' and ``Goodnight Vienna,'' Lennon
tunes that were eventually recorded by Ringo Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lost Weekend'' is predictably boozy and overblown; these
songs were mostly written and recorded during Lennon's lengthy,
highly publicized separation from Ono. It's probable that most
``Anthology'' purchasers will listen to this CD once, and then
leave it in the box while they replay the other three over and
over. Forget the warmed-over cover versions of '50s rock hits; the
stuff that matters here is pure Lennon, especially the two takes of
``Whatever Gets You Thru the Night'' and a heart-rending ``Steel
and Glass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dakota'' is a reminder of Lennon's happiest times. The best
``Double Fantasy'' songs are here, with ``Beautiful Boy'' the most
effective. ``Serve Yourself'' and ``The Rishi Kesh Song,'' two
hilarious Lennon skewerings of Bob Dylan and George Harrison,
respectively, will undoubtedly get a lot of notice. ``Anthology''
would have responsibly concluded with ``Dear John,'' ``Dakota's''
last cut, where Lennon sings to himself that everything's OK, the
troubles are over. But, no, someone had to stick on a few last
goofy outtakes. No purpose is served. We already know the irony of
how John Lennon died.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD: ``The John Lennon Anthlogy'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Record label: Capitol &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Price: about $70 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
