</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BALL OF CONFUSION: COUNTRIES STRUGGLE TO RAISE AWARENESS OF
'EURO'
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 450 words.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox New Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With eight weeks to go until the debut of the euro,
many Europeans remain confused about the new unified currency and
what it will mean to them.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent The Economist magazine survey, just over half the
people in the Republic of Ireland knew the name of the new
currency, while only half of Portuguese citizens asked could
correctly answer a basic six-question quiz on the currency.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, many European governments are launching campaigns
to inform their citizens about the big changes scheduled to begin
Jan. 1. The Finance Ministry in France -- whose citizens fared well
in the survey -- is sending a 16-page brochure to virtually every
home in the cou
</P>
</TEXT>
