<SLUG> BC-WOLFE-NOVEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM WOLFE PAINTS VIVID CHARACTERS IN A DICKENSIAN OPUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know the literary event of the year (the decade?) is here
when you see the smiling man in the white suit, there on the cover
of Time. You see Tom Wolfe on television, too, expounding on a book
that needs no promotion, with more than a million copies in print
before its official publication this week.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe's rhetorical corpulence is ``A Man in Full,'' already
overhyped and, I believe, already overrated. But at least in the
measure of its ambition, it is the equal of the same author's ``The
Bonfire of the Vanities,'' which was merely the best American novel
of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The two novels are similar in both design and theme. Charlie
Croker, the focal ``man in full,'' is, like Sherman McCoy in
``Bonfire,'' corrupted by his own success but ripe for spiritual
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a protagonist in the new novel, it has to be
Charlie, and he is so described in dust jacket copy; but ``A Man in
Full'' is a parallel construction, with a half-dozen major
characters (and hundreds of minor ones) riding three separate story
lines that of course will arrive at a confluence.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Croker at 60 is a fabulously successful real estate
developer in booming Atlanta. Intoxicated by sex, he has dumped
Martha, his well-born wife of three decades, in favor of sirenly
Serena, now 28. Charlie's ``cracker'' origin is unmistakable, and
his spiral into immense wealth was aided long ago by his celebrity
as Georgia Tech's ``60-minute man,'' a bruising running back who
also played defense.
</P>
<P>
   Now Georgia Tech has another celebrated running back, but Fareek
(The Cannon) Fanon is black; and he may or may not have raped the
daughter of one of the pillars of Atlanta's white establishment.
Atlanta's black mayor, Wes Jordan, determined to preserve the
city's delicate racial balance, enlists dapper black attorney Roger
White II _ not illogically called Roger Too White _ to defend The
Cannon against possible charges; and Jordan and White bring Charlie
Croker into their scheme.
</P>
<P>
   They can make it worth Charlie's while, because Charlie is in
trouble. The real estate developer has overextended himself with
the self-glorifying Croker Concourse and is in debt by more than a
half-billion dollars. The vultures at PlannersBanc, Charlie's
primary creditor, are out to get him; they've taken possession of
his Gulfstream Five jetliner and set their sights on Turpmtine,
Charlie's 29,000-acre plantation that exists mainly for shooting
quail.
</P>
<P>
   As Charlie begins the necessary downsizing of his empire, young
Conrad Hensley is an early casualty, laid off his job in Oakland,
Calif., where workers' noses drip icicles in the frozen-foods
warehouse of Croker Global Foods. Thus begins Conrad's undeserved
descent into the Hades of Santa Rita, the Alameda County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, all these things will come together, but it must take some
time, because Tom Wolfe _ prophet and architect of the New
Journalism _ must write a novel whose very size will dwarf its
complexity.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a novel other than ``Bonfire'' with which to compare
``A Man in Full,'' let it be ``Bleak House,'' Charles Dickens'
masterpiece of convolution. There is something quite Dickensian in
both of Tom Wolfe's novels, and not only in their excessive
reliance on coincidence and their big parades of richly drawn
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolfe is the master's equal at writing, whether or not it
may be called overwriting. The text of ``A Man in Full'' spans 742
pages, and its story could be related in half that or less; but
Wolfe exploits his glorious talent by elaboration, piling detail
upon detail. The reader is kept dangling, but the reader is
charmed.
</P>
<P>
   Some set-pieces in ``A Man in Full'' are quite marvelous. The
narrative gets good early steam in the second chapter, ``The
Saddlebags,'' when Charlie Croker is manipulated outrageously by
his bankers. There is a spellbinding if irrelevant passage in which
a bizarre cheering section watches a champion stallion copulate
with a mare. Scenes depicting Conrad Hensley's ordeal at Santa Rita
have surreal power. Wolfe is in his element when Atlanta's elite
all meet at the High Museum for the scandalous exhibition of Wilson
Lapeth's homosexual art.
</P>
<P>
   All of the descriptive writing is spectacular, but too much of
it testifies for the law of diminishing returns. And the
descriptive writing is so much better than the dialogue, of which
there is much. The characters are more vivid in Wolfe's
observations than in their distended speech.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the characters, however well-drawn, are not sufficiently
attractive. For all of Sherman McCoy's shortcomings, we finally
pulled for him in a way that we really can't pull for Charlie
Croker. The only truly sympathetic character _ Conrad _ is also the
least credible in his spiritual/intellectual development.
</P>
<P>
   The least consistent character is second wife Serena,
unexpectedly articulate near the end. The best character may be Ray
Peepgass, a PlannersBanc functionary whose cunning opportunism is
the heartbeat of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   This will be hailed as the great Atlanta novel, although most in
the city's power structure won't like it. ``A Man in Full'' is a
tour de force, and it will be a staple of cocktail-hour chatter,
probably a novel more talked about than read. It has been nominated
for the National Book Award in fiction because Tom Wolfe is its
author. No other reason.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Book: A Man in Full &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Author: Tom Wolfe &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Type: Fiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Farrar, Straus and Giroux, $28.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
