<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO CITY DOES NOT LEAVE THE HEART LIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was in Mexico City a couple of weeks ago for an international
seminar on journalism ethics. It was anything but stimulating.
</P>
<P>
   For years I have been hearing about all the problems facing
Mexico City: soaring population, terrible pollution, snarled
traffic, poverty. All the reports did not prepare me for what I was
to find.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't been to Mexico City in 30 years. As I looked out of the
airplane window as we were approaching the airport, I was stunned
at how much the city had grown.
</P>
<P>
   We landed in the afternoon. They say you get the full impact of
the city's size when you approach the airport at night. The city is
creeping up the sides of mountains that were on the far outskirts
of the city when I was last there.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those I talked to while attending the seminar estimated
the population at 20 million _ about the population of Texas. That
makes it the most populous city in the world. Its residents do not
boast about this, for it is a calamity, not a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, there simply is not enough water for that many
people. Signs in hotel bathrooms urge you, in both English and
Spanish, to conserve water.
</P>
<P>
   During a tour of the city, I noticed that most homes had metal
tanks on the roofs. Our tour guide said that people keep them full
of water because the supply is cut off from different parts of the
city from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't drink the water under any circumstances'' were among the
first words out of the mouth of one of my hosts on arriving at the
airport. It seems that even the residents do not dare drink the
water because it is so impure. I don't think things were that bad
the last time I was there.
</P>
<P>
   My chief host was Ernesto Villanueva, a professor at
Iberoamericana University in Mexico City. He teaches media law and
ethics. He made me promise, shortly after my arrival, never to hail
a taxi in Mexico City. He said it was too dangerous for a tourist.
</P>
<P>
   Street violence became a very serious problem in the city after
the 1995 economic crisis, when the peso was devalued from 3.5 pesos
to the U.S. dollar to seven pesos to a dollar, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Villanueva explained, ``it is not safe to take cabs
at the street for international tourists because they usually have
money in their pockets.'' In recent months, taxi drivers have
assaulted and robbed a number of tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Our hosts arranged for the seminar speakers to stay at a
comfortable hotel on the beautiful Reforma boulevard, which was
copied after the Champs-Elysees in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I also stayed in a hotel on Reforma when we were
there in the 1960s, and we loved to walk up and down the boulevard
at night. This time I was told never to stroll after sunset. It was
too dangerous for tourists, in spite of its being well-lighted and
heavily populated with pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic can be maddening, especially at rush hour. On one
occasion _ it was about 3 p.m. _ I saw an ambulance trapped in
traffic. No one seemed to pay any attention to its screaming siren.
When the traffic did inch forward, no one would yield to the
ambulance. I prayed that it was not on a life-or-death run.
</P>
<P>
   My hosts said I should have been thankful that there was little
pollution in the air. It seems that hurricanes lurking on both
sides of Mexico in the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans had a cleansing
effect.
</P>
<P>
   These problems were bad enough. But I think they are dwarfed by
the terrible poverty you encounter everywhere. Many of those who
continue to pour into the city are impoverished. And there are no
jobs for them.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva said there is no government welfare system to care
for them. There are no food stamps. Consequently, people will do
almost anything for a few pesos.
</P>
<P>
   You will see someone dash into snarled traffic and wipe a
windshield, hoping for a small tip. Girls who should be playing
with dolls resort to prostitution for their survival.
</P>
<P>
   One night, as we sat in stalled traffic on Reforma, a woman
suddenly appeared in the headlights with three children. She bent
over from the waist, and one of the children _ she looked to be
about 10 _ jumped on her back and began performing an acrobatic
dance. The other two children began working their ways through the
sea of halted vehicles, hands outstretched for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the only way they can live,'' our driver said.
</P>
<P>
   I left Mexico City with a heavy heart.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva said many consider the situation hopeless. We need to
pray for that city, for it probably is a hopeless situation for all
but God.
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be contacted at precord(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
