<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CONTRIBUTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA CANDIDATES SPEND RECORD SUM ON ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK  
 c.1998 San Francisco examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's enough to pay the annual salaries of 10,000
teachers or build Bill Gates' Seattle mansion nine times over.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the record $500 million raised for this year's
California elections paid for nasty television advertising, piles
of glossy campaign mailers and an army of political consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Although the final tabulations on spending are pending, the
money given to 1998 political campaigns for state and federal
office and ballot initiatives was up 25 percent over the election
four years ago, according to the nonprofit California Voter
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need for that much cash creates an exclusive club, which
you can only enter by either taking lots of special interest money
or being personally wealthy,'' said Ellen Miller of Public
Campaign, a Washington-based group that advocates overhauling
campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real shame of it is that most of that money is spent on
advertising meant to confuse voters, manipulate voters, instill
fear in voters and appeal to the emotions of voters rather than
their intellects,'' said Kim Alexander, president of the California
Voter Foundation, which has started a network of computerized
information to help voters get to the bottom of election issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking about what I could do with $500 million to
really educate voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Some political workers argue that skyrocketing campaign costs
are merely the price of democracy in an age of multimillion dollar
TV spots and jet travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, with the money spent on politics this year, you could
fund every orphanage from here to Saigon,'' said Bob Mulholland,
campaign adviser to the California Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is expensive,'' he said. ``Nobody should undercut
it. These are the most important jobs in the nation we're electing
here.''
</P>
<P>
   This year saw several firsts in California political spending.
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire Al Checchi made the record book by pouring
$38.9 million of his own money into his Democratic primary bid in
the governor's race. He lost.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was that sum more than had ever been spent in a state
gubernatorial primary, it topped the spending of all state Assembly
and Senate primary races combined.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, supporters and opponents of Proposition 5, which will
legalize casino gambling on Indian reservations, raised $96
million, more than any other initiative in state history. The
fund-raising blitz included $25 million in contributions from a
single Indian tribe, the San Manuel Tribal Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Gov.-elect Gray Davis and his Republican opponent, Dan Lungren,
topped the $31.8 million general election spending record set by
retiring Gov. Pete Wilson and his Democratic challenger in 1994,
Kathleen Brown. Davis and Lungren have reported spending nearly $40
million since the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Krumholz of the Center for Responsive Politics in
Washington said one reason the cost of campaigning keeps rising is
the pressure to support a growing industry of consultants and
election experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant money chase, and that money lines a lot of
pockets,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By far, the largest chunk of this year's campaign money went to
paying for television time to broadcast campaign advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In a 17-day period in October, Davis and Lungren reported
spending $13 million dollars on commercials, 87 percent of their
total spending during that time. During the same 2 1/2 weeks, Davis
spent $15,000 paying his campaign manager, Garry South, while
Lungren devoted $160,000 to catering costs, ballroom rentals and
other fees for organizing fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic campaign consultant Bill Carrick said it could cost
up to $1.6 million for a candidate to saturate the state with a
single 30-second spot. The cost is rising rapidly, not only because
of increased broadcasting fees, but because it's becoming harder
and harder to catch the attention of TV viewers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You end up advertising more and get less for it,'' Carrick
said. ``In the '60s on Sunday night you had 80 percent of America
watching the Ed Sullivan show. Now, you have dozens of different
channels. It's harder to reach people.''
</P>
<P>
   People vying for office are spending less time shaking hands and
more time raising money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates no longer have to hit the street and get out and
meet people,'' said Rich DeLeon, a professor of political science
at San Francisco State University. ``Activism and direct
involvement are on the decline. Election politics has become a
spectator sport of sitting around and watching stupid TV ads.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
