A1385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-SIDE10b-COX     11-09 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-SIDE10b-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHEN THEY WERE YOUNG
 &HT;    (Sidebar to WHEN-KIDS10b-COX)
 &HT;    By JEFF HOUCK
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Match the celebrities to their childhood nicknames:
</P>
<P>
   1. Louis Armstrong ..... A. Gloomy Gus
</P>
<P>
   2. Jimmy Carter ..... B. Baby Dumplin'
</P>
<P>
   3. Carl Bernstein ..... C. Gatemouth
</P>
<P>
   4. Miles Davis ..... D. Chatterbox
</P>
<P>
   5. William Faulkner ..... E. Pookles
</P>
<P>
   6. Richard Nixon ..... F. Worm
</P>
<P>
   7. H. Norman Schwarzkopf ..... G. Howdy Doody
</P>
<P>
   8. Dennis Rodman ..... H. Cuddles
</P>
<P>
   9. Orson Welles ..... I. Buckwheat
</P>
<P>
   10. Margaret Mitchell ..... J. Snake Lips
</P>
<P>
   ANSWERS TO NICKNAME QUIZ
</P>
<P>
   1-C (Because of his large grin)
</P>
<P>
   2-B (After the name of Dagwood's son in the comic strip
Blondie.)
</P>
<P>
   3-G (Because of his freckles.)
</P>
<P>
   4-I (Because he was short, dark and thin like the character in
the Our Gang comedies. He hated the racial caricature and got into
fights with whomever called him that name.)
</P>
<P>
   5-J (His father gave him his name because of the shape of his
lips.)
</P>
<P>
   6-A (Because he was a serious, introspective kid.)
</P>
<P>
   7-H (Because friends saw him as a teen cuddling and kissing his
girlfriend on the bus.)
</P>
<P>
   8-F (Because at age 15 he was shy, skinny and short.)
</P>
<P>
   9-E (He got the cute name because he was smart, sassy and very
cute as a child.)
</P>
<P>
   10-D (The Gone With the Wind author was a nonstop talker.)
</P>
<P>
   YOU'RE OUTTA HERE!
</P>
<P>
   Before they were successful, they got tossed out of school:
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey Bogart _ The tough-guy screen legend grew up in a
cultured and wealthy family, which, of course, meant nothing when
he was sent to an exclusive prep school in Andover, Mass.
Schoolmates said he never cracked a book and he failed three out of
five subjects his first semester. By the following May, he was
expelled, after which he left home to join the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Abbie Hoffman _ The soon-to-be political activist honed his
skills on the teachers and administrators of Seaver Prep in
Worchester, Mass. In his sophomore year, he wrote a paper for his
English class defending atheism titled, ``Reward, Punishment and
God.'' The teacher objected to the paper, called him a ``little
Communist bastard'' and ripped the collar off his shirt. Hoffman
overturned the teacher's desk and began hitting him, resulting in
his suspension from school.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Lewis _ In his first year of high school in Irvington,
N.J., Lewis caused an explosion in the chemistry lab. Called to the
school's office, the principal called the boy a ``dumb Jew.''
Without hesitation, Lewis punched the principal in the mouth and
knocked out one of his teeth. He was expelled from school and later
enrolled in a nearby vocational school.
</P>
<P>
   GIRLS WHO ACTED LIKE BOYS
</P>
<P>
   Katharine Hepburn _ When she was 8, ``Kathy'' called herself
Jimmy, after a friend of her brother Tom. To keep kids from pulling
her red hair, she cut it so that it was a half-inch long. She wore
boys' clothes and was sent home from school several times to change
into a dress.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Fonda _ Emulating her famous actor father, Fonda cut her
hair short, wore jeans and flannel shirts and purposely stood and
walked like him. When someone asked if she was a boy, she was so
overjoyed she couldn't sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Martin _ Before she was Peter Pan, she was a tomboy. In the
second grade, she put on a pair of boxing gloves she got for
Christmas and took on the best fighter in her class at school. She
won, knocking out the boy's two front teeth.
</P>
<P>
   BOYS WHO ACTED LIKE GIRLS
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway _ At age 3, he was worried that Santa Claus
would not know he was a boy because his mother, Grace, dressed
Ernest and sister Marcelline, as if they were twins.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Peary _ The arctic explorer was pampered as a boy by his
mother. To keep the sun from burning his fair skin, she sent him
outside in frilly bonnets. The girlish clothing, plus an
embarrassing lisp, were ridiculed by his playmates in Portland,
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Christian Andersen _ The Danish writer was quiet and timid
as a child and often spent time at home sewing clothes for his
dolls.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN I GROW UP
</P>
<P>
   Forget about being a firefighter or a nurse. This is what some
celebs said they wanted to become when they were kids:
</P>
<P>
   Madonna _ A nun . . . at least until she ``realized that nuns
didn't have a sex life.''
</P>
<P>
   Marian Anderson _ The opera legend doctored her dolls and
bandaged her friends, harboring wishes of becoming a surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   k.d. lang _ A roller derby queen. She watched roller derby shows
on television and then perfected her technique in the basement of
her home.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Lombardi _ A priest. He attended a seminary but dropped
out. (Probably a good thing. As a boy, a teacher at his Catholic
school left the room and put him in charge of the daily recitation
of the Hail Mary. She returned to find him hitting another boy's
head against the blackboard for not praying.)
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Stalin _ A priest. (Wonder how he said the Hail Mary . .
.? )
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Stewart _ An aviator.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Lancaster _ An opera singer.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Burnett _ A cartoonist.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Day-Lewis _ A woodworker.
</P>
<P>
   C'MON BABY, GIMME SOME SUGAR
</P>
<P>
   First-kiss memories of the rich and famous:
</P>
<P>
   Alan Alda _ At his 13th birthday party, the future star of M A S
H was dancing with Antoinette Dell'Olio to the song The Girl That I
Marry. At the end of the dance, he kissed her, but because his
mouth was full of silver braces, saliva ran down her face. She
waited until he wasn't looking to wipe her mouth off.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Reynolds _ His first long kiss happened at 15 when he and a
cheerleader named Margie were sitting under a tree in a park. Burt
thought Margie was a pretty experienced kisser, but when she put
her tongue in his mouth (``almost choked me to death,'' he wrote in
his 1994 book My Life) he questioned her sophistication. Later, a
friend explained that Margie had French-kissed him.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Davis _ At one birthday party _ either his sixth or
seventh _ he kissed Velma Brooks too aggressively. His sister,
Dorothy, told on him to their mother, who demanded that their
father stop Miles from smooching with the girl. When the father
refused, his miffed sister replied that someone had better stop
Miles before he gave Velma a baby. His mother told him later that
it was bad to kiss a girl with so much gusto and then slapped him.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Collins _ When she was 4, the singer went on a Halloween
hayride. On her way back to her home in Los Angeles, a boy she went
with told her to close her eyes and then kissed her. When she
opened her eyes, he asked, ``Do you know what that was?'' She said
no, but in her autobiography Trust Your Heart, she said she knew
what it was. ``It was the beginning of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   RED-FACED BEFORE THEY WERE FAMOUS
</P>
<P>
   Think you had it tough as a kid? Consider the childhoods of
these celebrities:
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Cage _ A not-so-rich kid attending the wealthy Beverly
Hills High School, Cage couldn't get girls to date him because it
meant riding the bus. When a beautiful girl agreed to go to the
prom, Cage cashed in a savings bond to rent a limosine. He was so
nervous though, that when he went to kiss her, he threw up. The
limo driver wouldn't let him back into the car because of the vomit
on his shoes and he had to walk home.
</P>
<P>
   Dolly Parton _ Parton grew up poor in Tennessee. When Dolly was
in grade school, her mother made a patchwork coat for her, tailored
from bright-colored scraps of material. Proud of the work of art,
Dolly couldn't wait to show off her coat at school. The kids
instead mocked her, saying it was nothing more than a bunch of
rags. She got the last laugh. Years later she turned the experience
into a song. Coat of Many Colors became her signature tune.
</P>
<P>
   J. Robert Oppenheimer _ A shy, sickly, intellectual kid, ``the
father of the atomic bomb'' was kidnapped at summer camp by fellow
campers and dragged to an icehouse, where he was stripped, beaten
and had his backside painted green.
</P>
<P>
   John Wayne _ Kids ridiculed Marion Morrison (his real name)
after he moved to California from Iowa because he was shy, skinny,
taller than the other boys and had a ``sissy name.'' They
repeatedly beat him up and called him ``little girl'' until he
filled out and began to play football.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
