<HEADER>
A1389 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHEN-KIDS10b-COX     11-09 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEN-KIDS10b-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHEN THEY WERE YOUNG
 &HT;    By JEFF HOUCK
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madonna wanted to be a nun. Oprah was abused. Elvis Presley was
a mama's boy sleepwalker who believed nightmares were hereditary.
Burt Reynolds' success began when he won a high school foot race. A
grief-stricken Martin Luther King Jr. threw himself out of a
second-floor window when he learned his beloved grandmother had
died. Barbra Streisand dressed a water bottle up as a doll and
filled it with warm water to make it feel like a real baby.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, famous people had strange childhoods, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's the point made by the new book, When They Were Kids,
(Random House, $14.95). No matter if you're the pope (who harbored
boyhood dreams of a life in the theater) or the president (Abe
Lincoln was a geeky six-footer at age 15), the message is: your
childhood probably wasn't much different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Childhood is a memorable experience for all of us, whether the
stuff that happened is good or bad,''
</P>
<P>
   ``The social mores may change over time and the accoutrements
accouterments of history may change,'' says author Carol Orsag
Madigan, who wrote the book with friend Ann Elwood, a history
professor who teaches at universities in southern California. ``But
what underlies many of the stories are emotions and relationships
and problems with self-esteem and self-worth that everyone goes
through.''
</P>
<P>
   That universality allowed Madigan and Elwood to examine equally
the likes of Dolly Parton (who endured poverty in the Tennessee
mountains), the Dalai Lama (who played war games with Lhasa monks)
and Salvador Dali' (who forever sought to shake the legacy of a
brother who died 10 months before the artist was born -- and with
whom he shared the same name).
</P>
<P>
   The book is a collection of lists that group batch familiar
subjects with history's most famous names. Chapters include
``Favorite Toys,'' (Truman Capote adored a tricycle shaped like a
red airplane), ``Fears, Phobias and Obsessions,'' (Wolfgang Mozart
was terrified by the sound of a lone trumpet), and ``Loners,'' (A
third-grade Bruce Springsteen was stuffed into a garbage can by a
nun). at his school).
</P>
<P>
   The authors pored for two years through hundreds of anectdotes
and quotes from dozens of biographies and articles in newspapers
and magazines to collect the more than 400 sketches of famous
childhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Madigan could be called a professional list maker. She helped
edit and write the landmark books The People's Almanac and The Book
of Lists with historians Amy and Irving Wallace and David
Wallechinsky. When They Were Kids is an extension of reference
books that she and Elwood wrote for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing the reference books, we started to notice common themes
of the various childhoods and thought they might make a good book
in list form,'' Madigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Movie titans Steven Spielberg and George Lucas make the most
appearances. (Spielberg had a messy room, was easily spooked by
scary TV shows and had two parakeets he named Schmuck and Schmuck
II. Lucas was an inept speller who loved to read comic books and
build backyard carnivals that featured a six-foot-high
rollercoaster.)
</P>
<P>
   A close third is Palm Beach County's favorite son, Burt
Reynolds, Madigan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a section dedicated
</P>
<P>
   to turning points in each person's life and he had a wonderful
story in his book My Life about how he had been a greaser but
wanted to be a jock,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds didn't like the ``Greaseball'' nickname and instead
wanted to be called ``Buddy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Reynolds was challenged by the jocks to run a foot race
against the best sprinter at Central Junior High in West Palm
Beach. Burt, running barefoot in front of a crowd gathered at the
football field, beat his opponent in the last 5 yards. The result:
He became a football player, lettered in several sports. And
everyone called him Buddy. The rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said in the book that while he'd like to think his success
was the result of luck and talent, he said it all might have worked
out differently for him if he hadn't won that foot race,'' Madigan
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's about as deep as the book strays into Freudian analysis.
(Yes, Sigmund Freud is here. He was the golden child of seven
offspring whose mother doted on him.) But Madigan said there are
some obvious personality traits that each notable displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of us are medically trained, but if I was playing
armchair psychologist, I'd say that all of the people in the book
had a lot of drive and ambition and success and a need to overcome
adversity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
