Reno.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A department store in Minnesota is trying to catch a woman who
has stolen over $1,000 worth of size 44-D bras. Police are looking
for the woman, as is every other guy in town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A plastic surgeon in Italy announced he's going to perform the
world's first penis transplant. Shortly thereafter, Hillary Clinton
called to say she knows the perfect donor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier today, President Clinton said, 'The American people
sent a message that would break the eardrums of anybody listening.'
In fact, the President said the last time he heard something that
loud, he had to tell Monica to keep it down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been reported that Jesse 'The Body' Ventura spent only
$250,000 on his entire campaign. It would have been even less, but
he spent $50,000 on body oil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Famous radio personality Dr. Laura Schlessinger apologized
yesterday for the nude photos of her that have popped up on the
Internet. Apparently, the photos reveal why Dr. Laura is on the
radio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore talked to the astronauts on board the space shuttle
today. Reportedly, he asked them what zero gravity is like and they
asked him what zero charisma is like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, the Republican National Committee rejected New York
as the site of their next presidential convention. A spokesperson
explained by saying, 'Just like any other convention, we want a
place with good strip bars.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``John Glenn's historic space flight is coming to an end and
he'll be returning to Earth tomorrow. Unless they let him drive and
then it could take a few more days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Paula Jones' lawyers have quit because they say that she is
'unreasonable.' After hearing this, President Clinton said, 'Hey, I
found that out the first time I met her.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``O.J. Simpson had surgery recently. Apparently, there was an
awkward moment just before O.J. went under when he told the
surgeon, 'You're holding the knife wrong.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There were two things I always wanted as a child _ a
three-wheeler and shoes that squeaked. I remember how my classmates
had shoes that squeaked as they walked, and I never knew what
caused it, but I liked the sound. I would walk through puddles of
water hoping that would do the trick, but it never did.
</P>
<P>
   I always loved any toy that had wheels, and it was a thrill when
my superintendent's son let me ride his tricycle. My parents were
poor, so I just dreamed about owning one. I never got the squeaky
shoes or the tricycle.
</P>
<P>
   The other day I wore my Nike shoes, and as I was walking to the
trash room, I heard them squeak. I couldn't believe it. After all
these years, I finally had a pair of shoes that squeaked.
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSAN SMPADIAN
</P>
<P>
   Edward Levine was playing a word game with Lily, his 9-year-old
daughter. The game covers a variety of subjects and requires each
player to come up with a word or phrase beginning with a particular
letter. In one round, the letter was H and the category was
``action words.'' Where else but New York would Lily have responded
with ``Hail a cab!''
</P>
<P>
   My 21-year-old daughter graduated from college in May and headed
to Europe for a planned three-month vacation. Six weeks later, she
was notified about a potential job in New York and deemed it such a
great opportunity that she returned immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Switching into her ``take charge mode,'' she bought a new suit
for the interview, had her hair styled, called her references in
advance and left me wondering if this was really my child. She got
the job, and in record time moved back into her dad's apartment in
Manhattan, reorganized her room there and went to work at a
prestigious media organization.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, we were discussing the nuts and bolts of her
new life, and I offered her one of my favorite and extremely hardy
plants for her room. ``No,'' she replied. ``I'm not ready for that
level of commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   _ VALERIE M. JOSEPHSON
</P>
<P>
   When her daughters were 5 and 7, Linda Weil attended a lecture
by a psychologist. The message she took home was that life was
filled with choices, and that a parent's job was to present the
choices on a regular basis as training for adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, as the girls were dressing, Ms. Weil asked if
they wanted pancakes or waffles. There were a few short ``I don't
care'' shrugs, but Ms. Weil was determined to make them choose. She
kept repeating the question. Finally, one of the girls looked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been something at last night's lecture,'' her
daughter said. ``Please don't go to any more of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The panhandler near Rockefeller Center wasn't doing too badly,
all things considered. His sign read, ``Help me continue my beer
research.'' A surprising number of passers-by did.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, my wife took our 10-week-old son for his first subway
ride. Everyone said that he would sleep through the whole ride. He
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   He started screaming as soon as they sat down. Instead of
leaving the car or rolling their eyes, the other passengers gave
advice. One woman suggested turning him around in his harness
(didn't work), a Russian woman came over and bounced him around and
sang (worked for about 40 seconds), and a guy offered what seemed
to be a lot of sympathetic advice (my wife couldn't hear it over
the screaming). Then he gave her a package of earplugs.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a homeless man, who gave his ``Ladiesanjennulmun may I
please have yer attention'' speech, even though it was completely
drowned out by the screaming, came over and said ``Don't cry baby!
Jesus loves you! Praise the Lord! Hallelujah! Hallelujah!''
</P>
<P>
   My son stopped crying immediately. The whole car burst out
laughing. He slept for the rest of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   _ JEM ASWAD
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Kristel was intrigued by recent sightings of two signs.
In Los Angeles, ``Antique tables made daily'' and in London,
``Breakfast served all day 9 a.m. to 2 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Metro-North train from Pawling to Grand Central Terminal
on a Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Henry Baker, sitting in a double seat with an
unobstructed view of the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Tall young man with a shoulder bag, making a beeline for
restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Action: None. The man doesn't emerge. Baker sits and thinks:
``Aha, he's hiding from the conductor. He's not going to pay his
fare.''
</P>
<P>
   The conductor goes by. More time passes. What could be going on
in there?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the restroom door opens. Out walks a tall, perfectly
coiffed, beautifully dressed, very elegant _ woman.
</P>
<P>
   As Baker summed it up: and so, another Saturday night in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Secunda was on the Upper West Side when he heard this
Clintonian exchange:
</P>
<P>
   A father, impatiently tugging a rambunctious boy about 10 years
old, said, ``If you don't start behaving, we're turning around and
going home this minute.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy replied, ``Define behaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Bass, the president of the Strand Book Store, has a new
definition of chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a man called the store saying he had a Britannica set
to sell. He was told the store would pay him $100, and he accepted.
A little later, as he drove up with his books and was unloading
them, a passer-by spotted them, offered him more money and within
the proverbial New York minute was carrying away the set.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later, the wheeler-dealer buyer returned. This
time he entered the store, but not to make a purchase. He demanded
satisfaction, he said. The set was incomplete. Bass suggested he
hang a shingle out on the curb.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Livingston, likely the next House speaker, says we're ``at a
crossroads.'' Right. Republicans are cross, Democrats on the road.
</P>
<P>
   _ (Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star)
</P>
