<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NEWS AND NOTES  
 
 IRON MEN TARDIGRADES  
 NEW USE FOR OLD TIRES 
OBSERVATORY IS NO MORE 
 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tardigrades are microscopic invertebrates that live among mosses
and lichens, and in lakes and oceans. They are sometimes known as
water bears, for their roly-poly appearance and ambling gait.
</P>
<P>
   But the cuteness is deceiving: Tardigrades are the Iron Men of
the animal kingdom. Scientists have been putting them through their
paces for years, discovering that they can survive temperatures
near absolute zero and above boiling, as well as high vacuum. They
have even been zapped with X-rays, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest stress test, researchers in Japan have subjected
them to extreme hydrostatic pressure, equal to six times what would
be felt 30,000 feet under the sea. Sure enough, the researchers
report in the journal Nature, the tardigrades pulled through.
</P>
<P>
   The key to their survival is an ability to enter a kind of
suspended animation in which they dry up to about one-third their
former size. Once the pressure is reduced, the tardigrades return
to normal and waddle off, as if nothing had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Used tires are an environmental nuisance, and with a
quarter-billion being added each year in the United States, the
problem is getting worse. Much research has gone into reclaiming
oils and gases from them. But researchers at the University of
Illinois and the state's geological survey have suggested a new
use, as a pollution scrubber.
</P>
<P>
   They have turned old tires into activated carbon (carbon black's
being a major component of tire rubber) and tested its ability to
remove mercury and other contaminants from smokestack emissions. It
has generally performed as well as activated carbon from other
sources, notably coal. And the researchers note that, with all
those old tires around, tire-based activated carbon should be
inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Greenwich Observatory, Britain's oldest scientific
institution, closed on Oct. 31, the victim of budget cuts. It was
founded in 1675 by Charles II to aid navigation. In recent years
its focus shifted to providing technical support for astronomers.
Its location shifted too, first to Sussex and then, in 1990, to
Cambridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
